<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Garagiola     03-25 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Garagiola,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pressed for Security Gate, Now Home Is Robbed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARADISE VALLEY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Garagiola lost his 1946 World
Series ring and other jewelry in a break-in at his home two days
after the baseball announcer pressed the Town Council to allow
security gates.
   Garagiola, 62, and his family were home at the time Wednesday
night but heard nothing, they said.
   The burglar got in by breaking a window in the closet of the
master bedroom and took $200,000 in jewelry from a chest in the
closet, said police Sgt. Ron Warner.
   The items stolen included the former St. Louis catcher's Series
ring from 1946, the year the Cardinals beat the Boston Red Sox,
Warner said.
   On Monday night, Garagiola pressed officials of this affluent
Phoenix suburb to amend rules against security gates at subdivision
entrances.
   Paradise Valley and two unincorporated luxury communities within
it have been hit by at least 15 similar burglaries since January,
police said.
   The Council agreed to study the proposal.
</TEXT>
