<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Advantage     03-25 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Advantage,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Working To Lay To Rest Talk Of Brokered Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis, with a widening edge in the delegate race, is working to
lay to rest talk of a brokered Democratic National Convention.
   As the campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination moves
into a springtime series of Northern and Midwestern state contests,
aides to the Massachusetts governor are laying plans to drive the
rest of the Democrats out of the race.
   ``It's conceivable we could have a nominating majority by the
day after California,'' which is among the states to vote on the
last day of the primary season June 8, says Tad Devine, a senior
campaign aide. More optimistic aides paint a scenario that would
effectively clinch the nomination earlier.
   Dukakis' rivals concede his superior organization, finances,
fresh endorsements and other advantages. ``There's no state that's
life and death for Dukakis,'' says Terry Michael, a spokesman for
Sen. Paul Simon, adding that most of the other contenders face
make-or-break elections in the next few weeks.
   But, they quickly add, Dukakis and his message of managerial
competence in the Massachusetts statehouse have yet to stir the
emotions of Democrats around the country, and a few bumps might be
all it takes to shatter his candidacy.
   ``I think his lack of a message of what a Dukakis administration
would do is catching up with him,'' says Mark Johnson, spokesman
for Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   ``They haven't captured the hearts of Democrats. All they've
been able to do is convince many that they're a safe bet,'' says
Simon aide Michael. ``They have been moving along picking up
delegates on tactics, not on message.''
   Dukakis' aides insist their candidate has a sound campaign
message.
   But they also argue tactics, saying that Vice President George
Bush's apparently secure Republican nomination is cooling the
enthusiasm for a brokered Democratic convention.
   ``The fear of giving George Bush a head start is eventually
going to help somebody, and if we do our job right, that person is
going to be Michael Dukakis,'' says Leslie Dach, communications
director.
   Dukakis' blueprint for the nomination calls for defeating
Gephardt in Saturday's Michigan caucuses and driving him from the
race. Next, aides seek a victory over Simon in Wisconsin on April
5, driving him from the race. They hope to follow up with victories
in New York or Pennsylvania that cripple Sen. Albert Gore Jr., even
if he remains a candidate.
   That would leave Jesse Jackson, but Dukakis' aides believe he
isn't likely to win more than 900 or so delegates, out of 2,082
needed to gain the nomination. They say Dukakis is prepared to
outline differences over policy issues with Jackson later in the
year, particularly over the Mideast and defense spending.
   During the period between New York's primary on April 19 and
Pennsylvania a week later, Dukakis' aides hope that many of the 645
``super delegates'' to the convention _ the party leaders, members
of members of Congress and governors _ will swing to their side.
   There is no disputing the strides Dukakis has made since he fell
to third place in Illinois:
   _ He has 533.55 delegates according to a count by The Associated
Press, an increase of 69 in the past week. Jesse Jackson, his
nearest pursuer, has 511.55, an increase of 51. But Gore, who has
360.8 overall, has added only six in that time, while Gephardt, at
154, has added only nine. Simon, the Illinois winner, has 171.5
delegates, 141 of them from Illinois.
   _ Dukakis has been endorsed since the Illinois primary by five
senators, 10 congressmen and a governor. The biggest prize, Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey, has been mentioned prominently as a
possible compromise candidate in case of a deadlocked convention
this summer. Dukakis and the other contenders continue to vie for
support from New York Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   _ Recent national public opinion polls show Dukakis running
strongly against Bush. A nationwide survey conducted for ABC and
the Washington Post showed Dukakis leading the vice president 50
percent to 45 percent. Bush led Jackson, Gore and Gephardt in
similar matchups.
   _ He won the Kansas caucuses a few days after Illinois voted,
his first triumph in a predominantly agricultural state.
   However, Dukakis' rivals say his finish in Illinois _ where he
got 17 percent of the vote behind favorite sons Simon and Jesse
Jackson, and no delegates _ is symptomatic of a failure to attract
widepsread support to his candidacy.
   They say he has particularly failed to demonstrate appeal among
blue collar workers and conservative Democrats who will be
essential to Democratic chances of capturing the White House.
   Dukakis also stands accused of flip-flopping on a key issue,
belatedly embracing trade legislation to make himself more
appealing to the United Autoworkers Union members who will
participate in Saturday's Michigan caucuses.
</TEXT>
