<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0828 03-25 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0828,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Military Reportedly Unpaid; Shops Ordered To Open</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 19-20 pvs, `It did not ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
that only one decree issued, sted of two as sent. PICKS up 21st
graf pvs bgng, It said store...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces that keep Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega in power went unpaid Friday and the broke and
beleaguered government ordered businesses closed in the general
strike to reopen.
   In a decree issued under a week-old state of emergency, the
civilian government that does Noriega's bidding said it would take
away the commercial licenses of any businesses ``offering goods and
services to the public'' if they remained closed.
   The decree specifically mentioned grocery stores, pharmacies,
transportation companies and gasoline stations.
   An estimated 90 percent of Panama's industry and businesses have
shut down in the strike that began Monday in an effort to force
Noriega's removal as the head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces
that includes the military and police.
   The government's inability to pay the Defense Forces kindled
hopes in the opposition that loyalty for him will wane.
   Several members of the Defense Forces, including a secretary at
military headquarters, said army, navy, police and air force
personnel did not receive their semi-monthly paychecks as scheduled
Friday.
   ``We did not receive our wages and we were not told when we
would receive them,'' said the secretary, who declined to give her
name. Soldiers questioned by reporters also said they had not been
paid.
   In mid-March, most of the 130,000 public employees were given
partial payment of at least $75 on their salaries. Those employees
whose monthly salaries are $1,000 or more were not paid. Social
security checks have been postponed.
   Demonstrators at the Roman Catholic cathedral protested the
church's failure to issue a denunciation of Noriega as expected.
   Pilots who guide ships through the Panama Canal and claimed they
had been harassed by soldiers in Panama City demanded protection
and met with the Panama Canal Commission. Some pilots had spoken of
a strike, but commission spokesman Frank Castrellon said the
situation was resolved at the meeting. He did not elaborate.
   John Maher, president of the Panama Canal Pilots Association,
said: ``There is no problem now.''
   Noriega remained obstinate.
   He was asked at a military ceremony about President Reagan's
renewed call for his departure and he replied:
   ``My president is called (Manuel) Solis Palma and my geographic
space is called Panama. I don't take orders from
extra-terrestrials.''
   Solis Palma was named chief executive by the legislature when
President Eric Arturo Delvalle was ousted on Feb. 26, the day after
he tried to fire Noriega.
   Two members of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, Reps. Gary
Ackerman, D-N.Y., and Peter H. Kostmayer, D-Pa., ended a two-day
visit Friday and told a news conference they thought the Reagan
administration should increase economic pressure on Noriega.
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States on narcotics
charges. The Reagan administration has cut the flow of money to
Panama, which uses the U.S. dollar as its currency.
   The order for businesses to reopen was in Decree No. 16 issued
under the state of emergency that enables the government to act as
it deems necessary ``to secure public order,'' including suspending
civil liberties.
   The decree also said any establishment that had been closed for
the past five days and sold food, meats or canned goods ``cannot
reopen unless it is first inspected by the Health Ministry.''
   It said store owners who do not comply face ``temporary
suspension of their licenses or, in case of repeated violations,
the cancellation of their commercial licenses.''
   The strike began Monday and was called by the National Civic
Crusade, a broad alliance of Noriega's opposition. Crusade leaders
said it would continue until Noriega was ousted.
   Panama Canal employees have worked throughout protests and
general strikes against Noriega that began last June. The canal
continues to operate normally while the nation around the waterway
is at a virtual standstill.
   Most of the canal's 230 pilots are American citizens.
   Soldiers man roadblocks around the capital and they demand
identification from drivers, search cars and rummage through
personal belongings. Some pilots complained about those actions.
   About 100 people stalked out of the cathedral after Archbishop
Marcos G. McGrath opened a special Mass by telling worshipers and
observers the church would not issue the anticipated anti-Noriega
statement.
   ``We don't know how this mistaken rumor originated,'' McGrath
said. ``We are sorry, but it is not our fault.''
   Civic Crusade leaders and Ackerman had said they had been
assured the church would issue a strong condemnation of Noriega.
   Those who walked out stood on the steps of the gray stone
cathedral chanting, ``Justice! Justice!'' and ``Noriega must go!''
   McGrath told those remaining inside that he and Noriega had a
``preparatory meeting'' Thursday. He did not explain and said he
could not discuss the conversation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
