<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Politics     03-25 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Politics,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Noriega Departure Could Mean Political Free-for-All</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
leaves, it could start a political free-for-all in Panama, where 20
years of military rule with a civilian facade have given opposition
parties little chance to mature.
   ``No dictatorship ever prepared a people for democracy,'' said
editor Winston Robles of La Prensa newspaper, which the
Noriega-controlled government shut down last month.
   Many political observers, including opposition party leaders,
predict a ``free-for-all, no holds barred'' if Noriega goes.
   The general, who heads the 15,000-strong Defense Forces, says he
isn't leaving. He has defied a huge opposition campaign and
crippling U.S. economic pressure and even indicated he might run
for president.
   The government-controlled news media have started referring to
Noriega as ``the undisputed leader of the political majorities'' of
Panama. His predecessor, Gen. Omar Torrijos, abolished political
parties in 1968 after taking power in a coup.
   In 1977, when he and then-President Jimmy Carter signed the
Canal Treaties, Torrijos founded his own party. He let other
parties campaign in 1984, but his Revolutionary Democratic Party
won in what the opposition called robbery.
   Most parties here revolve around a single personality _ like
87-year-old Arnulfo Arias Madrid of the Authentic Panamanian Party,
deposed three times as president by the military, and the leader of
the Christian Democratic Party, Ricardo Arias Calderon, who
returned Thursday from exile.
   Others parties are what Panamanians call ``stationery.'' They
exist on paper, issuing statements and communiques, but have no
popular following.
   Political parties have not been in the forefront of the campaign
against Noriega. The drive has been led by the National Civic
Crusade, a coalition of business, private organizations and
professional groups and some labor unions.
   ``We do not have any political leadership. We are being led by
businessmen,'' said a young man collecting food for residents of a
Panama City slum.
   While the Civic Crusade was organizing national strikes and
issuing calls for Noriega to resign, most politicians applauded
from the sidelines. Arias Calderon and some other Christian
Democratic officials have been an exception.
   Last month, the Civic Crusade and most of the opposition parties
formed an alliance and agreed that if Noriega goes, they will work
under a transitional government with deposed President Eric Arturo
Delvalle as its head. The next election is scheduled for May 1989.
   The Authenic Panamanian Party, however, refused to join the
alliance. Party leaders say they will never recognize Delvalle
because the party he represents robbed them of victory in the 1984
election.
   Arias Madrid is a populist first elected in 1940 and first
deposed late the following year. He was elected again in 1950 and
deposed in 1951. He was elected president a third time in 1968 and
deposed after 11 days in office.
   The Authentic Panamanians see Arias Calderon _ Arias Madrid's
vice presidential running mate in 1984 _ as a threat.
   The Christian Democrats, the nation's largest opposition party,
gave Arias Madrid the top spot on the 1984 coalition ticket because
Arias Calderon was seen as something of an egghead with little
popular appeal.
   But since then, Arias Calderon's close cooperation with the
Civic Crusade has positioned him for a presidential bid in a
post-Noriega Panama.
   When Arias Calderon returned Thursday, Aurelio Barria, the head
of the Panamanian Chamber of Commerce, Industry and Agriculture and
a founder of the Civic Crusade, stood next to him as he greeted
cheering well wishers.
   Arias Calderon has also been busy building bridges with other
political parties, particularly the Liberal Republican Nationalist
Movement, in what is seen as an attempt to forge a new coalition.
   Some politicians say they do not expect the Crusade to survive
long after Noriega because its leaders are mostly business people
without political affiliation.
   Typical of the Crusade leaders are Ernesto Gonzalez de la
Lastra, general manager of an insurance company, and Barria.
Neither is affiliated with a political party.
   Other politicians, however, say the strong role people like
Barria and Gonzalez de la Lastra have assumed in the Crusade could
make them forces to be reckoned with if they remain active in
public life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
