<DOCNO> AP880325-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson     03-25 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pat Robertson Says He'll Do Some Muscle-Flexing At GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FALLS CHURCH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson says his lagging campaign
for the Republican presidential nomination is being revived in
caucus states that will strengthen conservatives' hand at the party
convention in New Orleans.
   Beyond that goal, Robertson said Thursday night, he is looking
not only to lay the groundwork for another presidential campaign in
1992, but to help build GOP strength in state houses and Congress
for the 1990s.
   Although Robertson was beaten by George Bush in his home state's
non-binding primary on Super Tuesday, he told 700 supporters at
Falls Church High School that they can still capture most of the
state's delegates by turning out in force at local precinct
meetings.
   ``A few days from now we're going to be celebrating the most
important event in the entire Christian calendar,'' said the former
religious broadcaster, referring to Easter, which falls on April 3.
   He said the press wrote his candidacy off as dead after Super
Tuesday, ``but I don't think they're aware of the resurrection.''
   He said his campaign swept county convention delegates in Wake
County, N.C. on Tuesday, and had picked up other delegates in
Charleston, S.C., as well as Georgia, Washington, Nevada, Alaska,
Hawaii, Texas and elsewhere.
   ``All over this country, when June comes around and it's all
over ... our people should be in significant places of
responsibility in something like 15 or 20 of the state Republican
parties,'' he said.
   ``We are going to put together a coalition that will go to New
Orleans strong, speaking with one voice, and having enough
political weight to make sure that some of the things we hold very
dear ... are embodied in the platform of the Republican party,'' he
said.
   ``In the next few weeks, as these caucuses unfold in Virginia,
we are going to win the majority in the Republican Party,'' he
predicted.
   Asked as he left the rally if he was giving up in Colorado, a
caucus state where his campaign pulled the plug on a bank of 32
phones, Robertson said, ``We're going from paid phone banks to
volunteer phone banks. The operation is still under way. I'm going
out there for a series of meetings a week from Saturday.''
   In his speech, Robertson attacked the Civil Rights Restoration
Act that Congress passed Tuesday over President Reagan's veto, as
``a horrible bill. It was a federal power grab ... a blot on the
U.S. Congress.''
   Many of America's worst problems, including crime and drugs,
stem from erosion of morals, he said, adding, ``If we're going to
restore the greatness of America, we've got to go back to a sense
of personal, individual responsibility.''
   ``We must be No. 1 in our ethics, No. 1 in our morals, No. 1 in
our lifestyles, No. 1 in our adherence to freedom, No. 1 in our
trust and faith in God almighty,'' he said.
   ``We cannot allow the radical Democrats to institutionalize
aberrant behavior which is part of the destruction of America,'' he
said.
   A Falls Church High School freshman, Debbie Weisshaar, 14, of
Annandale, Va., said afterwards that she was discomfited by
Robertson's repeated references to God and Christianity.
   ``I wasn't sure if he meant freedom for everyone, or freedom for
the people who believed in what he believed in,'' said the
teen-ager, who is Jewish.
   Robertson has just 17 delegates in the latest Associated Press
count to 788 for Bush and 178 for Dole.
</TEXT>
