<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Haven     03-25 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Haven,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Town Is What Lebanon Used to be</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HASAN MROUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RMEILEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the chaos and intolerance that is
Lebanon, Rmeileh is an oasis of liberty, a haven for people fleeing
political and social persecution and assassination.
   This coastal town, 19 miles south of Beirut, is what Lebanon
used to be before 13 years of civil war, sectarian hatreds and
religious fanatacism turned it into a wilderness.
   Leftists and other refugees from Beirut and the south have fled
to Rmeileh following a campaign of assassinations by Shiite Moslem
fundamentalists against communists, pro-Iraqi Baath socialists and
other leftists.
   One of the things that makes Rmeileh different from just about
everywhere else in south Lebanon is that alcohol is sold openly at
the side of the road.
   Alcohol is banned in most areas of the region, dominated by
Shiite Moslem factions, and in Beirut's southern slums, the Shiite
stronghold in the capital.
   Islamic religious laws also ban mixed parties, mixed bathing and
the consumption of pork.
   But in the summer, Rmeileh's eight restaurants and three miles
of Mediterranean beaches and hillside picnic areas are packed with
males and females having a good time. Pork also is sold.
   Hamza, 35, comes from the staunchly Shiite town of Nabatiyeh in
the south.
   ``We can't buy drinks in Nabatiyeh any more, so we come to
Rmeileh,'' he said. ``In summer women have to come here to swim
because it's the one of the very few places they can do that.''
   Because he lives in a Shiite area, where such activities are
forbidden, Hamza declined to disclose his full name.
   Rmeileh was a mainly Christian town, with about 5,000 Maronite
Catholics, until 1985, when Moslem forces overran the coastal
plain. Now only about 60 Maronite families are left.
   But Rmeileh now is protected by Communist Party militiamen, most
of them Christians, who are allied to neighboring Druse and Sunni
Moslem forces who help keep the Shiites out.
   The Syrian army also has a checkpoint just south of Rmeileh on
the Awali River which also acts as a deterrent for Shiite gunmen.
   Abu Rim, a leftist official in the town, said 500 refugee
families _ Moslems, Christians and Palestinians _ live in Rmeileh
with the local Christians.
   ``Our aim is to get rid of the sectarian atmosphere and
implement co-existence,'' he said.
   Elias Tabet, director of the town's government school, said
ethnic mix gives Rmeileh a non-sectarian nature, where people from
different areas and religions ``feel safe and free.''
   Samih Germanos, 57, a Christian who fled Beirut's
Shiite-controlled southern slums, said: ``We're very happy and hope
things will stay this way.''
   Acting Mayor Halim Kleib, said the tourist influx last summer
was even better than pre-war times.
   ``People in the south prefer Rmeileh to other places because
it's the closest resort to them that provides restaurants and
private beaches as well as drinks,'' Kleib added.
   Ali Hujeiri, 40, a father of nine, who works at a Pepsi Cola
plant in a nearby town, said he sells alcohol on the street to earn
extra money and that most of his customers are from the Shiite
south.
   ``I'm the only one to sell pork in this area,'' said Abu Elie, a
32-year-old shopowner.``I started bringing it from Mount Lebanon
last week and in four days, I sold around 40 kilograms (88
pounds).''
   Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal movement and the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah (Party of God) have been blamed for many
of the assasinations of leftists in south Lebanon.
   But since many of those who have fled to Rmeileh _
``self-deportees,'' Amal calls them _ are skilled or professional
people, the Amal recently asked them to return to their villages.
   Wafiq Rihan, a 33-year-old Shiite school teacher, didn't sound
as though he is ready to return. He said that after he fled
Nabatiyeh last year the Communists and the leftist Druse ``helped
us find places to stay and in the beginning we relied on Red Cross
supplies.''
   ``I'm teaching at the school now,'' he added. ``I was originally
a teacher. But most of the other deportees here are also working in
their particular fields, medicine, the law, and so on.
   ``One doctor who fled Nabatiyeh even has some of his old
patients come here to see him for treatment.''
   Rihan said he wants to go back to his own village but only when
it's safe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Guards     03-25 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Guards,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs Stand Overnight Watch for Soldiers and Settlers</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARURA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinians on night guard
duty, masked and armed with clubs, sprinted down the main village
road passing the word: ``Israeli soldiers are coming!''
   Behind them, about 20 more moved in the dark with the speed of
practice to block the road in a half-dozen places. They dragged
stockpiled boulders and twisted metal onto the pavement to slow the
12 jeeps in the Israeli patrol.
   Palestinians whose faces were hidden by checkered keffiyeh
headdresses whistled shrilly to each other across the rocky hills,
tracking the army's progress on the narrow road.
   The overnight citizen patrol was in action, witnessed in this
case by a journalist. The patrol at Arura was one of dozens
organized after the army started nighttime raids, arresting
hundreds of alleged agitators in an effort to quell nearly four
months of violent anti-Israeli protests.
   Jamal, 30, stood watch atop a ridge on the outskirts of Arura, a
village of 2,200 Palestinians that sprawls over hills of the
occupied West Bank about 20 miles north of Jerusalem.
   ``Because of these patrols, we are ready for an attack from
anywhere,'' he said. ``But there is more than that. The guard duty
makes us unified as a people. Everyone feels he has a part in the
uprising.''
   Arab patrols are clandestine and all those interviewed would
agree only to the use of their first names.
   Riots began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel
has occupied since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war. More than 100 Palestinians and an Israeli soldier
have been killed.
   The patrols are a sign of the changing nature and steady
escalation of the ``intefadeh,'' Arabic for uprising. They
illustrate growing sophistication in a rebellion that began
spontaneously and, for that reason, worry Israeli officials.
   ``Illegal local organization could lead to illegal regional
organization, all of it directed against us,'' a military man said
privately.
   On this night the army jeeps stopped short of Arura, parked for
about half an hour, then drove away.
   Why the soldiers approached and left in the latest cat-and-mouse
game was not clear, but the villagers viewed called it a retreat by
the enemy and a victory for themselves.
   Residents said soldiers had approached Arura on three occasions
since the patrols began, but stopped each time when guards alerted
villagers and about 1,000 people gathered in the streets, chanting
and throwing stones.
   Patrolling in Arura, as witnessed on two evenings, is a
methodical and sometimes tense business.
   Men carrying clubs and rocks, their faces covered, stop each
passing car. Strangers are ordered out of their vehicles until they
are determined to be friends and not Israeli soldiers in
plainclothes or Jews from the nearby Ateret settlement.
   Between cars and sightings of soldiers, the sentinels often
engage in mutual pep-talk. They encourage each other to continue
the fight against Israel, make optimistic predictions about the
uprising and sometimes ward off the night cold with a shared glass
of sweet herb tea.
   Tahir, 23, said he would stand guard until 5 a.m. then leave for
his job in an Israeli factory, where he packs oranges.
   ``I'm one person at night and another in the day,'' he said.
``In Israel, they have no idea that I am taking my turn, once a
week, on patrol.''
   Nightly patrols were organized in Arura about a month ago after
the army had made four raids in a six-week period, arresting 21
young men.
   Israeli soldiers have rounded up more than 700 Palestinians in
the past week in an effort to end the rebellion, and about 3,000
have been detained since the violence began.
   Soldiers are ordered to make arrests overnight, when most people
are sleeping, to avoid causing violent protests.
   ``They won't catch us sleeping here and they won't be able to
arrest us. We are watching for them every night,'' said Salah, 22,
one of 250 men of Arura aged 16 to 45 who take turns on guard duty
from about 8 p.m. until dawn.
   Boys under 16 are not taken for the patrols, but many children
are eager to do their part.
   Four boys huddled for warmth over smoldering embers in a small,
smoky cave beside the road to the village.
   They said they would remain until 2 a.m., and if a man came
running with word of approaching soldiers they would race through
the rocky hills helping wake the villagers.
   ``I feel like a man because I am doing something to resist the
Israelis,'' Yassin told a reporter with a solemnity far beyond his
11 years. ``This is in the interest of our homeland. It is the duty
of everyone to help.''
</TEXT>
