<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRoucheTrial     03-25 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Fund-Raisers Ordered To Demand Money To Head Off Global
Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fund-raisers for Lyndon LaRouche were ordered to
tell people they owed the political extremist money because he was
preventing Soviet aggression and global economic collapse, a former
LaRouche aide testified.
   The fund-raisers also were told that LaRouche needed the money
to pay for security to protect him from assassins, former aide
Charles Tate testified Thursday at the federal trial of LaRouche,
six aides and five LaRouche political groups.
   Tate said LaRouche followers were treated as soliders and warned
repeatedly that falling short of daily quotas was ``the moral
equivalent of treason'' and would result in the immediate collapse
of Western civilization.
   Tate testified that LaRouche's top fund-raising operative, Will
Wirtz, said prospective donors should be told LaRouche prevented a
Soviet takeover, was the only Democratic presidential candidate not
under KGB influence and the only man on earth who could prevent
global economic disaster.
   The warnings were given in late 1983 and 1984, when LaRouche
followers were under stringent fund-raising quotas because of his
campaign and the pending move of organization headquarters from New
York to Leesburg, Va., Tate said.
   LaRouche, a candidate for the 1988 Democratic presidential
nomination, is charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand
jury investigation into allegations that his followers raised more
than $2 million through credit card and loan fraud.
   Four LaRouche organizations, including his two 1984 campaign
committees, are charged with fraud. Those organizations and a fifth
LaRouche group are charged in the alleged obstruction, as are the
six aides.
   Prosecutors, through Tate, are attempting to show that intense
pressure from LaRouche led followers to solicit loans by falsely
promising they would be repaid and by submitting unauthorized
charges to the credit card accounts of past donors to LaRouche
causes.
   LaRouche and defense lawyers have conceded some Boston
fund-raisers might have committed credit card fraud but contend
LaRouche and top aides relieved those fund-raisers of their duties
when allegations of impropriety surfaced.
   LaRouche contends the allegations of nationwide fraud were
concocted as part of a Reagan administration plot to ruin him
because he opposed Contra aid and because his fund-raising competed
with former White House aide Oliver North's private effort to
resupply the Nicaraguan rebels at a time when Congress had halted
government aid.
   The 125-count indictment against LaRouche and the other
defendants, however, charges that three Boston fund-raisers were
ordered by LaRouche to destroy records and flee the country to
avoid being called before the grand jury. The three were indicted
but are fugitives.
</TEXT>
