<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ChemicalWeapons     03-25 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Weapons,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Warfare Threat Mounts In Gulf War</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slaughter of Kurdish civilians in
Iraqi poison gas attacks and Iranian warnings of retaliation
underscore the growth of the chemical warfare arsenals of major
Middle East powers.
   Despite efforts to curb such weapons, their spread has added a
dangerous new dimension to conflicts in the volatile Middle East.
Their use, but not their production, is banned under a 1925 Geneva
agreement.
   The London-based Jane's Defense Weekly noted in a recent study
that the use of poison and nerve gases since 1984 in the
7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war has ``changed the rules of war in the
Middle East.''
   Tehran charges that Iraqi warplanes have dropped chemical bombs
on several villages in northwestern Iraq after Iranian forces
overran the Kurdish area in a round offensive.
   Western correspondents in Iran have reported evidence to
substantiate Iranian claims that 5,000 Iraqi Kurds were killed and
another 5,000 injured when Iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs
on towns captured by the Iranians in northeast Iraq last week.
   Nicholas Beeston of The Times of London reported from Halabja,
one of the towns, that ``hundreds and possibly thousands'' of the
Kurds, who have been rebelling against Baghdad for years, were
killed.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of Iran's Parliament and Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's representative on the Supreme Defense Council,
warned Thursday that Iran will be forced to use chemical weapons in
retaliation if the Iraqi attacks continue.
   The intensity of Tehran's accusations against Iraq in recent
days has heightened fears that the Iranians may be seeking to
justify using chemical weapons of their own.
   U.S. State Department Spokesman Charles Redman said Wednesday
there was evidence Iran may already have fired chemical artillery
shells into Iraq. He declined to elaborate.
   ``It's entirely likely that the Iranians could do so,'' said Don
Kerr of the International Institute for Strategic Studies in London
in a telephone interview.
   ``They've had these weapons used against them for a long time.''
   Iraq, a signatory to the 1925 agreement, has been condemned by
the United Nation four times since 1984 for using chemical weapons.
   The Iranians claim the Iraqis have launched around 100 chemical
attacks in that period, mainly against Iranian troops.
   Iranian-backed Kurdish guerrillas fighting the Baghdad regime
for autonomy have claimed scores of such attacks on their villages
in the last year. But last week's bombing appears to have been the
worst chemical attack in the Persian Gulf conflict.
   Germ warfare dates back to the 14th Century, when the Tartars
catapulted the rotting corpses of plague victims into the besieged
Crimean city of Kaffa in a bid to spread disease.
   Modern chemical warfare began at on April 22, 1915, at 5 p.m.
when the Germans released 180 tons of chlorine gas at Ypres on the
Western Front in World War I.
   Within an hour, 5,000 French soldiers were dead or dying from
the wind-blown gas rolling a few fet above their trenches.
   By the end of the war, gas had killed 100,000 men and affected
more than 900,000 others. Modern nerve gases are far more lethal.
   Iraq has the biggest chemical weapons armory in the region, with
sizable stocks of poison and nerve gases produced at three
top-secret plants, Western military analysts told The Associated
Press.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymnity, said Iraq is
now producing Sarin, a highly lethal nerve gas that can kill in
less than 10 minutes.
   They said there are indications that the Iraqis are also working
on germ warfare weapons.
   The sources estimated that Iraq can now produce 60 tons of
mustard gas a month and four tons each of Sarin and Tabun, another
highly lethal nerve agent.
   Tabun, first developed by Nazi Germany before World War II but
never used, is a colorless gas that attacks the body's muscular
centers and causes asphyxiation within 15 minutes.
   The sources said the Iraqis' main production plant is at
Samarra, a heavily guarded 10-square-mile complex ringed by
Soviet-supplied Sa-2 anti-aircraft missiles 70 miles north of
Baghdad.
   On the other side, Iran's chief military spokesman, Kamal
Kharrazi, has said his country is producing chemical weapons.
   The analysts and diplomatic sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Iranian chemical weapons are believed to be mainly
mustard and phosgene gases.
   Kerr noted: ``These are relatively simple to manufacture from
readily available industrial components, as is hydrogen cyanide.
Only the more complex nerve gases are likely to pose a chemical
challenge to the Iranians.''
   The Syrians, Moscow's main Arab ally, also have developed their
own chemical weapons industry over the last few years, intelligence
and diplomatic sources said.
   The Israelis allege the Syrian chemical warfare capability is a
serious threat and say Syria has the means to deliver nerve agents
with Soviet-supplied SS-1 Scud-B missiles and combat aircraft.
</TEXT>
