<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WellRescue-Movie     03-25 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Well Rescue-Movie,0601</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two Rival Associations Fighting Over Movie Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 58 hours after a toddler tumbled into
an abandoned well, hundreds of rescuers worked together to free
her, but now an effort to bring their heroism to television has
divided them.
   Two groups _ one mostly volunteer rescuers and the other city
officials _ are negotiating separately with different TV producers
for a movie of the story that captured the nation's attention as it
unfolded live on television.
   Both groups are awaiting the endorsement of Chip and Cissy
McClure, whose 23-month-old daughter Jessica became stuck in a
22-foot-deep well for 58 hours in October.
   One volunteer rescuer, Bruce Peeler, said he is remaining
neutral in the dispute. But he said he wonders whether the story
could be told properly in any case.
   ``I am wondering if a unified group got together ... if a really
true, accurate picture of what took place could ever be put on the
screen,'' said Peeler, president of Midland's Airmaster Equipment
Corp., which contributed drilling materials for the rescue.
   The effort brought praise and a spotlight to Midland, an oil
town of 97,400 people in western Texas.
   ``It was a special event. There was so much effort, and everyone
had their own story. Maybe it should be kept special like that,''
he said Thursday.
   The Jessica McClure Rescuer's Association, a group of about 30
volunteers, is committed to a movie deal with Los Angeles producer
Larry Spivey, president of Highland Communications Group Inc. The
group has asked all rescuers to join them.
   The association's president, Kragg Robinson, said 33 members
have signed a contract that includes an initial $200,000, plus
future payments, to be divided among the membership.
   The other group, the McClure Rescue Association, has narrowed
its selection to an unidentified producer but has not signed any
commitments. The association, comprising 11 municipal officials
including Police Chief Richard Czech, Fire Chief James Roberts and
paramedic Robert O'Donnell, wants nothing to do with Spivey.
   ``We found that he was going around to individual members of our
association offering each member side deals that the others didn't
know about,'' said Martin Allday, a lawyer representing the group.
   Spivey says everyone was offered the same deal _ a chance to
consult in the production or to act in it.
   Either group or neither group could end up actually making a
film. Spivey still needs a commitment from a network for his
project.
   ``My advice to anyone is if they have not signed with the
producer to not do so until the McClures say who they want the
movie to be made by,'' said Allday.
   The McClures have said they don't want to profit by their
daughter's story, but do not want to stand in the way of the story
being told.
   Peeler said Thursday he is concerned that the group of municipal
workers will not allow others to help negotiate a movie deal.
   He said he and other neutral volunteers are working to bring the
groups together ``so that the same type of unity and spirit as
depicted last October can return.''
   ``I'm sad about this problem,'' he said. ``My concern is that
there were several hundred people out there and it is not right
that maybe the lady that brought us hamburgers at three in the
morning, or the guy who brought the sanitary privvies down _ how do
you say they should not be in the movie, too?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
