<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HHS-Travel     03-25 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-HHS-Travel,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Examining Travel Records Of Couple In HHS Positions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Health and Human Services is
trying to determine whether a couple employed by the agency and
earning more than $100,000 a year improperly billed it for more
than $3,600 in personal expenses.
   HHS spokesman Chuck Kline said Thursday that department general
counsel Ron Robertson is heading the ethics board inquiry, which is
not expected to take more than a few days.
   The review was started after a Washington newsletter _ the Child
Protection Report _ obtained copies of travel vouchers for Paget W.
and Terry A. Hinch under a Freedom of Information Act request.
   Paget Hinch is associate commissioner of the family youth
services bureau of HHS. Her husband, Terry, is director of the
Social Security office of communications technology. Both are
political appointees who began working at HHS in 1985.
   The newsletter said the couple flew to the San Francisco area,
near the Hayward, Calif., home of Terry Hinch's family for a
one-week stay over Thanksgiving 1985, apparently taking their child
with them.
   They billed the government a total of $2,224 for that trip.
Paget Hinch's voucher said her purpose was to visit shelters for
runaway youth in the area. Terry Hinch said he attended a
conference and met with a video company in connection with a film
on the government's disability insurance program.
   The newsletter said Paget Hinch charged the government $1,410
for a 1987 Thanksgiving trip to the same area.
   Neither of the two people under investigation could be reached.
Officials in the branches where they work said it would be
inappropriate for them to comment while the matter was under review.
   Paget Hinch is paid about $57,000 a year and her husband about
$55,000.
</TEXT>
