<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Robin Hood,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheriff Of Nottingham Orders Robin Hood Brochures Burned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOTTINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brochures besmirching the legend of
Robin Hood were ordered publicly burned by an unlikely defender of
the medieval hero, the sheriff of Nottingham.
   Sheriff Royce Young told councilman Brian Marshal, chairman of
the city's tourism committee, to get rid of the glossy color
leaflets that took a skeptical view of the hero of Sherwood Forest.
   A pile of the brochures, which had been on display at the
Nottingham Information Center, were burned publicly on Thursday.
   Royce, whose medieval predecessor was Robin's enemy, said
earlier this month that he would like to see the researchers who
wrote it ``locked in the dungeons of Nottingham Castle.''
   The brochure caused a storm by claiming Robin Hood and Maid
Marian never met, Friar Tuck did not exist and Robin never robbed
the rich to feed the poor but was a highwayman in business for
himself.
</TEXT>
