<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Streets     03-25 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Streets,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguans Hopeful, But Skeptical, Cease-Fire Will Bring Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Nicaragua, Bjt
^By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of two soldiers was
relieved, a shoe store owner was hopeful and opposition leaders
welcomed the Contra-Sandinista cease-fire agreement, but all were
skeptical about whether it will bring peace.
   ``Every mother, even though she doesn't have sons in service,
should be happy about peace,'' said Auxiliadora del Carmen Acevedo,
whose two sons had been drafted into the army. ``Nicaraguans must
not continue dying.''
   ``We urgently need peace in Nicaragua,'' said Mrs. del Carmen
Acevedo, who sells cosmetics in the Roberto Huembes market. ``All
these eight years have been ones of horror.''
   More than 40,000 people have died since the fighting began in
November 1981, two years after the Sandinistas overthrew the
rightist regime of the late President Anastasio Somoza. The economy
is a shambles.
   Representatives of the leftist Sandinista government and Contra
rebels signed a 60-day cease-fire agreement Wednesday night that
promises the Contras a role in Nicaragua's political process.
   Talks beginning April 6 in Managua will seek a permanent peace.
   Alonso Moreno, a 57-year-old shoe store owner, said he hoped the
accord ``improves the economy and business and that everyone
dedicates themselves to producing to put this country back on its
feet.''
   ``This is the most important thing that has happened since 1979
when the Somoza dictatorship was overthrown,'' said Moreno, who has
three nephews in military service.
   ``I believe that those who are most happy with these announced
measures are the thousands of mothers who have sons in the war, the
thousands of prisoners in the country and thousands of exiled
Nicaraguans,'' said Ramiro Gurdian, an opposition leader and
president of the Nicaraguan Agricultural and Livestock Producers'
Union.
   But Gurdian said it should not create false hopes.
   ``The people should not believe that the problem is totally
resolved,'' he said. ``It's not that way. I would like to see in
the short term an adequate solution to the political-military
problem to bring the economy out of bankruptcy.''
   ``One hopes this will occur before May, when land is prepared
for next year's crops _ 87 percent of the country's exports come
from agriculture,'' he added.
   The war and a U.S. trade embargo have cost the country $3.8
billion in lost income, according to government figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
