<DOCNO> AP880325-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0350EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WarsawGhetto     03-25 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warsaw Ghetto,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warsaw Ghetto Uprising Commander To Shun Official Ceremonies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last surviving commander of the Warsaw
Ghetto Uprising said he was not invited and had no plans to take
part in government observances marking the 45th anniversary of the
Jewish anti-Nazi revolt.
   Dr. Marek Edelman, 66, a former commander of the Jewish
fighters, said Thursday he will organize a ceremony at Warsaw's
Jewish cemetery April 17 to dedicate a monument to two Polish
Jewish socialist leaders executed by the Soviets during World War
II.
   Edelman, a staunch supporter of the outlawed Solidarity free
trade union, said he has invited Lane Kirkland, chairman of the
AFL-CIO, and Western Europe leaders.
   Several thousand Jews from the United States, Israel and other
countries are expected to come for the weeklong official
observances that culminate April 19 with a ceremony at the Warsaw
monument to heroes of the uprising.
   Edelman said he was not invited to attend the official
celebrations.
   ``They didn't invite me, but I wouldn't have taken part in it
anyway,'' said Edelman, a cardiologist in the central city of Lodz.
   ``I have never taken part in it because I think this government,
which is a totalitarian government, has no right to act in such
matters,'' Edelman said in a telephone interview.
   He had refused an invitation from authorities to participate in
the April 1983 observances of the 40th anniversary of the uprising.
   In the uprising, several hundred poorly armed Jewish fighters
fought a desperate battle resisting the final Nazi drive to
liquidate the ghetto's 60,000 remaining Jews. About 360,000 Jews
had already been deported from the ghetto to Nazi death camps.
   This year, Edelman has invited Poles and foreign guests to join
him at the ceremony at the Jewish cemetery. He said Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa was expected to attend.
   Edelman plans to unveil a stone monument honoring Henryk Erlich
and Wiktor Alter, two leaders of the Bund, a Jewish socialist labor
organization in Poland, who were sentenced to death and executed in
the Soviet Union in December 1941.
   ``It is important for me personally because I was connected with
those people,'' said Edelman, who as a leader of the Bund's youth
organization in the Warsaw ghetto was given a command post in the
uprising led by Mordechai Anielewicz.
   Edelman escaped through the sewers when the Nazis finally
crushed the uprising.
   In addition to Kirkland, Edelman says he has invited members of
the Socialist International including its chairman, former West
German chancellor Willy Brandt, and officials of the European
Parliament.
   Edelman said the invitations were sent a week ago and he had not
yet received any responses.
   In his letter to Kirkland, Edelman recalled that U.S. labor
leaders had unsuccessfully intervened with Soviet authorities to
seek the release of the two Bund leaders.
   ``Your presence shall be an expression of solidarity with all
unionists and workers fighting for their rights and freedom,''
Edelman wrote to Kirkland.
   Edelman invited the Socialist International members to show by
their presence that ``the struggle for freedom, equality and
brotherhood has not ceased, that you solidarize with all those who
are repressed, and that this remains the superior ideal of
socialism.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
