<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0446 03-25 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0446,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Down In Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with closing prices, Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `The dollar ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed slightly lower against the
Japanese yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market Friday, while
stock prices also fell during the day's trading.
   After opening at 125.68 yen, down 0.62 yen from its close
Thursday, the dollar edged up marginally in midday trading before
closing the week at 125.74 yen, down 0.56 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 113.95-point loser Thursday, closed at 25,626.71
points, down 154.57 points, or 0.59 percent.
   The dollar declined after the overnight setback in New York.
   ``Profit-taking dollar buying stopped the dollar from falling
further,'' said an official of a major commercial bank, who spoke
on the condition of anonymity.
   There were also reports the Bank of Japan bought an estimated
$200-300 million to prop up the sagging currency.
   Commenting on stock exchange dealings, Tadaaki Uehara of Wako
Securities said ``the decline mirrors setbacks of both the dollar
and stock markets overseas.''
   He said, however, trends on the overseas markets did little to
affect Tokyo as investors remained confident about the condition of
the Tokyo market.
   On Wall Street Thursday, the Dow Jones Industrial Stock Average
lost 43.77 points, closing at 2,023.87.
   Institutional investors were sidestepping the market to watch
for movements, Uehara said.
   Tokyo shares on the first section plunged over 250 points early
in the session as the dollar's declined below the 126 yen-level and
following sharp losses in New York stock trading overnight.
   Trading volume on the first section at the close of the morning
was estimated at a light 370 million shares.
</TEXT>
