<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirt Hospitalized,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trumpeter Al Hirt Hospitalized For Hand And Arm Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpeter Al Hirt missed a charity concert after
being hospitalized with an infection in his playing hand, but
doctors said his prognosis was excellent.
   ``I'm OK,'' Hirt said Thursday. ``I had this infection or
something in my hand. It's like blood poisoning. It looks like it's
from a bite or something. It's all swollen and has red streaks.''
   Hirt, 65, flew from his home in New Orleans Thursday and was
admitted to Houston Methodist Hospital after consulting with his
longtime friend, famed heart surgeon Michael DeBakey.
   Doctors said the infection spread throughout his right hand and
arm. Hirt was being given antibiotics intravenously.
   Hirt said doctors think the problem may be related to his
trumpet playing and a growth that has developed on one of the
fingers of his right hand.
   ``I've never had anything like this before in my life,'' he
said. ``I've been playing for 59 years and I want to keep playing
... I'm going to be OK as long as I can keep blowing the trumpet.''
   Hirt missed a charity concert Thurday night to benefit New
Orleans' symphony. He also said he would miss a weekend appearance
in Fairfield, Conn.
</TEXT>
