<HEAD>Robertson Folds Colorado Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Americans for Robertson campaign has folded in
Colorado just when the organization's telephone bank was beginning
to build momentum for the April 4 precinct caucuses, says one of
the candidate's supporters.
   Former campaign coordinator Clarence ``Arch'' Decker said
Thursday the directive to close the operation came more than a week
ago from Robertson officials in Chesapeake, Va.
   Decker said the order surprised him, adding: ``We were on a
course to take more than half the caucuses in the state.''
   He said the action was ``probably a decision that Colorado
doesn't rank high on the priority scale. We had a bank account, but
they ordered it closed and directed that the records be sent to
them.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush Avoids Media Coverage Of Husband's Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush says she shuns watching
television coverage of the presidential campaign so she can avoid
the criticism her husband, Vice President George Bush, attracts as
a candidate.
   ``I don't watch it on television; I don't read about it,'' Mrs.
Bush said. ``In order to be able to survive what a campaign does to
you, you have to sometimes stick your head in the sand like an
ostrich and block it out.''
   Mrs. Bush, campaigning Wednesday in Cincinnati, said she spends
her spare time on the campaign trail reading novels or watching
movies. Mrs. Bush said she reads ``about a book a day, more than
I've ever read in my life.''
</TEXT>
