<TEXT>
   Former Federal Reserve Board Chairman Paul
Volcker says candidates don't seem to be ``running against
Washington'' in this year's presidential race and he wants it to
stay that way.
   Volcker, testifying Thursday before a House subcommittee in his
capacity as chairman of the National Commission on the Public
Service, said candidates should avoid ``the Washington bashing
syndrome.''
   ``We're never very far from the telephone,'' Volcker said. ``We
will try to keep after those candidates. ... We will urge them to
stay on the high road.''
