<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Burns-Cyclosporine     03-25 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burns-Cyclosporine,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyclosporine Used in Cadaver Skin Grafts on Burn Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A potent anti-rejection drug can safely be
administered orally to severe burn patients, and appears to help
skin grafts from cadavers last longer, says a leading burn
specialist.
   ``I think it's a good first step, but it needs a lot more
work,'' Dr. A. Richard Grossman, who used the immunosuppressant
drug cyclosporine on 13 patients, said in an interview Thursday.
   Grossman, a plastic surgeon and director of the Southern
California Burn Center at Sherman Oaks Community Hospital in Los
Angeles, was to report his findings today at the American Burn
Association's annual meeting here.
   Cyclosporine has been used in injection and oral form to prevent
rejection by the body's immune system of newly transplanted hearts
and other organs.
   Grossman said his work over the past year and a half showed that
oral doses of the drug are also safe for skin transplants.
   He said it also appears that cyclosporine enables cadaver skin
to ``take'' to the body's skin longer, reducing the need for
several expensive cadaver skin grafts and providing a more
attractive appearance than laboratory-grown skin.
   Without cyclosporine, cadaver skin is rejected within a week to
10 days, he said. Cadaver skin is mainly used to buy time for a few
weeks until the patient has enough skin of his or her own to be
transplanted. Repeated cadaver skin grafts are made until that time.
   Dr. David Herndon, chief of staff at the Shriners Burn Institute
in Galveston, Texas, has not seen Grossman's study, but said the
prolongation effect appears to represent ``tremendous potential.''
   Grossman said more studies comparing cadaver skin transplants
with and without the drug need to be done.
   Grossman is not the first burn specialist to use cyclosporine on
severe burn patients. Dr. Bruce Achauer of the University of
California at Irvine used injections of the drug with poor results,
and later used an oral dose on one patient, who survived, Grossman
said.
   Grossman said he decided to try lower, oral doses.
   Because of concern over kidney failure in burn patients, the
Grossman study on nine patients referred to in his paper and on
four subsequent patients used increasingly lower doses.
   ``Our original purpose was to let the cadaver skin stay on a
while until we could reharvest the patient's own skin,'' Grossman
said. ``But we found after about three or four weeks that it was
staying on for good.''
   The first patient in the study was kept on cyclosporine for two
months after his discharge from the hospital, Grossman said. ``But
with each successive patient we found they needed less and less''
cyclosporine.
   With the last patients in the study, the medication was
discontinued before discharge, within six weeks of the injury.
   ``I don't believe that using cadaver skin with a possibly
dangerous drug is the be-all and end-all,'' Grossman said. ``I
think we're plugging a dike until the right thing comes along.''
That, he said, would be improvements in the use of laboratory-grown
skin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0035 </DOCNO>
