<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RestaurantInspectors     03-25 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Restaurant Inspectors,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Inspections Halted Following Allegations of Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corrupt city health inspectors doubled and
tripled their annual salaries by extorting hundreds of thousands of
dollars from restaurants, federal officials said after the arrest
of more than two dozen employees.
   ``The restaurant owners would dread seeing these inspectors pull
up in their Cadillacs and Rolex watches,'' said James Fox,
assistant director in charge of the FBI's New York office. ``They
turned the Department of Health into their own Department of
Wealth.''
   City health-code inspections of restaurants will be temporarily
suspended while the Department of Health reorganizes.
   ``The revelations of widespread and longstanding corruption
among restaurant inspectors are particularly repellent and painful
because of the importance'' of public health, Health Commissioner
Stephen Joseph said.
   Twenty-eight people, including health inspectors, their
supervisors and former Health Department employees who acted as
middlemen, were charged Thursday with extorting money from
restaurateurs. The Health Department employees earned annual
salaries of $25,000 to $30,000.
   If convicted, each could face a maximum penalty of 20 years in
jail and a fine of $250,000.
   The charges contained in the complaint represent about one-third
of the employees responsible for enforcing the city's health code,
U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney said.
   Inspectors allegedly secured the extortion money by threatening
to cite restaurants for health-code violations.
   About 300 of the city's 15,000 restaurants were victimized,
ranging from fast-food establishments to little ethnic places to
some tony Manhattan spots. A chart released by the FBI showed that
the restaurants were in all five boroughs, with the largest
concentration on Manhattan's Upper East Side.
   The names of the restaurants were withheld because the owners
are considered victims and because the information could hinder a
grand jury investigation, Maloney said.
   The city's Department of Investigations and the FBI combined
separate investigations, dubbed ``Kitchen Net'' and ``Operation
Sanisweep'' respectively, in 1986. They used a combination of
confidential informants, undercover agents and physical and
electronic surveillance.
   Fox said if a restaurant owner refused to give an inspector a
payoff during a regular inspection, the inspector would claim to
find mouse droppings or dead flies in the restaurant and threaten
to issue violations or, in some cases, close the restaurant.
   In one case, on-site inspectors demanded $1,400 from a
restaurant owner to prevent the establishment from being closed for
serious health violations, authorities said. In another, inspectors
charged a Queens restaurant $1,200 to allow it to reopen despite
serious code violations.
   A confidential informant told authorities that he and another
inspector made up to six stops a day and collected $500 to $1,000
in payoffs from owners at each restaurant, according to Fox.
   The extortion payoffs were shared with inspectors' supervisors,
authorities said. One senior inspector was called ``Hungry Joe'' by
his fellow inspectors because he made so many demands.
   In addition, he said, former Health Department inspectors and
others established ``consulting'' companies that would advise
restaurants on how to pass inspections and would act as middlemen
for the extortions.
   Supervisors allegedly would recommend these consulting services
to restaurants and then take a percentage of the consultation fee,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0036 </DOCNO>
