<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InvestorPlea     03-25 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Investor Plea,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Whiz Kid Pleads in Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before his arrest on fraud charges, a
high-living 23-year-old investment adviser lured customers by
falsely telling them that his other clients included the
Rockefeller family and Bill Cosby, authorities say.
   Those allegations were contained in criminal charges against
David Bloom filed Thursday in U.S. District Court. Bloom is
expected to plead guilty at a court appearance next week, according
to his lawyer, Peter Morrison.
   Bloom, who was not licensed as an investment adviser, allegedly
lied to clients by telling them their funds were invested in the
stock market when he was actually pouring the money _ more than $10
million worth _ into private purchases.
   Among his purchases were works of art totaling $5.5 million; an
$830,000 Manhattan apartment; a beach house in East Hampton worth
$1.9 million; two cars _ an Aston-Martin convertible and a
Mercedes-Benz _ worth $200,000; and home furnishings that cost
$800,000.
   Bloom also bought ``numerous items of expensive jewelry; and
deluxe trips to Europe and the Caribbean for himself, his family
and friends,'' according to the federal charges of mail fraud and
securities fraud.
   The charges say that Bloom ``falsely told investors that he
managed money for prominent individuals and investors, including
the Rockefeller family, the Sultan of Brunei (and) Bill Cosby.''
   In a brief appearance before U.S. Magistrate Barbara Lee, Bloom
waived his right to have his case heard by a grand jury. After he
entered a plea of innocent, Ms. Lee assigned the case to U.S.
District Judge David Edelstein.
   Bloom apparently was ready to plead guilty before Edelstein, but
the judge was unavailable and the case was scheduled for next
Thursday.
   If found guilty of the two charges against him, Bloom faces a
maximum sentence of five years in prison on each count and a
maximum fine of twice the amount lost by investors.
   Bloom was arrested Jan. 14 on a federal complaint charging him
with fraud. He had begun investing money for friends while at Duke
University and had 130 clients at his Greater Sutton Investors
Group Inc. in Manhattan at the time of his arrest.
   Morrison has said many of the items Bloom purchased would be
sold and his clients could recover their money and a profit. The
assets were turned over to a court-appointed receiver.
</TEXT>
