<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-25 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Witness Says He Gave $30,000 to D'Amato Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. executive says the
scandal-plagued defense contractor contributed to numerous
political campaigns, not because of ideology but ``for favors we
expected to get.''
   Former Wedtech vice chairman Mario Moreno also testified
Thursday that he gave under different names, about $30,000 to Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., to evade election law contribution limits.
   Federal election law limits individual campaign contributions to
$1,000 per election and bars corporate contributions.
   A D'Amato spokesman branded Moreno's testimony ``ridiculous.''
   Moreno's claims came during defense cross-examination at the
racketeering trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and six others.
   Prosecutors have said D'Amato will testify for the government.
   The prosecution contends Biaggi enlisted the help of D'Amato and
other politicians to help secure no-bid contracts for Wedtech, then
extorted millions of dollars in Wedtech stock as a payoff.
   He and his co-defendants are accused of turning Wedtech into a
racketeering enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in bribes
for government contracts and other favors.
   Moreno is among four former Wedtech executives cooperating with
the government in return for leniency on state and federal charges
to which they pleaded guilty.
   Defense attorney Maurice Nessen got Moreno, who was on the
witness stand for the eighth day Thursday, to admit he and other
Wedtech executives contributed to D'Amato and other public
officials who have not been charged with wrongdoing.
   ``Now D'Amato, Sen. D'Amato. There were contributions to his
campaign that you in fact hid and put under different names so you
could violate the limits on campaign contributions. Isn't that
correct,'' Nessen asked.
   `Yes,'' said Moreno.
   When Nessen asked Moreno if he had given D'Amato close to
$30,000, the witness said it might have been more than that.
   ``And all the while, the senator from New York was helping you
get contracts with the government?'' Nessen asked later.
   ``Yes,'' said Moreno, later saying that D'Amato ``was one of the
most important people'' in helping Wedtech secure a
multimillion-dollar Navy contract without competitive bidding.
   Ed Martin, the D'Amato spokesman in Washington, said, ``We have
no knowledge of any secret contributions.''
   He said prosecutors told D'Amato staffers there was ``a lot of
false name-dropping going on'' at the trial. ``This is an example.''
   Moreno said he and Wedtech officials contributed to the
campaigns of Mayor Edward I. Koch, Gov. Mario Cuomo, city
Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin and state Sen. John Marchi, none of
whom has been charged with wrongdoing.
   He said contributions were made to the Democratic, Republican
and Conservative parties, not because of political ideology but
``in exchange for favors we expected to get.''
   Asked what favors Wedtech expected from the Republican state
committee, Moreno said, ``We expected to get the Republican Party
in our pocket.''
   ``By giving a check for $2,500?'' Nessen asked incredulously.
   ``By giving a lot of checks,'' Moreno said without elaborating.
   ``What he refers to, I have no idea,'' Ed Lurie, executive
director of the GOP state committee, said in a telephone interview
from his Albany office.
   ``If their (Wedtech officials') purpose was to get some sort of
hook into us, God, we didn't know it,'' Lurie said. ``I didn't know
certain people gave to us until I saw it in the newspapers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
