<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-25 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM, Government Differ On How To Fix Emission Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. is being ordered to
recall nearly 500,000 1985 vehicles for failure to meet federal air
pollution standards, but the automaker and the government are at
odds over how to fix the problem.
   The Environmental Protection Agency, which announced the recall
order Thursday, said a faulty thermal vacuum switch was part of the
reason the vehicles' exhaust contains excess carbon monoxide and
evaporated gasoline.
   GM spokeswoman Jane Mott said the automaker told the EPA it
believed replacing the switch on the vehicles would be sufficient
to bring emissions into compliance with federal standards.
   The EPA, however, said its tests showed that ``replacement of
the (switch) alone will not completely remedy the problem and that
additional repairs may be necessary.''
   GM has 45 days either to request a public hearing to contest the
order, or to submit a repair plan for EPA's approval before notices
are mailed to owners.
   The vehicles affected by the recall are equipped with 5.0 liter
(305 cubic inches) and 5.7 liter (350 cubic inches) engines, the
EPA said.
   They were sold as the Chevrolet Impala, Caprice Classic, Camaro,
Monte Carlo and El Camino; the Pontiac Firebird, Bonneville, Grand
Prix and Parisienne; and the GMC Caballero, EPA said. Models sold
in California, which are built to stricter standards, are also
included.
</TEXT>
