<HEAD>400,000 Americans Expected To Get Cholesterol Tests May 4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 400,000 Americans are expected to
participate in a May 4 national program offering blood cholesterol
tests.
   Hundreds of hospitals will offer free tests, while a few will
charge $3.
   The program, organized by the Voluntary Hospitals of America,
was outlined Thursday at a news conference. Officials said they
were announcing the national program well in advance to give people
plenty of time to learn where they can go for testing for the fatty
substance that is a leading contributor to heart disease and
strokes.
   About 400 not-for-profit hospitals that are members of the
association have agreed to participate. A public service television
spot promoting the program, called ``CountDown USA,'' will begin
airing next week.
   It includes a toll-free telephone number _ 800-634-9541 _ for
people to call weekdays from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. (EST) to find out
which hospitals in their areas will offer the testing.
