<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     03-25 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Honor Slain Bishop; Alleged Conspirator Defends Election
Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people marched in
memory of a slain archbishop while the man accused of ordering the
clergyman's assassination defended his far-rightist party's
nationwide election victory.
   About 10,000 people joined in Thursday's march, which was called
by student, labor, rights and church groups on the eighth
anniversary of Monsignor Oscar Romero's death. The bishop was shot
through the heart by a sniper as he celebrated Mass at a chapel in
San Salvador.
   The marchers carried flowers, large portraits of the
bespectacled bishop and banners saying ``Monsignor Romero did not
die in vain.'' They chanted calls for the prosecution an punishment
of those responsible.
   In the weeks prior to his assassination, Romero called on
members of the security forces to disobey orders to torture, kidnap
and murder their countrymen.
   The late 1970s and early 1980s were a time of intense activity
of Salvadoran death squads. In 1980, when Romero was killed, the
squads of soldiers, police and extremist anti-leftist civilians
were blamed for killing more than 500 suspected leftists a month.
   No one was indicted in Romero's slaying, but President Jose
Napoleon Duarte late last year publicly accused Roberto
d'Aubuisson, a right-wing legislator and former army major, of
masterminding the slaying.
   ``The case is solved. We know who did it, who ordered it, who
drove the getaway car,'' Duarte told the country on nationwide
television in November.
   He accused d'Aubuisson of issuing the order, and said testimony
from the driver of the killer's car backed up his claim.
   D'Aubuisson, the founder and a legislator for the far-rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, denies the charge. He
says it is politically motivated slander.
   Duarte's government has asked the United States for extradition
of a Salvadoran army captain, Alvaro Saravia, who allegedly hired
the sniper. Saravia, arrested for a traffic violation, is in jail
in Miami pending resolution of the extradition request.
   Local authorities say it could be granted in the coming months.
   But whether the case will ever reach court is not clear. As a
legislator, d'Aubuisson enjoys broad immunity from prosecution. His
party was the big victor in Sunday's elections for all 60 members
of the unicameral National Assembly and municipal officials across
this nation of 5 million.
   It is unlikely an Assembly controlled by d'Aubuisson's party
would strip him of immunity to allow him to stand trial as an
alleged conspiritor in Romero's assassination.
   Early returns indicated Arena would hold an outright majority in
the Assembly and most town and city posts nationwide.
   But on Wednesday, Arena leaders charged the governing Christian
Democrats with manipulating returns in an effort ``to steal'' the
right's parliamentary majority. D'Aubuisson and other Arena chiefs
said violence could erupt if the vote count was flawed.
   The Christian Democrats, who had 33 seats in the outgoing
Assembly but are expected to have fewer than 25 in the new one,
deny the charge.
   Arena had 13 seats in the old legislature.
   Talking with reporters Thursday, D'Aubuisson was calmer than the
previous day. But he insisted his party would not permit maneuvers
to erode its electoral result.
   ``The people's will cannot be subverted,'' he said. ``By
tomorrow (Friday) afternoon we believe the Central Elections
Council will be in a position to announce definitive official
results that will confirm the triumph of our party.''
   But there was no promise from the Council that final results
would be ready today.
   Council president Mario Samayoa told reporters: ``We will take
as long as is necessary to make sure the electoral law is
fulfilled, whether certain parties or individuals like it or not.''
</TEXT>
