<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0548EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     03-25 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Nuclear Activist Alleges Security Forces Tortured Him, Killed
Companion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old anti-nuclear activist
charged today he was tortured for two days at the headquarters of
President Corazon Aquino's security force and his companion was
murdered.
   A spokesman for Mrs. Aquino said he was unaware of the
allegations. Military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa said he
was willing to have authorities investigate the charge.
   Hilario Bustamante recounted his ordeal to reporters who
interviewed him at a government hospital. He was recovering from a
deep wound in the back of his neck doctors said must have been
inflicted with a machete or an ax.
   The injury was similar to that which killed Bustamante's
companion, Rey Francisco, whose body was found by police Monday
night in a field on the outskirts of the capital. The field is near
where a private security guard found Bustamante's near-dead body
hours earlier.
   Speaking in a low voice and unable to move his body, Bustamante
said an unidentified woman was also hacked that same night. Police
have not reported finding any female body in the field.
   Bustamante said he, Francisco and five other members of the
leftist Youth for Democracy and Nationalism were pasting up posters
against nuclear arms and U.S. military bases Saturday when about
six armed men in a jeep chased them.
   He said the men, in civilian clothes, claimed they were police
``authorized by Malacanang (presidential palace)'' to arrest the
youths. The men caught Bustamante and Francisco a few blocks away,
but the others escaped.
   Bustamante claimed he and Francisco were taken to a military
compound behind the presidential palace, where he said they where
they were handcuffed, blindfolded, interrogated and tortured.
   The compound houses the headquarters of the Presidential
Security Group.
   ``They wanted us to admit we were members of the Sparrow Unit,
that we were NPA,'' Bustamante said, referring to the communist New
People's Army and its assassination unit. ``They kept asking us
whether we killed such and such policeman or soldier.''
   ``They beat us with iron rods and burned us with cigarettes,''
he said.
   Late Monday, Bustamente said three men drove him, Francisco and
the woman to the field and hacked them.
   Deputy presidential spokesman Danilo Gozo said he was unaware of
Bustamante's charges.
   ``We will ask the Presidential Security Group, but it sounds
odd,'' Gozo said. ``We will have to check if it is a fact.''
   De Villa called on Bustamante to provide evidence to back up his
charge.
   ``I'm willing to have all these kinds of incidents
investigated,'' he told reporters. ``We do not tolerate, we do not
condone the use of torture. We are willing to subject our people to
genuine investigation.''
   Earlier this month, Amnesty International charged in a report
released in London that the Philippine military was using torture
and murder to fight the 19-year communist insurgency. Mrs. Aquino
called the report one-sided.
</TEXT>
