<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0899 03-25 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0899,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`The Gospel at Colonus,' A Musical, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs with other critics; no PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When ``The Gospel at Colonus'' sings, it soars,
raising the roof of Broadway's cavernous Lunt-Fontanne Theater and
the spirits of everyone within shouting distance.
   There isn't a more joyous expression of song on Broadway, and
that may be enough for some people. It's when the production stops
to tell its tale that the show sags, marking time until the next
musical explosion.
   This overlong gospel celebration, which opened Thursday, offers
a sketchy and an often confusing version of Sophocles' ``Oedipus at
Colonus,'' set within the framework of a rousing black Pentecostal
church service. What little is left of the Greek tragedy in Lee
Breuer's adaptation is overwhelmed by religious fervor.
   Oedipus, in this version, comes to Colonus seeking redemption
but is rejected at first by its citizens. When his prayers for
forgiveness are heard by Theseus, king of Athens, Oedipus and his
two daughters Antigone and Ismene are welcomed back to the holy
city.
   The daughters are seized by Creon, king of Thebes, but then
released after the intercession of Theseus. Oedipus then prepares
for a happy death.
   Breuer, according to program notes, sees the show as a sermon or
series of parables on fate, and much of the story is delivered
between songs by a minister, played by Morgan Freeman. He's a
commanding figure on stage but must muddle through the rudimentary
narrative that rarely clarifies its characters.
   The real passion comes from the singers, many of them gospel
music veterans, led by Clarence Fountain and the Five Blind Boys of
Alabama. They all sing different facets of the role of Oedipus.
   Fountain has an ingratiating, swivel-hipped stage presence, a
booming voice and sass to spare. He gets ample support from several
other soloists and gospel groups including Jevetta Steele and the
J.D. Steele Singers and J.J. Farley and the Soul Stirrers.
   The entire production is backed up by the Institutional Radio
Choir, a Brooklyn-based church group. Its 30 members, dressed in
colorful African robes, sit on bleachers that climb high above the
stage. Large Greek columns, designed by Alison Yerxa, rise behind
them.
   The choir shouts its affirmation to much of Freeman's preaching,
and their enthusiasm is infectious. The choir is the focal point of
the evening's two show-stopping numbers _ ``No Never,'' a rousing
hymn of welcome, and ``Lift Him Up,'' a song of redemption after
Oedipus has gone peacefully to his death.
   The music by Bob Telson is melodic, just right for hand-clapping
and toe-tapping, while Breuer's lyrics are simple without being
simplistic.
   Breuer also directed the musical, and he could have trimmed the
show without diluting its impact. As it stands, ``The Gospel at
Colonus'' is often a long wait between the hosannas.
   In other reviews:
   ``This is a show that never stops advertising its
high-mindedness, whether in its program notes or on stage,'' writes
Frank Rich in The New York Times.
   ``But happily, there is the music, too, and it is so rousing ...
that the considerable spoken text ... can never completely upstage
it. ... Even a cynic may feel that the tidal wave of music is
lifting him to some higher, ecstatic plane.''
   In the Daily News, Don Nelson called the conception ``innovative
and brilliant,'' although the show itself ``seemed somewhat longer
than it should be ...''
   But, he said, ``the power of this production cannot be denied.
There is no Broadway musical _ none _ that attains the rarefied
heights that `Gospel' does at its best.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
