<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Iditarod     03-25 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iditarod,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Englishwoman Is Last In Alaska's Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leslie Anne Monk of England won the
less-than-coveted ``Red Lantern'' award, finishing last in the
Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race and eight days after winner Susan
Butcher.
   The rookie musher crossed the finish line in the 1,150-mile
Anchorage-to-Nome race at 10:22 p.m. Thursday, in 45th place at 19
days, 13 hours, 22 minutes and 55 seconds. Fifty-two teams started
the 16th annual Iditarod on March 5.
   Butcher crossed the finish line on March 16 to claim her third
straight Iditarod victory.
   Monk said she walked 11 of the last 22 miles until a lead dog
that had run in a previous Iditarod recognized the trail and got
the other six moving again.
   The Iditarod, named after an old supply route to the gold mining
districts of interior Alaska, draws its inspiration from a 1925
relay of diphtheria serum to Nome, which was hit hard by an
outbreak of the disease.
</TEXT>
