<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EctopicPregnancy     03-25 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ectopic Pregnancy,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Identify Problems That Lead To Dangerous Pregnancies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who let sexually transmitted diseases go
untreated run the risk of dangerous pregnancies, researchers say.
   Medical investigators at the national Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta explored 22 possible problems they thought might
lead to ectopic or tubal pregnancies, in which the fetus develops
outside the womb.
   Their study is reported in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   Ectopic pregnancies occur tens of thousands of times annually,
and account for 10 percent of all U.S. maternal deaths and are a
major cause of infertility, the researchers said.
   They examined 274 cases of ectopic pregnancy diagnosed from 1935
to 1982 in Rochester, Minn., and compared the cases with 548
live-birth deliveries during the same period among similar women.
   One of four problems researchers identified more often among
women with ectopic pregnancies was previous pelvic inflammatory
disease, an infection of the upper genital tract that can result
from untreated diseases of the lower tract.
   The study's lead authors, Polly A. Marchbanks of the CDC, said a
history of venereal disease alone does not appear to increase
ectopic pregnancy risk, but appears to increase risk if it advances
to the upper genital tract.
   That means women have another good reason to seek medical help
if they think they have a sexually transmitted disease, she said.
   Other problems in women with ectopic pregnancies were previous
infertility for at least one year and having undergone reproductive
surgery of the Fallopian tubes, the researchers said.
   And they found a strong association between conception while
using an intrauterine birth control device and ectopic pregnancies.
Women who had an ectopic pregnancy were 13.7 times more likely to
have been using IUDs at the time of conception than women in the
comparison group, the study said.
   A CDC researcher not involved in the study, Dr. Nancy Lee, said
that figure is inaccurate because it compares two groups that
shouldn't be compared: women using birth control and women using no
birth control.
   In an ectopic pregnancy, the fertilized egg lodges somewhere in
the abdomen besides the womb. In 97 percent of cases, the site is
in the Fallopian tubes, where as the fetus enlarges, it can rupture
the tubes or cause severe bleeding.
   Though ectopic pregnancy is dangerous, it can now be detected
early and the pregnancy ended surgically before damage makes a
woman infertile, wrote Dr. Robert N. Taylor, in an editorial
accompanying the study.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BreakawayBases     03-25 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Breakaway Bases,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Softball Players Would Get Hurt Less if Breakaway Bases Used</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Softball players would break considerably fewer
bones if breakaway bases replaced anchored bags on recreational
league diamonds, says a study published today.
   ``No system is foolproof, because poor technique can defeat a
lot of safety measures,'' Dr. David Janda, one of the study's four
authors, said Thursday. ``But this is one place where we can do
something almost immediately.''
   Breakway bags could reduce injuries by more than 90 percent,
according to the study published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   The study even contains some good news for baseball purists
worried that using breakaway bases would detract from the game's
tradition.
   ``We did not have a single problem about an out call from either
a player or an umpire in the more than 600 games we looked at,''
said Janda.
   ``Not only was there not one complaint, but we had a meeting of
managers after the season, and virtually everybody said we had to
have breakaway bases on the rest of the fields,'' he added.
   Janda, two colleagues from the orthopedic surgery section at the
University of Michigan at Ann Arbor, and a director of the city's
softball league gathered data from 633 softball games on diamonds
that used breakaway bases and 627 games on stationary-base fields.
   Stationary bases usually are anchored with a nut-and-bolt type
arrangement in a tube driven into the ground. A set of three
breakaway bases costs $295 vs. $150 for stationary bases.
   The breakaway bases used in the study had two parts: a rubber
plate mounted flush with the ground and a base secured on top with
suction and small rubber grommets that can pop loose.
   There were 45 sliding injuries, or about 7.2 per 100 games, on
the stationary-base fields compared to two, or about 0.3 per 100
games, on the breakaway field _ a ratio of nearly 23-to-1.
   Medical costs for the 45 injuries totaled more than $55,000.
   Dr. Jeffrey Sacks of the Atlanta-based federal Centers for
Disease Control, took the numbers from the study and extrapolated
them nationwide.
   ``If all games were played on stationary bases _ and we know
they're not _ we could expect 1.7 million sliding injuries and
medical costs over $2 billion,'' Sacks said.
   ``Put those same people on fields with breakaway bases and the
numbers are just over 70,000 injuries and $24 million in medical
costs,'' he said.
   Janda said his study revealed that most of the injuries resulted
from ``things like not knowing how to slide, poor conditioning,
late decision-making on when to slide, and even alcohol
consumption.''
   Janda, who described himself as ``a no-hit, no-field'' second
baseman, declined to say how frequently alcohol figured into the
equation.
   ``Nobody on our team drinks,'' he said, ``but we've played teams
where everybody does.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0048 </DOCNO>
