<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSKnowledge     03-25 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Knowledge,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Federal Surveys Find Increasing Public Knowledge About AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Americans are learning about the causes of
AIDS and discussing it with their kids, according to a new federal
report.
   The National Center for Health Statistics, which launched its
AIDS awareness interviews in August, reports that children are
getting more education about AIDS at school and at home.
   The most notable changes between the November survey results _
the latest available _ and those from one month earlier ``were in
the proportion of adults who reported having discussed AIDS with
their children and who stated that their children had received AIDS
education at school,'' the center reported.
   In November, 68 percent of those surveyed said they had
discussed AIDS with their children ages 10-17. That was up 5
percent from October, and up 8 percent from August, according to
the report, released Thursday by the center's parent agency, the
federal Centers for Disease Control.
   Also in November, 51 percent of the adults surveyed said their
kids had received AIDS instruction in school; that was up 6 percent
from October, and 15 percent from August.
   Throughout the surveys, about one-third of the adults questioned
did not know if their children had learned about acquired immune
deficiency syndrome in school.
   The center also reported that public awareness about AIDS
increased noticeably over the first four months of surveys.
   For example, in August, only 61 percent of the Americans
surveyed by the center believed it very unlikely or impossible to
get AIDS from shaking hands with a patient; in November, the
percentage had risen to 70.
   And only 53 percent of those surveyed in August believed it very
unlikely or impossible to get AIDS from working near someone who
has it; by November, it was up to 61 percent.
   AIDS experts say the disease is not spread through such casual
contact. AIDS, which had struck 57,024 Americans and killed 31,836
as of March 21, is spread most often through sex or shared drug
needles.
   The 3,333 adults questioned in November were not the same group
interviewed in previous months. The survey is designed with a
margin of error no more than 1 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0714EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OldComputers     03-25 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Old Computers,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Computers May Find New Life In Third World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new non-profit group is saving old
computers from the scrap heap and shipping them to Third World
countries.
   ``Equipment which is outdated here is often state-of-the-art in
Africa, Asia and Latin America,'' said Phillip Friedman, executive
director of Global Technology Foundation.
   The group based in Boulder hopes to improve the quality of life
in the Third World, create new markets for advanced equipment and
provide tax breaks for donors of old computers.
   It has filed for tax-exempt status with the Internal Revenue
Service so corporations would be able to claim the book value of
donated equipment, while individuals could deduct fair market
value, Friedman said.
   The Philippines is targeted for a pilot project because a
distribution system is already established there through another
non-profit group, he said.
   ``We will focus on sending equipment into communities, rather
than government bureaucracies,'' Friedman said.
   More than $80,000 in equipment already has been donated,
officials said.
</TEXT>
