<HEAD>23 Arrested in Sports Betting Operation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to fix typo in ``Queens.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 23 people in connection with a
mob-controlled betting operation that netted $75 million a year
from wagers on college basketball, a spokesman said.
   Authorities seized two satellite dishes, 33 telephones, four
shotguns, a stolen handgun, ammunition and $25,000 in cash while
making arrests Thursday night in Manhattan, the Bronx and Queens,
said police Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell.
   The betting ring was controlled by the Genovese crime family,
O'Donnell said. He said police were not sure how long it had been
in operation.
   All 23 people arrested were charged with promoting gambling,
possession of gambling records and possession of gambling devices,
all felonies, the spokesman said.
   The arrests and seizures followed a six-week investigation
involving city police and state police from New York and New
Jersey, O'Donnell said.
