<2ND_LINE>PM-Bodies Found,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Arrested in Family Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DICKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philadelphia teen-ager whose parents and
brothers were found slain in a bathtub was arrested by Tennessee
state troopers at a truck stop.
   Jose Enrique Hernandez, 17, was scheduled to appear today in a
detention and extradition hearing in Charlotte. Philadelphia police
were in Tennessee to escort him back to Pennsylvania to face four
counts of murder.
   Hernandez was arrested early Thursday at Reed's Truck Stop near
Interstate 40 after he had bought a cup of coffee.
   ``When he got out of the car, he looked real surprised to see
us. Then he looked like he made every attempt to act like he didn't
notice us. He kept his head down,'' Trooper Joel Deal said.
   Deal and Trooper Richard Austin checked the Honda's Pennsylvania
license plate number with the National Crime Information Center.
   ``It was kind of shocking,'' Deal said.
   The troopers found Hernandez was wanted in connection with the
deaths of his 4-year-old stepbrother, Frankie; 9-month-old
stepbrother, Jonathon; his father, Catalino Hernandez, 34; and
pregnant stepmother, Carmen Hernandez, 23.
   The bodies had been dead six days when Hernandez's aunt found
them in the family's apartment Monday. The bodies were stacked and
covered in a bathtub.
   Hernandez did not resist arrest and said nothing to the
troopers, Deal said. The youth slept as he was driven to the
Davidson County Juvenile Detention Center in Nashville.
   ``There was really no emotion from him at all,'' Deal said.
   Investigators searched the Honda for clues to the killings, but
nothing was found, Deal said.
   Officers have failed to find the .22-caliber handgun that killed
Hernandez's father and stepmother. Frankie was strangled with a
bandage and Jonathon was beaten to death with a blunt object,
possibly a baseball bat, police said.
   The killings followed an argument between Hernandez and his
father, police said.
