<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Movie,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director Defends Gang Movie Slammed By Cops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fears that a movie about Southern
California gangs might spark new violence when it is released next
month show how out of control the problem is, its director says.
   ``I live in a gang area. I live in Venice (Beach),'' Dennis
Hopper, director of ``Colors,'' said recently.
   The film, starring Robert Duvall and Sean Penn as policemen
fighting gang drug dealing and street crime, drew fire from real
law enforcement officers who were given a preview.
   The movie, scheduled for release in mid-April, features graphic
depictions of gang violence, including a gang drive-by shooting and
the killing of a police character by gang members.
   Several detectives said the film glamorizes the gang lifestyle
and could trigger violence among gang audiences. Assistant Police
Chief Robert Vernon suggested it be banned.
   Hopper, best known for his acting in such films as ``Easy
Rider,'' ``Apocalypse Now,'' ``Hoosiers,'' and ``Blue Velvet,''
said the official reaction shocked him.
   He said banning the movie would be ``like burning books ... And
they wanted to burn it before it could even be seen or read.''
   ``What they're basically saying is that they have a police
problem and they can't handle it,'' Hooper said. ``The gang thing
is out of control.''
   Hopper defended his use of real gang members as extras and the
realistic presentation of gang dominance in many Los Angeles
neighborhoods, using some statistics in the film to show what
police are up against.
   ``At the beginning we point out that there are 250 men and women
in law enforcement working against 600 gangs with over 70,000
members,'' he said. ``How can they possibly handle it?''
</TEXT>
