<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Train,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll in China Train Crash At 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers struggled through the night to
free victims trapped in the crushed cars of two passenger trains
that crashed head-on outside Shanghai, killing at least 28 people
and injuring 109.
   Chinese officials said today that 27 Japanese high school
students and one Chinese passenger died in Thursday's accident.
   A spokesman for the Shanghai Foreign Affairs Office said by
telephone that 37 students from Gakugei High School in southern
Japan's Kochi prefecture and 72 Chinese passengers remained
hospitalized.
   Ten other Japanese from the 193-member school tour group were
treated for injuries and released, said Fu Yatao, a Foreign Affairs
spokesman.
   It was China's fourth fatal train collision this year, bringing
the total death toll to 169.
   Fu said the cause of the crash was still under investigation.
   Bundo Takagi, deputy director of the Foreign Ministry's Second
Consular Division, said a team of three Japanese doctors will leave
for Shanghai Saturday morning to assist in the treatment of injured
students.
   The school group arrived in China on March 21 for a tour of the
Shanghai area and the nearby city of Hangzhou.
   The crash occurred at 2 p.m. Thursday when train No. 311,
carrying the Japanese group, ignored a stop signal as it left
Shanghai station for Hangzhou and smashed into the southbound train
No. 208 arriving from Changsha, in the Shanghai suburb of Fengban.
   The Japanese group was traveling in the first-class cars in the
front of No. 311. The cars were knocked off the track along with
the baggage car of No. 208.
   Fu said the trains were not traveling at high speeds at the time
of the crash.
   Chinese officials responded last month to the string of
transportation disasters by demanding greater attention to safety.
China's railway minister was forced to resign to take
responsibility for three fatal train accidents in January.
</TEXT>
