<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSCommission     03-25 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President's AIDS Commission Hears From Minorities In San Francisco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts to educate minorities about AIDS
have failed to stop the deadly disease because they have largely
ignored differing customs and languages, witnesses told a
presidential commission.
   Most black men with acquired immune deficiency syndrome in San
Francisco are homosexual or bisexual, yet have been nearly
untouched by efforts to halt the spread of the disease among white
gay men, said Amanda Houston-Hamilton, chairwoman of San
Francisco's Black Coalition on AIDS.
   ``We believe these men have fallen through the cracks,''
Houston-Hamilton told members of the Presidential Commission on the
Human Immunodeficiency Virus Epidemic.
   ``They are dying alone, frequently coming for medical services
when they are too sick to walk, incontinent, demented,'' said
Houston-Hamilton, one of a panel of Asian, Hispanic, Native
American and hemophiliac leaders who testified Thursday as the
commission began a three-day visit here.
   ``There are 32 distinct Asian ethnic groups, with different
languages, cultures, traditions and customs. These differences have
been been largely overlooked by AIDS education programs,'' said
Davis Y. Ja, of the San Francisco-based Asian AIDS Project.
   The group represents the Filipino, Chinese, Japanese, Korean and
Vietnamese communities and runs the only Asian AIDS education
program in the nation with $230,000 in federal funds and a staff of
six.
   Lillis Stephens, of the Sacramento-based Hemophilia Council of
California, told the panel that of the state's 2,300 hemophiliacs,
at least 1,600 are infected with the virus, an infection level
exceeding that of gay and bisexual people in the state.
   An estimated 10 to 20 percent of sexual partners of infected
hemophiliac men infected are also infected with the AIDS virus,
according to surveys by the organization.
   Although the Centers for Disease Control estimate 53 cases of
AIDS among Native Americans nationally, Phil Tinsley, a community
leader, contended the number is much higher and will mushroom as a
result of a 20.8 percent teen-age pregnancy rate and the nation's
highest levels of drug abuse.
   John Wahl, a San Francisco gay activist and former co-chair of
the National Mobilization Against AIDS, told the commission it
should use its influence against those who claim the virus
justifies discrimination against homosexuals.
   ``The AIDS epidemic will not destroy our liberation movement,
but attempts to misuse the fear of AIDS to suppress us will be very
destructive to social peace,'' he said.
   The testimony will be considered by the full 14-member
commission, which is about two-thirds of the way through its
national tour. The commission will deliver its recommendations for
a national strategy to stop AIDS to the White House by June 24,
said spokesman Tom Brandt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
