<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlexanderSentencing     03-25 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alexander Sentencing,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Say Lee Alexander Didn't Surrender All His Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor has alleged that
former Mayor Lee Alexander, sentenced 10 years in prison for
running a $1.5 million extortion-kickback scheme, did not surrender
all of his illegal profits.
   Alexander, one of the most visible U.S. mayors of the 1970s,
also was ordered to repay the city $100,000 in lieu of a $100,000
fine recommended by prosecutors.
   ``We're satisfied. It's what we requested and recommended and
what we felt was appropriate,'' U.S. Attorney Frederick J. Scullin
said after the sentencing Thursday.
   But Scullin said he still doesn't think Alexander has been
truthful about surrendering all his assets, as stipulated in the
plea bargain the former mayor made with the government Jan. 6.
   Alexander has turned over $1.4 million to the government, but
Scullin alleged during Thursday's hearing that Alexander is hiding
$200,000 and has lied about other kickbacks.
   Alexander, 60, who spent 16 years as mayor of New York's
fifth-largest city, had faced up to 30 years in prison for his
admission to charges of racketeering, conspiracy to obstruct a
government investigation and tax evasion. But U.S. District Judge
Thomas J. McAvoy followed the sentencing recommendation made by
prosecutors.
   ``I've brought great pain to my loved ones and the people of my
city and stand here now ready for my punishment,'' Alexander said
at the close of a 10-minute statement he gave before his sentence
was pronounced.
   ``The punishment you are about to impose on me ... pales against
the pain and remorse I feel.''
   Alexander was indicted July 16, 1987, by a special grand jury
empaneled 18 months earlier to investigate public corruption in
Syracuse.
   Alexander initially denied the charges. But he sought a plea
bargain after being faced with evidence the government had
gathered, including testimony from Alexander's bagmen and other
co-conspirators.
   He admitted running the extortion-kickback scheme during his
four terms as Syracuse mayor between 1970 and 1986. A 40-count
federal grand jury indictment charged that Alexander extorted
kickbacks of up to 25 percent from businessmen, professionals and
consultants doing work in the city.
   Alexander will be eligible for parole after about 40 months, but
Scullin said he believes Alexander will serve at least five years.
He must surrender by April 14.
   Also Thursday, seven co-conspirators were sentenced to terms
ranging up to 2{ years.
</TEXT>
