<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Israel     03-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Israel,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mubarak Warns Against Israeli Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak has warned that an
Israeli attack on Saudi Arabia's new intermediate-range missile
launchers would ``blow up the entire peace process'' in the Middle
East.
   Mubarak said Thursday he had sent an urgent message to President
Reagan urging him to ``use his influence with Israel and urge it to
stop threatening Arab states in this irresponsible way.''
   He said he also sent a verbal message to Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir via Egypt's ambassador to Israel, Mohammed
Bassiouny. The Egyptian president said other senior Israeli
officials also had been contacted.
   Mubarak's remarks to local reporters was Egypt's second sharp
response to Israeli warnings about Saudi Arabia's Chinese-supplied
CSS-2 missiles.
   On Wednesday, an unidentified Egyptian official said Cairo would
consider any Israeli attack on the installations an attack on Egypt
itself.
   Mubarak's comments were distributed by the state-owned Middle
East News Agency.
   ``I warn against any attack on ... Saudi Arabia, which is a
sister and friendly country,'' Mubarak said. ``This is a grave,
grave matter. If an attack on Saudi Arabia occurred, it would blow
up the entire peace process.''
   Jordan and Syria also have said they would regard an Israeli
attack on Saudi Arabia as aggression against them.
   The Egyptian warning, however, appeared to carry greater weight
because of its 1979 peace treaty with Israel, the only one between
an Arab country and the Jewish state. Egypt also is the Arab
world's strongest military power.
   Saudi Arabia recently acquired the missiles, which have a range
of 2,200 miles, enough to reach Iran and Israel. The missiles are
capable of carrying nuclear warheads, but both China and Saudi
Arabia have given assurances they will be fitted only with
conventional warheads.
   After disclosure of the missile deal, Shamir was reported to
have told U.S. officials that the Saudis must get rid of them.
   On Sunday, Israeli Radio quoted close Shamir aide Yossi Ben
Aharon as referring to Israel's reputation not to let potential
dangers become actual ones, an apparent reference to Israel's 1981
air raid on a nuclear reactor being built in Iraq.
   Shamir said later that Ben Aharon denied making the statement,
but the premier said Tuesday that Israel and the United States were
``making efforts to deal with ... the grave development.''
</TEXT>
