<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaptiveWomen     03-25 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Captive Women,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Year Later, Heidnik To Go To Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago today, police discovered three
half-naked women chained in a north Philadelphia basement and limbs
of another in the house's freezer.
   A grisly tale unfolded of how they were kept prisoners, one for
four months. The trail led to a New Jersey forest where the naked
body of another woman was found.
   The man who lived in the house, Gary Michael Heidnik, 41, faces
trial April 4 on rape and murder charges in a case that has already
attracted the attention of authors and could lead to a movie.
   Any profits from such a venture cannot go to Heidnik if he is
convicted, and at a federal bankruptcy court hearing Wednesday,
attorneys debated what should be done with the money.
   Heidnik's attorney, A. Charles Peruto Jr., said two-thirds of
the profits should be assigned to the estates of Heidnik and a sect
he started, United Church of the Ministers of God. If Heidnik were
convicted, the money would then go to his victims.
   Both Heidnik and the church are in bankruptcy.
   ``If I bring in money to enhance the estates, I get one-third of
what I enhance,'' Peruto said. ``The estates would get
two-thirds.'' As part of the agreement, the lawyer would not get
any legal fees for defending Heidnik.
   Assistant District Attorney Harriet Brumberg argued the state's
victim compensation law provides that 100 percent of such book or
movie profits goes to the victims.
   ``If anything in the book contains any thoughts, feelings,
impressions of Mr. Heidnik, that belongs to the victims,'' she said.
   At least two of the women are undergoing psychiatric treatment.
   Josephine Rivera, 27, a prostitute who police say was held by
Heidnik the longest _ four months _ and who escaped to notify
police, still is undergoing periodic counseling.
   Lisa Thomas, 20, another captive, continues to undergo weekly
psychiatric counseling.
   Cyril ``Tony'' Brown, Heidnik's retarded friend who is charged
with assisting him in the house, recently got married. Brown, 32,
who is free on bail and has been cooperating with police, on Nov.
13 married Gail Lincow, 37, a mildly retarded woman who had been a
friend and, police say, a temporary prisoner of Heidnik's.
</TEXT>
