<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeenSuicides     03-25 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen Suicides,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School Tries To Curb Teen-Age Suicides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suicides of three teen-age boys in
two weeks have shocked students and faculty at a high school here,
but they are trying to avert further tragedies with a vigorous
counseling program, including teen advisers.
   ``It's a scary situation,'' said Patty L. Kelly, 18, one of
several students receiving training as a peer group counselor at
Reitz High School after the suicides. ``Even people who didn't know
them are affected by it.''
   More than 600 parents and students attended a meeting at the
school auditorium Thursday night to talk about the deaths, the
latest of which occurred Wednesday morning.
   ``We're concerned about the families it happened to,'' said Judy
G. Elfreich, whose daughter is a freshman at Reitz. ``I'm not
really worried about more (suicides), but you just can't predict
things like that.''
   Along with the peer counseling groups, Reitz Principal Christine
Settle said the school would begin a ``buddy system'' to pair
newcomers with older students.
   In addition, six school psychologists and two counselors were
sent to the school of 1,350 students on Wednesday to assist the
four counselors normally assigned to Reitz.
   ``I hope all this helps,'' Miss Kelley said. ``People have come
to me to talk, but they're afraid to tell their parents because
they know they'll get sent to get help. And then they'll have to
come back (to school) and have people tell them, `Well, we know
you're crazy now.' So it's a lot easier for them to talk to us.''
   Vanderburgh County Sheriff Clarence C. Shepard told the audience
that an investigation had turned up no connection between the
deaths and satanism or cults, despite rumors to that effect.
   Shepard said before the meeting that ``all three were immediate,
personal, emotional problems with the young men. One was a
boyfriend-girlfriend problem, and the others were family problems.''
   The three victims were boys who knew each other and were in the
same year in high school, the sheriff said. Two were Reitz
sophomores, and the third was a former student who transferred to
another school.
   The latest victim, Larry E. ``J.J.'' Orth, 15, was found dead of
a self-inflicted gunshot wound at 6:30 a.m. Wednesday. Orth left a
note indicating he was having family problems.
   Eric G. Sanders, 16 and also a Reitz student, died March 10; and
Steven R. Schaefer, 15, who left last year, died March 13. Both
Sanders and Schaefer also shot themselves.
   The school system began a weeklong spring vacation today, and
school officials hoped the break would help settle the students.
   ``They will still see their friends, but they won't be together
in one building and rumors won't be spreading as much,'' said Susan
G. McDowell, head of psychological services for the
Evansville-Vanderburgh School Corporation.
   ``We think that will help,'' she added.
   The suicide rate for those ages 15 to 24 more than doubled, from
5.2 per 100,000 in 1960 to 12.5 in 1984, according to the national
Center for Health Statistics.
</TEXT>
