<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 2ndLd-Writethru a0511 03-25 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0511,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrations Banned In Armenia, Soviet Troops Patrol Republic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-10, with new reports from Armenia, demonstrations
banned, Soviet troops in Yerevan, Armenian committee disbanded,
Picks up graf 4 pvs, ``Armenians, who are...' Minor editing
throughout to conform and to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red Army troops patrolled the tense Armenian
capital today to enforce a ban on public demonstrations by
Armenians locked in a violent territorial dispute with neighboring
Azerbaijan.
   The Kremlin took a series of decisive steps to quell the ethnic
violence, which has claimed more than 30 lives and posed a serious
challenge to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Soldiers and helicopters were deployed to Yerevan, the Armenian
capital, to prevent the kind of massive demonstrations staged by
Armenians to demand the return of the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh
region that is now part of Azerbaijan.
   Demonstrations had been planned for Saturday, but Armenian
activists reported they had been called off.
   Armenian activists reported that authorities have ordered
disbanded an Armenian committee that spearheaded the drive to annex
Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia.
   The government on Thursday announced an eight-year plan to build
more housing, roads, schools and social services in the disputed
region, where nearly 75 percent of the population of 160,000 is
Armenian.
   The Kremlin has accused the demonstrators of being extremists
and demanded an end to the Armenian protest actions as
``intolerable.'' The demonstrations led to retaliation aganst
Armenians in Azerbaijan, where at least 32 people were killed and
nearly 200 injured.
   Sources in Armenia told The Associated Press by telephone that
the atmosphere was tense, but they reported no outbreaks of
violence. Western reporters have not been allowed to visit the area.
   Hovik Vassilian, an activist in the protest, said the Armenian
Literary Gazette newspaper announced today that the committee to
annex Nagorno-Karabakh was being disbanded ``because it was working
against the people's interests.''
   Vassilian said the planned demonstrations Saturday ``won't
happen.'' He said they have been called off ``considering the
situation.''
   Armenians, who are predominantly Christian, have been demanding
that the Nagorno-Karabkh region, which is smaller than Delaware, be
annexed to the neighboring Armenian republic, though there is no
common border. Azerbaijan is overwhelmingly Moslem.
   The Kremlin plan for Nagorno-Karabkh also assures the local
population that television transmission will be upgraded so they
can receive broadcasts in Armenian as well as the national network
and Azeri programming.
   Other assurances, such as better supplies of Armenian-language
books and preservation of historical and cultural monuments,
address issues that incited Armenians to demand annexation for the
mountainous region, which has been part of Azerbaijan since 1923.
   In Azerbaijan, Radio Baku reported today that public assemblies,
meetings and street demonstrations will be allowed only by permits,
which must be applied for at least 10 days in advance. Those
violating the order face criminal penalties, according to the
broadcast monitored in London.
   Armenia instituted a similar ban on unsanctioned demonstrations
earlier in the week, according to Radio Yerevan.
   It was not immediately clear whether the government plan would
succeed in pacifying Armenians worried that Nagorno-Karabakh is
losing its ethnic identity. But one official source in Armenia
reported a generally quiet, though tense, atmosphere today.
   A duty officer at the republic's Ministry of Internal Affairs,
responsible for police operations, told The Associated Press by
telephone from Yerevan that the city was ``fairly quiet.''
   The officer, who declined to give his name or detailed
information, confirmed Red Army helicopters and security troops
were patrolling the capital to keep order.
   Calls to Azerbaijan did not go through today.
   Moscow-based dissidents reported Thursday that the atmosphere in
Armenia was ``filled with tension.''
   On Wednesday, the Soviet government rejected as ``intolerable''
the Armenian campaign for annexation, indicating it would not bend
to pressure brought on by mass demonstrations and strikes in the
republic last month.
   The unrest brought an unusual personal appeal from Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev for calm and reason in dealing with the ethnic
dispute. Gorbachev also promised the leadership would review
Armenia's claims to Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Gorbachev's address calmed the demonstrators in Yerevan. But on
Feb. 28, ethnic extremists went on a rampage of murder, rape,
robbery and other crimes in the Azeri city of Sumgait.
</TEXT>
