<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FatStatStudy     03-25 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fat Stat Study,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Virginia Town Selected For $4 Million Cardiovascular Health
Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This small, Ohio River town has been
chosen as the focus of a $4 million, two-year, privately funded
study aimed at reducing heart attacks, strokes and high blood
pressure, officials said.
   Sponsors of the pilot program said they chose Wellsburg because
of its small population _ 4,000 _ and because West Virginia
registered the highest obesity rate in the country at 24 percent in
a 1986 federal study that also found 31 percent of West Virginians
smoke cigarettes.
   West Virginia trails only Iowa in the annual death rate from
heart disease, according to state Health Director Dr. David
Heydinger.
   ``Education, especially health education, is lacking in West
Virginia,'' said John W. Bertram, administrator for the Brooke
County Health Department and a member of the program's advisory
board.
   The program, one of the first privately funded public health
education programs aimed at rural areas, is sponsored by The Bayer
Co., an aspirin and over-the-counter drug manufacturer, and
Glenbrook Laboratories, Bayer's New York-based parent.
   However, aspirin, recently linked to the prevention of heart
attacks and strokes, will not be part of the program, said Robin D.
Mills, president of the Bayer Co.
   ``We already have ongoing research into that,'' Mills said.
``What we want to develop is a health program that we can offer to
rural Americans.''
   The program will begin in May when 1,000 volunteers will be
checked for high blood pressure, high cholesterol, obesity and
other cardiovascular risk factors.
   Participants must be at least 21 years old and willing to return
for checkups every three months over a two-year period.
   Health professionals will attempt to lower the weight,
cholesterol and blood pressure of participants and eliminate other
risk factors through education and behavior modification.
   Some aspects of the study, including nutrition seminars, weight
reduction techniques and smoking clinics will be available to all
of the town's 4,000 people, Mills said.
   The company will also sponsor walks, runs and other exercise
activities for the town, which is about 40 miles southwest of
Pittsburgh.
   ``If people listen, it will be a good thing,'' said Nora
Hartley, 46, owner of Nora's Novelty Nook, as she smothered a
cigarette in a full ashtray.
   ``I'd go crazy if I had to quit smoking and I don't have to lose
weight, but I'll probably check it out,'' she said.
   Cardiovascular disease _ the leading cause of death in the
United States _ kills nearly a million Americans each year,
according to the National Center for Health Statistics. Nearly
one-fifth of those deaths occur in people under the age of 65.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
