<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0502,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab Reports Say Two Killed in West Bank Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with further reports of two
killed, army saying it is investigating, not denying. Other
details. Changes byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TARQUMIA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fired on
Palestinian demonstrators who hurled rocks and broken bottles in
the occupied West Bank today, killing two and wounding six,
hospital officials and witnesses said.
   The army said five protesters were wounded in the attack on a
makeshift army headquarters in Tarqumia and in a clash in the
nearby city of Hebron. It said it was investigating the reports
that two were killed.
   Officials close to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir protested a
meeting planned Saturday between Secretary of State George P.
Shultz and two Palestinian-Americans tied to the PLO.
   As part of a campaign to crack down on leaders of recent unrest,
the army arrested a prominent Gaza lawyer under special laws
allowing detention for up to six months without trial.
   Israel radio quoted an unidentified military source as saying
the military had evidence that the attorney, Raji Sourani, was
linked to the organization of the uprising. The army has not
commented.
   More than 4,000 Palestinians have been detained since the unrest
began Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and 3,000
remain in jail. But unlike previous roundups, which focused on
stone-throwers, the current one has zeroed in on the underground
leadership.
   In Tarqumia, a village of 9,000 near Hebron, hundreds of
stone-throwing youths set out before dawn to attack a school that
troops had turned into makeshift headquarters, said Naim Odeh, a
52-year-old schoolteacher.
   ``The troops came into the village at 4 a.m. and took over the
school,'' Odeh said. ``Then about 500 youths marched out to the
school and started throwing rocks and broken bottles.''
   Troops responded by opening fire, Odeh said, and the
confrontation lasted several hours. He said two youths were shot
and killed.
   Villagers and an official at Hebron's Alia hospital identified
the dead as Khaled Hassan Ahmed Murktan, 18, who was shot in the
stomach, and Walid Abdul Fatatta, 18, who was shot in the chest.
   Odeh said the bodies were buried in the town's cemetery. There,
villagers pointed out to a journalist two freshly dug mounds of
earth, with an inscribed rock beside them.
   In Hebron, soldiers surrounded Al Haras mosque following noon
prayers on the Moslem Sabbath when 20 youths took up positions on
the roof and began throwing stones and waving a Palestinian flag,
which is outlawed in Israel.
   As a reporter watched from a nearby vantage point, troops fired
tear gas and the sound of shots also could be heard.
   Three protesters were shot and critically wounded, the
Arab-owned Palestine Press Service said.
   Later, three Arab teen-agers were seen sitting on the ground
with their hands tied behind their backs. A soldier was seen
kicking one of the young men, who was wearing a blue sweater.
   The army said an empty passenger bus headed for the Jewish
settlement of Qiryat Arba near Hebron was surrounded by residents
of an Arab village, who beat the driver and set the vehicle on fire.
   Israel radio said the driver was hospitalized with two broken
arms.
   Israeli officials reacted angrily to Shultz's plans to meet with
two Palestinian-American members of the Palestine National Council,
the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   The officials said the meeting violated a U.S. commitment not to
talk to the Palestine Liberation Organizaton.
   Edward Said, a professor at Columbia University in New York, and
Ibrahim Abu Lughod, a professor at Northwestern University in
Chicago, were to discuss the latest American peace initiative with
Shultz.
   Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Shamir, said the prime minister
planned to raise the issue today with U.S. Ambassdor Thomas
Pickering.
   Ehud Olmert, a senior legislator from Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc, said he was ``very upset about this because they are not just
Americans; they are members of a group the U.S. government has
promised not to talk to.''
   Israel refuses to deal with the PLO, which it views as a
terrorist group. The Palestinian death toll in the violence is 109,
according to U.N. figures. One Israeli soldier has been killed.
</TEXT>
