<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Gore-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0412 03-25 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0412,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Backing Off `Electability' Argument</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts top two grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAGAUNEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the heady days following his Southern
victories, Democratic presidential candidate Albert Gore Jr.
depicted rival Michael Dukakis as having the electoral appeal of
George McGovern and Walter Mondale.
   Two weeks later, the harsh rhetoric is gone. With recent polls
showing Dukakis _ not Gore _ as the only Democrat running even
nationwide with GOP front-runner George Bush, Gore is having a more
difficult time pinning his rival with the image of the Democrats'
landslide losers of 1972 and 1984.
   Gore, the Tennessee senator who needs a victory in the North to
remain a top contender, has hardly mentioned Dukakis, Jesse Jackson
or his other rivals for the Democratic presidential nomination as
he campaigns in Michigan and Wisconsin. Instead, he is focusing on
Bush and the Reagan administration in a slight retooling of his new
populist message.
   His silence on Dukakis has caused some to speculate about Gore's
intentions _ whether he is holding his fire against a candidate who
could, as nominee, offer him the second spot on the ticket. Gore
maintains he has ``no interest'' in the vice presidential
nomination _ a statement that stops short of ruling it out.
   There are also suggestions Gore may be awaiting a better
opportunity to engage Dukakis, when the field has narrowed and Gore
can find a state where he does not speak from a position so far
behind Dukakis that his remarks seem born of desperation.
   Gore catapulted to the top tier of Democratic presidential
contenders through his victories in the South and West on Super
Tuesday, March 8. Two days after that, campaigning in Chicago
toward Illinois' primary, Gore delivered a strong assault on
Dukakis as representing the Democrats' past losing formula.
   ``For those who want another election blow-out, and see the
Democratic Party losing 49 out of 50 states, vote for Michael
Dukakis,'' Gore said then.
   ``How long will it take for us to learn the approach that
Michael Dukakis represents does not sell to the American people?''
he asked.
   Campaigning this week across Michigan's sparsely populated Upper
Peninsula, Gore was asked why he is not continuing that language,
and did he no longer think Dukakis would be a ``blow-out'' loser.
   ``I said that the approach he represents runs that risk,'' Gore
responded. ``I'm not going to say any of my opponents are not
electable.
   ``I think the recent history suggests there are only two kinds
of elections in modern history _ Republican landslides or
Democratic squeakers. This is going to be a Democratic squeaker.''
   When he was pinning his hopes on appeal among the South's
independent and conservative-minded Democrats, Gore argued that he
is the most electable Democrat.
   Two polls this week _ one by CBS News and The New York Times,
the other by The Washington Post and ABC _ both showed Dukakis and
Bush in a virtual dead heat. Gore, meanwhile, was far behind Bush
when paired against the likely GOP nominee.
   Gore now refers to the ``electability'' issue as one of
importance primarily to the Democratic ``super delegates,'' the
nearly 650 elected officials who will get delegate berths and be
free agents at the convention, unbound by primary or caucus results
in their states.
   He still contends he has demonstrated an appeal to swing voters
that Dukakis and Jackson have not. But he usually couples it with
an acknowledgement that it is more an issue for party insiders than
average voters.
   ``Many Democrats, particularly the so-called super delegates,
are interested in finding a candidate who has the best chance of
winning in the fall, the best chance of appealing to the
independently thinking voters who hold the balance of power, the
best chance of carrying areas like the South, West and Midwest,
where we have lost overwhelmingly these last several elections,''
Gore said.
   ``I think it's a legitimate question to ask _ who can best win.''
   Gore disputed the answer presented in the recent polls, saying
it is too early to measure such sentiment accurately.
   ``Hypothetical matchups of that kind ... are entirely
meaningless,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1018EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gibraltar-Election     03-25 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gibraltar-Election,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independence Advocate Pulls off Big Gibraltar Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Labor leader Joe Bossano, a staunch
defender of independence for this British colony, was declared the
victor today in local elections.
   Bossano, who rejects a competing Spanish claim of sovereignty
over the fortress colony at its southern tip, received 8,128 votes,
or 58 percent of the votes cast Thursday.
   Incumbent Chief Minister Adolfo Canepa was next with 4,442
votes, or 29 percent, in the most lopsided victory ever by a
Gibraltar party.
   The incumbent leads the Advancement of Civil Rights party, which
had long dominated Gibraltar politics.
   The party of Bossano, branch officer of the 7,000-member
Transport Workers General Union, won eight seats in the 15-seat
House of Assembly. Canepa's party won the other seven.
   The conservative Independent Democratic Party led by former
civil servant Joe Pitaluga got 13 percent of the vote, but none of
its candidates won enough votes to gain a seat.
   In his first comments to reporters after the victory, Bossano
asserted that most of Gibraltar's 29,000 residents reject a 1984
British-Spanish accord known as the Brussels agreement. Under that
accord, Britain for the first time said it would discuss the
question of sovereignty with Spain.
   Spain ceded Gibraltar to Britain in the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht
following its defeat in the War of Succession. The treaty
stipulates that Spain recover sovereignty over the territory if
Britain relinquishes it.
   Canepa is a protege of longtime party leader and Gibraltar Chief
Minister Joshua Hassan, who governed the colony for 40 of the last
43 years.
   In campaigning for Canepa, Hassan accused Bossano of being a
radical who would harm Gibraltar's relations with Britain and
Spain. But Bossano said he intended to better relations with both
countries.
   Presiding senior election officer Eugene Howes said 13,473 votes
were cast, representing just over 76 percent of the colony's 17,500
registered voters. The highest previous turnout had been 74 percent
in 1984 elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
