<HEAD>Iranians Pound Basra, Iraqis Claim New Ship Raids</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th, graf: ``The official...,'' to fix typo and 8th
graf: ``It said...'' to CORRECT Iranian troops to Iraqi troops.
Pick up 9th graf pvs: ``Baghdad's al-Thawra...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said today it hammered Iraq's
southern port of Basra with missiles and shellfire and repulsed an
Iraqi counterattack in the northern Kurdistan mountains, killing or
wounding 500 men.
   Both sides claimed to have shot down four jets, and Iraq claimed
it attacked two ships off Iran's coast in the Persian Gulf.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Revolutionary
Guards in northeast Iraq pushed back four infantry battalions and a
brigade _ about 7,200 troops _ that Iraq moved up from its southern
7th Army Corps to reinforce the northern front.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the fighting centered
around the Rishan mountains east of the town of Sayyid Sadiq.
   Iranian forces, estimated at around 30,000 men, were reported
Thursday to be five miles east of the town, a strategic transport
hub, after punching 10 miles into Iraq in an offensive launched
March 16.
   Tehran Radio reported four Iraqi fighter-bombers were shot down
by ground fire today and the pilots killed.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said four
U.S.-built Iranian F-5 jets were shot down by Iraqi anti-aircraft
fire over the battle zone.
   It said Iraqi fighters destroyed four Iranian helicopters on the
ground. IRNA, quoting military communiques, said Iranian jets
carried out 14 attacks on Iraqi troop concentrations in the
northeastern battle zone and around al-Amarah in the south. It said
all the planes returned safely to their bases.
   Baghdad's al-Thawra daily, the mouthpiece of the ruling Arab
Baath Socialist Party, said Iraq's air force flew 224 combat
missions Thursday.
   That was one of the highest one-day totals in the last year and
underlined the growing intensity of the current fighting. The
newspaper said the planes dropped nearly 200 tons of bombs and
destroyed three Iranian jets and two helicopters.
   IRNA said six missiles were fired during the night into the
strategically important city of Basra and the border town of
Mandali, 80 miles east of the Iraqi capital of Baghdad.
   The agency said long-range artillery also pounded ``military,
economic and industrial centers'' in Basra and the border town of
al-Gharbi farther north.
   There was no immediate word on casualties. In recent weeks,
hundreds of civilians on both sides have been killed or wounded in
missile, air and artillery attacks in the so-called ``war of the
cities.''
   The Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi fighter-bombers attacked two
``large maritime targets,'' which usually means tankers, off the
Iranian coast during the night. It reported ``accurate and
effective hits.''
   There was no immediate independent confirmation of the ship
attacks.
   Iraq said 13 people were killed and 68 wounded Thursday when two
Iranian missile crashed into downtown Baghdad.
   Among the victims was a woman, killed in a hospital bed while
breast-feeding her newborn baby, INA reported. The infant was found
alive in his mother's arms several hours later.
   Iraq said it fired six long-range missiles into Tehran, a city
of 6 million. IRNA said 10 civilians were killed and 100 wounded
when the missiles hit two schools, two mosques and two hospitals as
well as shops and houses.
   Both sides have fired more than 250 missiles into each other's
cities since Feb. 29, when Tehran was hit by long-range Iraqi
missiles for the first time in the war.
   Iran said Thursday that its troops advanced further into Iraq's
northeastern Kurdistan province. It claims to have killed or
wounded 11,000 Iraqis, captured 4,500 and destroyed 200 tanks and
armored vehicles in the 10-day offensive. Iraq claims it has killed
thousands of the invaders but has admitted losing several towns.
   Iranian President Ali Khamenei, meanwhile, intensified a
propaganda campaign against Iraq for allegedly dropping chemical
bombs on three towns captured by the Iranians.
   IRNA quoted Khamenei Thursday night as calling on international
organizations, including the United Nations, to expel Iraq for
using chemical weapons, outlawed under a 1925 Geneva agreement.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani earlier in the day that
Iran may use chemical weapons itself unless the United Nations
takes action against Iraq.
</TEXT>
