<2ND_LINE>PM-Hollywood Strikes,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commercial Strikers Agree To Federal Mediation, Writers Fallout
Builds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking unions representing people who perform
in commercials have agreed to meet with a federal mediator in two
weeks, while fallout from the scriptwriters' walkout builds in the
television industry.
   Television production companies said they have laid off more
than 1,000 people because of the writers' strike, costing workers
more than $4 million in salaries and benefits.
   Union actors who appear in radio or television commercials
walked off the sets March 21 in a dispute over payments from ads
run on cable television.
   But Thursday, negotiators for the Screen Actors Guild and the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists agreed to meet
with advertisers and a federal mediator in New York City on April 6.
   Performers' unions and representatives for the American
Association of Advertising Agencies and the Association of National
Advertisers said no preconditions were attached to the planned
talks.
   The Writers Guild of America went on strike March 7 when talks
broke down with producers over rerun payments and creative control
on the set. No new talks are scheduled, and representatives from
both sides expect a long strike.
   About 125 writers and producers have had to suspend TV
development deals at a cost to them of about $1.5 million a week,
according to the Alliance of Movie and Television Producers.
   Some prime-time TV shows ended production early when scripts ran
out, and several projects in the works had to be shelved. Talk
shows like Johnny Carson's ``Tonight Show'' and ``Late Night With
David Letterman'' are broadcasting reruns until the strike is
settled.
   SAG and AFTRA represent more than 100,000 actors and announcers
working on commercials, while the WGA represents more than 9,000
script writers coast to coast.
</TEXT>
