<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Terrorism     03-25 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Terrorism,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrorist Suspect Released for Insufficient Evidence, Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigating magistrate has released a Lebanese
man held in a series of Paris bombings because of insufficient
evidence, a well-informed source said today.
   Mohamed Mouhajer, who was arrested last March in a police sweep,
was freed Thursday by magistrate Gilles Boulouque, according to a
source in the magistrate's office. Seven Tunisians also were
arrested in the sweep.
   Mouhajer was released ``because there was not sufficient
evidence to keep him in temporary detention'' any longer, according
to the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Boulouque has been in charge of investigating a series of Paris
bombings in 1985 and 1986 that left 13 people dead and 250 injured.
   French authorities have said Mouhajer, a former philosophy
student at the Sorbonne, was an ideologist for the Committee for
Solidarity with Arab and Middle East Political Prisoners, a group
which claimed responsiblity for five of the violent attacks.
   The source said Mouhajer was held while police investigated his
relationship with Fouad Ali Saleh, a Tunisian immigrant described
by authorities at the time of his arrest as the leader of a
pro-Iranian terrorist network. Saleh has been charged in several of
the bombings, including a Sept. 17, 1986, attack at the Tati
department store that killed six people and injured 51 others.
   Mouhajer still faces charges of criminal association and illegal
possession of arms and has been forbidden to leave the country.
Neither charge is related to the terrorist bombings, the source
said.
   A French newspaper today implied that Mouhajer's release might
be connected to Conservative Premier Jacques Chirac's hopes for the
upcoming presidential election. Four Frenchmen are missing and
believed to be held captive in Lebanon.
   The daily Liberation said, ``In this electoral period, Jacques
Chirac would not be displeased with the release of some French
hostages in Lebanon.''
   Earlier this week, Jacques Kosciusko-Morizet, national secretary
of Chirac's party, the Rally for the Republic, visited Damascus
where he met with a number of Syrian officials.
   Syria is the main powerbroker in Lebanon and maintains troops in
west Beirut.
   On his return to Paris, Kosciusko-Morizet told the French news
agency Agence France-Presse that the meetings were not related to
the French hostages in Lebanon.
   In all 22 foreigners are missing and believed to be held captive
in Lebanon. The longest held hostage is Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
