<2ND_LINE>PM-Caveman Arrest,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest `Caveman' In String of Robberies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robbery suspect who lived in a cave was
lured into custody with promises of cigarettes and a hot meal,
police said.
   The man who allegedly put the suspect in a cave was later
arrested as well, and apparently tried to commit suicide, police
said.
   Joseph E. Steffani, 24, had long, dirty hair and apparently had
not shaved for at least a week when he was arrested Wednesday night
for investigation of robbery, according to Sgt. Dan Mercado.
   He said Steffani was addicted to tranquilizers and was put in
the cave by Kenneth Hawtin, 37, of El Cerrito, who was arrested
Thursday.
   In what police say may have been a suicide attempt, Hawtin
jammed a key into an electrical outlet at a police station and was
knocked unconscious. He was taken to a hospital and booked for
investigation of robbery.
   Steffani was held at the Oakland City Jail.
   Steffani, who told officers he had been addicted to
tranquilizers since he was was 14, admitted at least 15 robberies
in Alameda and Contra Costa counties, Mercado said.
   Police said Steffani had lived with Hawtin until last week, when
Hawtin took him to the cave in the hills above the community of
Canyon.
   Steffani has a history of emotional problems and ``was afraid to
be around people,'' Mercado said.
   Hawtin and a few other friends knew of Steffani's hiding place,
Mercado said. They would drive to the area with food and other
supplies, and honk to let Steffani know they were there.
   When the two undercover officers following a tip drove to the
area Wednesday night and honked, all they could see at first was
``eyes in the bushes,'' Mercado said.
</TEXT>
