<2ND_LINE>PM-Body Dig,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warrant Affidavits Allege Man Died During Fight With Police Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARLOW, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affidavits released today show that
authorities found a skeleton buried in the police chief's yard
after being told the man died during a fight with the chief, who is
now married to the victim's ex-wife.
   Authorities on March 14 found the skeleton of Russell Bean about
20 feet down after they were told to dig in Police Chief Robert
Chambers' front yard.
   Chambers, who has since resigned as the part-time chief, has not
been charged in connection with the death. His lawyer has said
Chambers had nothing to do with it.
   An autopsy showed that Bean, 25, died 10 years ago of severe
blows to the head and chest.
   Affidavits unsealed in District Court today paint a picture of
wife swapping, brutality and alcohol abuse by Bean and Chambers,
who was a logger at the time.
   The statements allege that Chambers told his father 10 years ago
that he had accidentally killed a man in a fight and that father
and son buried the body.
   The affidavits allege that Chambers, now 36, and Bean, who were
considered close friends, had been drinking together in Marlow and
got into a fight, and that Bean fell and hit his head and died.
   The affidavits, used to obtain a search warrant to excavate the
yard, contained statements by Melissa Chambers, Lorrie Chambers and
Louis LaCourse. Melissa is Chambers' sister, Lorrie is her
daughter, and LaCourse is married to Chambers' sister Susan.
   Melissa said her father, Clifton, 61, told her about the
incident twice, but made her promise not to say anything until
after his death.
   The elder Chambers died March 9 of natural causes. Melissa went
to police the next day.
   Lorrie's affidavit confirmed Melissa's story.
   State Police Sgt. Clayton Young was quoted as saying that he
learned from the family that Bean's wife, Sylvia, telephoned Bean's
mother in September 1978 to say he had disappeared. Sylvia told
Bean's mother that she had learned from Chambers that Bean had
borrowed money, and Chambers had given him a ride to the Vermont
state line and dropped him off.
   Mrs. Bean won a divorce in June 1979, and she and Chambers were
married in September 1979.
   LaCourse's affidavit said Chambers initiated a conversation
about Bean shortly after the man was last seen.
   LaCourse said Chambers told him that ``he hit him so hard, no
one would ever see him again.
   ``Robert Chambers told Russ to hit the road and Russ did.''
   LaCourse said Chambers also told him that he, Bean, Sylvia and
Chambers' then-wife, Debbie, were swapping partners for sex.
   Melissa's statement was similar. She said the relationship
between the two couples ``was weird. ... I know Robert always beat
Debbie, that was why she ran off. (She) couldn't take it any
longer.''
   In addition to his Marlow job, Chambers has taken a leave of
absence as part-time chief in nearby Gilsum and has been suspended
as a trainee with the Winchester police department.
</TEXT>
