<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingHouse     03-25 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing House,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stolen House Driven Past Stunned Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHIRLEY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Frank Calabro glanced out a window just
in time to see his beach house trundling down the street on a truck.
   ``I looked out the window and my house went by with a police
escort. I ran onto the street and said `Where are you going with my
house?''' Calabro said today.
   Calabro already had planned to move the two-bedroom,
960-square-foot beach house, which he valued at $12,000.
   ``I guess he (the thief) walked by, saw a house he liked on
moving stilts and decided he was going to take it,'' said Calabro.
   Calabro was visiting a real estate office Thursday when he saw
the traveling house and ran out and told the police escort it was
his house.
   ``He thought I was crazy,'' said Calabro. ``How often do you
stop a police escort and say, `This is my house'? He stopped the
truck. We were standing out there laughing hysterically. I had the
contract in my car for the house.''
   The thief, who was in a separate car behind the convoy, fled.
   ``Had I not seen it go by, we would have never found it. How do
you report a stolen house?'' said Calabro.
   John Williams, spokesman for Suffolk County District Attorney
Patrick Henry, said an arrest was expected.
   Calabro, a physician with a family practice in Mastic Beach,
said he already had accepted a deposit to sell the house to someone
else. ``They didn't know they were going to get a famous house,''
he said.
</TEXT>
