<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Death-RowLove     03-25 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death-Row Love,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Love Sparked On Death Row Ends In Freedom, Wedding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUTLER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 minutes after Willie Brown
walked out of prison, he married the woman who fought for five
years to get him off death row.
   ``I search for words to describe what I'm feeling. So far the
proper words to describe it haven't surfaced,'' Brown said Thursday
after he and Esther Lichtenfels exchanged vows on the lawn of the
Clay County Courthouse.
   ``I feel like I'm getting out of prison myself,'' his bride said
before they left for their new home in Springfield, Mass. ``I feel
wonderful. I'm so happy I can't tell you.''
   Brown, 37, was on parole from a Massachusetts prison when a
Pinellas County judge sentenced him to 20 years for armed robbery
in 1976. On July 7, 1981, while he was serving the time at Union
Correctional Institution, fellow inmate Earl Owens was stabbed to
death.
   Brown and another prisoner were charged with the slaying after a
third inmate, Frank Wise, said he saw them leaving Owens' cell
shortly before the murder was discovered. The two were convicted
and condemned.
   Ms. Lichtenfels met Brown on Christmas 1983 when she was with a
group visiting condemned prisoners who had no holiday visitors.
   ``He was the saddest face I'd ever seen when I met him. It was a
spiritual love right from the start,'' recalled Ms. Lichtenfels,
54, a divorcee with three grown children.
   It was at her prompting that defense lawyers pursued and won an
appeal on technical grounds in November that overturned the
convictions of Brown and co-defendant Larry Troy.
   Ms. Lichtenfels then she hired a private investigator and
tracked down Wise. They agreed to meet and she was given a hidden
microphone, with which Wise was recorded admitting that Brown was
innocent and asking for $2,000 to recant his testimony.
   Wise was arrested on bribery charges in December and Assistant
State Attorney Harris Tobin said in February that he would not to
prosecute Brown and Troy again because Wise's credibility was
damaged.
   Brown said that while Ms. Lichtenfels was fighting for the
appeal, he considered her optimism unrealistic. He tried to talk
her out of it, he said.
   But ``I didn't know what kind of person she was,'' he said.
``She believes in action.''
   Brown must complete his parole term in Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
