<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fires,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Battle Tennessee Blazes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 firefighters from western
states were sent to the Smoky Mountains of eastern Tennessee today
to fight fires which have broken out there, authorities said.
   Fires, abetted by strong shifting winds and dry weather, have
burned more than 1,300 acres in Tennessee since Wednesday. Five
separate fires were burning today.
   ``Even if it does rain it will probably be less than an inch,''
said Wilma Marine, a spokeswoman at Cherokee National Forest, where
a 300-acre fire had been contained.
   The U.S. Forest Service crews of about 200 firefighters from
Colorado, New Mexico and Arizona arrived Thursday.
   The largest blaze in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park has
grown to 500-plus acres about two miles west of Chilhowee Lake.
   A colony of red cockaded woodpeckers, an endangered species, was
threatened by that fire, said Misty Seagle, a clerk in the park
superintendent's office.
   No homes have been damaged by any of the fires.
</TEXT>
