<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0483 03-25 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0483,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Returns to Fight for Noriega's Ouster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with sources saying church to
release sharp denunciation soon. ADDS background on Arias Calderon.
Picks up 14th graf pvs, `His return...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition leader returned to
Panama vowing to rid the nation of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, and
sources today said the Roman Catholic church would issue its
harshest denunciation yet of the military strongman.
   It was the fifth day of a general strike that has paralyzed the
economy.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, head of the Christian Democratic Party,
arrived Thursday to find Panama in the midst of the anti-Noriega
general strike, which has shut down more than 90 percent of
business and industry.
   The government refused to allow Arias Calderon into the country
when he tried to return from a business trip to the United States
on Feb. 25, the day President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire
Noriega. Delvalle was in turn ousted by Noriega supporters.
   There was no reason given for blocking Arias Calderon's return,
and there was no reason given for his being allowed back. A
spokesman for the Christian Democratic Party, William Cochez, said
without elaborating that ``the government backed down.''
   Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., said local U.S. officials warned
Arias Calderon to be prepared for a ``longer haul'' before Noriega
is forced from power. ``Nobody's talking about hours, nobody's
talking about days,'' said Ackerman, who is on a fact-finding tour
with Rep. Pete Kostmayer, D-Pa.
   Noriega is the country's de facto leader by virtue of his
influence as chief of the Defense Forces.
   Ackerman said he had been assured that the church soon would
release a statement carrying a ``strong message'' against Noriega.
   Sources from the opposition National Civic Crusade, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the message would be the church's
strongest statement yet against Noriega.
   Panama's Episcopal Conference of Bishops, led by Archbishop
Marcos G. McGrath, has sharply criticized Noriega in the past but
fallen short of calling for his ouster.
   McGrath met with Noriega on Thursday. McGrath had refused to
discuss the talks, saying only that he was not negotiating
Noriega's departure.
   Today was payday for the 15,000-strong Defense Forces. On
Monday, Noriega must come up with money for retirees already forced
to wait an extra week for their pensions.
   A banking source who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Thursday the government had pleaded with local banks to hand over
an estimated $70 million in their vaults. But the banks said the
money belonged to their depositors and they could not legally give
it up.
   In an attempt to force Noriega into exile, the United States has
frozen Panamanian deposits in U.S. banks and withheld payments for
use of the Panama canal. The U.S. dollar is Panama's currency.
   The country has been in an increasingly chaotic state since
Noriega was indicted on U.S. drug traffickng charges last month.
   Arias Calderon arrived on a commercial flight from Miami and
told a cheering crowd that Noriega must go.
   His return had ``but one objective _ to get rid of Noriega,''
Arias Calderon said. He was accompanied by Christian Democratic
leaders from Venezuela, Costa Rica and West Germany.
   Arias Calderon, a likely presidential candidate in scheduled May
1989 elections, said he would meet with other opposition leaders to
plan a strategy for ousting Noriega.
   The government stepped up its propaganda attacks Thursday
against the United States and its military presence along the
Panama Canal. The state radio station again urged Panamanians _
particularly soldiers and youth _ to be on guard against ``any
aggression by the United States.''
   The Foreign Relations Ministry denounced a background briefing
for journalists at the U.S. Southern Command headquarters on
Saturday. The Ministry accused the U.S. military of ``instructing''
reporters that they ``must help remove'' Noriega.
   The last of 670 military police and support personnel arrived
Thursday at U.S. bases to beef up security.
   Southern Command officials had said earlier the reinforcements
were ``simply good planning in view of the current unrest in
Panama.''
   President Reagan told high school students in Vienna, Va.,
Thursday he had no plans to take military action to get rid of
Noriega.
   ``We're not going to be the big colossus of the North once
again, coming in to ... our smaller neighbors' places of living and
business and trying to guide and direct them,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
