<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Chambers 1stLd-Writethru a0501 03-25 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chambers Trial in Uproar After Juror's Note</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with jury returning today,
picking up 3rd graf pvs, `Chambers, 21 ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the case of a man accused of
strangling a young woman during a Central Park tryst began their
ninth day of deliberations today after a tumultuous day during
which one juror reportedly asked to be dismissed.
   Jurors were expected today to begin rehearing medical testimony
that state Supreme Court Justice Howard E. Bell estimated would
take a day and a half to two days to complete.
   But shortly before noon, the jury had yet to hear a single word
of testimony and had not appeared in the courtroom. It was not
clear if the panel was deliberating the fate of Robert E. Chambers
Jr. as they awaited the readback of testimony.
   On Thursday, a juror asked Supreme Court Justice Howard E. Bell
to be dismissed because of an argument over the meaning of medical
testimony in the case, said a source, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Chambers, 21, is accused of second-degree murder in the death of
18-year-old Jennifer Levin on Aug. 26, 1986. He could be convicted
of the lesser crimes of first- or second-degree manslaughter or
criminally negligent homicide.
   Bell, defense attorney Jack Litman and prosecutor Linda
Fairstein met in the judge's robing room. Despite requests from
lawyers for the New York Post and Newsday, the judge refused to
divulge what was discussed.
   Litman and Fairstein referred to ``that matter discussed in your
honor's robing room'' without providing details.
   One of the 12 jurors _ who have heard eight weeks of testimony _
could be replaced by an alternate at this point only with the
consent of both sides, and a mistrial could result if a juror
wanted to leave.
   Jurors were expected back in the courtroom today to begin
rehearing medical testimony that Bell estimated would take 1{ to
two days to complete.
   The prosecution contends Chambers strangled Miss Levin in a
rage. The defense has argued he killed her accidentally when he
yanked her backward to stop her from hurting him during rough sex
in Central Park.
   At jurors' request, Bell on Thursday instructed them on several
points of law, including burden of proof, circumstantial evidence,
reasonable doubt and presumption of innocence.
   The jury's request for a rereading of most of the medical
testimony by key defense and prosecution witnesses means lawyers
must go through about 1,500 pages of transcripts.
   The jury asked to hear testimony that bears only on the facts on
Miss Levin's injuries, not experts' theories on how they occurred.
</TEXT>
