<DOCNO> AP880325-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1220EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-UnfunnyCandidates     03-25 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unfunny Candidates,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professor Says Presidential Campaign Needs a Sense of Humor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential candidates could have
stifled all that derisive early campaign talk about being ``the
seven dwarfs'' by simply playing along with the gag, says Professor
Joseph Boskin.
   ``If they were smart they would have labeled themselves _ `I'm
Grumpy, I'm Doc' _ and that would have undercut it. Whatever
happened to play in America?'' said Boskin, who is writing a book
about the connection between humor and social change.
   The Boston University history professor is disturbed that this
year's presidential candidates generally seem about as funny as a
doorknob.
   He labels Vice President George Bush the most sanctimonious in a
field full of self-righteousness and calls former candidate Gary
Hart ``a clear example of a dour approach to life.''
   The other men who would be president are no better when it comes
to humor, he said. ``They're basically a sterling bunch but I don't
hear the humanity of humor in them.''
   Boskin, 58, believes candidates need humor to prove they are
human, quick-thinking and slightly self-effacing _ ``not humor as a
form of oppression or a weapon but as a means of liberation or
perspective.''
   He links a demise of lightness with the rise of electronic
media, starting with radio. Until the 1930s, storytelling was an
art form, and public figures could rise a long way with a knack for
spinning good yarns.
   Now, with television time so precious and expensive, Boskin
said, ``Politicians think they have to get everything in in a
minute instead of seeing things in a larger contextual way.''
   The candidates do manage an occasional jab, an occasional jibe,
he admits. Bushy-browed Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis
recently joked that Rep. Richard Gephardt had ``eyebrow envy'' _ a
line fed to him by an aide.
   ``You don't hear them spontaneously making things up as they go
along,'' Boskin said. ``What I've often argued is Dukakis needs a
levity adviser. The story about him is he's so straight he even
lines up his socks in his top drawer.''
   So who among recent U.S. leaders had a light touch? Boskin
admired John F. Kennedy and Hubert Humphrey.
   Asked why he appointed his brother attorney general, Kennedy
once replied ``because he needs the experience.'' Boskin said
Humphrey ``would poke fun at himself for talking too long. He would
say `I should shut up now, but I can't.'''
   And which of this year's candidates are featured in the jokes
that criss-cross the nation and sometimes connect with pop culture
via television comedians?
   ``I hear jokes about Bush and Hart and nobody else,'' Boskin
said. ``And a continuance of Ronald Reagan jokes and how ridiculous
he is. He's fallen in prestige. You can tell through the humor.''
   According to Boskin, President Reagan is a ``throwback'' because
he tells stories. Reagan displayed an ability to laugh at himself
after he was shot in 1981, quipping that he hoped the doctors were
Republicans and quoting Winston Churchill about being shot at
``with no apparent effect.''
   ``If you can't laugh at youself and laugh at a situation it
bespeaks an inflexibility,'' Boskin said.
   ``I think one of the problems in America is we separate humor
out from seriousness. Politicians who are obviously concerned about
getting elected are more hypersensitive to this than others. They
think if they use humor they can't be taken seriously.''
   On the contrary, Boskin argues, if candidates show a sense of
humor the public is more likely to warm to them when talk turns to
weightier issues.
   To counter the Seven Dwarfs talk, the Democrats ``should have
gone to the five and dime and bought masks and gone before the
cameras,'' Boskin said, in all seriousness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
