<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Germany-Scam     03-25 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Germany-Scam,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Yugoslavs Bilked West German Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslav workers cheated West
Germany of up to $60 million in unemployment funds, authorities
said Friday.
   Bavarian police spokesman Gerhard Hoppe said 74 Yugoslavs had
been arrested in the past two weeks in the case. He said more
arrests were possible.
   Those arrested were suspected of fraudulently obtaining jobless
compensation worth $303,000. But he said other Yugoslavs apparently
bilked the West Germany government of $30 million to $60 million.
   The suspects had formerly worked in West Germany and applied for
unemployment compensation after losing their jobs, according to
Hoppe. They later moved back to Yugoslavia but made regular trips
to West Germany to continue collecting unemployment funds, he said.
   West German law stipulates only residents of the country are
eligible for unemployment payments.
   About 590,000 Yugoslavs live in West Germany. Most are employed
as ``guest workers'' who remain citizens of their home countries.
</TEXT>
