<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Torture     03-25 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Torture,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Suspects Kenyan Died of Police Torture, but No Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man linked to a leftist opposition group
probably died from police torture, but no one can be charged
because the authorities' own inquiry was substandard, a judge ruled
Friday.
   Njenga Karanja, 42, was held without charge and incommunicado
for three weeks before he died in February 1987 with injuries
consistent with beatings, according to testimony at the High Court
Inquest.
   Government Special Branch officers, who are responsible for
internal security, arrested Karanja at a coffee shop he owns in
Nakuru, 100 miles northwest of Nairobi, on Feb. 7, 1987. They
accused him of links with Mwakenya, a clandestine Marxist group.
   The group opposes the one-party state run by the
Western-leaning, capitalist government of President Daniel arap
Moi's Kenya African National Union.
   Ooki Ooko-Ombaka, a lawyer for Karanja's family, told the
inquest Karanja's death was the result of officials ``gone crazy
with unchecked power.''
   Amnesty International, a London-based human rights group, said
in a July report on Kenya that Karanja reportedly was tortured by
Special Branch officers.
   Chief Magistrate Joseph Mango said he suspected the prisoner had
indeed been tortured. However, he said the Special Branch's own
investigation into Karanja's death was ``not up to standard'' and
conducted ``with some kind of fear.''
   He recommended that Attorney General Matthew Muli's office
further investigate the case, but Muli wasn't bound by Mango's
ruling.
   Karanja, also a well-known road rally driver, is one of six
people who have died in police custody in Kenya in the last 14
months.
</TEXT>
