<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Funeral     03-25 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Funeral,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Bury Victims of Israeli Air Raid Vowing Revenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry Palestinians on Friday buried six
of the eight women guerrillas killed in an Israeli air raid, and
they vowed to avenge their death by continuing the fight against
the Jewish state.
   ``Allahu Akbar (God is great), we shall avenge your death!''
chanted the mourners, many with their eyes brimming with tears.
   ``We shall kill all those who killed you! Your blood will not go
cheap!'' shrieked the mother of one of the dead women.
   The coffins, draped in Palestinian flags, were driven to Beirut
in ambulances from the southen port city of Sidon, where the eight
were killed Wednesday in an Israeli air strike on bases manned by
guerrillas of Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council.
   About 3,000 Palestinians, men, women and children, carrying
Palestinian and Lebanese flags marched in the funeral procession
from west Beirut's Mar Elias refugee camp to the cemetery.
   Children carried wreaths from various Palesitnian and Lebanese
leftist factions. A wreath, signed Fatah-RC, led the procession
ahead of a contingent of armed Palestinian guerrillas.
   Many mourners carried placards proclaiming the Palestinians'
determination to continue the fight to liberate Palestine.
   Women ululated as the procession marched slowly to the
accompaniment of Palestinian revolutionary songs blared from
loudspeakers.
   Only six of the women were buried in Beirut's Martyrs' Cemetery.
The bodies of the other two were buried in refugee camps elsewhere
in Lebanon.
   Helmeted Syrian soldiers in charge of security in west Beirut
fired their Soviet-made Kalashnikov rifles in a final salute as the
six coffins were lowered into the ground.
   The Fatah Revolutionary Council group is led by convicted
terrorist Abu Nidal, who broke away from Yasser Arafat's mainstream
Palestine Liberation Organization in 1974.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, tops the wanted
lists in the United States and Europe.
   In addition to the eight girls killed in Wednesday's raid,
another 15 people were wounded.
   An Israeli air raid Thursday against Fatah-RC bases in the same
three villages of Bekesta, Majdelyoun and Salhiyeh south of the
port city of Sidon left nine people dead and five wounded.
</TEXT>
