<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Zoo-Tuberculosis     03-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zoo-Tuberculosis,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Zoo Animals Expose Employees To Tuberculosis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four San Diego Zoo employees tested positive
for tuberculosis after being exposed to infected monkeys, and a
state health official blamed improper quarantine procedures.
   Three of six endangered Tibetan macaques have died of
tuberculosis since arriving last March from the Chengdu Zoo in
China, officials said Thursday. The other macaques remain
quarantined although they tested negative for the disease.
   None of the four workers has tuberculosis so far, though one is
under medication, The San Diego Union quoted an unidentified source
as saying.
   A veterinarian who inspected the zoo for the state last spring
said Thursday he found several deficiencies that could have led to
the infection.
   Edmond Bayer, a consultant with the state Department of Health
Services, said employees did not regularly wear masks or gloves
while around the infectious macaques and were not told to wash
their hands before leaving the quarantine area.
   Don Janssen, the zoo's director of veterinary medicine, said
those safety procedures weren't in effect at that time. A memo
shows Janssen implemented changes last May to comply with Bayer's
findings.
   Among those infected with tuberculosis was Debbie Hewitt, 27, a
senior hospital keeper.
   ``I was upset and I'm still upset because we didn't have any
policy about quarantine procedures at the time,'' Hewitt said.
``I'm working there and I expect my employer to protect me about
things I don't know about and that wasn't being done.''
   In another incident, the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration recently fined the zoo $1,060 for two violations
stemming from improper animal and keeper contact.
   Zoo officials say the facility is contesting the citations and
declined comment.
   OSHA officials said their inspection was prompted by a complaint
and not related to the tuberculosis infection or the state
inspector's findings.
   OSHA cited the zoo for failing to protect its employees from the
possibility of contracting infectious diseases from animals, and
because keepers failed to use such protective equipment as boots,
gloves, aprons, pants, and protective eye wear or face shields.
   Tuberculosis, a bacterial disease, once was a leading cause of
death in the United States. It now is rarely fatal. Those who test
positive for the disease don't necessarily develop active cases,
said Nancy Bowen, TB control officer for the county.
</TEXT>
