<DOCNO> AP880325-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Republicans-Nicaragua Bjt   03-25 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Republicans-Nicaragua, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Congressmen Wary of Accord; To One It's `Disguised
Surrender'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Republican members of Congress are
wary of the cease-fire pact in Nicaragua _ one calls it a
``disguised surrender'' _ and say the United States will have to
continue pressuring the Sandinistas until they install a truly
democratic system.
   At the same time, the congressmen _ attending a GOP retreat here
_ say it was American pressure and American aid to the Contras that
forced the Sandinistas to deal with the Contras.
   The result was this week's dramatic turn of events: a 60-day
cease-fire agreement signed by representatives of the Nicaraguan
government and the guerrilla leaders, and a Sandinista promise to
institute democratic reforms.
   ``The goal has never been just a cease-fire,'' said Rep. Dick
Cheney, R-Wyo., one of six dozen GOP lawmakers at the retreat.
   The provisions on democratic reforms in the cease-fire pact are
``weak,'' he said, and the United States should try to keep the
Contras alive as a fighting force ``as a spur to continued good
faith on the part of the Sandinistas.''
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said it was ``reasonably
implausible'' that the Sandinistas would live up to their promises
for reforms. But if they do, it would have made the years of
supporting the Contras a successful policy.
   ``The values of the West will have won,'' he said. ``Our goal
was to have freedom, not to have a war.''
   Gingrich said one of the reasons he had doubts about the pact
was because the Contras were negotiating from a weakened state,
their U.S. aid having been cut off by Congress a month ago.
   It's too early to tell, he said, ``to what degree this is a true
negotiation and to what degree this is a disguised surrender'' by
the Contras.
   Cheney acknowledged that the Contras were ``in difficult
straits'' but said they ``still have some potential.''
   Rep. Rod Chandler, R-Wash., who has co-sponsored a plan to renew
military aid to the Contras, said the Sandinistas had ``failed
miserably'' when they crossed over into Honduras recently in what
he said was an attempt to ``deal a knockout blow to the Contras.''
   Chandler said the Sandinistas were under pressure not only
because of the Contras but because of their war-torn economy that
has resulted from the insurgency. ``If we had never supported the
Contras, they'd have never been a factor,'' he said.
   But if the Contras fold their tents and it is ``back to the
usual Sandinista behavior'' of totalitarian rule, he said, the
United States will have to ``take some action with external forces
... external, including the United States.''
   ``It's down to that,'' he said. ``It's definitely a new era.''
   In the meantime, Chandler said, he expected Congress to rapidly
approve some new humanitarian support for the Contras with the
option of adding military aid if things turn sour.
   Democratic leaders have been discussing with the White House and
with congressional Republicans a $48 million, year long package of
non-lethal aid. The plan would allow expedited consideration of
arms shipments if President Reagan requested them.
   Rep. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said that he felt the Contras ``were
not put in a very good bargaining position by the United States
Congress.'' He said he hopes that democracy takes root, but added:
``I'm a cynic.''
   DeWine said he feared ``this is just the beginning of the end
for the Contras.'' He said he wouldn't be surprised if the
Sandinistas over the next six to nine months tightened up their
authoritarian rule and at that point the United States is left with
``very little leverage.''
   ``It's a containment policy at that point'' with the U.S. trying
to help neighboring countries such as El Salvador and Costa Rica
maintain democracy.
   DeWine said he supported peace but, he added, ``Is it the peace
of slavery? Is it the peace of Eastern Europe? Is it the peace of
North Korea? Is it the peace of Cuba?''
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., said he was more optimistic.
   ``If they really live up to their commitments, then it really is
a good deal,'' he said. If not, however, ``then we've got really
big problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
