<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Homework     03-25 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Homework,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Mounts Last Effort to Ease Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration today launched its
final effort before leaving office to remove four-decade-old
prohibitions on industrial homework in five industries.
   The Labor Department said it will publish proposed regulations
next week that would allow employers to contract work from people
in their homes in producing gloves and mittens, embroideries,
buttons and buckles, handkerchiefs and some jewelry.
   Unlike the administration's two earlier attempts to deregulate
industrial homework, officials said this time they will not try to
remove the ban on women's apparel.
   Assistant Labor Secretary Fred Alvarez acknowledged that the
exclusion of women's apparel, an area in which investigators have
found about half of the violations of the current law, was aimed at
defusing opposition from the 210,000-member International Ladies
Garment Workers Union.
   The proposed revisions also do not attempt to overturn state
bans on the same type of work at home in Hawaii, California,
Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, Connecticut, New York, Rhode Island
and New Jersey.
   The ILGWU, other unions and employer associations in California
and New York led a firestorm of attacks on the administration's
last two efforts to repeal the bans in 1981 and 1986.
   As a result, only the ban on knitted outerwear was lifted in
1984.
   Alvarez said the latest proposal will be open for 30 days of
public comment after it is published in the Federal Register next
week.
   Despite expected challenges from unions and anticipated court
appeals, he said the administration hopes to have the prohibitions
removed before Reagan leaves office next January.
   ``It seems to me we ought to be able to get a final rule
sometime this summer,'' he said.
   All of the current prohibitions were adopted from 1941 to 1943
under the Fair Labor Standards Act in response to what then was
perceived as rampant exploitation of mostly immigrant home workers
paid on a piecework basis.
   ``The recommendations of this administration demonstrate that it
has learned nothing from history,'' said the AFL-CIO. ``The record
shows that industrial homework has brought nothing but unfair
competition, long hours and low wages for our poorest and most
disadvantaged workers.''
   Alvarez, however, said unions have not yet had a chance to study
the latest proposal, which includes what he called a new set of
``enforcement teeth'' such as requiring bonds from employers with
records of paying less than minimum wages or other labor law
violations.
</TEXT>
