<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0552 03-25 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Son Says Auto Dealership Was in Good Financial Shape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Mecham's son appearing
today, picking up 11th graf pvs, `Mecham agreed ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Arz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's son testified today that
the family auto dealership was in ``very strong'' shape and that an
$80,000 loan from the governor's protocol fund was intended to
provide higher interest for the fund.
   Dennis Mecham, general manager of Mecham Pontiac, testified at
the governor's impeachment trial that his father called him in
mid-July 1987 and ``asked if I could use $80,000 in the dealership
operations.''
   The governor was expected to take the stand later today.
   Dennis Mecham said his father told him ``they were looking to
generate additional interest'' for the protocol fund.
   The prosecution has contended that the dealership was in dire
financial straits and needed the loan to meet its payroll.
   However, Dennis Mecham, asked by defense attorney Jerris Leonard
to describe the dealership's general financial condition at the
time, said, ``It was very strong.''
   About $6,000 of the loan was repaid to the protocol fund in
early October, and the governor's son said he was asked Oct. 22 by
Mecham then-chief of staff Jim Colter to repay the balance ``since
there was a political question.'' The repayment was financed by
family members, he said.
   On Thursday, former Mecham special assistant Sam Steiger said he
did not consider the protocol fund to be public money and thus the
loan was legal.
   ``I think we have a politically stupid thing that was done, but
not an illegal thing,'' Steiger said. ``I think it's a very clear
demonstration that here was a man, Governor Mecham, who had total
confidence that he was going to be able to repay this.
   ``He did not sense the public perception of what that might
appear to look like to other people because he was so convinced of
the correctness of his own approach,'' Steiger said. ``Now that's
the man that I knew as governor.''
   Steiger is scheduled to go on trial Monday on a charge of theft
by extortion for allegedly trying to influence the vote of a state
Parole Board member.
   Mecham is accused of misusing the protocol fund, which was
created with inaugural proceeds and intended to pay for gifts for
visiting dignitaries.
   Prosecutors claim the money became public funds when it was
turned over to the governor's office and that Mecham tried to cover
up the loan.
   However, the defense contends the protocol fund was private
money and that the loan was a good business deal because it earned
a higher interest rate for the fund.
   Mecham agreed Thursday in Tucson that borrowing from the
protocol fund ``was a dumb thing to do politically,'' but he
insisted it ``wasn't illegal.''
   He accused House prosecutors of having ``to make some kind of a
devious program out of this in order to have any fabric to say
anything about us.''
   ``They would be laughed out of any court in the country,
really,'' Mecham said. ``The only place they've got any standing is
because this is a political issue; it's really kind of a tragedy,
but I think our case will take care of that very easily.''
   The Senate already has heard testimony on the first impeachment
allegation that Mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an
alleged death threat by a state official against former top Mecham
aide Donna Carlson.
   The third allegation charges him with concealing a $350,000
campaign loan.
   A conviction would remove Mecham from office, although the trial
could continue on whether to bar him from holding any future office.
   A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required to convict
Mecham. He is the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six
decades and the first ever in Arizona.
   Mecham is scheduled to go on criminal trial April 21 on six
felony charges of hiding the $350,000 loan and faces a May 17
recall election.
</TEXT>
