<2ND_LINE>PM-Visitor's Nightmare, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Parents Stand Vigil Over Critically Injured Daughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf, `When she ...,' with comment
from boyfriend.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young Irish woman, who came here to visit a
sweetheart but found him jailed on murder charges, was struck by a
car on St. Patrick's Day and lapsed into a coma, say her family and
friends.
   ``The girl is a beautiful looking girl. When I first saw her
lying there in the hospital, I thought to myself, `It's Snow White
in a trance,''' said Gerry Archbold, a director of the city's
Irish-American Heritage Center.
   Margaret Hanley, 22, was listed in critical condition today at
Weiss Memorial Hospital, where her parents are keeping a vigil at
her bedside.
   Stephen and Ann Hanley left their 13 younger children behind in
Coolock, a suburb of Dublin, and flew to Chicago to be with her.
Neighbors collected money to help pay for their trip.
   Miss Hanley's father said he was against his daughter's trip to
the United States earlier this month. ``But she wanted to travel
the world, you know,'' he said. And she had a special reason for
her trip.
   Last year she met a man named Danny Stokes, the brother of a
girlfriend, who'd returned to Ireland for a visit. She was
attracted to him.
   ``He took her out, and they must have communicated (when he
returned to Chicago),'' Archbold said. ``She was infatuated with
him.''
   So Miss Hanley, an aspiring actress who dreamed of traveling the
world, left her home for a three-week vacation and a visit to
Stokes.
   When she arrived in Chicago, she learned that Stokes was in
jail, charged with murder, Archbold said. He said he did not know
the details of the case against Stokes, but officials at the Cook
County Jail confirmed Thursday night that a Daniel Stokes was held
there on murder charges.
   Stokes said today in a telephone interview from jail that Miss
Hanley knew he was in custody before she came and wanted to help
him.
   ``It was very hard to accept, the emotional stress of seeing me
behind bars,'' he said.
   A disillusioned Miss Hanley called her family, telling them
she'd decided to return home and was planning to leave last Friday.
``She said she'd explain it all to us later,'' her father said.
   But the day before she was to leave, Miss Hanley was struck by a
car as she crossed a street on the North Side.
   Her leg and hip were broken, but she was conscious as she was
taken to a hospital emergency room, where she slipped into a coma
apparently induced by a blood clot, doctors said.
   Her parents spend their days at their daughter's bedside and
their nights at a room given to them by priests at the St. Patrick
Fathers home.
   ``All we can do is wait,'' Hanley said. ``There is nothing we
can do for her. Where there is life, there is hope.''
</TEXT>
