<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomeSales     03-25 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Of Existing Homes Up 3.8 Percent In February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes, after declining for
three straight months, posted a modest increase of 3.8 percent in
February, a real estate trade group reported Friday.
   The National Association of Realtors said that existing
single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.29 million units in February. While this was 11.3 percent
below the sales level of a year ago, it was the first advance since
a 1.2 percent rise in October.
   Sales fell 2.9 percent in November, 1.2 percent in December and
4.8 percent in January as the housing market was rocked by volatile
mortgage rates and consumer worries sparked by the October stock
market collapse.
   The February increase in sales was credited to better economic
news, falling interest rates and renewed consumer confidence.
Fixed-rate mortgages, which stood at 10.61 percent at the beginning
of the year, have fallen into single-digits, standing at 9.92
percent currently.
   ``Lower interest rates have brought the consumer back into the
market,'' said John Tuccillo, chief economist for the association.
``February's existing home sales numbers indicate good health on
the part of the housing sector, which, in the sixth year of
expansion, is far from dead.''
   Tuccillo predicted the lower mortgage rates would help boost
sales even further in the months ahead.
   The rise in home sales was accompanied by a slight increase in
home prices. The median or mid-point price of a home increased to
$88,300, up from $87,400 in January.
   The increase in sales was led by a 12.8 percent jump in sales in
the South, which rose to an annual rate of 1.23 million units,
still 4.7 percent below the level of activity a year ago. This
region has been hard hit by depressed conditions in the oil
industry.
   Sales were also up in the Northeast, climbing 8.2 percent to an
annual rate of 660,000 units.
   Sales fell 5.4 percent in the Midwest to an annual rate of
870,000 units, but analysts blamed this decline on unusually severe
weather in the region during February. Sales dipped a small 1.9
percent in the West to an annual rate of 520,000 units.
</TEXT>
