<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0407 03-25 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0407,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Belaguer remarks; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
Belaguer elected.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Joaquin Balaguer of the Dominican
Republic met with President Reagan today, declaring that his island
nation is ``as peaceful and tranquil as it can possibly be in
today's world.''
   Balaguer was expected to seek increases in aid and sugar quotas
during the meeting, according to a senior administration official
who spoke on condition he not be identified.
   The official said the United States was ``looking for ways to be
helpful.''
   As the two leaders posed for photographers before their meeting,
Balaguer was asked if everything was calm and peaceful in his
country, which has seen violent uprisings in the past.
   ``Yes, everything is calm and peaceful,'' he said. ``As peaceful
and tranquil as it can possibly be in today's world.''
   Reagan, asked if the same could be said of the United States,
replied, ``I would say that the situation is normal.''
   Balaguer, elected to his fifth term as president of the
Caribbean island nation in 1986, arrived in Washington on Thursday
and was meeting with Secretary of State George P. Shultz and
Secretary of Defense Frank C. Carlucci as well as Reagan today.
   Reagan's meeting with Balaguer follows a visit Thursday to a
high school in the Washington suburb of Vienna. Appearing with
Education Secretary William J. Bennett, Reagan praised a trend
toward ``free-market principles'' in education that provide
incentives for teachers who achieve superior performance.
   The United States has sharply reduced aid to the Dominican
Republic in recent years and has lowered its quotas on imports of
sugar, a major Dominican crop.
   ``Their economic difficulties, and they have economic
difficulties, are largely the product of our sugar policy,'' said
the senior official, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified.
   ``Our imposition of lower and lower sugar quotas every year has
diminished their ability to sell sugar to the United States and
that has been a really crippling blow to the Dominican economy,''
the official said.
   The Reagan administration has pressed Congress unsuccessfully
for changes in U.S. sugar policy.
   Inflation is running at around 30 percent and unemployment at
close to that figure in the Dominican Republic, the official said.
   ``We are very appreciative of the efforts of President Balaguer
to keep the economy of his country on an even keel,'' the official
said. ``I don't think there is anybody in the Dominican Republic
who is appreciative of our aid cuts or cuts in the sugar quota.''
   Although the Dominican Republic has received substantial U.S.
aid in the past, it is down for nothing in either economic support
funds or military assistance in the fiscal 1988 budget. The figure
for development assistance is a relatively modest $18.7 million.
   The sugar quota declined about 27 per cent this year and is ``on
a downward trend,'' the official said.
   In 1983 the United States bought 500,000 tons, or $188 million
worth, of Dominican sugar. This year the total was 125,000 tons,
valued at about $50 million.
   ``They will ask for additional aid, either direct financial aid
or other forms of assistance,'' the official said.
   ``We are looking for ways to be helpful,'' he added.
 
</TEXT>
