<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   03-25 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists' Committee Dissolved in Effort to End Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Armenia's government ordered the
dissolution Friday of a committee agitating for annexation of a
region in neighboring Azerbaijan. Soldiers and helicopters
patrolled tense Yerevan, the capital, in case of trouble.
   The Kremlin declared this week that the campaign for annexation
of the Nagorno-Karabakh region was ``intolerable.''
   Public protests had been called for Saturday in Yerevan, but
radio broadcasts in Armenia and Azerbaijan warned citizens of both
Caucasus republics Friday against illegal demonstrations.
   The broadcasts announced new regulations requiring permits 10
days in advance of all public gatherings.
   Hovik Vassilian, an Armenian activist reached by telephone, said
the Saturday demonstrations ``won't happen.'' Vassilian said they
were called off, ``considering the situation.''
   He also said activists had learned that Armenian nationalist
Paruyr Arikyan was arrested Thursday night. He said they did not
know the charges, but Arikyan had provided information about the
protests to foreign reporters in Moscow.
   An Armenian Communist Party newspaper reaching Moscow on Friday
said the republic ``remains tense and explosive.'' It spoke of
``unpredictable consequences'' if the demonstrations were held.
   Activists and official sources in Yerevan most Armenians
appeared to be wary of illegal protest because of the crackdown.
   A duty officer at the police ministry described the security
precautions by telephone and said Yerevan was ``fairly calm.'' He
would not give his nam.
   Vassilian said groups of three to five soldiers of the internal
security forces were patrolling with police and that helicopters
had been circling over the city for three days.
   Repeated attempts to telephone Azerbaijan on Friday were
unsuccessful.
   On Thursday, the national party's governing Politburo issued an
eight-year plan for dealing with complaints about discrimination
against ethnic Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh, where they are more
than 75 percent of the population.
   Pravda and Izvestia, the party and government newspapers, gave
prominent display Friday to letters from readers urging reason and
patience in resolving the territorial dispute between Armenians,
most of whom are Christians, and the predominently Shiite Moslem
population of Azerbaijan.
   The letters, and official commentaries, had the apparent purpose
of portraying the leadership's approach to the sensitive ethnic
issue as a wiser course than strikes and demonstrations.
   Tass, the official news agency, said the Politburo's eight-year
plan provides for more housing, roads, schools and social services
in the disputed region, and more Armenian television programming
and literature.
   Concern that Nagorno-Karabakh was losing its traditional
Armenian character was among the reasons prompting calls for
annexation.
   Armenian residents of the area began protests in mid-February
after the national party Central Committee rejected a request from
the the Nagorno-Karabakh government for union with Armenia. The
region, slightly smaller than Delaware, was part of Armenia until
1923.
   Official media described the annexation drive as an extremist
action, and hundreds of thousands of Armenians demonstrated in the
streets of Yerevan. The mass unrest abated only after Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed for calm and reason.
   On Feb. 28, extremists in Sumgait, Azerbaijan, went on a rampage
to protest the Armenian demands, and officials said at least 32
people were killed. The official reports said 197 were injured and
about 400 arrested for murder, rape, robbery or other crimes in the
industrial city.
   Armenian supporters of the annexation proposal, including some
prominent officials in the southern republic, formed a committee to
press the Nagorno-Karabakh issue and called the protests for
Saturday.
   The committee withdrew the appeal for protests, but nonetheless
became a target of authorities.
   Wednesday's issue of Kommunist, the Armenian party daily that
reached Moscow on Friday, accused the committee of blackmail,
threats and anti-party attacks.
   It said officials were ordered to ``take measures necessary to
avert meetings on March 26'' and party organizations were told to
``neutralize activities of Nagorno-Karabakh `committees' because at
present their actions are politically harmful.''
   Vassilian, the activist, also said the committee was ordered
``closed'' Friday.
   Prominent officials and literary figures appealed on radio and
television for patience and an end to protests and strikes, he said.
   Pravda said it was suspending an Armenian journalist who
contributed to a report on the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute but
denounced it after publication Monday.
   The party newspaper said it had handwritten copies of the
information submitted by the journalist, identified as Y.
Arakelyan, and his report conformed with the published article. It
did not give details of his original material.
</TEXT>
