<HEAD>Twelve Injured When Oil Rig Explodes in `Big Ball of Fire'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE conditions, count shows only 12
people injured, picking up 3rd graf pvs, `The men ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NESS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil rig explosion unleashed a ``big
ball of fire'' that injured 12 people, including several women and
children, who were celebrating a new well, authorities said.
   Ten people were still hospitalized today, including a 5-year-old
boy and a 32-year-old man reported in critical condition with
burns, hospital officials here and in Wichita said. One man was
listed in serious condition, and the others were in fair condition.
   The men, women and children were gathered in front of the oil
rig shortly before 10 p.m. Thursday and were ``supposedly bringing
in a new well'' when it exploded, Ness County Sheriff Gary O'Brien
said.
   Flames engulfed the building before firefighters could control
the fire, O'Brien said. Crews extinguished most of the fire by
11:30 p.m. The cause of the fire and explosion has not been
determined.
   O'Brien said he did not know the name of the company that owned
the well, about 3{ miles northwest of Ness City in western Kansas.
