<HEAD>Hindus Gather in Show of Solidarity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Birendra of Nepal called for
solidarity among the globe's 650 million Hindus Friday as he opened
the World Hindu Conference.
   About 1,200 participants from 19 countries attended the opening
ceremony of the four-day meeting in Katmandu.
   Representatives from Bangladesh, Canada, Fiji, Guyana,
Indonesia, India, Kenya, Mauritius, Nepal, Netherlands, New
Zealand, Norway, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Singapore, Spain, the United
Kingdom, the Soviet Union and West Germany paraded through the
conference venue at National Stadium.
   King Birendra, in his inaugural speech, said the conference
would ``succeed in establishing unity and solidarity among Hindus
wherever they be showing the ideal way of life.''
   Hindus live in significant numbers in at least 80 countries
worldwide, with the vast majority in India. Their religion grew
from a synthesis of indigenous beliefs with culture brought to
India by the Aryan people around 1500 B.C.
