<HEAD>Taxi Drivers Get Jail Sentence in Protest of Smog Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge sentenced 20 taxi drivers to jail
Friday after they defied the city's new anti-smog ban.
   The new rules, which allows taxis and private cars in a
5-square-mile area of downtown only on alternate weekdays and on
weekends, are aimed at dispelling the acrid cloud that hovers over
the city in still weather. The cabbies say they are not at fault
and the ban hurts their business.
   The 20 taxi drivers were sentenced to five weeks in jail.
Another 35 cabbies were fined $150 each, said a judiciary spokesman
requesting anonymity.
   The 55 cabbies drove into the banned area on Monday and Tuesday
during protests organized by their union, which seeks daily access
for all the city's 15,000 taxis.
   The spokesman said all 20 cabbies were freed after appealing the
sentences.

</TEXT>
