<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eggs-Dioxin     03-25 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eggs-Dioxin,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Advisory Issued On Egg Contamination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OROVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health authorities have warned that eggs
from two farms near the site of a chemical fire last year contain
toxic dioxin at levels 100 times greater than in normal eggs.
   Officials of the state Health Services Department said Thursday
they advised about about 45 familes living near the Koppers Wood
Treatment Plant not to eat eggs or chicken from the two family
farms.
   Koppers was the site last April of a fire and explosion that
left residues of a toxic wood preservative used at the plant.
   Dioxins are a class of toxic chemicals found in a variety of
chemical compounds, including some preservatives. Minute levels are
also generally found in all animal products.
   While there is no proof that dioxin has ever killed anyone, a
1980 report by the Environmental Protection Agency said immediate
effects of exposure to dioxin can include burning in the eyes,
nose, and throat; headaches; itching, swelling and redness of the
face; dizziness; nausea and vomiting.
   There is also increasing evidence of an association between
occupational exposure to dioxins and a rare form of tumor called
soft tissue sarcoma, according to the national Centers for Disease
Control.
   The eggs and chickens may have been contaminated as a result of
the Koppers accident, but an investigation is continuing to pin
down the source, said state Health Services Director Ken Kizer.
   ``If we knew the cause of the contamination, we would say so,''
said Bob Borzelleri of the department's toxics division.
   Samples taken from the two affected farms last May showed dioxin
levels of 10 parts per trillion, compared with levels of 0.1 parts
per trillion found in eggs a few miles away.
   Samples taken this month show dioxin levels ranging from 15 to
30 parts per trillion.
   Eating one contaminated egg a day over a 70-year lifetime would
increase a person's chances of developing cancer from 250-in-1,000
to 253-in-1,000, the department's scientists estimate.
   Herb Lightle, who owns one of the farms, said he was angry that
the state testing took so long.
   ``One of my daughters loves to eat eggs. ... I'm worried for my
kids,'' Lightle said. ``The state told us after the fire it was OK
to eat our eggs and stuff out of the garden. They should have
issued an advisory from the very start. I would rather have buried
the eggs or thrown them out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1347EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Congress     03-25 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Congress,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Li Endorces Reform, But Sounds Note of Caution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Premier Li Peng declared Friday that
economic reform was irreversible but cautioned against hasty change
as he opened the National People's Congress.
   The 59-year-old technocrat is expected to be confirmed as
premier during the legislature's 20-day session.
   In the 2{-hour speech, Li resoundingly endorsed the nation's
reform goals. But he stayed true to form by sounding repeated notes
of caution against expecting rapid prosperity or making changes
faster than people can accept them.
   ``We must not rush headlong into mass action, issue arbitrary
orders and spoil things by excessive enthusiasm,'' Li warned. ``We
cannot succeed if we are too impatient for quick results.''
   The new National People's Congress, which sits for five years,
is expected to approve key measures giving legal underpinning to
the market-style economic reforms that have doubled Chinese incomes
over the past decade.
   The congress itself is intended to be a showpiece of the
reforms. Its 2,970 delegates were elected by provincial
legislatures and the military using multiple candidate balloting
for the first time.
   Several working meetings are being opened for the first time to
foreign reporters, in addition to the ceremonial opening and
closing sessions. Before the start of Friday's session, reporters
were allowed to mix freely with delegates as they drank tea at
small tables in the cavernous entry room of the Great Hall of the
People and watched ``Tom and Jerry'' cartoons on a small TV at one
end.
   In his speech, Li applauded the achievements of China's economic
decentralization and said the state's role in the economy gradually
will be reduced from that of planner to indirect market regulator.
   Li generally is regarded as more cautious than his predecessor,
Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, who has become the leading
architect of all-out economic and political decentralization.
   However, he echoed Zhao's words by declaring that increased
productivity must be ``the criterion for judging all our work.''
   At a major party congress in October at which he was named party
general secretary, Zhao said development must take precedence over
ideology if China is to end its chronic poverty.
   ``We should continue to put reform at the center of all our
undertakings,'' Li said in agreement. ``It has become an
irreversible trend for the masses and cadres alike to take an
active part in the reform.''
   Zhao, who sat behind Li on the stage, appeared restless during
the long speech. On his left, senior leader Deng Xiaoping, 83, the
initiator of the reforms, followed the text closely while
chain-smoking.
   He said price increases were China's No. 1 economic and social
problem, but for the first time in public endorsed continuing the
gradual decontrol of prices long distorted by stae subsidies.
   However, he said workers will be given direct subsidies for some
staple foods, on which price ceilings will be imposed. Inflation
was 7.3 percent nationwide last year but hit 19 percent in some
cities during the summer.
   Li said that in the next five years, China must increase grain
production, encourage scientific development, revitalize the
bureaucracy and reduce controls on enterprises.
   One of the few specific goals he set was to raise grain
production by about 8 million tons, or 2 percent, per year. Grain
production hit a record of 407 million tons in 1984 but since has
declined, causing shortages of livestock feed and pork rationing.
   Delegates interrupted Li's speech with applause 17 times,
generally at natural pauses in the text. When he finished, applause
was brief and perfunctory and the huge hall emptied within five
minutes as top officials rushed to their chauffeur-driven Mercedes
Benzes and ordinary delegates to their buses.
   Li, grinning widely, was congratulated by his colleagues in the
party and government leadership as he walked back to his seat and
gulped tea.
   The congress will hold four more plenary sessions to hear
reports from top officials before gathering April 13 to vote on
proposed legislation and elect top officials.
   The congress also is expected to name Gen. Yang Shangkun as
successor to outgoing President Li Xiannian.
   Although the congress long has served as a rubber-stamp body for
Communist Party decisions, in the past few years it has taken a
more active role in debating and even amending party proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0121 </DOCNO>
