<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BlueFlu 4thLd-Writethru a0575 03-25 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blue Flu, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0575,0938</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police, Firefighters Ending Sick-Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with agreement to end sick-out,
edit to conform, picking up 13th graf pvs, `Gardner, appearing
....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and firefighters today agreed to
end their day-and-a-half bout of ``blue flu'' and return to work
after city officials promised to set up a committee to discuss
their salary complaints, a police representative said.
   ``Apparently, the mayor is appointing a committee this afternoon
comprised of members of the City Council,'' said Cpl. Dave Dickens,
adding that the committee would meet with police officers Monday.
   He said police and firefighters would return to work this
afternoon as part of an agreement that included creation of the
committee.
   Mayor Chuck Gardner this morning ordered police and firefighters
to end their sick-out, saying there's a strong possibility those
who refused to return to work would be fired.
   On Thursday, officers ignored similar back-to-work orders from a
circuit judge and the City Council, forcing city officials to call
in state police, shut down two fire stations and declare a civil
emergency.
   This morning, 119 of 144 police officers remained off the job
for the second consecutive day to protest a 2 percent pay raise,
but 30 of 44 firefighters reported for work, said Ed Esposito, a
City Hall aide.
   ``They seem to be recognizing the concern that firefighters who
had been on duty since 8 a.m. Wednesday were exhausted,'' he said,
adding there was no indication the firefighters were ending their
sick-out. Most of the firefighters held over when the job action
began were sent home this morning to rest.
   At a press conference today, Gardner said that Thursday was ``a
grace period, allowing cooler heads to review this situation.''
   ``I believe the last 24 hours have given police and firefighters
enough time to obey the court order and return to work, and in
keeping with uniformed services policy I am ordering all police
personnel to report for duty by 2 p.m. this afternoon, and all fire
personnel to report for duty by 6 p.m.''
   When asked what would happen if the officers remained defiant,
he said there was a ``strong possibility'' that those who ignored
his order would be fired.
   The job action in this state capital of 63,000 people, West
Virginia's largest city, began after city officials announced a 2
percent pay raise for city employees effective July 1. Police and
firefighters say the raise is inadequate.
   Gardner said today he will not meet with police and firefighters
until they return to work, and that there is no money for larger
raises.
   ``Let them come forward and show me where the money is,'' he
said.
   Firefighters and police who return to work today face no
punishment, Gardner said, but must have a doctor's excuse.
   Gardner, appearing on television Thursday night, read a
statement announcing that two fire stations in outlying areas of
the city were being closed temporarily because of manpower
shortages.
   ``At this time I am again asking the police and the firefighters
to return to duty at the earliest time or on their next shift,''
Gardner said on WSAZ-TV.
   Earlier in the day, Gardner _ after declaring a state of
emergency _ warned absent workers that ``if you don't come back to
work, you are in contempt of court.''
   Less than an hour before an emergency city council meeting
Thursday, Kanawha County Circuit Judge Patrick Casey issued a
temporary injunction ordering police and firefighters to return to
duty.
   The order was ignored, with 42 of 44 firefighters not reporting
and about a dozen policemen out on a shift that normally has 16 or
17 officers, Gardner said.
   At most, three patrol cars cruised the city Thursday, police
chief Ed Garnett said. ``We're at skeleton now,'' Garnett said, but
the public was ``helping out quite a bit'' by not making
unnecessary calls to dispatchers.
   In addition, two state police cruisers patrolled Charleston
because of the sick-out, state police Sgt. Don Cook said.
   Two fire trucks were taken out of service Thursday evening
because of a manpower shortage and officials said an additional
fire station could be shut down today if the protest continued.
   The city council Thursday unanimously suspended the city's
sick-leave policy, meaning those who called in sick would have to
have a doctor's excuse to get paid for any additional absences.
   The sick-out had the ``potential effect of rendering the city
unable to maintain public order,'' Gardner told the 26 council
members.
   About 20 police officers' wives picketed City Hall on Thursday.
Passing motorists honked their horns in support, and some _ aware
that patrols were down _ took the opportunity to run red lights.
   Many of the wives denied their husbands were striking. ``Mine is
sick. I don't know about everybody else,'' Vicki Robinson said.
``There's no strike.''
   The 2 percent raise averages $438 per employee annually, mayoral
aide Ed Esposito said. He said the uniformed services got a 3
percent raise in the last fiscal year and raises totaling 8 percent
over the past five years, he said.
   The city budget, approved Monday night, includes appropriations
for 165 policemen, 147 firefighters and 10 paramedics.
   Police salaries range from $18,589 for a patrol officer at three
years to $27,673 for a captain with 20 years' experience.
Firefighters pay ranges from $18,409 for a first-year firefighter
to $27,673 for an assistant fire chief with 20 years' experience.
</TEXT>
