<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Shultz-MiddleEast 1stLd-Writethru a0558 03-25 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Middle East, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0558,640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz today
arranged to meet with two members of the Palestine National Council
and discouraged Americans from traveling to the Israeli-held West
Bank and Gaza.
   The travel advisory cited ``continuing disturbances'' in the
areas. In nearly three months of Palestinian protests, 111
Palestinian Arabs and an Israeli soldier have been killed.
   ``We are not issuing am advisory for Israel itself,'' Phyllis
Oakley, the State Department's deputy spokeswoman, said. ``Israel
is safe for American travel.''
   Shultz will hold the meeting with Edward Said, a professor at
Columbia University, and Ibrahim Abu-Lughud, a professor at
Northwestern University, on Saturday ``to discuss our approach to
the Middle East peace process,'' the announcement said.
   Mrs. Oakley stressed that Said and Abu-Lughud are U.S. citizens.
She said the 13-year-old U.S. policy of not dealing with the
Palestine Liberation Organization remained intact.
   ``There is no change in U.S. policy on negotiating with or
recognizing the PLO,'' she said. ``That policy remains as it has
been since 1975.''
   The council is the legislative arm of the PLO. The brief
announcement identified Said and Abu-Lughud only as ``prominent
Americans with an intimate knowledge of contemporary Middle Eastern
politics.''
   The United States, in persuading Israel to relinquish territory
to Egypt and Syria, promised in 1975 it would not deal with the
PLO, which is committed to dismantling the Jewish state. The pledge
subsequently was incorporated into U.S. law.
   Asked if the PLO had given Said and Abu-Lughud permission to
meet with Shultz, the U.S. official said, ``I have nothing on
that.''
   Mrs. Oakley said Shultz initiated the meeting. ``He will discuss
the Palestinian point of view,'' she said. ``They have an intimate
knowledge of Middle Eastern politics.''
   The travel advisory cautioned Americans to avoid going to the
West Bank and Gaza ``until further notice.'' It said Americans
living there ``should exercise particular caution.''
   The situation in East Jerusalem, which was held by Jordan until
1967 and is now part of Israel's capital, was described as
``unpredictable.'' The advisory said Americans should check with
U.S. diplomats in the city before entering the area.
   ``Under all circumstances, Americans should avoid demonstrations
and other situations that have the potential to lead to violence,''
the advisory said. ``American travelers should carry their U.S.
passports at all times.''
   Moshe Arad, the Israeli ambassador, telephoned M. Charles Hill,
an assistant to Shultz, on Thursday to protest the meeting as a
violation of the pledge.
   Said and Abu-Lughud could not be reached immediately to be asked
what they intended to take up with Shultz and whether they had
sought PLO approval for the meeting.
   Earlier this year, Shultz met here with two Palestinians from
the West Bank and Gaza. Their visit was arranged with Israel's
cooperation.
   Shultz had excluded the PLO from his proposal to open
Arab-Israeli negotiations on May 1. His plan calls for Palestinians
approved by the PLO to participate in a joint delegation with
Jordan.
   During a Mideast shuttle last month, Shultz tried to arrange a
meeting in Jerusalem with 15 Palestinian Arabs. Apparently under
PLO orders, none of them showed up.
   Shultz went to a hotel in east Jerusalem, stood in the floodlit
courtyard and read a statement suggesting the Palestinians were
fearful of working with the United States.
   ``Opportunity knocks loudly on your door,'' he said then. ``Now
is the time to get to work. We have a workable plan, and we are
ready to commit our efforts to it. The time is right, together, to
make decisions of historic proportions.''
   Some 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs live on the West Bank of the
Jordan River and in Gaza, along the Mediterranean. The lands were
held by Jordan and Egypt until they were lost to Israel in the 1967
Six-Day war.
</TEXT>
