<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Chad     03-25 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Chad,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Gadhafi Group Claims Libyan Forces Chief in Chad Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of Libya's forces in Chad has
joined a group opposed to Col. Moammar Gadhafi, the opposition
group said Friday.
   The National Front for the Salavation of Libya reported the
defection of Col. Khalifah Abu el-Kassem Haftar, a participant in
Gadhafi's 1969 revolution against the Libyan monarchy, in a
statement distributed to Cairo news agency offices.
   Considered the strongest Libyan exile opposition group, the
National Front's headquarters are in the Egyptian capital.
   Telephone calls to Mohamed Yusef al-Magariaf, the Front's
secretary general and Gadhafi's former Libyan ambassador to India,
went unanswered.
   The Front statement quoted Haftar as saying that hundreds of
Libyan officers in Chad agree on ``the necessity to struggle
together with their brothers in the NFSL ... to save the country
from Gadhafi's terrorist and dictatorial rule.''
   The statement did not indicate where Haftar is or say when he
was supposed to have defected. A National Front spokesman known by
the nom de guerre Abu el-Nour said the man was a prisoner of war in
Chad before his defection.
   Libyan claims to a large zone of northern Chad along their
border have been the object of a long-running war between the two
north African nations. Gadhafi backs rebel forces against the
current central government in N'Djamena.
   If the National Front statements were true, Haftar's defection
apparently would be the first of such a high-ranking officer among
Libyan forces in Chad. Colonel, Gadhafi's rank, is the highest
attainable in the Libyan armed forces.
</TEXT>
