<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Train     03-25 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Train,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brake Failure Caused Train Collision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brake failure caused two passenger trains to
collide head-on outside Shanghai, killing 28 people and injuring
99, officials said Friday.
   Among the dead were 27 members of a Japanese high school tour
group.
   The two trains crashed head-on Thursday in a Shanghai suburb,
crushing and derailing several front cars. About 400 rescue workers
were dispatched to the scene.
   The crash injured 99 people, 17 of them seriously, the state-run
Xinhua News Agency quoted officials as saying at a Shanghai news
conference.
   Most of the survivors from the 193-member Japanese tour group
boarded a chartered plane in Shanghai on Friday night to return
home. Dozens of relatives of the Japanese dead and injured,
meanwhile, arrived in Shanghai.
   Xinhua quoted Mu Kaixiang, deputy director of the Shanghai
Railway Administration, as saying the No. 311 train from Nanjing to
Hangzhou tried to halt at a station as scheduled.
   But its brakes failed and it continued 460 feet into the path of
train No. 208 arriving from Changsha. The driver of No. 208 applied
his emergency brakes but was unable to prevent the collision,
Xinhua quoted Mu as saying.
   Both trains were moving slower than 25 mph, he said.
   The Japanese students and teachers were in the two first-class
cars of train No. 311, which were derailed and badly crushed.
   Acting Premier Li Peng sent a telegram to Japanese Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita on Friday expressing ``deep sympathy'' to
the families of the Japanese victims.
   Japan's vice minister of foreign affairs, Hamada Takujiro, also
arrived to take charge of arrangements for the Japanese involved,
Xinhua said.
   The school group, which included 11 teachers and 182 students,
had arrived in China on Monday to visit Shanghai and nearby
Hangzhou.
   The nationally televised evening news said rescue workers
labored until 3 a.m. Friday to free passengers trapped in the
crushed cars.
   It showed the baggage car of one train resting partially on top
of the other train's engine and passengers being passed out of
train windows on stretchers.
   The collision, China's fourth fatal train accident this year,
came one day before Li convened a session of the legislature, the
National People's Congress, at which the Railways Ministry is
expected to be reorganized.
   A derailment Jan. 24 killed 88 people, a train collision on Jan.
17 killed 19 and a train fire Jan. 7 killed 34.
   Railways Minister Ding Guangen resigned this month in disgrace
because of the earlier train crashes, and no replacement has been
appointed.
</TEXT>
