<1ST_LINE>d a AM-CankerAward     03-25 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canker Award,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Nurseries to Share $1.5 Million for Canker Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUCHULA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded two nurseries $1.5 million
to cover losses to their citrus stock during the 1984 canker scare
in a case that could set precedent.
   A circuit jury returned its verdict Thursday night in a trial to
set damages.
   Mallory Horne, representing the state Department of Agriculture
and Consumer Services, had argued that $600,000 would be a fair
settlement for the loss of 280,000 trees at Mid-Florida Growers
Inc. and Himrod & Himrod Citrus Nurseries.
   The nurseries had received $248,000 from the state and federal
governments as compensation after their stock was destroyed. That
amount will be deducted from the $1.5 million judgment.
   Richard Polk has a similar suit pending for the destruction of
510,000 trees.
   Statewide, more than 20 million nursery-stock or newly planted
trees were burned after inspectors discovered what they thought was
a virulent strain of incurable citrus canker in August 1984. It
later was found to be a much less threatening form of disease and
some nursery owners sued, claiming the burning unnecessary.
   The Florida Supreme Court determined that state officials acted
properly to protect the state's multibillion-dollar industry, but
ruled that owners should receive full compensation for destroyed
propery.
   Pete Packett, spokesman for the Florida Department of
Agriculture, said Friday he expected the state to appeal.
</TEXT>
