<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Cocaine     03-25 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Cocaine,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize Biggest Haul of Cocaine Ever in Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized 880 pounds of cocaine worth
about $45 million and arrested 12 people Friday in what they
described as the largest seizure of the drug in European history.
   Authorities believe the find could be linked to the ``Cartel de
Medellin'' ring of Colombia, the alleged supplier of 80 percent of
the cocaine to the U.S. market, according to Madrid drug
enforcement chief Florentino Gomez.
   Among the suspects arrested in Madrid were four Colombians,
three Ecuadorians and a Spanish woman. The others were not
identified.
   Police on Friday were still gathering the drug hidden inside
prefabricated housing panels inside a warehouse in the Madrid
suburb of Fuenlabrada. The total weight of the seizure could
eventually surpass 880 pounds, Gomez said.
   Gomez said the seizure capped an eight-month investigation.
Authorities made a breakthrough when they tracked a container sent
from Ecuador to the port of Barcelona, which was later trucked east
to the Fuenlabrada warehouse, he said.
   The chief of the National Plan to Combat Drugs, Miguel Solans,
said the drug haul represented a major blow to international drug
traffickers. Mainly South Americans dealers have converted Spain
into a gateway to the European drug market.
   On Nov. 11, British and Dutch drug agents claimed the previous
largest seizure in Europe after they found 550 pounds of cocaine
aboard a Colombian freighter in Britain.
</TEXT>
