<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SalamanderStreet     03-25 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salamander Street,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salamander Tunnel Fails The First Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempt by townspeople to protect
mating salamanders from being killed by cars was thwarted when all
but one of the amphibians ignored tunnels installed for them
beneath a busy street.
   The 50 people who turned out in drizzle Thursday night to watch
the first salamander crossing of the year ended up barricading the
street and carrying about 40 of the yellow-spotted salamanders
across to a breeding pond.
   The animals spend the winter hibernating in woods and try to
reach the pond every spring with the first warm rain.
   Shouts went up when one salamander was discovered crawling along
a fence leading to one of the tunnels under Henry Street. The
salamander made it through in five minutes, 20 seconds, said
Shutesbury teacher Ken Lindsay.
   ``It was an historic event,'' Lindsay said Friday. ``It was the
first salamander to go through a tunnel all on its own.''
   The world's first salamander tunnels were installed after a
public outcry over the amphibians' plight.
   Many salamanders faced certain death when they slithered across
the road. Local naturalist Robert Winston persuaded town selectmen
to close the street last year until all the salamanders, members of
the mole salamander family, made the trek, which usually takes a
week.
   The salamanders are not on the state's endangered species list,
although the Henry Street population is the last in town.
   The three 19-inch-high tunnels were donated by ACO Polymer
Products of Cleveland and installed in November for about $2,000.
Volunteers erected fences in January to guide the salamanders to
the tunnels.
   The fences failed their first test, but townspeople said it was
too early to tell how the whole experiment would fare.
   Lindsay said there were very few salamanders out Thursday night.
   Winston's wife, Janet, said the salamanders may have changed
their usual migration pattern to start at a spot beyond the fence.
   Lindsay said they might have been hibernating between the fence
and the road. Richard Minear, chairman of the board of selectmen,
said the tunnels might not be wet enough for the discriminating
amphibians.
   In any event, the salamanders took townspeople by surprise, said
Mrs. Winston, one of the flashlight-toting helpers at the crossing.
``They came a little sooner than we were quite prepared for,'' she
said.
   The town's superintendent of public works said he hadn't yet
hung the ``Salamander Crossing'' signs designed by Shutesbury
fourth-grader Rachel Mackintosh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0131 </DOCNO>
