<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilkProgram     03-25 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Milk Program,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Milk Giveaways Coming Back for One Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government distribution of surplus milk to
needy families will resume on a temporary basis in June following a
one-month suspension, the Department of Agriculture announced
Friday.
   ``At this time, we do not know if distribution of non-fat dry
milk can be continued beyond June,'' Assistant Secretary for Food
and Consumer Services John Bode said in a statement.
   USDA announced last month it would suspend milk and cheese
distributions under the Temporary Emergency Food Assistance
Program. USDA officials said the suspension was necessary because
of dwindling inventories of the goods. The program began on orders
from President Reagan in 1981 when surpluses were piling up.
   The suspension announcement had drawn immediate fire from
Capitol Hill.
   Bode said Friday that a new upturn in USDA inventories prompted
the June distribution of 8 million pounds of non-fat dry milk
through local food banks. He said the department would monitor its
inventories ``and keep states informed of availability.''
   ``The same is true for cheese,'' he said. ``If we get more,
we'll give it away.''
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee, said he was ``pleased that there's an additional
temporary supply for the month, but this does not address the
long-term problem.''
   Leahy has been calling for renewal of the TEFAP program, and he
scheduled a grocery-bagging session in a downtown Washington food
bank on Monday morning in an effort to focus the spotlight on the
hunger issue.
   The food giveaway program has distributed more than 5 billion
pounds of surplus food worth more than $5 billion since 1981, the
department said.
   Seven types of food have been provided: cheese, butter, non-fat
dry milk, honey corn meal, flour and rice.
</TEXT>
