<HEAD>They Came for the Spoils of Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spoils of the drug business went up for
auction, with everything from sweat socks to a white fur coat
available for bidding.
   Hundreds of people showed up Thursday looking for a steal among
about 300 items, worth an estimated $50,000. Up for sale were gold
chains, a motor scooter, a vacuum cleaner and something no one
quite recognized.
   ``Whatever it is, let's go for it,'' said a police department
auctioneer, holding up a metal box with a bunch of long wires
hanging down from the sides.
   It brought $50.
   Proceeds go to the police forfeiture fund, used by the Narcotics
Division, said Lt. Martin Rosenau.
   Nick Rubino of East Detroit plunked down $905 for a heavy gold
necklace.
   ``It's a big silly gold chain,'' he said, adding he hopes to
have it melted down. ``I hope it's worth more than $905.''
