<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Jessica'sBirthday     03-25 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jessica's Birthday,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subject Of Well Rescue Celebrating Quiet Birthday; Movie Dispute
Rages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The toddler who was trapped for 58 hours
in an abandoned well celebrates her second birthday Saturday
without the cameras and reporters that greeted her rescue last fall.
   Jessica McClure and her parents, Reba and Chip, plan a quiet
observance at home, said a spokesman, Pete Snelson of Midland.
   But a controversy between rival associations of rescuers over
telling the tale for televison is far from quiet.
   The rescuers were among more than 200 firefighters, law
enforcement officers, cave explorers, construction workers,
drillers, welders and others who worked for three days to free
Jessica from the 8-inch well shaft.
   ``Personally, I hope it doesn't get to the point where you're
embarrassed to say you were involved in the rescue,'' said Richard
Galle, a caver who assisted at the well site.
   Galle, Odessa's recreation superintendent, handled climbing
harnesses for dusty workers who repeatedly descended a newly dug
parallel shaft and bored horizontally through solid rock to reach
the girl, 22 feet down.
   The two rescuers' groups _ one mostly volunteers and the other
city officials and employees _ are negotiating separately with
producers for a television movie.
   The Jessica McClure Rescuer's Association, a group of more than
30 volunteers, is committed to a movie deal with Los Angeles
producer Larry Spivey, president of Highland Communications Group
Inc. The group has asked all rescuers to join them.
   Kragg Robinson, the association's president, said members have
signed a contract that includes an initial $200,000, plus future
payments, to be divided among the members. Spivey has yet to
negotiate a deal with a network.
   The other group, the McClure Rescue Association, comprises 11
municipal officials and has not yet committed to work with a
producer.
   The rescuers' gatherings started calmly enough. Some, in the
spirit of solidarity and friendship, agreed to meet regularly for
reunions and an informal group was created, said David Lilly, a New
Mexico mining expert.
   Jessica's parents have not yet signed any movie agreements, said
Snelson.
   ``It's a beautiful, heart-warming story'' that needs to be told
in the right way, he said. The McClures are ``appreciative of
everyone and haven't measured one group against the other.''
   Police Cpl. Jim White, a member of the municipal workers' group,
said its members harbor no animosity toward the volunteers'
association.
   ``We just don't agree on movie producers,'' said White.
</TEXT>
