<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuelSpill     03-25 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland to Raze Used Tank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. says it will dismantle a
3.4 million-gallon petroleum storage tank it was building with
18-year-old steel at an Ohio River terminal.
   Ashland stopped construction on the tank Jan. 6, just four days
after a 4 million-gallon tank built with 40-year-old steel
collapsed at its terminal in Jefferson, 27 miles south of
Pittsburgh on the Monongahela River. About 730,000 gallons of
diesel fuel spilled into the Monongahela and Ohio rivers.
   Ashland spokesman Roger Schrum said the company decided to tear
down the tank, which was 90 percent completed, because ``we decided
we didn't want to use a used tank at that location.''
   Dismantling will begin within a week, he said.
   Skinner Tank Co. of Yale, Okla., which erected the failed tank
in Jefferson, was reassembling the tank in Midland. The partially
erected tank, 56.5 feet tall and 100 feet in diameter, is about
1,000 yards from the Ohio River in a tank farm purchased from
Pennzoil Inc. about a year ago, the company said.
   The tank was being constructed with steel from a Shell Oil Co.
tank built in Cincinnati in 1970. It was one of 11 tanks, and one
of two that were to be reconstructed from used steel, Ashland
planned to build at the Midland terminal. Schrum said construction
had not begun on the other tanks.
   ``We still have plans to build a good, first-class terminal in
Midland, but we still haven't totally decided how many tanks we
will build up there,'' he said Thursday.
   Schrum said the company's report on the Jefferson tank collapse,
and one being done at Ashland's expense by the Battelle Institute,
won't be completed for several more weeks.
</TEXT>
