<1ST_LINE>r w AM-States-Budgets     03-25 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-States-Budgets,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State `Rainy Day' Funds Usually Are Undernourished or Empty,
Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-six states have established ``rainy
day'' funds as a hedge against economic downturns, although seven
states have put no money in them and most of the rest haven't put
in enough to deal with serious financial troubles, a report issued
Friday said.
   Two of the states, Alaska and Wyoming, both suffering from the
drop in energy prices, actually have drawn upon those reserves to
avoid deep spending cuts and to keep their budgets balanced, the
report said.
   ``That proves the funds are working,'' said Raymond Scheppach,
executive director of the National Governors' Association.
   The association, along with the National Association of State
Budget Officers, put together the report on the financial condition
of the 50 states, ``Fiscal Survey of the States.''
   In general, the report found that most states tightened their
budget belts last year and are reluctant to start major new
programs this year because of uncertainty about the economy.
   States such as Louisiana and West Virgina are facing tough
financial times because of their reliance on the troubled energy
industry. But the majority of states are in sound health, the
report said.
   Still, that figure belies the fact that most states are close to
the financial edge. The report found that the majority of states
will end the year with only small budget balances. Those balances
are expected to fall to 1.5 percent of total expenditures at the
end of next fiscal year, the lowest level since the recession of
1983, when it was 1.3 percent.
   California and New Jersey, both with booming economies, are
among the handful of states expecting to end the next fiscal year
with large balances. California is projecting a $1.1 billion
balance and New Jersey, $231 million.
   Louisiana, on the other hand, is the only state forecasting a
deficit at the end of next fiscal year _ an estimated $731 million.
   The report also found that some states are putting money aside
into contingency funds instead of counting unspent dollars as
end-of-the-year balances. Such reserves are a relatively recent
phenomenon, formed to buffer state finances from the disruptions of
an uneven economy, the report said.
   But the funds, overall, are small. At the end of last fiscal
year, the reserves totaled $2 billion, or just under 1 percent of
expenditures, the report said. The amount of money in the reserves
is expected to increase slightly to $2.3 billion at the end of this
fiscal year, but that still will equal just 1 percent of
expenditures.
   ``Clearly,'' the report said, ``small reserves can help relieve
less serious fiscal conditions, but states will still be unprepared
for an extended economic downturn.''
   Seven of the states have yet to put money into their reserves:
Alaska, Idaho, Iowa, Utah, Virginia, Washington and Wisconsin, the
report said.
   The other 29 states that have established such reserves are
California, Colorado, Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Georgia,
Indiana, Kentucky, Louisiana (which refers to its program as a
deficit elimination fund), Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts,
Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, Nebraska, Nevada, New
Hampshire, New Mexico, New York, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania,
Rhode Island, South Carolina, Tennessee, Vermont and Wyoming.
   New Jersey and Hawaii are considering creating a ``rainy day''
fund.
   Most states expect little fallout from last October's stock
market collapse, although Florida, Washington, Tennessee and New
York are planning for revenue losses.
   The report found that the economic picture generally differs by
region, with New England in a strong financial position. One
measure of its strength was its unemployment rate, which averaged
3.4 percent in 1987, far below the national rate of 6.2 percent.
   The Mideast also boasts a strong economy, while recessions in
the Midwestern farm states and Western energy states seem to have
bottomed out, the report said. In the South, the economic picture
is mixed, with some states, like Florida, North Carolina and
Virginia, experiencing strong growth and Louisiana, West Virginia
and Kentucky facing economic hard times.
</TEXT>
