<DOCNO> AP880325-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Austria-Jews     03-25 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Jews,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Jewish Congress Calls Austrian Reparations To Jews
`Desecration''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edgar M. Bronfman, president of the World
Jewish Congress, on Friday condemned the payment voted by Austria's
parliament to compensate victims of Nazism as ``a desecration.''
   The decision to grant between $200 and $400 to each victim
``represents a desecration of the memory of the victims of the
Holocaust at the very moment of Austria's reflection on the 50th
anniversary of its union with Nazi Germany,'' Bronfman said.
   The parliament in Vienna voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to pay a
one-time sum of $4 million to victims of Nazism.
   Some 68,000 Austrian Jews died in Nazi concentration camps
during World War II, and more than 120,000 others were incarcerated
in camps or fled the country. In all, the Nazis exterminated some 6
million Jews.
   Bronfman's statement noted that the Austrian decision was in
marked contrast to West Germany's 1952 agreement to compensate the
victims of Nazism for life with monthly reparation payments.
   The World Jewish Congress, based in New York, has been at the
forefront of a two-year campaign to expose the Nazi past of
Austrian President Kurt Waldheim. ``The recent attention focused on
Kurt Waldheim's Nazi past has exploded the long-held myth that
Austria was a victim of Nazi persecution rather than its very
willing collaborator,'' Bronfman said.
   A team of international historians found that Waldheim was
implicated in Nazi persecution while serving as an officer in the
German army during World War II.
