<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1647EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-666Building Bjt   03-25 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-666 Building, Bjt,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No. 666: Luxury Apartment Owners Move To Change `Satanic' Address</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Upchurch knew little about apocalyptic
imagery in the Bible and cared less about satanic symbols until the
new owners of her lakefront luxury building said it was no longer
666 North Lake Shore Drive.
   ``I never knew it had satanic connotations until one night when
I was watching `The Omen' on television,'' Ms. Upchurch said,
referring to the 1976 movie in which a boy named Damien has the
numbers ``666'' on his scalp.
   ``When I saw that,'' she continued, ``I said to myself, `Isn't
that amazing? He has our address on his head.' It actually made me
feel kind of proud.''
   The building's new owners and management felt differently. In a
March 1 letter, they notified commercial leaseholders and occupants
of the nearly 400 residential units that as of May 1, the building
will be known as Lake Shore Place at 680 North Lake Shore Drive.
   Spokesmen for the owner, a Chemical Bank of New York subsidiary,
and the local management company, Golub & Co., say the address
change had nothing to do with the devil.
   They say their intent was to disassociate the building from a
spate of financial problems that befell its previous owner, a New
York real estate developer who bought the building in 1979 and lost
a mortgage foreclosure battle with the bank last year.
   ``It certainly wasn't us who raised this devil thing,'' said
Michael Schramm, executive vice president of Golub & Co.
   Some Chicagoans have taken to calling the building the
Mark-of-the-Beast Building or the Devil's Building, apparently in
light-hearted reference to passages from the book of Revelation in
the New Testament.
   The book tells of a beast with two horns like a lamb that arose
from the earth and caused every person to receive its mark on the
right hand or the forehead. ``Let him that hath understanding count
the number of the beast: for it is the number of a man; and his
number is six hundred threescore and six,'' according to Revelation
13:18.
   Ms. Upchurch said a supervisor in the city department that
approved the address change told her the owners specifically
mentioned that ``666 refers to the devil.''
   If the owner's motive is open to debate, the inconvenience the
name change will cause many tenants is not.
   ``They're fighting mad and ... we're talking about wealthy
people, not the kind of people you'd expect to pick this kind of
fight,'' said Ms. Upchurch, 36, who makes her living writing and
recording commercial jingles with her husband.
   ``I'd just bought a year's supply of client forms and checks:
10,000 envelopes with the wrong address were delivered four days
before we were notified,'' said Sharon Cooper Wottrich, owner and
president of A-Plus Talent Agency in the building.
   The tenants have collected $1,600 thus far and retained an
attorney about making a legal challenge, Ms. Upchurch said.
   The final blow to some tenants isn't even the name change. It's
the new _ some say stuffy _ moniker of Lake Shore Place.
   ``It's absolutely pretentious,'' said Zacharias Rosner, another
leader of the tenant uprising. ``It's like painting a Rolls-Royce
orange.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
