<DOCNO> AP880325-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Satellite     03-25 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Satellite,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satellite Launched To Study Earth's Atmosphere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MARCO EQUATORIAL RANGE, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-built rocket
carrying a satellite with Italian, West German and U.S. scientific
experiments was launched from an Indian Ocean platform off the
coast of East Africa on Friday night.
   The satellite will orbit the Earth on a yearlong mission to
study the lower atmosphere.
   The Scout rocket, a four-stage, solid-fuel booster, rose in a
plume of fire and smoke into a cloudless sky beneath a quarter moon.
   The launch at 10:55 p.m. came 12 hours after an original
daylight launch was postponed. Weather forecasters had predicted a
thunderstorm, which did not materialize.
   Aboard the 522-pound satellite was equipment from NASA's Goddard
Space Flight Center in Maryland to measure the electric field
outside the craft.
   Another experiment from the University of Texas will measure hot
gases and ion winds surrounding the spacecraft.
   The Italian space agency sent a device designed to measure drag
forces on the orbiting satellite, and the West German space agency
sent equipment to measure solar ultraviolet radiation and radiation
of interplanetary and intergalactic origin.
   The satellite, which will be monitored from a control room in
Rome, will make a complete loop around the Earth, above the
equator, every 100 minutes.
   Friday night's launch was the first from the Italian-run San
Marco Equatorial Range since 1974.
   The range, 90 miles north of the port city of Mombasa, was
established in 1965 and has been the site of eight previous
launches, all of them involving Scout rockets.
   The University of Rome operates the range. Friday's launch was
conducted in collaboration with the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   The San Marco platform, named for the patron saint of
navigators, is three miles offshore and similar to those used in
offshore drilling.
   The Scout rocket is one of the most reliable ones used by NASA.
Friday night's launch was the 53rd success out of 54 attempts in
the past 20 years, NASA officials said.
   The launch had been postponed from last week because of
mechanical problems.
</TEXT>
