<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TentFamily     03-25 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tent Family,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Evicted From Tent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Varryl cq in 1st graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADISONVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Varryl Thomas says her family had two
choices: ``It was either come here to St. Tammany and live in a
tent or stay in New Orleans and live in the streets.''
   St. Tammany gave the family an unexpected third choice _ to move
the tent because it was violating sanitation and building codes.
   However, the deputy who ordered them to move put them in touch
with a church, which is helping them find a home.
   ``We have no relatives around here and didn't know anybody,''
Mrs. Thomas said. ``We had no place to go. My husband's disabled
and I don't have a job. If it wasn't for the churches, we would be
some pitiful people.''
   The Thomases' problems began in New Orleans about a month ago,
when the house they were living in was sold. They'd been living
rent-free in exchange for watching the property, Mrs. Thomas said.
   ``We didn't have enough money to rent a new house,'' she said.
``Rent there is about $175. Plus you have to have that much more
for a damage deposit and more money for utility deposits.''
   They took their $277 monthly welfare check and every penny they
could scrape up and made a $200 down payment on a 75-by-125-foot
lot in a subdivision near Madisonville.
   Last weekend, they loaded their belongings in plastic garbage
bags, put them on a small pickup truck and drove across the
Causeway to their new lot. Several of the bags blew into Lake
Pontchartrain on the way over.
   ``That didn't help matters,'' Larry Thomas said.
   Their 9-by-12-foot tent made it, however. The family improvised
an outhouse from a blue tarpaulin over a hole in the ground.
   The couple and their children _ Benjamin, 4, Alaster, 5, and
Luwana, 6 _ planned to live there until they could afford to build
a small house.
   ``We didn't know we weren't supposed to put up a tent on the
lot,'' Mrs. Thomas said. ``We were told the only thing you couldn't
put on the lot was a trailer.''
   After learning the family's plight, the St. Tammany Parish
sheriff's deputy who ordered them to move called St. Anselm
Catholic Church in Madisonville. Deacon Philip Baham put the family
up in a motel for the rest of the weekend and found them a house in
Covington, Mrs. Thomas said.
   The church paid $100 for a month's rent and the Covington Food
Bank and the Vincentian Center in Covington gave the family food,
said food bank manager Beverly Sharp.
   Mrs. Thomas said the family paid $200 down and $125 in closing
costs for the $9,500 lot. The 17-year mortgage was to be paid at
$95 a month.
   ``We were going to try to pay it out of our welfare check, I
guess. And I was hoping to find a job,'' Mrs. Thomas said.
   Sharp said the Vincentian Center is trying to find a job for
Mrs. Thomas, who has worked as an auto mechanic.
   ``But I'll do anything at all,'' Mrs. Thomas said. ``I'm not
choosy about a job. I went to three places today, but they didn't
have any openings.''
</TEXT>
