<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0650 03-25 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unanimous Senate Urges Reagan to Step Up Heat on Noriega</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 4th graf, ``An administration,'' with reaction;
subs pvs 3rd graf from end, ``A senior,'' with 2 grafs to update
with Reagan, Balaguer comments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, voting 92-0, urged President
Reagan on Friday to increase U.S. economic pressure against
Panamanian military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega as part of a
campaign to drive him from office.
   The unanimous vote was intended to demonstrate Noreiga has lost
all U.S. support.
   The non-binding resolution also urged the White House to
consider ``a comprehensive package of emergency financial and other
economic assistance'' to help a democratic successor government
rebuild Panama's economy.
   An administration official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said, ``We have been aware of the Senate resolution for
days and consider it to be completely complementary to U.S. policy
in Panama.''
   ``The impression in all our minds is that Noriega must go,''
said Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee.
   ``He will go, and this will help him down the slippery slope,''
Pell said.
   ``To Gen. Noriega, we say step aside now, while you still have
the chance _ for your own sake and for your family''s future,''
said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., a principal sponsor of the
resolution.
   The resolution declared that Noriega's military rule and his
alleged involvement in large-scale international drug running and
money laundering represent ``an unusual and extraordinary threat to
the national security, foreign policy and economy of the United
States.''
   But senators stressed that any action the United States takes
against Noreiga is in response to the direct request of President
Eric Arturo Devalle, who was ousted as Panama's chief executive on
Feb. 25 after trying unsuccessfully to remove Noriega as head of
the Panamanian Defense Force.
   ``This battle is going to be won or lost by the Panamanian
people,'' Kennedy said. ``But I think it is important that in this
struggle they know where the United States stands.''
   Several senators urged Noriega to reconsider his refusal of a
Justice Department offer not to seek his extradition for trial on
U.S. narcotics-trafficking charges if he gives up power and goes
into exile in Spain.
   ``Noriega needs to know that offer is not good forever _ and
that he will not be free to pursue his sordid activities without
fear of paying the consequences,'' said Sen. David Durenberger,
R-Minn.
   ``If he thinks this is the end of it _ if he feels this is all
we are going to do _ he'd better think again,'' said Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C. ``This is a man who is a symbol for destroying
liberty.''
   Among the options available to the United States is the
imposition of a total trade embargo against Panama, a step the
administration has resisted in favor of a more measured,
incremental approach.
   Many members of Congress originally called for such action
before joining forces behind the resolution approved Friday.
   After two federal grand juries in Florida charged Noriega with
multimillion-dollar drug trafficking and money laundering,
President Reagan cut off the flow of U.S. dollars to Panama.
   Panama uses dollars as its own currency and the move paralyzed
the Panamanian banking system.
   Before meeting in the Oval Office with Dominican President
Joaquin Balaguer on Friday, Reagan was asked whether Noriega might
seek exile in the Dominican Republic.
   ``No,'' he replied. ``That's not far enough.''
   Reagan, asked about the Senate resolution at a departure
ceremony for Balaguer, said, ``We're considering everything, but I
can't take any questions.''
   Balaguer said in an interview with the Voice of America that he
would grant asylum to Noriega if asked.
   Meanwhile, the federal Agency for International Development has
agreed to release $250,000 in emergency funds to buy food for the
poor in Panama.
   The food will be purchased in Panama if it is available and
distributed through Caritas, a Roman Catholic relief agency, said
AID spokesman Jim Kunder.
</TEXT>
