<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Saudi     03-25 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Saudi,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deny Israel Considering Attack on Saudi Arabia Over Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking official indicated Friday that
Israel might take action if the United States fails to deal with
long-range Chinese missiles sold to Saudi Arabia.
   Other officials, however, denied that Israel was considering an
attack on the Arab kingdom.
   ``Israel has a tradition of not standing by quietly when there
is a real threat against it,'' said Yossi Ben-Aharon, a senior aide
to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. ``The question is if this is a
threat or not. There are people to deal with it, the Cabinet, the
government.''
   Saudi Arabia recently acquired the CSS-2 missiles, which have a
range of 2,200 miles, enough to strike anywhere in the Middle East.
They also are capable of carrying nuclear warheads.
   Both the Chinese and the Saudis said the missiles won't be armed
with such warheads, and Saudi Arabia has said it purchased the
weapons to deter attacks on its territory during the Iran-Iraq war.
   But Israel radio reported Friday that Saudi Arabia issued a
warning through the United States that it would use any remaining
missiles to strike at the Jewish state if Israel attempted a
pre-emptive strike.
   Ben-Aharon said the issue should be left for U.S. officials,
``who told us they are going to deal with the matter the best they
can, both in China and in Saudi Arabia.''
   The Washington Post quoted U.S. intelligence sources as saying
the Israeli air force has been conducting unusually intensive
low-lewel bombing practice. It said such runs could be preparation
for a strike on Saudi Arabia, though there was no hard evidence to
support that interpretation.
   The paper also noted that such exercises could help Israel
prepare for raids on Palestinian targets in Lebanon.
   Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner, denied that Israel had made any
threats. ``We did take up our concern with the United States. But
we never made any threat against Saudi Arabia,'' he said.
   Earlier reports of a similar Ben-Aharon statement sparked strong
warnings from Egypt and Syria, and the U.S. State Department
expressed concern.
   The Syrian government said Monday that ``any agression against
the sister Saudi Arabian kingdom would obviously be an attack
against Syria.''
   Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak said he sent an urgent message
to President Reagan asking him to ``use his influence with Israel
and urge it to stop threatening Arab states in such irresponsible
way.''
   Egypt is the only Arab country to have peace treaty with Israel.
   An Israeli official who demanded anonymity said Syria and Egypt
were ``overreacting to a report that has been denied.''
   The official said Israel was going to mount a diplomatic
campaign to ``take the missiles out,'' but stressed that ``we never
made any threat to take them out militarily.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
