<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IslamicConference     03-25 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islamic Conference,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Branded as Moslem Nations End Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem countries ended an international
conference Friday by denouncing an absent Iran for riots last year
in Mecca and for refusing to sign a cease-fire in its war with Iraq.
   Iran's delegation to the Organization of Islamic Conference in
Amman had stormed out of the five-day meeting Thursday. It
complained that the 46-member conference was only serving the
interests of Iraq, its enemy in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   The foreign ministers and other officials of Moslem nations
worldwide, in their final communique, lamented what they called
``terrorism'' by Iranian rioters in Saudi Arabia in July, according
to Jordanian Foreign Minister Taher Masri. They also praised Saudi
measures, announced Thursday, to control future disorders.
   The rioting occurred as Saudis tried to stop Iranian pilgrims at
the holy city of Mecca from marching in a political demonstration.
The violence left 402 people dead, including 275 Iranians and 80
Saudi security men.
   The Moslem nations specifically approved the Saudis' decision to
set limits on the number of pilgrims traveling to Mecca and Medina
this year.
   Masri, who chaired the final session of the gathering, said the
conference also agreed to ``make extensive efforts to force the
United Nations to take the necessary measures to force Iran to
accept'' U.N. Security Council Resolution 598. That document calls
for a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war and a return to international
borders.
   Iraq has agreed, but Iran says it first wants its enemy branded
as the aggressor.
   Iran, a mainly Persian nation, has often been the target of
criticisms from Arab lands.
   The conference also:
   _ Declared its support for Palestinian protests in the
Israeli-occupied territories. However, no specific action was given.
   _ Welcomed Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's offer to pull
troops out of Afghanistan and called for it to be put into effect
immediately.
   _ Asked non-Islamic countries with Moslem populations, such as
Bulgaria, to take steps to guarantee the rights of the minorities.
   _ Withheld full recognition of Moslem rebels from the
Philippines who are fighting the Manila government.
</TEXT>
