<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole     03-25 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Concedes His Battle Against Bush Appears Doomed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole, saying ``I can read the numbers
and I know probably what's going to happen,'' conceded Friday that
his uphill race against Vice President George Bush for the
Republican presidential nomination appears doomed.
   In downbeat comments that departed from his prepared text, the
senator from Kansas, who has 178 delegates to Bush's 788 in the
latest Associated Press tally, told the U.S. Chamber of Commerce:
``I think it's probably a foregone conclusion what's happening on
the Republican side.''
   However, a Dole spokesman later said the candidate isn't ready
to abandon the race.
   Dole himself suggested he was re-evaluating his campaign.
   ``Whatever happens in the next few days or the next few weeks, I
still have some things I want to say,'' Dole told the business
group, which gave him a standing ovation.
   ``I intend to be a leader in my party. Whatever the role may be,
it will be a role of leadership, constructive leadership, keeping
the White House Republican,'' Dole added.
   Speaking with reporters afterward, Dole gave a clear indication
that, at the very least, he would scale back his campaign
appearances.
   ``I said I had a different strategy, and I think you're seeing
some of it,'' he said.
   Asked about his change in tone and comments that Bush's GOP
victory seemed a ``foregone conclusion,'' Dole told reporters:
   ``I can read the numbers and I know probably what's going to
happen.''
   After finishing first in the Iowa Republican caucuses Feb. 8,
Dole lost a series of GOP events to Bush, including a defeat in the
New Hampshire primary Feb. 16 and losses in the big round of
primaries and caucuses on Super Tuesday March 8.
   Despite his poor showings, Dole had vowed to press ahead with
his campaign.
   But on Friday he told reporters:
   ``My view is that there's some things I want to say in this
campaign and I think sometimes if you're not out there making four
or five stops a day, people are more apt to listen.''
   Asked if these were things he planned to say on his way out of
the race, Dole said, ``No. I'm not going out. I'm just going out of
here,'' meaning the building where he had been speaking.
   Walt Riker, a Dole spokesman, later said that despite Dole's
comments, ``we haven't made any official announcements'' on a Dole
withdrawal from the race.
   ``His hallmark is his candor, and today's statement reflects
that,'' Riker said. ``We're the underdog, the big underdog. We've
never said anything different about that. We know the numbers and
we know what the score is.''
   ``But that doesn't mean we have to give up. We have to
re-evaluate the campaign day by day,'' Riker said.
   When Dole was asked by reporters whether he planned to push on
at least to the Wisconsin primary on April 5, he replied: ``I may
tell you that later this week, probably next week.''
   In his remarks to the Chamber of Commerce, Dole opened on a
pessimistic note. ``I've been saying now for some time as a
candidate all the things I thought we should focus on and nobody
really seems to care,'' he said.
   ``But I still have some things to say,'' he added. ``Lo and
behold, as your candidacy weakens, you find more people willing to
listen.''
   Dole told the business audience that ``it's going to be a tough
race'' for Republicans this year and it was time for the party to
pull together.
   ``We need to keep a Republican in the White House. That's where
I'm coming from. And if it can't be me, it will be George Bush,''
he said.
   ``I'm not here in a partisan sense. I'm not going to attack any
Republican,'' he added.
   Turning to congressional races, Dole said: ``If I can count, the
next president of the United States will be dealing with a
Democratic Congress.''
   He told his audience that the federal budget deficit, $150
billion last year, was ``public enemy No. 1'' and reiterated his
proposal for a one-year across-the-board freeze on all federal
spending.
</TEXT>
