<1ST_LINE>u w BC-CanadianEarthquake     03-25 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Canadian Earthquake,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Quake Occurs in Canada's Northwest Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake occurred in Canada's
Northwest Territories Friday and was felt over a wide area of
Canada, the U.S. Geological Survey said.
   The tremor was recorded at a preliminary magnitude of 6.2 on the
Richter scale and occurred at 12:37 p.m. MST. USGS earthquake
monitors in Golden, Colo., said seismographs placed the center of
the earthquake about 320 miles west of Yellowknife, the capital of
the Northwest Territories.
   Early reports said the tremor was felt over a wide area,
including at Yellowknife; at Whitehorse, the capital of the Yukon
Territory; and at Edmonton, the capital of Alberta Province.
   USGS scientists said two other strong earthquakes occurred in
the same general area late in 1985: a magnitude 6.6 tremor Oct. 5
and a magnitude 6.9 earthquake two days before Christmas on Dec. 23.
   The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by
an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake with a magnitude of 4 can cause moderate damage in a
populated area, a quake of magnitude 5 considerable damage, a
magnitude 6 quake severe damage, one of magnitude 7 widespread,
heavy damage and a magnitude 8 quake, a ``great'' earthquake
capable of tremendous damage.
   A quake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans.
</TEXT>
