<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-Election     03-25 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-Election,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bossano Victory in Gibraltar Election Marks New Era</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialist Labor Party sailed to a record
victory Friday in local elections, marking stiff local opposition
to Spanish claims of sovereignty over the British colony.
   In his first comments to reporters after his win, Joe Bossano,
who rejects Spanish demands for a return of sovereignty over the
enclave at its southernmost tip, restated his objection to a 1984
Brussels accord. In that document, Britain for the first time
agreed to discuss sovereignty with Spain.
   Spain ceded control over the 2-square-mile limestone rock to
Britain in 1713 following its defeat in the War of Succession.
   Bossano also said he intended to start his four-year term as new
chief minister with objections to a British-Spanish accord in
December allowing Spain access to the colony's commercial airport
and partial control of its administration.
   A conservative Spanish party leader publicly expressed worry
about the election results. Christian Democrat party leader Javier
Ruperez said Bossano's position ``makes it evident we're headed for
stormy times.''
   Final election results showed Bossano received 8,128 votes or 58
percent of votes cast Thursday to unseat incumbent Chief Minister
Adolfo Canepa of the long dominant centrist Association for the
Advancement of Civil Rights.
   Canepa, a protege of longtime party leader Sir Joshua Hassan,
received 4,442 votes or 29 percent of the total.
   Also reacting to final results Friday in Madrid, Juan Lena, a
spokesman for the government of Socialist Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez, said the election results would have no effect on Spain's
claims on the colony and its ongoing dialogue with Britain.
   ``The elections are of great importance for the colony itself,
but they will not affect the nature of the British-Spanish
negotiating process and discussions on cooperation on Gibraltar,
including the question of sovereignty,'' he said.
   Bossano told reporters Friday he was prepared to meet with
Gonzalez in Madrid to discuss bilateral issues. But such a meeting
appeared unlikely because Spain accepts Britain as its only
legitimate negotiating partner on the matter.
   Bossano heads the 7,000-member Transport Workers General Union,
the sole industrial union in the colony. He won fame for gaining
parity in pay with Britain for workers at the colony's shipyard.
   His party won eight votes in the 15-seat House of Assembly, and
Canepa's party gained the other seven.
</TEXT>
