<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Dominican     03-25 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Dominican,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dominican President Says He'd Give Noriega Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assdociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Joaquin Balaguer of the Dominican
Republic said Friday he would grant asylum to Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega if asked, but President Reagan said the
Dominican Republic isn't far enough away.
   Balaguer, in an interview with the Voice of America, said: ``We
are willing to receive anyone who has political problems. If Mr.
Noriega or anybody else requests our hospitality, we would give it
to them, not because we agree with his regime, but rather that the
traditional policy of our country has been one of open doors to all
political refugees.''
   Reagan, asked whether he expected Noriega to go to the Dominican
Republic, replied, ``No, that's not far enough.''
   A senior administration official said Reagan referred to this
remark during his private 50-minute meeting with Balaguer, but the
veteran Dominican leader did not respond.
   The official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said,
``We do not believe that having him (Noriega) that close to Panama
is a sensible move.''
   Noriega has been indicted on drug-trafficking charges by two
federal grand juries in Florida. The Justice Department has said it
would not seek his extradition if he would agree to leave Panama
and take asylum in an agreed-upon country elsewhere. Spain has
offered him exile.
   The apparent disagreement over Noriega came during a Washington
visit in which Balaguer met with Reagan, other administration
officials and senators and expressed hope that his pleas for higher
U.S. sugar quotas would be heeded.
   ``There are problems which subsist in our relations, especially
in connection with the lowering of our sugar quota, but this we
have discussed with president Reagan and with his senior advisors
in this area of expertise,'' Balaguer said in a departure statement.
   ``We also discussed the subject this morning on Capitol Hill
with a number of senators who are friends of the Dominican
Republic,'' he said. ``We found there a very receptive climate and
feel confident that the problem will be solved, taking into account
the interests of both our countries.''
   Reagan, in his remarks at the departure ceremony on a porch
facing the White House Rose Garden, did not refer to the issue of
sugar quotas, a touchy issue with the Dominicans since sugar is
their major crop.
   The annual quota for sugar imports from the Dominican Republic
to the United States has been reduced from about 750,000 tons in
the early 1980s to 123,000 tons this year.
   The senior official said the administration will continue to
press Congress for changes in U.S. sugar policy. He said Balaguer
``asked for help,'' both with the sugar quotas and with the
declining levels of U.S. aid.
   Reagan and Secretary of State George P. Shultz told Balaguer the
United States would make available $10 million worth of surplus
U.S. corn, providing the Dominicans with food as well as $10
million in foreign exchange, the official said.
   Reagan, in his departure remarks, said, ``Within our budget
limitations, we will continue to support development and growth in
the Dominican Republic.''
</TEXT>
