<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENA PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a duo, The Judds are an
award-winning combo, but the mother and daughter say they'd team up
with others if it would help country music.
   ``We'll do just about anything as long as it's legal to promote
the goodness of country music,'' said daughter Wynonna Judd.
   ``We're pretty joined at the lips, you know,'' added her mother,
Naomi.
   After collecting another vocal duo of the year award from the
Academy of Country Music here Monday night, the women talked about
the responsibility each new award means.
   ``You have people who support you. You read your mail,'' Wynonna
said. ``We get lots of letters from people saying, `You helped me
through such a hard time in my life.'
   ``You get so much support from people that you really feel you
want to do your best. You want to be the best you can be.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist Ellen
Goodman says women have been successful in getting into the male
world, but have not been able to get that world to adapt to their
needs.
   The workplace, though welcoming more women than ever, still is a
man's world and that perpetuates a conflict between work and
family, she said.
   In addition, women in the work place are seen as isolated
individuals with no families, she said Thursday.
   Speaking at the 25th anniversary celebration of the University
of Missouri-Kansas City Family Study Center, Goodman said
individual rather than community goals are being emphasized in this
decade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW CASTLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven-year-old Nikki Edwards says
she'll never wash her face again, at least not the cheek that
singer Michael Jackson kissed.
   ``So every time I take a shower, I put a wash cloth over my face
so it doesn't get wet,'' she said Friday, a week after the kiss.
   Nikki and her sister, Mari Anna Miller, 24, were in the front
row at Jackson's concert March 18 in Indianapolis when the
fifth-grader was selected to come on stage.
   A burly man grabbed Nikki's arm and Ms. Miller, thinking the
fellow was trying to hurt her sister, belted him.
   ``He flashed his light on Mari Anna's face and then on his
security badges,'' Nikki said. ``The security man said, `Mr.
Jackson was wondering if you would appear on stage with him.'''
   When Jackson led Nikki on stage, ``I thought to myself here he
comes and I'm going to die,'' she said. ``Then I thought what a way
to go.''
   Jackson, a Gary native, hugged her while he sang ``She's Out of
My Life.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis Hopper says he was shocked by the
police reaction to the new movie he directed, ``Colors,'' which
features police battling drug dealing and street crime by violent
southern California gangs.
   Real law enforcement officers were given a preview and several
detectives said the film glamorizes the gang lifestyle and could
trigger violence among gang audiences. Assistant Police Chief
Robert Vernon suggested it be banned.
   Hopper says that reaction shows how much the gang problem is out
of control.
   ``At the beginning we point out that there are 250 men and women
in law enforcement working against 600 gangs with over 70,000
members,'' he said. ``How can they possibly handle it?''
   The film, scheduled for release in mid-April, stars Robert
Duvall and Sean Penn as policemen.
