<HEAD>Bush Sends Autographed Portrait to 101-Year-Old Supporter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vote of confidence can sometimes be as
good as a vote itself for Vice President George Bush _ just ask
101-year-old Mary Fishbyrne.
   Bush sent her an autographed color portrait of himself after
learning that Fishbyrne, who prefers to be called Miss Mary, had
been frustrated when she tried to vote for him in Louisiana's Super
Tuesday primary.
   Miss Mary, a registered Democrat who has voted in every
presidential election since women were granted suffrage in 1920,
thought Bush was a smart man and ``would make a good president.''
But she could not cast her ballot for him because voters in the
state's presidential primary aren't permitted to cross party lines.
   A Bush campaign spokesman said a campaign worker heard of Miss
Mary's frustrations on Super Tuesday and decided to send her the
picture in appreciation for her would-have-been vote.
   She said Bush has her support in November. ``If I can make it
there, I'll vote for him.''
