<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2043EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-INFInspections     03-25 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-INF Inspections,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Preparing Force Of Arms Control Inspectors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will begin a series of mock
inspections next month to prepare its new force of arms control
inspectors and escorts to deal with Soviet facilities and
personnel, a ranking Pentagon official said Friday.
   The exercises will be staged at the 21 sites in Europe and the
United States where Soviet inspectors will be allowed to visit to
ensure compliance with a treaty banning intermediate and
shorter-range nuclear missiles, the official added.
   The mock inspections will begin April 6 and should be completed
by May 10, hopefully in plenty of time to allow final preparations
for the real inspections that will begin 30 days after the U.S.
Senate ratifies the pact, the source said.
   The official agreed to meet with a group of reporters Friday to
discuss the Defense Department's formation of the On-Site
Inspection Agency, or OSIA, only on condition he not be identified
publicly.
   The agency is to be the arm of the federal government
responsible for verifying Russian compliance with the new treaty.
Signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev on
Dec. 8, the treaty specifies that all nuclear missiles in the two
superpower arsenals with a range of roughly 300 miles to 3,500
miles be destroyed within three years.
   The OSIA will be responsible for escorting Soviet inspectors who
travel to the United States and sites in Western Europe to monitor
the removal and destruction of American nuclear weapons, as well as
performing the same role inside the Soviet Union by visiting
Russian facilities and deployment sites.
   The official said next month's practice sessions would involve
both inspectors and escorts, with the inspectors pretending to be
Soviet officials who are met by the American escorts.
   Under the treaty, there are 10 sites open to Soviet inspection
inside the United States and another 11 in Western Europe. All 21
sites will be tested to ensure they're ready for hosting Russian
inspectors, the official said.
   ``And we will challenge them (the escorts) with all kinds of
possible variances in the (inspection) routine,'' said the source.
   According to the official, the task of staffing the OSIA has now
been completed. The agency will keep in place 20 teams of 10
members each for the inspections, plus a headquarters' staff of 50
in Washington. Perhaps a third of the inspectors are women, the
official said, and a sufficient number of Russian linguists have
been located, although with some difficulty.
   The U.S. Military Airlift Command will be responsible for
providing the aircraft and crews needed to ferry American
inspectors to two ``entry points'' into the Soviet Union and to
move Russian inspectors around inside the United States, the
official continued.
   The two entry points for the Russians will be Washington, D.C.,
and San Francisco, Calif., and the Pentagon intends to inform the
news media when the Soviets arrive for spot inspections, the source
said.
   The head of the OSIA, Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie, and his Soviet
counterpart have already met once _ during a technical meeting in
Moscow earlier this month _ and will meet again in Washington
starting April 12, the official continued.
   The technical meetings are being held to sort out questions
about the type of monitoring and survey equipment that will be used
by the inspectors, the source said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1632EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-JailedAmerican 1stLd-Writethru a0625 03-25 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jailed American, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0625,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photographer Awaits Trial On Cocaine-Smuggling Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to change tense.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conan Owen knew it was Thursday once
again when officials served up beef stew in Gallery One of the
Model Prison.
   Owen, a 23-year-old free-lance photographer from Annandale, Va.,
has been marking off the days in his stark white cell for more than
a year, ever since a Spanish Civil Guard found more than four
pounds of cocaine in a suitcase registered in his name.
   ``I don't belong in here because I'm innocent, and if this were
the United States, I would have been out a long time ago,'' Owen
said in an interview in this 85-year-old prison in the heart of
downtown Barcelona.
   Owen, whose case has drawn the attention of Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, is to stand trial Saturday before a three-judge
panel. The prosecution is asking for a 10-year sentence.
   He arrived at Barcelona's El Prat airport on March 13, 1987 _
Friday the 13th _ on a flight from Santiago, Chile, via Amsterdam.
He said he was on his way to Spain for the first time to shoot
pictures for tourist agency travel brochures.
   ``I was working as a free-lance, and the guy offered me $1,000
for four days' work. I like to travel, so I accepted and thought I
was taking a suitcase full of travel brochures and film to someone
in Spain,'' he said.
   Owen was booked on charges of cocaine smuggling, denied bail and
taken to the Modelo, as the jail is known here.
   ``This is the worst jail in Spain, the oldest and the
most-crowded,'' said guard Manuel Escobedo. ``It was meant to hold
600 people, but there are about 2,400 in here now.''
   According to the U.S. Embassy in Madrid, as of last month there
were 25 U.S. citizens in jail in Spain. Six are serving prison
terms following conviction on drug-related charges, and another
nine, including Owen, are awaiting trial.
   Owen's attorney, Ana Campa, plans to enter as evidence results
of a polygraph test administered to Owen by an agent of the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Agency, which she says indicates Owen is telling
the truth about his photo job and the suitcase.
   On Feb. 5, George Barahona, the man who offered Owen the job,
pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court to a drug conspiracy count.
He told the court he had shared a hotel room with Owen in Santiago
and planted the cocaine-lined suitcase on the unsuspecting
photographer.
   Barahona received a two-year suspended sentence and a promise he
would not be extradited to Spain in return for his cooperation.
   Following his testimony, three Spaniards and three Bolivians,
all fugitives, were indicted by a federal grand jury in Virginia on
cocaine conspiracy charges in connection with the case.
   ``It was my parents who first confronted Barahona, because my
cousin Maria Teresa Corrales knew him and he lived in the area,''
Owen said. ``At first he denied everything, but then he told the
truth.''
   When Meese came to Spain to sign an annex to a 1970 extradition
treaty Feb. 9, he also handed over copies of Barahona's statement
to Spanish judicial authorities.
   Owen is a 1986 graduate of Syracuse University and in 1984 was a
summer intern in Vice President George Bush's office.
   The walls of the halls leading to the five sections of the
prison are decorated with travel posters for Catalonia, the region
in which Barcelona is located, and neighboring France.
   Owen said what he has seen of Spain consists of the Barcelona
airport, the court where he was arraigned and the Modelo.
   During his year in jail Owen has read 150 books, written letters
and walked miles around the patio during the daily morning and
afternoon recreation periods.
   Guards in Spanish jails are unarmed, and inmates wear street
clothes. Prisoners in the Modelo are allowed one, one-hour conjugal
visit every month with a woman of their choice.
   ``It's the boredom that gets you more than anything, the lack of
stimulating conversation, someone to talk about serious things
with,'' said Owen.
</TEXT>
