<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Submarines-Canada     03-25 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Submarines-Canada,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Shouldn't Make Quick Move To Give Submarine Secrets to Canada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should think very carefully
before permitting highly secret U.S. submarine technology to be
sold to Canada, two senators said Friday.
   ``This is a decision that should be very carefully scrutinized
before we decide to go ahead,'' said Sen. James J. Exon, D-Neb.,
chairman of the Senate Armed Services strategic weapons
subcommittee, in a speech on the Senate floor.
   ``We have a number of questions which need to be answered before
this decision is made,'' agreed Sen. John Warner, R-Va., ranking
Republican on the Armed Services Committee and a former secretary
of the Navy.
   Canada last year proposed to construct a fleet of 10 to 12
nuclear-powered submarines and is considering building boats which
are updated versions of the British Trafalgar-class subs or the
French Rubis-class subs.
   The Trafalgars use U.S. technology, which means the information
could not be supplied to Canada by the British unless the United
States approves, both Exon and Warner said.
   If the Pentagon decides to permit Canada to use the American
technology, Congress could block the plan within 90 days if both
the House and Senate pass resolutions of disapproval, Exon added.
   The Pentagon has not yet decided to grant a waiver to Britain,
Navy Secretary William Ball III told the Armed Services Committee
earlier this week.
   Exon noted that U.S. nuclear-powered sub technology had only
been transferred once in the past, to Britain, and he questioned
whether Canada has ``the money and the enormous infrastructure''
needed to safely operate the subs.
   ``In this era of nuclear phobia, we must maintain and enhance
our shipboard standards of nuclear propulsion,'' Exon said. Any
accidents aboard Canadian subs which involve U.S. technology would
raise fears about U.S. subs and could hamper the American Navy's
operation, he told his colleagues.
   Warner said, ``before we approve this decision, we need to know
how Canada proposes to fund this program, how Canada proposes to
insure that the standard of nuclear safety will be at least as high
as the United States and the British.''
   Exon said the technology involved may be outdated and he noted
that the Soviets are building a bigger, faster class of attack
boats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
