<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Toddler'sDeath     03-25 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toddler's Death,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says He Wanted Children Taken From Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old boy scalded to death in a welfare
hotel reportedly was removed from foster care and returned to his
mother and father last summer despite a judge's reservations.
   Police have charged that the mother, Marian McKenzie, 21,
murdered Quintin by holding him in 136-degree water because he had
soiled his diaper. The boy's father, Calvin, 23, has been charged
with beating him earlier that day.
   The McKenzies received custody of Quintin and his older sister,
Tanisha, after Judge Joseph Esquirol of Family Court in Brooklyn
dismissed a case brought in December 1986 by city child welfare
authorities.
   The city sought to remove the children from the McKenzies on
grounds that the father had beaten Quintin at a shelter in New
Jersey where the family then was living.
   New York Newsday and the Daily News reported that after numerous
delays during which the city produced no evidence of a beating,
Esquirol dismissed the case May 26.
   The judge stayed return of the children to June 3 and urged that
city or New Jersey officials refile the case.
   ``I know I certainly didn't want to return the children. The
mother had admitted to New Jersey authorities that the father beat
her and the children,'' the judge told Newsday. ``It was very, very
frustrating.''
   William Grinker, head of the city's Human Resources
Administration, has declined to comment before completion of an
investigation of his agency's handling of the case.
   Quintin had spent more than half his 41-month life in foster
care or hospitals, including the first six months of his life. He
weighed only 1.8 pounds when he was born prematurely.
</TEXT>
