<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HulaHoops     03-25 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hula Hoops,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hula Hoopers Set Twirling Record Amid Disneyland Hoopla</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey and Minnie Mouse led baby boomers
and their swivel-hipped soul mates of all ages back to the 1950s
Friday as 1,527 people simultaneously spun Hula Hoops at Disneyland
to claim a world record.
   The crowd _ certified by a turnstile count _ gyrated to the
strains of ``Whole Lotta Shakin' Goin' On'' until a representative
of the Guinness Book of World Records was satisfied he had
witnessed history's biggest crowd of Hula Hoopers.
   But for most of the swirlers, making Hula Hoop history took a
back seat to having fun.
   ``I'm reliving my childhood,'' said Frank Samagaio, 36, an
investigator with the San Diego district attorney's office.
   ``I was 7 years old when these came out,'' Samagaio said,
demonstrating that Hula Hooping, like riding a bike, is a skill one
never loses entirely.
   Some hoopers woke up as early as 4 a.m. to reach the park from
distant points of Southern California. They were all given
T-shirts, free park admission and Hula Hoops.
   The record try was a promotion by Disneyland and Hula Hoop maker
Wham-O, which is celebrating the 30th anniversary of the toy this
week.
   Some inept hoopers twirled the hoops on their wrists while
others madly twisted while the hoops inexorably spun farther and
farther down their legs.
   ``It's in the hips,'' confided Jackie Eastman, 11, of
Penasquitos, who got a hoop for her birthday March 9 and already
can twirl it for 10 minutes at a stretch.
   After three false starts, Dan Roddick, a Wham-O employee who
also serves as a Guinness field representative, proclaimed success,
which he had earlier defined as everyone putting his or her hoop
through three revolutions at once.
   While Guinness doesn't actually recognize a mass Hula Hoop
record at present, Roddick said the largest known mass swivel
appears to have been performed by about 350 people some 25 years
ago in the Northwest. That event is recorded only by a photograph,
he said.
   For some of the teens and young adults in Friday's crowd, the
event was sort of a ticket to more innocent times, symbolized for
them by pompadour hair-dos and the do-wop music of the 1950s and
early '60.
   ``It was happier,'' said Sarah Culver, 20, a college student
from Tustin who favors 1950s music, dance and clothes.
   ``The styles, they fit better, they're more feminine,'' Miss
Culver said. ``You can dance with the guys _ closer _ you don't
have to dance by yourself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
