<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathRow     03-25 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Row,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Says Investigators Will Look Into Affidavits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez said Friday that
investigators will look into claims that attorneys for death row
inmates asked witnesses to lie to save the prisoners' lives.
   Martinez, who earlier this week ordered the Florida Department
of Law Enforcement to check out the methods of the state-funded
defenders, said he didn't plan to interfere.
   ``I probably won't make any more announcements now until the
report comes in. It wouldn't be appropriate,'' he said.
   Martinez also established an independent seven-member commission
to review the investigation's findings to avoid any appearance that
he was mounting a political attack against the Office of Capital
Collateral Representative, a 3-year-old agency that has won stays
of executions for dozens of inmates.
   The St. Petersburg Times reported Friday that allegedly false
affidavits were given to Martinez and Attorney General Bob
Butterworth after witnesses _ two prison inmates, a Miami
prosecutor and a Miami lawyer _ complained about the conduct of
several employees of the collateral appeals office.
   In each case, inmates who testified against men on death row say
they were asked to sign false affidavits that would be used to gain
a stay of execution.
   Ronald Guralnick, the Miami lawyer who represented one of the
inmates, said attorneys from the Office of Capital Collateral
Representative in Tallahassee told him they had filed a motion
alleging ``everything possible'' and would ``try to prove it
later,'' the newspaper said.
   In both cases the affidavits, allegedly prepared by the death
row lawyers, accused police who handled the murder investigations
of inventing testimony that witnesses later repeated in court.
   Larry Spalding, the lawyer who supervises the collateral appeals
office, said he has questioned the lawyers involved in one instance
and will support them until he sees evidence to change his mind.
   ``The other one I know nothing about, but I will immediately
talk to those involved,'' Spalding said Thursday.
   Spalding blamed the investigation on the continuing controversy
between his office and a governor who, he said, wants to speed up
executions.
   Spalding's office was established in 1985 to handle appeals
filed by death row inmates. Those appeals traditionally involve
issues not concerning guilt of innocence, but legal procedures.
   The stae set up the appeals agency to provide lawyers for
indigent inmates making their final appeal and do away with claims
that inmates were not properly represented.
</TEXT>
