<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says He's the Moderate in the Democratic Field</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. portrayed his Democratic
presidential opponents as too liberal on Friday, saying ``you don't
have to be very far to the right to be to the right of this crowd.''
   Gore also said he was optimistic about his chances in Saturday's
Michigan caucuses.
   ``Wherever we have had a level playing field and enough time to
get the message out and become known by the voters, we have won,''
he told a radio audience in Detroit. ``The time in Michigan has
been short ... but we've got a lot of good friends working for us
and I hope that we'll do significantly better than people expect.''
   Gore has steadfastly tried to depict himself as the moderate
candidate in the presidential field.
   The Tennessee senator addressed the subject anew on Friday after
being asked a question on his defense posture.
   ``It's not conservative. I've never used that word. Let me
hasten to add, you don't have to be very far to the right to be to
the right of this crowd,'' he said.
   Earlier, in Racine, Wis., Gore rolled up his sleeves and joined
foundry workers at their jobs. Wearing a shiny white hardhat, blue
jeans and a leisure shirt, Gore took a 1{-hour tour of the Racine
Steel Casting plant.
   The campaign stop gave Gore a chance to shovel chunks of metal
into a furnace, to help a worker form a casting mold and to drive a
forklift and unload large metal sprockets.
   ``I think getting some hands-on experience is a way to
communicate symbolically with the workers,'' he said.
   Gore told reporters he will continue to campaign heavily in
Wisconsin, which will hold its primary April 5.
   ``I predict we're really going to surprise people in
Wisconsin,'' he said. ``Wisconsin has a chance to play a unique
role.''
   Gore also picked up the endorsement Friday of one-time
presidential candidate Eugene McCarthy.
   McCarthy, who was a senator from Minnesota when he sought the
Democratic nomination in 1968, said he endorses Gore because of his
experience and voting record on foreign affairs and economic and
environmental issues.
   ``There is no better preparation for the presidency than being
in Congress, especially the Senate,'' McCarthy said.
   ``I've felt for some time that the governorship is the worst
preparation for the presidency,'' McCarthy said. ``It provides a
great oversimplification of how the federal government operates.''
</TEXT>
