<2ND_LINE>AM-Surrogate Mom,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby M's Father Asks That Mother's Visitation Be Halted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allowing surrogate mother Mary Beth
Whitehead-Gould to continue visiting Baby M will hurt the child
psychologically, the toddler's father argued in court papers
released Friday.
   William Stern, who won custody of the baby in a landmark state
Supreme Court ruling Feb. 3, asked a Superior Court judge to
discontinue visitation. Stern's attorney said he will call expert
witnesses to show that halting visitation would be in the best
interest of the child, now legally known as Melissa Stern.
   ``Testimony will again reconfirm ... that visitation at this
particular point could only have a destabilizing influence on the
child and result in very grave consequences on her future mental
health,'' attorney Gary Skoloff said in court papers.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould has asked that she be allowed to spend more
time with the baby, with the meetings expanded eventually to half
the summer and some holidays.
   She has been allowed to see Melissa once a week, for two hours,
under supervision. Court papers released Thursday by Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould's attorneys call that schedule ``insufficient.''
   She contends that the child would be harmed if those visitations
were discontinued.
   ``Mrs. Whitehead-Gould has fashioned an excellent relationship
with Melissa and is devoted to promoting an even more flourishing
and productive relationship,'' said court papers filed by Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould's attorney, Harold Cassidy.
   The documents, filed earlier this week, give an indication what
both sides will argue when Superior Court Judge Birger M. Sween on
Monday convenes a visitation hearing that may be the final legal
skirmish in the fierce battle over the child, who turns 2 Sunday.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's $10,000 contract with Stern became a
highly publicized court case after she refused to turn over the
child she agreed to bear. Since the case began, Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould divorced her first husband, Richard Whitehead, and
married a Wall Street broker, Dean Gould.
</TEXT>
