<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Israel     03-25 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Israel,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says US `Totally Opposed' To Any Israeli Attack On Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan warned Israel on Friday that
the United States would be ``totally opposed'' to any Israeli
attack on Saudi Arabia's new intermediate-range missile launchers.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley, meanwhile,
confirmed that the administration has cautioned Israel not take
action against the newly delivered Chinese missiles.
   Mrs. Oakley refused to comment on reports that the Israeli air
force has been conducting low-level practice bombing runs.
   Reagan, asked how the United States would feel about Israeli
attacks on the Saudi sites, said, ``Naturally, we would be totally
opposed to any such thing and hope that they are not considering
any such act.''
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said in Cairo Thursday that he
had sent an urgent message to Reagan urging him to ``use his
influence with Israel and urge it to stop threatening Arab states
in this irresponsible way.'' Mubarak said such an attack would
``blow up the entire peace process'' in the Middle East.
   Reagan was asked about the situation as he prepared to meet with
visiting President Joaquin Balaguer of the Dominican Republic.
   On Wednesday, an unidentified Egyptian official said Cairo would
consider any Israeli attack on the installations an attack on Egypt
itself.
   Saudi Arabia recently acquired the missiles, which have a range
of 2,200 miles, enough to reach Iran and Israel. The missiles are
capable of carrying nuclear warheads, but both China and Saudi
Arabia have given assurances they will be fitted only with
conventional warheads.
   In Jerusalem, Yossi Ben-Aharon, a senior aide to Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir said, ``Israel has a tradition of not standing by
quietly when there is a real threat against it. The question is if
this is a threat or not. There are people to deal with it, the
Cabinet, the government.''
   Israel radio reported that Saudi Arabia issued a warning through
the United States that it would use any remaining missiles to
strike at the Jewish state if Israel attempted a pre-emptive strike.
   Ben-Aharon said U.S. officials had ``told us they are going to
deal with the matter the best they can, both in China and in Saudi
Arabia.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the Reagan
administration was ``concerned about any instability that is
introduced by weapons changes in the area'' and had made its views
known to both the Israelis and the Saudis. He added that ``our
protests have gone to the nuclear capability as opposed to the
site.''
</TEXT>
