<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunder In South, Warm In Northeast, But Snow In Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms battered parts of the South on Friday, locally
heavy rain fell around the lower Great Lakes and temperatures
reached record highs in the Northeast and Southern California. Snow
blew across the northern Plains.
   Thunderstorms reached across the lower Mississippi Valley into
Georgia and northwestern Florida. Hail as big as golf balls fell at
Natchez, Miss., in the morning and thunderstorm wind gusts caused
damage at Franklinton, La.
   During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 3.19 inches of rain fell
at McComb, Miss., and 1.61 inches fell at Jackson, Miss. West Palm
Beach, Fla., got 1.40 inches.
   Showers extended from the lower Great Lakes across the Ohio
Valley.
   More than 1.5 inches of rain fell from Wednesday night into
Friday afternoon across sections of northwestern Ohio, and the
National Weather Service warned of local flooding.
   Record high temperatures for the date included 71 at
Binghampton, N.Y.; 75 at Rochester, N.Y.; 88 at San Diego; 83 at
Santa Maria, Calif., and 77 at Williamsport, Pa.
   Snow continued to fall from northern North Dakota across
northern Minnesota.
   Advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted in North Dakota
and Minnesota. Seven inches of wet snow were reported overnight at
Bottineau, N.D., and 1 to 2 inches were reported over northwestern
Minnesota in the morning.
   Wind gusting to 50 mph caused blowing and drifting snow in open
areas.
   As much as 7 inches of snow were expected across the mountains
of northern Colorado, accompanied by high wind creating
near-blizzard conditions.
   Wind gusted to 120 mph in the morning at the top of Rendezvous
Peak, Wyo., to 90 mph at Wyoming's Curt Gowdy State Park, to 86 mph
at Colorado's Squaw Mountain and to 73 mph at Garden of the Gods in
Colorado.
   Wind and ice were blamed for a collision involving up to a dozen
vehicles in the morning along Interstate 70 near Georgetown, Colo.
The Colorado State Patrol said several people were taken to
hospitals with minor injuries.
   Elsewhere, showers extended along the northern Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 1 p.m. EST ranged from 27
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 96 at Palm Springs, Calif. The
morning low for the nation was 11 degrees at Yellowstone National
Park, Wyo.
   For Saturday, showers were forecast from the northern Pacific
Coast to the northern Rockies. Scattered snow was forecast over
Upper Michigan, changing to rain across Lower Michigan and eastern
Wisconsin. Rain and occasional thundershowers were forecast from
Maine across Georgia, the lower Great Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley
and the Appalachians.
   High in the mid 20s were predicted over northeastern Minnesota;
in the 30s and 40s over the remainder of the upper Great Lakes, the
upper Mississippi Valley, North Dakota and the northeast half of
South Dakota; in the 50s and 60s from New England across the
Virginias, over the lower Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the
Tennessee Valley, the central half of the Mississippi Valley,
southwestern South Dakota, the central Plains, the upper Missouri
Valley, and the Rockies to the northern half of the Pacific Coast;
in the 80s over much of Florida, southern through southwestern
Texas, and over much of central and southern California; in the 90s
across the desert Southwest, and in the 70s over most of the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
