<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Protest     03-25 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Protest,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police With Water Cannon Break Up Religious Freedom Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRATISLAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police used water cannon
Friday to break up a Roman Catholic demonstration for religious
freedom held in downtown Bratislava in defiance of an official ban,
Western observers said.
   Clashes broke out when police tried to clear the square of
thousands of Catholics who gathered in front of the Notre Dame
Cathedral. Injuries and arrests were reported, but no figures were
available.
   Bratislava is a southern city near the Czechoslovak-Austrian
border.
   Witnesses said it took security troops and riot police about 45
minutes to push the Catholics, who were singing, praying and
holding candles, into side streets to end the protest.
   Two television teams, sent to Bratislava from the Austrian state
radio-television corporation, ORF, and the West German ARD station,
were seen being shoved by police and detained as Catholics gathered
on the square. They were prevented from filming the protest.
   Frantisek Miklosko, a Slovak Catholic activist, had told
authorities of plans for a peaceful rally and organizers were
expecting up to 70,000 people would take part.
   But communist authorities Thurday banned the demonstration,
saying it was ``an event guided from abroad'' and directed against
the socialist system.
   Protesters defied the ban, saying they wanted a free and
independent church and 10 bishops appointed to fill vacant
bishoprics throughout Czechoslovakia.
   Government officials have been arguing with the Vatican over the
vacancies. Organizers also wanted to show support for a petition
calling for separation of church and state and for free expression
of religion, which has been signed so far by more than 430,000
Czechoslovak Catholics.
   The Austrian TV crew was released after 2{ hours, ORF journalist
Otto Hoermann reported.
   In a broadcast telephone call from his car driving toward the
nearby border, Hoermann said he and his colleagues saw about 100
Catholics who were taken to police headquarters.
   ``They were totally drenched,'' he said, referring to police use
of road-cleaning trucks and water cannon. ``It has also been
raining. So Bratislava must be today the cleanest city in central
Europe.''
   Hoermann said he saw many police with clubs around Bratislava as
he drove from the city.
   Demonstrators began gathering at 3.30 p.m. A witness said
shortly before 6 p.m., when the crowd was several thousand strong,
people clutching candles sang the Slovak and Czech national anthems.
   Police began moving street-cleaning trucks and police cars
toward the square. Authorities used loudspeakers to urged
demonstrators to vacate the square, saying: ``This demonstration
has not been allowed according to state laws. Will you please
disperse?''
   But the appeal went unheeded. Police cars, six abreast, drove
through the crowd. The scene became chaotic as demonstrators
blocked off some of the cars.
   Elderly women, middle-aged people and youngsters were among
those resisting.
   Then came the street-cleaning trucks, spewing water.
   Most of the demonstrators stood fast on the square.
   Authorities brought in riot police and three water cannon
drenched the crowd. The demonstrators still were not entirely
dispersed, and security troops shoved people off the square,
herding them into side streets.
   Students were warned this week not to take part in the protest
and threatened with losing their place at universities and
dormitories, the Austrian Catholic news agency Kathpress reported
Wednesday.
   Kathpress said the organizers insisted the event was registered
officially as a ``peaceful assembly of citizens.''
   They were also quoted as saying, ``Is it unlawful to stage a
rally for religious freedom, observance of human rights and
appointment of bishops by the pope ?''
   The state news agency CTK later said members of illegal church
structures tried to organize a ``quiet religious demonstration,''
the aim of which was to abuse religious feelings of believers,
violate relations between the socialist state and the church, and
undermine negotiations with the Vatican.
</TEXT>
