<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CanadaQuake     03-25 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada Quake,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Reported in Northwest Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake shook a sparsely populated
area of the Northwest Territories on Friday. There were no reports
of injuries or damage.
   The quake registered 6.0 on the Richter scale and was centered
about 95 miles west of Fort Simpson, 750 miles northwest of
Edmonton, said Bob Wetmiller, a federal seismologist.
   An earthquake of that magnitude can do serious damage, but
Wetmiller said it was too far from populated areas to pose a danger.
   It struck 12:36 p.m. MST and was felt in communities several
hundred miles away, he said.
   The last earthquakes of that magnitude in the region were in
1985. One of 6.6 was reported Oct. 5 and another of 6.9 on Dec. 23
that year.
   The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by
an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake with a magnitude of 5 can cause considerable damage in a
populated area; a magnitude 6 quake severe damage, one of magnitude
7 widespread, heavy damage and a magnitude 8 quake, a ``great''
earthquake capable of tremendous damage.
   A quake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans.
</TEXT>
