<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MillionaireSuicide     03-25 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Millionaire Suicide,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employee Sentenced To 10 Years For Helping Boss Commit Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scuba instructor was sentenced Friday
to 10 years in prison for fatally shooting his boss, who
authorities said was a suicidal millionaire who badgered and bribed
the employee to pull the trigger.
   Frederick Wisniewski, 27, of Linden had pleaded guilty to
aggravated manslaughter and aiding a suicide in the Nov. 25 death
of Julius ``Alex'' Bittmann, 44, of North Brunswick.
   ``I am sorry for it,'' Wisniewski told Superior Court Judge Paul
R. Kramer at sentencing.
   Wisniewski told authorities Bittmann badgered him for two months
before he agreed to kill him in return for $40,000 in cash and a
$60,000 Mercedes Benz.
   Wisniewski said Bittmann pleaded, ``Do it, do it!'' before he
killed Bittmann with a shot from a .357-caliber Magnum pistol in a
forest, authorities say. Bittmann had attempted suicide four times
previously, authorities said.
   Authorities said Wisniewski told them he drank a six-pack of
beer and some Scotch and snorted cocaine before going through with
Bittmann's request.
   Burlington County Prosecutor Stephen Raymond said the sentence
``sends out a clear message that this type of conduct isn't
excusable.''
   ``Julius Bittmann really did do everything but actually pull the
trigger,'' he said.
   Wisniewski will be eligible for parole after three years and
three months, authorities said.
   Bittmann owned a scuba shop in Edison where Wisniewski worked as
a diving instructor. Bittman amassed his fortune through several
businesses and real estate.
   Relatives and acquaintances have said that they do not know what
led to Bittmann's chronic depression, but that he had been taking
excessive amounts of anti-depressant drugs in recent years.
</TEXT>
