<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0662 03-25 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Denounces Reagan and Bush, Campaigns at Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update INSERTS six grafs after 12th graf bgng ``Mr. Reagan
... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson denounced President Reagan and
George Bush on Friday for opposing civil rights legislation and
accused presidential rivals in both parties of ``not offering
leadership to stop the flow of drugs.''
   Jackson, striving for a win in a big industrial state,
campaigned at the county jail, inner-city union halls and a
suburban high school, blending his criticism of Republicans with
stirring calls to shun the ``short-term thrill, long-term chill''
of drugs.
   On the eve of Michigan's statewide Democratic presidential
caucuses, Jackson provided his own answer to those who ask what he
seeks to accomplish with a candidacy that is dogged by the
assumption he cannot win the nomination, even as he leads the
Democratic field in popular votes cast.
   ``People always ask, no matter how we're winning, what does
Jesse Jackson want,'' Jackson said before a crowd of more than
1,000 people, jammed into the United Auto Workers Local 212 next
door to a shut-down Chrysler plant.
   ``What does Jesse want? I want to wipe out illiteracy,'' he said.
   ``What do I want? I want to raise the minimum wage. What do I
want? I want comparable worth for women. ...
   ``I want head start and day care early on, rather than jail-fare
and welfare later on,'' Jackson said.
   He called Reagan's veto of legislation extending a civil rights
law, and Bush's support for that veto, ``an attempt to turn back
the clock.'' Congress on Tuesday overrode Reagan's veto of the
bill, which covers discrimination by institutions that use federal
money. Reagan argued that the legislation would expand federal
power.
   ``Any man who stands ... against civil rights restoration in
this country is not fit to lead our nation,'' Jackson said.
   Linking drugs to problems of inner cities such as the one where
he was campaigning, Jackson criticized Vice President Bush
repeatedly and noted Bush's position as head of the
administration's fight against drugs.
   ``George Bush ... he's over the drug commission, and offers no
leadership,'' Jackson said at the UAW hall.
   ``Mr. Reagan, Mr. Bush, my competitors, are not offering
leadership to stop the flow of drugs,'' Jackson said.
   Later in Flint, Jackson named rivals Michael Dukakis and Albert
Gore Jr., and said he was outspent 50-to-1 by them in the South
``yet we got the most votes.''
   ``If they had my budget, they would surrender. If I had their
budget, they could not compete,'' he said.
   Jackson spoke at a Baptist church where the crowd was so large
people stood outside unable to get in. He also spoke in the parking
lot beside a UAW hall where Democrat Richard Gephardt spoke a day
earlier. Across the street was a GM auto assembly plant closed
three months ago, laying off some 3,500 workers.
   ``Foreign labor is not better labor, it's just cheaper labor,''
Jackson said. ``South Korea didn't take jobs from us, GM took jobs
to them.''
   At each stop Jackson gave careful instructions on how to vote in
Michigan's unusual caucus system. At one rally he called all the
young children in the crowd to gather around him.
   ``Who are you going to vote for?'' he asked them. ``Jesse,''
they responded.
   Jackson was running in a tight Michigan race with Dukakis,
according to most polls in Michigan, with Gephardt running third in
a state where he must win.
   Jackson, the black civil rights activist, is counting on doing
well in heavily black Detroit, even though the city's black mayor,
Coleman Young, is backing Dukakis.
   A Jackson victory in Michigan would be a major achievement for
his candidacy in a state of the industrial North _ one where only
16 years ago George Wallace won a stunning Democratic primary
victory.
   He spoke in a Detroit neighborhood not far from empty factories,
vacant lots and gutted storefronts.
   ``What does it matter to have civil rights, if you can march
downtown but can't walk down your own neighborhood streets?''
Jackson asked.
   Hours earlier, he visited the Wayne County jail and met with
about 30 inmates, all facing misdemeanor charges, and urged them to
use their time to read and learn and to reject drugs.
   ``Just because you're down, you don't have to be out; you can
change your situation,'' he said.
   Jackson urged the inmates to ask for absentee ballots and vote
in the presidential balloting being conducted at Saturday's
caucuses.
</TEXT>
