<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StolenHouse     03-25 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen House,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Sees His Beach Property Headed Down The Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHIRLEY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor said Friday he was looking out his
office window when he saw his house passing before his eyes.
   It was on a flatbed truck, headed out of town with a police
escort.
   ``I ran down the street and yelled, `Hey, where are you going
with my house?''' Dr. Frank Calabro, a general practitioner and
part owner of a real estate business, said in relating Thursday's
events.
   ``The cop looked at me like I was crazy,'' said Calabro, 55.
   ``This is your house, mister?'' the officer asked.
   ``This is a house-napping,'' Calabro told him.
   The officer stopped the convoy and walked to the back to talk to
the man who had ordered the house moved. He was gone.
   ``We all stood in the street laughing,'' said Calabro. ``It
seemed so ridiculous. Who would steal a house?''
   The answer, provided by the boss of the flatbed truck, was a guy
who sold it to someone else for $500, then hired the mover to
deliver it.
   ``The concept of a man's home being his castle has been shaken
to its very foundation,'' Suffolk County District Attorney Patrick
Henry said.
   The two-bedroom yellow beach house with a white door had been
placed on runners for removal because Calabro had sold it _ a
$12,000 value _ earlier in the week.
</TEXT>
