<DOCNO> AP880325-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1910EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Waldheim     03-25 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents Show Waldheim Transcribed, Forwarded Order To Kill
Partisans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austrian President Kurt Waldheim, while
serving in the German army, received and then forwarded Adolf
Hitler's order to kill captured Greek partisans, according to
documents released Friday.
   The documents from the U.S. National Achives are Waldheim's army
group's war diary and a corresponding Nuremberg War Trial document.
They were provided by the World Jewish Congress.
   ``The chief witness against Kurt Waldheim is the one he can
never refute _ his own name on the captured Nazi war records,''
said Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish
Congress.
   John Russell, a Justice Department spokesman, confirmed Friday
that the war diary and Nuremberg records were among documents used
in deciding to place Waldheim on the ``watchlist'' that bars
undesirable aliens from the United States.
   The Austrian government has protested that the U.S. government
has not disclosed the documents. Waldheim, U.N. secretary-general
from 1972 to 1982, has denied committing any war crimes, although
his army unit was accused of them.
   Waldheim served with the German army during World War II in the
occupied Balkans. He was a lieutenant in the German General Staff
attached to the 11th Italian Army in Athens.
   The documents show that on Aug. 8, 1943, Waldheim entered
Hitler's order to kill captured Greek partisans in his army group's
war diary in Athens and on the same day transmitted the order by
radio to a German division in the field.
   The diary entry signed by Waldheim said: ``According to a new
Fuehrer order bandits (partisans) captured in battle are to be
shot. Others suspected of banditry, etc., are to be taken prisoner
and sent to Germany for use in labor details.'' The translation was
provided by the World Jewish Congress.
   The word ``bandit'' was used to describe partisans.
   The Nuremberg document shows the actual transmission of the
order: ``To the 1st Mountain Division: Reference Teletype Ia No.
959-43 Secret of 7 Aug. 1943 concerning shooting of bandits. A new
Fuehrer order is at hand, which will be transmitted. Bandits taken
in battle are to be shot. Other bandit suspects etc. are to be
arrested and evacuated for `Sauckel' labor service.''
   SS Gen. Fritz Sauckel, sentenced to death at Nuremberg, ran a
network of slave labor camps. The 1st Mountain Division was
operating against the anti-Nazi resistance in northern Greece.
   Steinberg said the documents were made available at this time
because Waldheim, despite his protests, has failed to appeal the
``watchlist'' decision.
   ``These documents demonstrate the basis for that decision and
the evidence is devastating,'' he said.
   An Austrian ``white book'' rebutting charges against Waldheim
makes brief reference to the war diary but does not mention his
role in forwarding the Hitler order and does not mention the
Nuremberg document.
   Steinberg said that in the ``white book'' Waldheim ``ignores
half the diary entry which says these instructions on treatment of
bandits are being transmitted.''
   The World Jewish Congress located the Waldheim war diary and
Nuremberg document at the U.S. National Archives in 1986 and turned
them over to the Justice Department.
   A commission of historians appointed by the Austrian government
issued a report earlier this year saying Waldheim was in a position
to know of atrocities but did not try to stop them.
</TEXT>
