<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HumanRights     03-25 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Human Rights,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Agree To Allow US Psychiatrists To Visit Soviet Mental
Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials agreed in principle during a
human rights conference that ended Friday to allow American
psychiatrists to visit Soviet mental hospitals, a high-ranking
State Department official said.
   That could lead to examination by Americans of Soviets believed
to be incarcerated in mental institutions solely because they are
dissidents.
   Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for human rights,
said the agreement was reached during a unique ``roundtable
discussion'' between Soviet and U.S. psychiatrists and legal
experts.
   The purpose of the conference, from the American side, was to
press the Soviets to put into practice recent pledges to improve
human rights, to allow judicial review of government actions
affecting human rights and to explore ways the Soviets could
moderate policies on capital punishment, control of religious
activity and use of mental hospitals.
   Unlike the United States, where commitment is a legal process,
the Soviet Union permits incarceration in a mental hospital if two
psychiatrists sign the order.
   For years, the United States, Soviet activists and psychiatrists
around the world have accused the Russians of using the system to
lock up dissidents who are perfectly sane. The practice has
reportedly been stopped in new cases, but Schifter said: ``there
are certain persons whose names have come up _ still in psychiatric
institutions _ who in the opinion of a great many people may be
there for reasons other than their mental health.''
   Under the agreement at the conference, in addition to visiting
the Soviet institutions, there may be requests for visiting
psychiatrists to examine specific patients, Schifter said. ``I
consider that a possibility.''
   Soviet psychiatrists will also visit U.S. mental institutions.
   Schifter said the U.S. government would not be involved in the
exchanges, but would leave all arrangements to private psychiatric
groups.
   At the conference, Schifter said, the Soviets also were willing
to discuss the issue of capital punishment. He said the Soviet
Union performs 10 times as many executions as are carried out in
the United States each year and that there have been some
indications Moscow is examining whether to continue applying the
death penalty for major economic crimes.
   He said the U.S. participants also suggested the Soviets
consider dropping use of capital punishment in national security
cases. The last spies executed in the United States were Julius and
Ethel Rosenberg, who were convicted in the early 1950s of giving
atomic bomb secrets to Russia.
   Among the participants in the roundtable _ the first conference
of its type under a 1975 agreement to hold them _ were Loren Roth,
of the Western Psychiatric Institute, Roger Peele, director of St.
Elizabeth's Hospital in Washington and Frank Kaufman, a federal
judge in Baltimore.
   The Soviet delegates included Anatoliy L. Adamishin, the deputy
foreign minister, Vasiliy A. Vlasikhin, of the USA-Canada Institute
and Gennadily N. Milekhin, of the Serbskiy Institute, a Soviet
hospital.
   Paul Kamenar of the Washington Legal Foundation said the chief
accomplishment of the conference was ``the recognition by the
Soviets that they have shortcomings; that they have problems.'' He
said the Soviets agreed to hold several workshops on human rights
and appeared to be eager to talk about the rights situation.
   ``Talk is cheap, but this is a beginning and we'll see where it
goes,'' Kamenar said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
