<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0660 03-25 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central American Leaders Praise Nicaraguan Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Mexico, Guatemala, Cuba reax
and EDITS to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By OLDEMAR RAMIREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Oscar Arias hailed a
60-day cease-fire between the Nicaraguan government and rebels as
offering a ``a new and firm hope that all Central Americans can
live in peace.''
   The presidents of Mexico and Guatemala, meeting Friday at
Mexico's Caribbean resort of Cancun to discuss the cease-fire
accord, denounced what they called foreign interference and
military threats in Central America.
   They did not specifically name the United States, but their
remarks appeared directed at Washington.
   ``Mexico is demanding absolute respect for the sovereignty of
peoples'' in Central America, Mexican President Miguel de la Madrid
said in a speech welcoming President Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala.
   Cuba, which along with the Soviet Union has been helping
Nicaragua with military advisers and weapons, called the truce
agreement a hope for peace but said it would not undermine the
revolutionary principles of Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government.
   In a dispatch, the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina noted that
President Reagan said he welcomed the agreement between Nicaragua
and the rebels, but that he also added there ``is reason to have
caution'' because of the Sandinistas' past actions.
   ``It would not be surprising if the United States would now
exert pressure on the Contra leaders to abhor the agreement with
Managua and force them to retake the path of war,'' Prensa Latina
said in its dispatch, received Friday in Mexico City.
   Arias, who won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for drawing up a
Central American peace plan that calls for cease-fires in the
region's wars, said Thursady he believes the Nicaraguan agreement
can succeed.
   ``I want to be optimistic and trust the good faith of those who
signed the document,'' he said.
   The agreement was signed Wednesday in the Nicaraguan border town
of Sapoa, near the Costa Rican border.
   ``If an effective cease-fire is achieved for 60 days and can be
extended there is no reason whatsoever not to advance in fulfilling
the other points'' in the peace plan, he said.
   The peace plan, signed by the five Central American presidents
last Aug. 7 in Guatemala, also calls for democratic reforms,
amnesties and an end to outside aid to insurgencies.
   Arias said the region's conflicts also must be dealt with by the
United States and Soviet Union ``who will have to do their share so
that they get their hands out of Central America.''
   De la Madrid and Cerezo are to hold two days of talks in Cancun.
High on their agenda is the Nicaraguan pact and U.S. efforts to
force Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega out of
office.
   ``We observe with worry how in Central America military threats
and foreign interference are taking on a new impulse ... along with
economic aggression and military intimidation,'' de la Madrid said
in his welcoming speech.
   Cerezo, referring to U.S. troops in Honduras, said, ``We are
ready to do everything possible so that the nations of the world
learn to respect us and to help other peoples of the world become
masters of their own destinities.''
   The Reagan administration sent 3,200 American soldiers to
Honduras last week at the request of Honduran President Jose Azcona
Hoyo, who accused Nicaraguan troops of crossing the border into his
country to attack base camps of the U.S.-backed Contras.
   Nicaragua denied its troops had entered Honduras. Honduran
officials said earlier this week the Sandinistas had withdrawn.
   De la Madrid and Cerezo made no mention of the Nicaraguan
cease-fire agreement in their remarks at Cancun.
   Arias told a news conference Thursday in San Jose the United
States was not justified in sending troops to Honduras and there
was no reason for them to remain there any longer.
   He also said he had discussed with Cerezo the possibility of
another meeting of Central American presidents.
   ``There is much to talk about and clarify,'' he said, but did
not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
