<HEAD>Six Killed, 20,000 Evacuated As Storm Pounds Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential rains swept across
central Argentina Friday and civil defense officials reported six
storm-related deaths. They said flooding forced the evacuation of
about 20,000 people.
   Two women were electrocuted by downed power lines as they tried
to cross streets in suburban Buenos Aires, according to the
officials. They said a 19-year-old woman drowned in Villa Ponsati
and three people drowned in Florencio Varela _ two girls ages 3 and
4 and a 24-year-old man.
   It was the second day of haevy rains. Among those evacuated were
many of the 11,000 residents of Moron and Quilmes near Buenos Aires.
   Flooding disrupted rail and road transportation and telephone
service.
   There were widespread power outages in Buenos Aires, which has a
population of 10 million, and the port city of La Plata, 30 miles
south of the capital.
   Weather forecasters said the rains could continue through Sunday.
</TEXT>
