<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Dorrian's     03-25 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dorrian's,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bar Becomes Symbol for `Preppie' Lifestyle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chambers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On Aug. 25, 1986, Dorrian's Red Hand was just
another Upper East Side bar catering to the young and upwardly
mobile: a hangout for yuppies and preppies, where the Izod crowd
came to knock back a few.
   Twenty-four hours later, all that changed.
   With the death of Jennifer Dawn Levin early on the morning of
Aug. 26, Dorrian's became _ fairly or unfairly _ a symbol of
youthful decadence, of teen-agers with too much money and no place
to go.
   Among them was Robert Chambers, who sat at the bar drinking
shots of tequila with beer chasers the night he killed Miss Levin.
   ``He fouled everybody's life up,'' bar owner John F. ``Jack''
Dorrian said recently. ``Who needs this guy?''
   After Miss Levin's death, investigators returned to Dorrian's
and closed the bar for 10 days for serving underage patrons in
November 1986. Dorrian has put the bar up for sale; no buyer has
been found.
   Chambers, now 21, had been a regular at Dorrian's. He also was a
college dropout who had a very proper upbringing.
   Dinner at the Chambers house, located next to the former Andrew
Carnegie mansion a few blocks north of Dorrian's, ``always had
silver involved,'' said Ralph Destino, a friend of Chambers,
shortly after his arrest.
   Chambers apparently had no steady job at the time of his arrest,
yet was drinking and flirting ``five or six nights a week'' at
Dorrian's, said its owner.
   Interviews in the months since the slaying indicate Dorrian's
remains attractive, a place where young people can gather in front
of an ornate fireplace and play backgammon at the tables.
   Regulars said they avoided Dorrian's after Miss Levin died,
fearing the bar had been taken over by the curious. But the young
men and women who grew up in the wealthy neighborhood and knew one
another in the best prep schools came back.
   Miss Levin was not a regular at Dorrian's but was known there.
Patrons don't talk much about the case, they said.
   ``I come here when I feel like sitting around like I'm in my
living room,'' said Alyssa Donati, 21, who said she has been
frequenting Dorrian's for five years.
   Dorrian himself knows who's who in the bar; he can point out the
child of a well-known writer and the daughter of a presidential
adviser. John Zaccaro Jr., son of ex-Democratic vice presidential
nominee Geraldine Ferraro, was tending bar the night of the death.
   Chambers would no longer be welcome, Dorrian said. Other
regulars would say tourists, out-of-towners and the curious are not
welcome either.
   ``Parents like their kids to come here,'' Miss Donati said 17
months after Miss Levin's death. ``Here they know the people are
from at least good families, they've been to good colleges, and
they're not out to rape people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BalloonTrip 1stLd-Writethru a0640 03-25 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Balloon Trip, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloonists' Bid to Circle Earth Scuttled By Weather</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 pvs bgng: ``The last word...' with 3 grafs on
storm across Argentina, six deaths. PICKS up 5th graf pvs,
`Petrehn, head of...' ADDS 3 grafs at bottom on flight plan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempt by two U.S.
adventurers to circle the Earth in a balloon in 9 to 14 days was
scuttled Friday by bad weather, officials said.
   The attempt by John Petrehn and Rowland Smith, both of Kansas,
to launch their 360-foot-high balloon from Mendoza was canceled by
heavy rains, and poor weather forecast this weekend jeopardizes the
entire project, said U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Patricia Rosker.
   Torrential rains lashed central Argentina from the Atlantic to
the Andes for the second day and officials on Friday blamed the
storms for six deaths. Weather forecasters said the rain would
continue through Sunday.
   Ms. Rosker said of the balloonists, ``The last word I have is
that they're planning to launch on Tuesday. That will be the final
day. After that, the project will have to be canceled, which would
be a pity because of all the effort they've put into this.''
   The balloonists are trying to do what no one else has: Circle
the Earth around the 45-degree parallel in the Southern Hemisphere
using longitudinal winds that carry them to the east, Ms. Rosker
said.
   Petrehn, head of the project, is a 52-year-old businessman from
Topeka, Kan., while Smith, 50, is a former Vietnam War pilot and a
Kansas-based pilot for Trans World Airlines.
   They chose Mendoza, 660 miles west of Buenos Aires as their
launch and landing site because ``apparently it was the part of the
world where there are more days of sun and good weather and because
it had good wind conditions,'' Ms. Rosker said.
   The balloonists have received about $2.5 million in donations
for the project, which includes scientific experiments measuring
ozone levels along the 45th parallel, she said.
   They plan to ride in a specially devised gondola. It contains a
small porthole for a window, a bed and one chair. They plan to
maintain contact along the route with radar and sophisticated radio
equipment, she said.
   ``It has a small window like a mini-sub and is quite
uncomfortable. Also very dangerous because practically all the time
they will be flying over water with no help. If a storm arises and
it's not predicted by satellite, they will be in trouble,'' she
said.
   Two balloons, one of hot air and the other of helium, will ride
piggyback above the gondola, allowing the craft to rise and fall by
opening valves of hot air as it travels east with the prevailing
winds, Ms. Rosker said.
   ``They can reach an altitude of 30,000 feet. The gondola is
pressurized for their comfort and they will use the same type of
food as astronauts, dehydrated food and lots of water,'' she said.
   According to Petrehn, Smith and members of the crew of 24 that
helped bring the balloons and gondola to Argentina, the flight
would be the first non-stop, unrefueled, manned balloon trip around
the world.
   The craft's intended flight from El Plumerillo air base outside
Mendoza would take it over the Atlantic, about 200 miles south of
Africa, across the Indian Ocean, south of Australia, over the
southern New Zealand island of Campbell Island to Chile where it
would cross the Andes and arrive back in Argentina after 17,545
miles.
   Petrehn and Smith said the longest manned balloon flight was
that of the Double Eagle V, which in 1981 crossed the Pacific and
covered about 5,000 miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Chambers 3rdLd-Writethru a0768 03-25 0949</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0768,0976</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chambers Pleads to Manslaughter in `Preppie Murder' Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to ADD definition of manslaughter,
CLARIFY when trial opened, UPDATE with explanation of plea bargain
and quotes from victim's mother and a juror, and ADD detail on
prior relationship of defendant and victim. Picks up 18th graf pvs,
`For four ...' Trims last two grafs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Chambers pleaded guilty to a lesser
charge of manslaughter Friday for strangling a young woman during
sex in Central Park, halting jury deliberations in the ``preppie
murder'' case after nine days.
   State Supreme Court Justice Howard E. Bell asked Chambers
whether he intended to cause ``serious injury'' to 18-year-old
Jennifer Levin ``and thereby cause her death.'' State law defines
first-degree manslaughter as causing a death while intending to
cause serious injury.
   ``Looking back on everything, I have to say yes,'' Chambers, 21,
said. ``It breaks my heart to have to say that.''
   At that, prosecutor Linda Fairstein shot up and said loudly,
``We're asking about his mind and his hands, not his heart.'' The
judge repeated the question, and Chambers replied, ``Yes.''
   Chambers' mother, Phyllis Chambers, stared straight ahead,
showing no emotion. His father, Robert, also sat silently.
   Miss Levin's death in the summer of 1986 focused attention on
the lives of wealthy young New Yorkers. It also drew protests from
feminists, who argued that Chambers' defense was an example of
blaming women for male violence.
   Chambers had maintained that he never intended to hurt Miss
Levin, whom he had dated before, and killed her accidentally with a
swipe of his arm when she hurt him during rough sex. The sexual
encounter was not their first.
   Chambers originally was charged with second-degree murder, which
carries a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
   Under a plea bargain, he will be sentenced to five to 15 years.
He could have received up to eight and one-third to 25 years on the
charge. Sentencing was set for April 15.
   The plea bargain, reached after two days of negotiations, came
as the jury was in its ninth day of deliberations. Chambers' trial
began with jury selection Oct. 21. Opening arguments started Jan. 4.
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said that the
prospect of a possible mistrial, the strain on the Levin family and
the circumstantial nature of the evidence prompted the plea bargain.
   ``I'll feel better tomorrow when he's in jail, where he should
be,'' said Ellen Levin, Jennifer's mother. ``He wasn't the
lily-white altar boy he appeared to be.''
   Chambers, who was free on $157,500 bail during the trial, will
surrender Saturday morning, said his attorney, Jack Litman.
   Chambers also pleaded guilty to second-degree burglary in an
unrelated indictment, with his sentence to run concurrent with his
manslaughter sentence.
   One juror said the votes on the murder charge swung from 8-4 for
acquittal to 9-3 for conviction, and the last vote was 7-5 for
acquittal. But he said he felt the jury could have reached a
verdict. The judge had sealed the jurors' names, and the juror who
spoke would identify himself only as Mike.
   When lawyers involved in the burglary case appeared earlier in
the day, prompting speculation about a plea bargain, Miss Levin's
grandfather Arnold Domenitz, 72, said he found such talk
``sickening.''
   ``If that wasn't so tragic, it would be funny,'' he said.
   Shortly after Miss Levin's body was found, Chambers told police
in a videotaped statement that she had ``molested'' him sexually
and hurt his genitals.
   For four hours during his closing argument, Litman appealed to
the jury to acquit Chambers. ``What he was doing was reacting to
the pain,'' Litman said. ``He was trying to stop her'' and the
result was a ``tragic accident.''
   Fairstein called the story ``ludicrous.'' She said he attacked
Miss Levin in a rage, punched her, chased her when she tried to
flee, caught her and ``squeezed the life out of her.''
   Fairstein, holding a photo of Miss Levin taken in a bar hours
before her death, told the jury: ``One can't help but look at that
photograph and pray for time to stand still, for time to grab her
and say, `Don't go with Robert Chambers.'''
   The judge told the jury that while ``motive is not an element of
the crime charged here,'' the lack of one is a circumstance from
which they might infer innocence.
   Fairstein had been hard put to offer a motive, and suggested
Chambers strangled Miss Levin after an argument which started when
he was impotent after a night of drinking.
   ``Perhaps he couldn't perform because he had too many beers and
shots of tequila that night,'' she said.
   At 11:30 p.m. Aug. 25, 1986, Chambers arrived at Dorrian's Red
Hand. The bar-restaurant on Manhattan's Upper East Side, in the
heart of one of the city's wealthiest areas, was popular among
privileged young people, many of them younger than New York's legal
drinking age of 21.
   The atmosphere, bartender John Zacarro Jr. testified, was
festive. Patrons on their way to colleges table-hopped, embraced
friends and laughed.
   That night Chambers, a Boston University dropout, talked with
Miss Levin, who was planning to go to college that fall. They left
together.
   The prosecution presented 25 witnesses and 120 exhibits,
including many color photos of Miss Levin's bruised and nearly nude
body beneath a tree behind the Metropolitan Museum of Art where she
was found by a bicyclist at daybreak.
   The prosecutor argued the victim's left eye, red and swollen,
and the fracture in a small bone in Chambers' hand show that the
defendant assaulted her with ``hands as deadly as any arsenal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
