<DOCNO> AP880325-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2317EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HaroldsSold     03-25 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harolds Sold,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landmark Casino and Last of Hughes' Gaming Empire Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harolds Club, the last remaining property in
the gaming empire of the late Howard Hughes, has been sold, it was
announced Friday.
   The Lincoln Group, which owns Fitzgeralds hotel-casino across
the street from Harolds and operates the Nevada Club next door,
announced the purchase from Hughes Properties Inc. The price was
not disclosed.
   Harolds Club was founded in 1935 by gaming pioneer Harold Smith.
   Hughes arrived in Las Vegas in 1966 and began buying gaming
properties the following year with the purchase of the Desert Inn.
Within a few years he owned the Desert Inn, the Landmark, the
Frontier, the Sands, the Silver Slipper and the Castaways in Las
Vegas and Harolds Club. The reclusive billionaire died in 1976.
   Lincoln Group President Phil Griffith, who was president of
Harolds Club from 1978 until 1984, called the purchase ``a project
close to our hearts.'' The Lincoln Group also owns Fitzgerald's
hotel-casino in Las Vegas.
   The Lincoln Group said it will take over Harolds on May 31 and
close it for about a month for remodeling.
   Hughes revolutionized gaming in the late 1960s by introducing
corporate ownership into a business previously dominated by
individual owners like Smith.
   Hughes' company in December sold its last two Las Vegas
properties, the Frontier and the Silver Slipper.
   Earlier last year, it sold the Desert Inn and Sands resorts to
financier Kirk Kerkorian and previously sold the Castaways to
Golden Nugget owner Steven Wynn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
