<DOCNO> AP880325-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Nazis     03-25 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Nazis,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>War Criminals Wanted: Britain Advertises For Nazi Info</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government began using newspaper ads Friday to
drum up information about Nazi war criminals, apparently in reponse
to charges it has not been energetic in pursuing perpetrators of
World War II atrocities.
   ``War Criminals _ Evidence Wanted,'' read the heading of the ad
that appeared in the Times of London and other papers with national
circulations.
   The advertisements were taken out by a special war crimes
inquiry panel set up after the Nazi-hunting Simon Wiesenthal Center
accused the British government of failing to seek and prosecute war
criminals.
   ``It is alleged that some war criminals responsible for
genocide, murder or manslaughter in Germany or German-occupied
territories during the Second World War are in the (United
Kingdom),'' the ad says.
   ``Others with British nationality may be living elsewhere in the
world. The names of some suspects have already been sent to the
Home Office.''
   The advertisements say that when the inquiry is complete, Home
Minister Douhlas Hurd will advise the government ``whether there is
sufficient evidence to justify the prosecution of the alleged
offenders.''
   They ask anyone with ``any information that you think may be
relevant'' to write the Home Office. The ads are to be repeated in
newspapers Sunday.
   The inquiry panel is headed by the former director of public
prosecutions, Sir Thomas Hetherington, and William Chambers, a
former senior government official in Scotland.
   Hetherington and Chambers will spend a year investigating
evidence and interviewing people with information in Britain and
abroad, including the Soviet Union.
   Efrain Zuroff, director of the Wiesenthal Center's Israel
office, last month gave British officials the names of two more
alleged war criminals and more evidence against nine suspects the
government already confirmed are living in Britain.
   Zuroff said at that time that the center expects dozens of
suspected war criminals living in Britain and other Western
countries to stand trial within 18 months as new legal changes
close in on the suspects.
   He said in an interview in London last month that, before Hurd
set up the inquiry, Britain was the only major Western country that
refused to take any action against alleged war criminals.
   The Los Angeles-based Wiesenthal center has submitted the names
of a total of 256 suspects to eight countries _ Australia, Brazil,
Britain, Canada, Sweden, the United States, Venezuela and West
Germany _ where they are alleged to have fled after the war ended
in 1945.
   The suspects are mainly from the Ukraine, Latvia and Lithuania,
all now part of the Soviet Union. They are accused of collaborating
with Nazi invaders in killing Jews and others.
   British-resident suspects include a former Lithuanian platoon
commander, 71-year-old Antanas Gecas, who lives in Edinburgh,
Scotland.
   The Wiesenthal center alleges Gecas killed more Jews than Klaus
Barbie, the so-called Butcher of Lyon. Gecas, a retired mining
engineer, says he is innocent and the accusations have wrecked his
life.
   The Wiesenthal center tracked down the suspects, mostly over age
70, after gaining access to international immigration data in late
1986.
   West Germany and the United States are probing cases identified
by the center, while Australia and Canada set up inquiry
commissions and changed their laws recently to allow prosecutions.
   Zuroff charged last month that Brazil, Sweden and Venezuela have
done little or nothing to trace the individuals or prosecute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0699 03-25 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0699,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Son Testifies Dealership `Very Strong'; Governor to Testify</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Mecham returning to stand, saying he
was told he could use money for practically `any damn thing.' No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham, fighting charges he
misused $80,000 from a ``protocol fund'' by loaning it to his auto
dealership, testified Friday he was told he could use the money for
practically ``any damn thing that you want.''
   The first-term Republican said he had never heard the money
referred to as public funds.
   Testimony at the governor's Senate impeachment trial in recent
days has focused on his borrowing at 9 percent interest money that
had been raised by his inaugural ball.
   State law had barred him from using the money to pay off
campaign debts, and a ``protocol fund'' was set up instead last
year. Witnesses said the fund was intended to promote Arizona
through events and gifts to visiting dignitaries.
   The prosecution contends the fund was public money; the defense
contends that it was private and that it was borrowed because
Mecham's dealership was in desperate financial straits.
   Mecham said he received instructions on use of the money from
William Long, chairman of Mecham's inaugural committee, which had
raised the funds before learning they could not be used to retire
campaign debts.
   ``Mr. Long said, `We have gone through all of this rigamarole
and you can spend it for any damn thing that you want,' those were
his words, `except you can't spend it for politics or personal
living expenses,''' Mecham testified.
   ``I never heard the words discussed, `public funds,''' the
63-year-old governor said under questioning by his attorney, Jerris
Leonard.
   A key piece of evidence in the case is a letter of agreement
signed by Long and the Maricopa County attorney agreeing that money
placed in the fund could be used only to promote the interests of
Arizona and encourage public service.
   However, Long, in an affidavit submitted by the defense Friday,
said he ``did not intend to transfer these monies as a gift to the
state of Arizona.''
   The misuse of funds charge is the second of three impeachment
counts before the Senate, which earlier heard testimony on an
allegation Mecham attempted to obstruct an investigation of an
alleged death threat. The governor has also been accused of
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial in
six decades, also faces a recall election May 17 and a criminal
trial April 21 on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan.
   Mecham, who took the stand shortly before the trial recessed for
the weekend, began answering allegations that his Mecham Pontiac
dealership was in financial trouble and needed the $80,000 borrowed
in July.
   He and his attorney presented documents that they said showed
the company had an unencumbered net value of $2.5 million at the
time. A prosecution accountant had testified the company owed more
than it was worth.
   Asked about a $101,900 loan that was in default last summer,
Mecham said that was a mistake.
   ``Quite frankly, I wasn't watching my details,'' he said. ``I
was a little red faced when they caught up with me and I took care
of it.''
   In testimony earlier Friday, Mecham's son denied the family car
business was in financial distress when the $80,000 loan was made
in July.
   Dennis Mecham, 37, who took over as general manager of Mecham
Pontiac when his father was elected in 1986, supported his father's
statement that he borrowed the money only so it would earn higher
interest than it was getting.
   ``He called up and asked if I could use $80,000 in the
dealership operation,'' Dennis Mecham recalled of his talk with his
father last July. ``I said yes. I'd say yes to anyone who had
$80,000 to loan me.''
   ``He said it was the inaugural fund and it was just sitting
there,'' the younger Mecham recalled. ``He wanted to roughly double
the interest it was getting.
   ``I needed the money, but the rate of interest had to be
reasonable. I didn't want him to stiff me,'' the younger Mecham
said with a laugh. ``Of course, I knew he wouldn't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-Prison     03-25 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Prison,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Salvador Prison, Two People Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 guerrillas blew a
hole in the wall of El Salvador's largest prison Friday, entered
the compound and fought guards in a half-hour battle that left two
people dead, officers reported.
   Gen. Rinaldo Golcher, deputy security minister, told reporters
about 10 prisoners escaped from the Mariona penitentiary just north
of the capital of San Salvador as the lestist guerrillas withdrew.
No guerrilla casualties were reported.
   Officials did not give a breakdown on the number of common
criminals and the number of rebels held in Mariona, a facility that
normally holds 1,000 prisoners.
   Seven guards were wounded by rifle fire and grenade shrapnel and
``some prisoners'' also were injured, Golcher said. ``There are
probably some dead,'' he added.
   A guard interviewed by journalists as he left the prison said
two civilian employees were killed. Some inmates set fires as the
left-wing rebels launched their attack in the early afternoon,
according to the guard.
   He said ``about 200'' guerrillas made the assault and Golcher
reported a large number managed to get into the prison grounds
during the ``very strong'' attack.
   A first-aid worker said three civilian employees suffered
serious bullet wounds and were taken by ambulances to hospitals.
   Journalists were kept hundreds of yards away from the
penitentiary as scores of soldiers were rushed to the prison. Two
helicopters flew over the compound.
   The guerrillas have been fighting the U.S.-backed government
since 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
