<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Protest     03-25 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Protest,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Striking Teachers Rally To Demand Higher Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30,000 striking teachers
rallied in front of the federal government building Friday,
demanding higher wages to end a walkout that has idled 7.2 million
schoolchildren.
   The protesters are among 505,000 public school instructors who
remain off the job. Primary school teachers went on strike March
14, the first day of the Argentine school year, and were joined
Monday by secondary school teachers.
   No violence was reported during the giant rally in front of the
Government House, the seat of the federal government. Teachers
waved placards, taunted the government and listened to remarks by
union leaders.
   Teachers are seeking a minimum salary of $118 a month. The
government has countered with an offer of $84 a month, saying it
cannot afford more because of Argentina's economic crunch.
   The teachers' union, the Confederation of Educational Workers of
the Argentine Republic, is part of the four million-member General
Confederation of Labor, Argentina's largest and most influential
union.
   Argentina's foreign debt of $50 billion is among Latin America's
largest and payment of interest on the debt seriously drains its
reserves. Inflation in 1987 was 175 percent, more than twice the
rate of 1986.
</TEXT>
