<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoBuggies     03-25 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Buggies,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palm Beach Rejects Horse-And-Buggy Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite promises of horse-diapers and
careful drivers, this luxury resort has said neigh to a
$100-an-hour horse-and-carriage service similar to those operated
in New York's Central Park.
   ``Horses are lovely animals. I think they're very beautiful _ in
someone else's town,'' Town Councilman Paul Ilyinsky said Thursday
after the Palm Beach Public Safety Committee turned down the
proposal.
   Ilyinsky said there would be accidents and ``a lot of mangled
horses'' if they were allowed to trot around town.
   Darcy Canevari, 24, who runs a horse-drawn carriage service in
Norwalk, Conn., had asked for a trial run.
   ``I think people would love it,'' she said. ``It's very
romantic.''
   If anyone objects to manure on the streets, Canevari said, the
animals will be fitted with diapers. She said, however, that in
some towns ``they like to have the manure on the streets to let
people know the horses are there.''
</TEXT>
