<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SovietExchange     03-25 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Exchange,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rare Islamic Art To Be Exhibited in Two U.S. Museums Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is lending nine rare works of
Islamic art for an exhibition of ancient Persian art and culture
planned next year at the Smithsonian Institution's Arthur M.
Sackler Gallery and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, it was
announced Thursday.
   The art works from the Hermitage Museum in Leningrad and the
State Armory at the Kremlin in Moscow have been seen rarely outside
the Soviet Union and never in the United States.
   The Soviet loan will include a pair of 14th century gold bowls
with dragon handles, two 15th century bronze oil lamps commissioned
by the Central Asian warlord Timur, also known as Tamerlane, and a
polychrome tile mosaic from Timur's monumental tomb in Samarkand.
   In exchange, the Sackler gallery and the Los Angeles museum will
lend master Islamic paintings, calligraphies and ceramic vessels to
be exhibited at the Hermitage for its 225th anniversary next year.
   The exchange was authorized by a protocol signed recently by the
Soviet Union, the Sackler and the Los Angeles museum under terms of
a cultural agreement reached at the 1985 Geneva summit meeting
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The American exhibition, ``Timur and the Princely Vision:
Persian Art and Culture in the 15th Century,'' will appear at the
Sackler from April 14, 1989, through July 9 and in Los Angeles from
Aug. 13 through Nov. 5.
   Initial support for the exhibition is being provided by the
National Endowment for the Humanities and the Smithsonian's special
exhibitions fund.
</TEXT>
