<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FairnessDoctrine     03-25 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fairness Doctrine,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Reaffirms Decision To Abolish Fairness Doctrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday reaffirmed its decision to abolish its policy requiring
broadcasters to air conflicting views of controversial issues.
   The action will allow a lawsuit filed by supporters of the
fairness doctrine to go forward in the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia.
   The FCC voted 3-0 to deny reconsideration of its Aug. 4 decision
to scrap the doctrine on the grounds that it violated the First
Amendment and chilled broadcasters' coverage of controversial
issues of public importance.
   ``We anticipated this. We're happy the commission finally
acted'' so the court case can move along, said attorney Donna
Lambert, who with Henry Geller, a former FCC general counsel, are
asking the court to revive the doctrine.
   The case before the court stems from allegations by the Syracuse
Peace Council that Meredith Corp. station WTVH-TV in Syracyse,
N.Y., violated the fairness doctrine by broadcasting editorial
advertisements favoring construction of a local nuclear power plant
without presenting opposing views.
   The FCC's decision to abolish the doctrine infuriated Democrats
in Congress, who mustered the votes to pass legislation to
reinstate the policy but were unable to override President Reagan's
veto of the measure.
   These supporters say they will make another attempt to revive
the policy this year, against the wishes of broadcasters who oppose
the doctrine.
</TEXT>
