<2ND_LINE>AM-Market Shootings,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Charged With Murdering Five During Supermarket Robbery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By R.B. FALLSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were charged Friday with murdering five
supermarket employees during a robbery Sept. 4 in which the victims
were shot in the back of the head after being ordered to lie on the
floor.
   One suspect was arrested without incident Friday after a grand
jury handed up the indictments; the other remained at large, said
police Capt. Charles McCrary.
   Each was charged with five counts of murder, one of robbery and
two of assault in connection with two supermarket employees who
were wounded in the hold-up after closing time by gunmen posing as
a cleaning crew.
   Investigators have said they believe the two gunmen surprised
and shot to death a supermarket security guard. The four other
slain employees, including a 16-year-old bag boy, were shot while
lying on the floor.
   The gunmen robbed the cash register of several hundred dollars.
Most of the store's cash was kept in a safe that could be opened
only with the help of a Wells Fargo guard, police said.
   McCrary said the key to the arrests was the discovery of the
security guard's .38-caliber revolver in the trunk of a car
Brentwood police stopped for speeding.
   The police captain said the investigation continued another four
months because ``a lot of information needed to be checked into.''
   Donnie Blankenship of Overland had been jailed since November on
charges of receiving stolen property and unlawful use of the
guard's weapon, but posted bail in the last week or two and
remained at large, McCrary said.
   The other suspect, Marvin Jennings of Overland, was taken into
custody Friday, McCrary said.
   McCrary said more people may have been involved in the crime.
   ``I'm pleased we've got the indictments, but there's more work
to be done,'' he said. ``We're still at a critical point in this
investigation. There are still a lot of things we can't tell you.''
   Relatives of the victims expressed relief.
   ``It brings a little justice if they got the right people,''
said Sonja Spahn, the widow of the slain security guard,
27-year-old David Spahn.
</TEXT>
