<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trident-Aegis     03-25 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trident-Aegis,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Questioning House Plan To Kill Trident Funding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon on Thursday expressed
reservations to a House panel's plan to kill funding for a Trident
nuclear submarine and instead build two destroyers that would give
Japan more security without disclosing secret U.S. technology.
   ``It really isn't the answer,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Chris Baumann, a
Defense Department spokesman.
   The House Armed Services seapower subcommittee voted this week
to delete the administration's request for $1.4 billion for a 16th
Trident submarine in the fiscal 1989 budget.
   Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla., subcommittee chairman and
architect of the funding maneuver, is wary of an administration
plan to sell sophisticated Aegis radar systems to Japan for new
Japanese destroyers.
   Instead, he wants the United States to build two extra Aegis
DDG-51 destroyers and station them in Japanese waters under U.S.
control, a move that would provide Japan with extra security while
not divulging technology.
   But Baumann said Bennett's plan would hinder U.S. efforts to
have Japan patrol its own waters. Under an agreement reached early
in the Reagan administration, Japan agreed to patrol waters out to
1,000 miles and U.S. forces would cover the rest of the Pacific.
   ``What we're trying to do is get Japan to do more, not to do
less,'' Baumann said. ``All of a sudden, we would be taking their
mission.''
   Bennett, however, said keeping a tight rein on technology
secrets should take precedent.
   ``I just don't want them to have our secret of our Aegis
ships,'' Bennett said in a telephone interview. ``It's not just
against Japan. We shouldn't unnecessarily share a secret with
anyone. ... It opens another channel of opportunity for spies.''
   The issue comes before the full Armed Services Committee next
week, and Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., plans to oppose the move,
said a congressional source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Bennett said he did not know if the full committee would support
his plan. He said that if he loses, he will take his case to the
House floor, where he predicted he would prevail.
   Meanwhile, lawmakers from Connecticut and Rhode Island, where
Tridents are built by the Electric Boat Division of General
Dynamics Corp., vowed to fight the move.
   Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I., a former Navy secretary, wrote to
House Armed Service Committee members urging them to reject the
Bennett proposal.
   ``At a time when U.S. defense resources are so stretched, and
when increased burden-sharing by Japan has been endorsed by both
houses of Congress, it seems unwise to sacrifice a crucial Trident
submarine in favor of this new naval commitment of questionable
merit,'' Chafee said.
   The 18,750-ton Tridents each carry 24 long-range, multi-warhead
missiles. Trident contracts create thousands of jobs in southern
New England at Electric Boat's plants in Groton, Conn., and North
Kingstown, R.I.
</TEXT>
