<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EasternAirlines     03-25 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Airlines,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Air Shuttle Case Moves to Appeals Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legal battle between Eastern Airlines and
its largest union over the carrier's proposed sale of its East
Coast air shuttle service moved to a higher court Thursday.
   Attorneys for Eastern filed papers with the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia, asking for dismissal of an
earlier ruling that the airline was in contempt.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt, who on March 10 found the
airline in contempt for attempting to sell the shuttle, on
Wednesday denied Eastern's request that he overturn his own ruling.
   The case pits the Miami-based carrier against the International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers, which represents
12,000 mechanics and other ground workers at Eastern. The union and
the airline are in mediation seeking new contract terms.
   Eastern, whose parent company is Texas Air Corp., has proposed
selling its shuttle to another Texas Air subsidiary for $225
million. Company officials say Eastern needs cash, but union
leaders say the sale is simply an attempt to pare the union's
membership.
   The shuttle flies between Washington, New York and Boston and
earned a $17 million profit for Eastern last year. Overall, Eastern
lost $182 million in 1987.
   In another dispute, Pratt ordered Eastern last July to refrain
from taking any actions that would alter the machinists' working
conditions. On March 10, Pratt ruled that the proposed shuttle deal
violated that order.
   Eastern's lawyers also want dismissal of sanctions Pratt levied
against the airline on Monday. Pratt forbade Eastern to pursue
government permission to sell the shuttle, and threatened
$10,000-per-day fines for future transgressions.
</TEXT>
