<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     03-25 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He'd Consider Hispanic Runnning Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fielding questions in English and Spanish,
Democratic presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis on Thursday
denounced the U.S. role in Central America and said he would
consider a Hispanic running mate.
   Courting the Hispanic vote in the nation's largest
Spanish-language media market, the Massachusetts governor said he
favored a one-year extension in the deadline for illegal aliens to
apply for amnesty.
   Asked in Spanish if a Dukakis ticket would consider a Hispanic
as a vice-presidential running mate, he answered ``Tal vez
(perhaps),'' adding: ``Vamos a ver (We'll see).''
   Dukakis, who noted his own ethnic background as the son of Greek
immigrants, impressed some Spanish-speaking reporters with his
command of the language, although he spoke carefully and a
translation was sometimes requested.
   Invited to a question-and-answer session were reporters, editors
and executives of Los Angeles' Spanish-language media: three daily
newspapers, two television stations and at least five radio
stations.
   In blasting the Reagan administration's Central American
policies, Dukakis said Costa Rica's President Oscar Arias deserved
much of the credit for the recent cease-fire agreement between
Nicaragua's Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   The Reagan administration's backing of the Contras and recent
dispatch of U.S. troops to Honduras did nothing to contribute to
the peace process, Dukakis declared.
   On the amnesty issue, Dukakis called for extending the May 4
deadline by which illegal aliens must apply for temporary resident
status another year.
   But regardless of whether Congress extends the deadline, Dukakis
said that as president he would ensure that the immigration
bureaucracy does not break up families in cases where only some
members qualify for amnesty.
   The U.S. Immigration Reform Act offers resident status to
illegal aliens who can prove they have lived continuously in the
United States for the last five years.
   It also sets stiff penalties for employers who knowingly hire
illegal aliens.
   Asked about the minimum wage, a perennial concern of minority
groups, Dukakis called for an increase.
   ``I don't see how you can support a family on $3.35 an hour,''
the candidate said.
</TEXT>
