<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DominicanRepublic     03-25 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican Republic,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massive State Spending Reduces Unemployment, Fuels Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's
massive program of public works has created jobs but fueled
inflation in this Caribbean nation, a top presidential aide said.
   ``It's not that we don't want stability. That's a top goal of
the Balaguer government,'' Technical Minister Guillermo Caram said
in an interview before leaving with President Joaquin Balaguer on
Thursday for a meeting with President Reagan in Washington.
   ``But it has to be understood that we have to sacrifice now in
order to strengthen the base for tomorrow's growth,'' Caram said.
``For that, we have to make sacrifices today.''
   Balaguer was scheduled to meet with Reagan on Friday and then
with officials of international lending agencies. On Balaguer's
agenda was the U.S. sugar quota, which he wants increased, and the
Dominican Republic's $4 billion foreign debt.
   The government's $600 million program of construction of roads,
bridges, schools and hospitals has created 210,000 jobs within the
last year, Caram said. The money, to be spent through Balaguer's
four-year term, has spurred the country's economic growth rate to 9
percent, he added.
   But it also touched off double-digit inflation that private
economists say is closer to 40 percent than the official government
figure of 30 percent.
   The foreign exchange value of the peso, the Dominican currency,
has declined steadily since and now is worth less than 20 cents.
Just four years ago the peso traded evenly with the U.S. dollar.
   Increases in prices of gasoline, milk, rice and other basic
commodities earlier this month touched off strikes and skirmishes
between soldiers and stone-throwing youths. The clashes threatened
to escalate into full-scale riots such as occurred in April 1984,
when more than 100 people died.
   Balaguer fended off protestors by pledging to increase the
minimum wage by 30 percent to $75 a month, and to implement price
controls. Representatives from the government, labor, private
business and the influential Roman Catholic Church are to meet for
a second time in early April.
   Politically, the 80-year-old Balaguer seems to be in firm
control. He began a fifth presidential term in August 1986 after
being out of office for two consecutive terms.
   The opposition Dominican Revolutionary Party, split into camps
supporting former presidential candidate Jacobo Majluta and former
Santo Domingo Mayor Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, has not sought to
use the unrest to challenge Balaguer.
   Relief may come from Washington.
   Balaguer would like the United States to lift its sugar import
quota from the Dominican Republic from its current level of 160,000
tons annually. In 1983, the quota was 525,000 tons a year.
   In 1987, revenue from sugar sales was a record low $150 million.
   Balaguer also would like international lending agencies to ease
his country's debt repayment schedule, which last year totaled $700
million, or almost the entire value of Dominican exports.
   U.S. Ambassador Lowell Kilday traveled with the Balaguer
delegation, which includes Central Bank Governor Roberto Saladin.
   Before returning home, Balaguer, who suffers from glaucoma and
is nearly blind, was scheduled to visit a hospital in Boston for an
eye examination.
</TEXT>
