<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bishops-AIDS     03-25 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops-AIDS,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishops To Discuss AIDS Education at June Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Roman Catholic bishops, at odds over what
role the church should play in AIDS education, will discuss the
issue at their June meeting in Minnesota, the president of the
national bishops conference said Thursday.
   Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis said the administrative
board of the U.S. Catholic Conference decided at its two-day
session, which ended Thursday, to schedule a discussion of ``the
pastoral, theological and moral dimensions of AIDS.''
   The board agreed that the discussion should ``be open-ended in
format with its direction determined by the will of the bishops,''
May said.
   He added that the discussion at the June 24-27 meeting in
Collegeville, Minn., would be held in executive session.
   The bishops conference's board recommended last December that
condom use be explained in church-sponsored AIDS education
programs, touching off a spate of criticism from conservative
bishops.
   Those bishops, led by cardinals Bernard Law of Boston and John
O'Connor of New York, said they would not allow condom use to be
explained or discussed in their dioceses' schools, hospitals and
youth programs. And they argued that abstinence is ``the only
morally acceptable way to avoid the sexual transmission of AIDS.''
AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is spread through
close contact with blood or semen from infected persons.
   The conservative bishops were particularly concerned that the
bishops conference's 50-member board had made the condom
recommendation without a full vote of the conference's 380 members.
   In the wake of the criticism, May had suggested that the full
body of bishops discuss the issue at their meeting in Minnesota,
and the administrative board made that recommendation official.
</TEXT>
