<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Hart-Money 1stLd-Writethru a0734 03-25 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hart-Money, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEC: Hart Can Use Some 1988 Funds to Pay Off 1984 Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 15th graf bgng ``Two businesses'' with details of
two lawsuits</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Hart won permission Thursday to use
whatever is left of his skimpy 1988 campaign fund toward paying off
the $1.15 million debt from his 1984 presidential campaign.
   He cannot use any of the $1.12 million in federal matching funds
he received, however, leaving the prospect of only a projected
$100,000 or so in the kitty to transfer to the 1984 creditors once
the 1988 accounts are settled, his campaign said.
   Somewhat ironically, it was only Hart's exit from the 1988 race
this month that won him Federal Election Commission permission to
transfer the funds.
   Were he still a candidate, he would be excluded from using the
1988 money for anything other than 1988 campaign-related expenses,
the commission ruling said. He had submitted the request before he
quit the race on March 11, so the commission was in a position of
applying a different set of rules to the question.
   Once a campaign is concluded, the leftover money can be used for
any lawful purpose, election regulations state. That would include
paying some of the 1984 debts.
   But it is unclear how much money Hart will have left by the time
he pays winding down costs and the FEC conducts its lengthy audit
process. He must return to the federal Treasury anything left of
the federal matching funds that he received this year. Matching
funds accounted for about one-third of his total fund raising for
1988.
   Hart's campaign attorney, Bernie Schneider, said the campaign
was pleased with the FEC decision.
   He anticipated that after final 1988 bills are paid, the
campaign will have about $110,000 leftover to apply to the 1984
debt.
   Commissioner Lee Ann Elliott at Thursday's meeting raised doubts
that any any significant amount will remain.
   ``We're going to be talking about a small trickle of money as
against the '84 debt,'' she said.
   And the ruling Thursday does not end the saga of Hart's nearly
four-year-old debt, and Schneider said Hart will still work on
raising money to pay the rest.
   ``Nobody is running away,'' he said, but he could not specify
what kind of fund-raising efforts will be undertaken by the former
Colorado senator.
   Some creditors have taken Hart to court _ so far unsuccessfully
_ to try and place liens on the 1988 funds to recoup money they are
owed from 1984.
   One creditor got a court order that resulted in federal marshals
seizing $30,000 in proceeds at a Hollywood fund-raiser for Hart
last year.
   Two businesses filed suit in Denver. Tri-State Envelope Corp. of
Beltsville, Md., claims Hart owes it $133,600. Semper-Moser
Associates of Venice, Calif., an advertising agency, claims it is
owed $172,920.
   Hart's most recent campaign financial statement showed that at
the end of February he had $488,966 in cash on hand and $34,661 in
bills to pay.
   Schneider said the FEC audit staff will probably begin its audit
in the summer. The agency audits all presidential campaigns as a
routine once the campaign is concluded. The agency was still
finishing up 1984 audits last year.
   The FEC decision Thursday came in response to Hart's second
request on the same topic. He first asked if he could use 1988
funds toward the 1984 debt last spring. But after the commission
denied him federal matching funds on the basis that he was not an
active candidate, his campaign withdrew the request as moot.
   He withdrew from the race for the first time in May in the wake
of disclosures about his relationship with part-time Miami model
Donna Rice.
   When Hart re-entered the race last fall, he resubmitted the
request in hopes of wiping out the nagging 1984 debt.
</TEXT>
