<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Herbicides     03-25 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Herbicides,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Block Spraying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has refused an
immediate ban on the spraying of herbicides on federal rangeland in
Oregon and Washington.
   In an order made public Thursday, a three-judge panel of the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals denied an emergency injunction sought
by rural and environmental groups. The court said it would explain
its reasons later.
   However, no spraying is expected until at least late spring,
said Norma Grier, director of the Northwest Coalition Against
Pesticides, one of the groups filing suit.
   She said she hoped the court would rule before then on the
groups' appeal of a decision by a federal judge in Oregon who ruled
the U.S. Bureau of Land Management had adequately studied the
environmental effects of the weed-killer.
   The chemicals, including the controversial 2,4-D, are to be
sprayed on weeds that threaten forage or cause other harmful
effects on BLM land in the two states.
   U.S. District Judge James Burns blocked the spraying in 1984,
ruling that the BLM's environmental analysis had not considered the
range of possible danger to humans.
   The agency, supported in the case by a group of farmers and
ranchers, revised its analysis last year and concluded that under
the worst foreseeable circumstances, the herbicides were still
relatively safe.
   Burns in November lifted his injunction.
   At a hearing March 7 in Portland, Ore., opponents asked the
appellate court to reinstate the ban while it considers their
appeal of Burns' ruling.
   The appellate court's unanimous order Thursday did not address
the merits of Burns' ruling, which remains under appeal.
   John DiLorenzo, a lawyer for a group of farmers, ranchers and
herbicide users called Oregonians for Food and Shelter, said he was
encouraged by the court's decision. The group considers the
herbicides safe.
   But Ms. Grier said the government agency had ignored studies
showing health problems and had failed to consider non-chemical
approaches.
   The bureau ``should have looked at how to prevent problems
before they exist,'' she said. ``Are we managing our lands in a way
that encourages problem weeds? Could we alter the use of land by
livestock in a way that would make the land less susceptible to
noxious weed problems?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
