<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-Election     03-25 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-Election,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Turnout for Gibraltar Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record number of voters turned out Thursday
for an election late polls indicated would oust the incumbent
government of this British fortress colony.
   Clive Coon, the government press officer, said 13,325 _ or 76
percent _ of Gibraltar's 17,530 registered voters cast ballots. The
previous record, 74 percent, was set in 1984, the last election for
the 15-seat House of Assembly.
   Opinion polls among 29,000 citizens this week indicated victory
for Joe Bossano and his Gibraltar Socialist Labor Party over
incumbent Chief Minister Adolfo Canepa of the long-dominant
Association for the Advancement of Civil Rights.
   Coon attributed the high turnout to ``a lovely day.''
   An opinion poll published this week by the Gibraltar magazine
Panorama indicated 63 percent of voters favored Bossano, 26 percent
were for Canepa and 11 percent supported the Independent Democratic
Party of Joe Pitaluga.
   Canepa's party controlled the government for all but three years
since 1945 under the flamboyant leadership of Sir Joshua Hassan,
who retired last December at age 72.
   Bossano, 48, advocates self-determination and opposes Spain's
efforts to regain sovereignty over the 2.2 square miles of
limestone rock on its southern coast.
</TEXT>
