<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhoneSuit     03-25 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phone Suit,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bell Moves To Clarify Sales To Consumers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bell of Pennsylvania announced Thursday
that it is clarifying instructions to sales representatives and
mailing information to customers following charges of deceptive
sales practices.
   The announcement came after the state attorney general and
consumer advocate filed a suit and a complaint alleging the state's
biggest phone company stuck customers with such options as call
waiting, three-way calling and speed calling.
   While insisting the allegations were unjustified, Regis Filtz,
Bell vice president and chief operating officer, said the telephone
company was taking steps to resolve what he called confusion about
the options.
   ``We are going beyond what normally we would do to strengthen
and clarify and assure there is absolutely no misunderstanding in
terms of what customers order, what options they get, what the
value of those options is (and) what the prices are,'' Filtz said.
   ``We believe we go the extra mile to make sure that customers
are fully informed about their services, and have every opportunity
to change it whenever they wish.''
   State Consumer Advocate David Barasch said the company is ``at
least in part admitting the allegations we've been making.''
   But the state has not withdrawn the suit filed Monday in state
court or the complaint filed with the state Public Utility
Commission.
   The allegations made by Barasch and Attorney General LeRoy
Zimmerman were based on 32 test calls made to Bell representatives.
Of those calls, more than 70 percent were assigned one, two or
three optional services they had not requested or were not told
were optional.
   In one case, an agent posing as a single mother on welfare was
assigned service at $28.55 monthly, when basic service could have
been obtained for $6.65 per month, the officials said.
   Barasch alleged the representatives were subject to quotas or
``bonus'' plans geared to the optional services.
   Filtz said the workers did not receive commissions but can
qualify for prizes including toasters, appliances and pizza lunches
based on sales performance.
   In a complaint filed with the PUC, Barasch said Bell
representatives followed guidelines directing them to include
certain options, including a maintenance plan, when recommending
rates to new customers.
   The ``clarified'' guidelines do not include such instructions,
and also specify that customers be told the services such as call
forwarding and call waiting are optional.
   Bell of Pennsylvania has more than 3.7 million customers, or
about 80 percent of the state's telephone lines.
   The PUC complaint and the lawsuit seek fines, an end to the
allegedly deceptive sales practices, and customer refunds that
Barasch said could involve millions of dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
