<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0634EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EastSt.LouisWoes     03-25 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East St. Louis Woes,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Already Strapped City Faces Bankruptcy, Assets Frozen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family trying to force payment of
a $4 million jury award has obtained a freeze on the city's bank
accounts, apparently plunging this desperately poor community into
a payroll crisis.
   At least $85,000 in city checks were outstanding when the
accounts were frozen Wednesday, including about $37,000 in
paychecks issued March 15 but not yet cashed by municipal
employees, said city Treasurer Charlotte Moore.
   ``That kind of puts us in a destitute situation,'' said Alderman
Melvin Frierson. ``My real interest right now is payroll. That's
critical.''
   Mayor Carl Officer and city attorney Samuel F. Ross Jr. did not
return calls Thursday, but officials have said there was no way a
municipality with an annual budget of about $6 million could afford
to pay a $4 million.
   The money was awarded in 1985 to Walter DeBow, a Granite City
man who suffered permanent brain damage when he was beaten by a
fellow inmate in the East St. Louis jail.
   In November, the Illinois Supreme Court ordered the city of
55,000 people to pay the judgment, clearing the way for the DeBow
family to seize its bank accounts.
   On Wednesday, city accounts containing about $1.2 million were
frozen at four local banks.
   Clyde Kuehn, DeBow's attorney, said he did not think the city
would file for bankruptcy in federal court, a move that would put a
court-appointed trustee in control of municipal funds. ``They don't
want a trustee running the city,'' he said.
   ``As far as the people of East St. Louis are concerned, this
isn't going to hurt the citizens any more than they already are,''
he said. ``They already don't get their trash picked up. They
already have a fire department and police department that isn't
properly equipped.''
   William Stodghill, president of Local 50 of the Service
Employees International, said the 35 or 40 City Hall employees
represented by his union would meet Monday to discuss options that
could include a walkout.
   East St. Louis, once a thriving industrial city, became one of
the nation's poorest with the decline of the industries and the
exodus of whites in the 1960s.
   The city is 98 percent black, and 61 percent of its residents
receive some kind of assistance. Unemployment is unofficially
estimated at 40 percent.
   DeBow, who had been arrested for driving with an open bottle of
malt liquor, was placed in a cell with a man who was being held on
misdemeanor charges but had a history of violent crime.
   The man beat DeBow severely, causing permanent brain damage,
said Kuehn, adding his client would need constant medical care for
the rest of his life.
</TEXT>
