<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EconomyRdp     03-25 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Tumble; Personal Income, Spending Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled Thursday even as the government reported
that Americans' personal incomes and consumer spending surged in
February.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell
43.77 points to 2,023.87. Declining issues outnumbered advances by
more than 5 to 1 on the New York Stock Exchange whose composite
index dropped 2.82 to 149.00.
   Analysts cited a continued decline in the dollar, which fell to
its lowest level in nearly two months against the Japanese yen and
West German mark, as contributing to the weakness in stocks.
   In its latest eonomic report, the Commerce Department said
personal incomes advanced 0.9 percent in February, reflecting
strong employment gains in the past few months. Spending rose 0.7
percent, up sharply from a tiny 0.1 percent January increase.
   Meanwhile, the government reported the savings and loan industry
last year recorded its worst annual loss since the Great Depression.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said a $3.2 billion loss in the
last three months of 1987 pushed the industry's red ink for the
year to a record $6.8 billion. That was nearly 50 percent greater
than the previous post-Depression record of a $4.6 billion, set in
1981.
</TEXT>
