<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Hostages,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Gives Hope for Captive Britons Waite, McCarthy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Hashemi Rafsanjani said Thursday that
Britain must help free Iranian hostages in Lebanon before Iran will
intervene on behalf of Anglican envoy Terry Waite and another
missing Briton, the BBC reported.
   A spokesman for Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie said,
``If he (Rafsanjani) is confirming that John McCarthy and Terry
Waite are alive and being well treated by captors that is indeed
good news.''
   At a news conference in Tehran attended by British Broadcasting
Corp. correspondent John Simpson, Parliament Speaker Rafsanjani
said Britain must help free three missing Iranians kidnapped by
right-wing Christian Phalangists in summer 1982.
   Simpson interpreted his remarks as indicating Waite and British
reporter John McCarthy were alive. They are among 24 foreigners
missing in Lebanon. The BBC radio report, broadcast in London, made
no mention of non-British Western hostages. The longest held
hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, who was kidnapped on March 16, 1985.
   ``Rafsanjani said at first that he did not know if they were
alive or dead,'' Simpson said in a broadcast from the Iranian
capital. But when pressed, he began to talk of the conditions for
their release.
   Waite, Runcie's personal envoy, disappeared Jan. 20, 1987 after
leaving his west Beirut hotel to negotiate with an Islamic group in
his efforts to gain the release of Western hostages.
   No claim of responsibility has even been made in Waite's
disappearance.
   Simpson said, ``He (Rafsanjani) accepted that there was a clear
difference between on the one hand Mr. Waite, from a religious
background and Mr. McCarthy, a journalist and, on the other, a spy
or a military man.''
   When Simpson said that the Iranians were almost certainly dead,
Rafsanjani said someone should show Iran the bodies.
   The news conference took place during an Iraqi air strike in
which three missiles fell on the city.
   Rafsanjani showed no reaction during the bombing.
   McCarthy, a journalist for the London-based Worldwide Television
News agency, was kidnapped April 17, 1986.
   Two other Britons are being held, along with nine Americans and
other nationalities.
</TEXT>
