<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NIreland-Soldiers     03-25 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Soldiers,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media Surrender Film Of Irish Attack On Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republic's
broadcasting service said Thursday it gave British police video
segments of an angry funeral mob attacking two soldiers at an IRA
funeral.
   RTE turned over the videotape one day after Britain's two
television networks, the British Broadcasting Corp. and Independent
Television News, complied with similar demands for unbroadcast
footage from the funeral.
   Britain's Defense Ministry, meanwhile, denied British news
reports that the two soldiers were on an undercover mission when
they were hauled from their cars, beaten severely and then shot to
death.
   The three networks initially refused to hand over unbroadcast
film on the ground it would endanger crews covering future violence
in the British-ruled province.
   They complied after the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the
provincial police force, threatened court action under British
anti-terrorist legislation.
   The two British corporals, Derek Wood, 24, and David Howes, 23,
were dragged from a car by a mob at an Irish Republican Army
funeral in Belfast on Saturday. They were beaten with iron bars and
then taken to a nearby soccer stadium, where IRA guerrillas shot
them to death.
   The crowd stopped TV crews filming when the soldiers were pulled
from the car.
   RTE said two detectives called at its offices in Belfast and
took away a 65-second videotape of the attack. The network said
most of the film was transmitted on the network.
   Security forces will examine the film to try to identify those
who took part.
   The Defense Ministry Thursday denied a report in the news, arts
and current affairs magazine The Spectator that Wood and Howes were
on an undercover mission in west Belfast when attacked. They were
in plainclothes in an unmarked car at the time.
   The Spectator, which supports the governing Conservative Party,
said: ``We shall never be told, though it seems to be the case,
that Cpls. Wood and Howes were on an undercover operation.'' It
gave no other details.
   Members of the Royal Corps of Signals are often employed on
surveillance work and other undercover activity. But a ministry
spokesman, who in accordance with British practice refused to be
identified, said the claim in The Spectator was ``inconceivable.''
   The army has said it thinks the soldiers may have become
involved with the cortege purely by accident while on their way to
their base at Lisburn barracks south of Belfast.
</TEXT>
