<DOCNO> AP880325-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0151EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Austria-Reparations     03-25 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Reparations,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austrian Parliament Approves Compensation To Nazi Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament has passed a law that will
provide payments of up to $416 each to people victimized by the
Nazis when Austria was under German rule during World War II.
   The law, which had been planned for months, was passed Wednesday
by all three main political parties in Parliament. Five of the six
deputies from the small Greens Party voted against it, saying the
measure provided too little compensation.
   Under the law, those deemed to have suffered under Nazi rule
will receive one-time payments of from $208 to $416 at current
exchange rates. The payments vary depending on whether the
potential recipient was persecuted by the Nazis, forced to leave
the country or served in the resistance.
   No estimates have been published of how many people will be
eligible for payment.
   Alfred Dallinger, the Socialist welfare minister in the
coalition government, told Parliament he hoped the payments would
be understood as a symbolic gesture, since no sum could compensate
for such suffering.
   Adolf Hitler sent his troops to annex Austria to the Third Reich
in March 1938, a move many Austrians welcomed.
   Austria already pays small pensions to individuals persecuted by
the Nazis. Unlike West Germany, however, it never paid compensation
to Israel or any other state or group for Nazi crimes.
   The proposal was approved by the Socialist Party, the
Conservative People's Party and the rightist Freedom Party.
   Austria has been mired in a controversy over President Kurt
Waldheim's wartime past. Waldheim served as a lieutenant in a
German army unit in the occupied Balkans. His unit was linked to
war crimes, including the deportation of Jews to concentration
camps and the murders of partisans.
   Waldheim kept his military service in the area secret until 1986
and has denied wrongdoing since. A historians' commission said
Waldheim was in a position to know about Nazi war crimes and did
nothing to stop them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0226 </DOCNO>
