<HEAD>Mother Loses Custody of Infant She Used as Collateral in $50 Drug
Buy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has awarded the state permanent custody
of a 2-year-old whose mother accused of having used him as
collateral for $50 worth of cocaine.
   Lou Ann Powell, 26, did not appear at Wednesday's court session
during which Cook County Circuit Judge Claude Whitaker stripped her
of all parental rights to her son, Anthony.
   The boy has been in foster care since he was found outside a day
labor agency June 16.
   Ms. Powell told authorities when she identified the child in
October that she had a cocaine habit, was behind in payments to a
drug dealer and had offered the boy as collateral.
   ``She apparently planned to redeem him when she got some money,
kind of like when you take a promissory note from the bank,'' Frank
Giunta, a police youth division investigator, said at the time.
   Ms. Powell was charged with felony abandonment, said Lisa
Howard, spokeswoman for the state's attorney office.
   ``Anthony's foster parents already have moved to adopt him, and
we hope that becomes final soon,'' said Dave Schneidman, spokesman
for the state Department of Children and Family Services.
   Ms. Powell is also charged with neglect stemming from her
treatment of her younger son, Joseph, 13 months old. Ms. Howard
said authorities will seek to have her parental rights to Joseph
terminated in that case.
