<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhillyBudget     03-25 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philly Budget,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goode Proposes Tax Increase In New $2 Billion Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode on Thursday proposed a
$1.93 billion budget that would turn trash collection over to a
contractor, freeze wages and raise taxes for the first time since
he took office in 1984.
   The mayor of the nation's fifth-largest city, in asking for a
$67 million tax increase, left it up to City Council to decide
which taxes to raise.
   The increase will help ``meet human needs, create jobs, promote
economic development, care for and nurture our children and
revitalize our neighborhoods,'' said Goode, a Democrat elected in
November to a second term.
   His budget for fiscal 1989, which starts July 1, represents a
6.4 percent increase over the current budget of $1.86 billion.
   Goode proposed cutting $50 million in costs through new labor
contracts or new contract terms and by turning over garbage
collection to private industry, a move that could eliminate several
thousand jobs and save $35 million annually.
   Garbage collection in Philadelphia has come under attack as
sloppy and rife with overtime abuse.
   ``I am a lifelong supporter of organized labor and while part of
my financial plan anticipates privatization, which they may find
difficult, I am resolute in pursuing this only to the extent that
labor fails to work with the city to find meaningful and cost
effective alternatives,'' Goode said.
   The mayor's budget offers no wage increase to the city's
blue-and white-collar employees, whose contracts expire this
summer. The spending plan does not include the school system, which
has proposed a $1 billion budget.
   It would add $44.3 million to basic services, which include
police and fire protection, street cleaning, job training, housing
rehabilitation and programs for children, the homeless and AIDS
victims, who would receive $7.5 million.
   Tax revenue for the current fiscal year is projected at $1.4
billion. The mayor's spending plan for the coming year projects tax
revenue of $1.5 billion.
   ``Everybody's inclination is against a tax increase,'' said
Councilman David Cohen, a Democrat.
   Republican Councilman Thacher Longstreth said he considered
raising taxes ``a disgrace'' but also said it probably would be
done.
   Council President Joseph Coleman, a Democrat, said: ``We are
going to have to raise taxes or cut the budget tremendously.''
</TEXT>
