<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     03-25 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Took 4-Year-Old Son On Smuggling Runs As Cover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot testified Thursday that he
took his 4-year-old son with him as cover while flying cocaine into
the United States for alleged drug kingpin Carlos Lehder Rivas.
   ``I believe he was the youngest drug smuggler at that time,''
said Andrew Richard Barnes, 32.
   Lehder, 38, is on trial on charges of smuggling about 3.3 tons
of cocaine into the country from Colombia via Norman's Cay in the
Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   Barnes, a native of England known as British Andy, said he
transported 3,000 kilograms, or about 6,600 pounds, for Lehder
while working for him in 1978 and again in 1980.
   Barnes told the jury that he would receive a telephone call the
night before each trip from one of Lehder's employees.
   ``Come over and pick up the children and take them to school,''
was the message he said he received. ``Children'' was Lehder's term
for cocaine, witnesses have testified.
   In October 1980, Barnes said, he transported two loads of 450 to
500 kilos each from Norman's Cay, which was Lehder's private
island, into Fort Lauderdale International Airport.
   ``He (Lehder) said it was the largest loads we'd done,'' Barnes
said, adding he was paid $225,000 for the flights.
   Three other flights were made in the latter part of 1980, and
Barnes said he took his son with him to appear that they were on a
family outing.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged with taking part in a smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
