<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Hirt     03-25 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Hirt,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trumpeter Al Hirt Hospitalized For Infection In Hand And Arm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz trumpeter Al Hirt was admitted to a hospital
Thursday for treatment of an infection in his playing hand.
   The 65-year-old Bourbon Street musician flew from his home in
New Orleans to be under the care of his friend, famed heart surgeon
Michael DeBakey, at Methodist Hospital.
   ``I had this infection or something in my hand. It's like blood
poisoning. It looks like it's from a bite or something. It's all
swollen and has red streaks,'' Hirt said.
   ``But my prognosis is excellent. I'm going to be OK as long as I
can keep blowing the trumpet.''
   Hirt said doctors think the problem may be a related to his
trumpet playing and a growth that developed on a finger of his
right hand after 59 years of horn work.
   He was expected to remain hospitalized for at least several
days, DeBakey said. Hirt had been scheduled to perform at a benefit
Thursday for the financially troubled New Orleans Symphony.
   ``The prognosis is excellent for Mr. Hirt,'' DeBakey said. ``I
am sorry he will miss his performance, but his health is most
imporant at this point.''
</TEXT>
