<1ST_LINE>a e PM-TV-MoyersonEvil Adv28   03-25 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Moyers on Evil, Adv 28,0710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, March 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Moyers Program on Evil Inevitably Discusses Good</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The title of ``Facing Evil, with Bill Moyers''
evokes images of 90 minutes in front of the television in a dark
depression contemplating the worst in human nature.
   Not so. As Moyers says in his introduction to this surprisingly
uplifting report, a discussion of the dark mystery of evil seems
inevitably to lead to a celebration of the light.
   Part of Moyers' ``news of the mind'' series for PBS, the former
network journalist taped the special at a symposium called
``Understanding Evil,'' sponsored by the University of Texas and
featuring a distinguished group of speakers, including poet Maya
Angelou, Holocaust scholar Raul Hilberg, choreographer and author
Chung-Liang Al Huang, author Philip Paul Hallie, and Dr. Samuel D.
Proctor, a Baptist preacher.
   Often as eloquent as the featured speakers are the audience
members, ranging from a Holocaust survivor still struggling to
understand what happened to her, to a Vietnam veteran who says his
experience ``has made me think of evil in another way, coming out
of Vietnam, turning around and seeing it wearing my own face.''
   The message from the program _ and it's never forced _ is that
good and evil reside in the human spirit, and it takes an act of
will to repress evil in favor of good.
   Angelou, a striking television presence, tells of being raped
when she was 7. The man who attacked her was known to her family.
Soon after he was released from jail, he was found dead, apparently
kicked to death. The child believed she had brought on the man's
death by speaking his name. She didn't speak again for five years.
   A horrible thing to happen to a child. But, she said, during
those five years, she sought solace in reading, everything she
could get her hands on, memorizing poems, stories and plays. When
she finally spoke again, she had truly found her voice, thanks to
words and wisdom of others.
   Hallie still grapples with the concept of evil after a lifetime
of study. A soldier in World War II, he says he is horrified to
recall enjoying the violence of conflict. He was so moved by the
story of courageous, peace-loving French villagers who disarmed the
German invaders with love, he wrote a book about them and found
himself transformed. But later, he realized, it was not the
villagers who defeated Hitler, but those like himself who killed
the Germans.
   Hallie likens the struggle between good and evil to the
experience of being in a hurricane _ all around is fury, but there
can still be blue sky above. To a quotation from George Santayana,
``In the midst of battle there is room for love,'' Hallie adds his
own thought _ ``We can push back and expand the blue, but we're in
the eye of the hurricane, and don't ever forget it.''
   Hilberg is more pessimistic, having studied the Holocaust and
realized that it took thousands of typical _ and well-educated _
citizens to produce it. His presentation prompts audience members
to wonder whether they could be caught up in evil mob psychology,
be it Nazism or a lynching, if they had been there.
   It's a compelling 90 minutes, thanks to Moyers' insistence on
presenting ideas, not neat conclusions. Stylistically Moyers
ignores the accepted television tenet that talking heads are
boring. He believes in the power of storytelling and pushes the
camera up close, but avoids visual monotony by interspersing
footage of the speakers at the podium with often emotional
one-on-one interviews. He also artfully refers with the camera
occasionally to the incongruously serene central Texas landscape.
   Moyers, who has only been seen in a brief introduction, returns
at the end of the program to offer, not a conclusion but a question
_ if we can identify an evil act after it occurs, why can't we stop
it before it happens?
   ``That we usually fail to see an act in time,'' he says, ``is as
puzzling to me as the persistence of evil itself.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, March 28</NOTE>
