<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-SpankingBacklash Adv28   03-25 1145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spanking Backlash, Adv 28,1181</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 28 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>School Paddling Opponents Fight Back With Lawsuits, Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board president in Jackson, Mich., disagreed strongly
with a recent board vote that outlawed paddling. ``I went to a
school where we were spanked when we misbehaved. It didn't damage
us,'' said L. Michael Ketchens. ``It didn't teach us that physical
violence is the only response.''
   Many educators around the nation concur. And yet teachers and
administrators increasingly look to alternative ways of controlling
unruly students: counseling, suspensions and restrictions on
special privileges.
   They cite lawsuits over allegedly abusive corporal punishment
and research indicating that minority and poor students are paddled
disproportionately.
   Spanking has been prohibited in California, Hawaii, Maine,
Massachusetts, Nebraska, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Rhode
Island and Vermont. Movements are afoot in at least 15 more states
to try to outlaw corporal punishment.
   And, as in Jackson, Mich., many localities have banned spanking
_ among them, the school districts of Anchorage, Alaska; Atlanta;
Baltimore; Chicago; Cleveland; Columbus; the District of Columbia;
Fargo, N.D.; Minneapolis; New Orleans; Philadelphia; Pittsburgh;
Portland, Ore.; Seattle; St. Louis; and Tucson, Ariz.
   California child psychologist Adah Maurer, who has spent the
last decade in an anti-paddling crusade, said it's been difficult
to persuade state legislators to support anti-spanking bills
because they get mixed signals.
   Teachers don't like to be told how to run their classrooms, said
Maurer, founder of End Violence Against the Next Generation Inc.
   ``They vote for the status quo. If paddles are in use, teachers
will vote in favor of them. We have found that all over,'' she
said. ``But if they've never had corporal punishment, as in New
Jersey, they don't miss it.''
   The National Education Association is on record as opposing
corporal punishment in schools, but its position is not binding on
the various state chapters.
   Religious educators also are of two minds. Some favor banning
corporal punishment, saying violence begets violence. Others cite
Solomon's biblical admonition: ``Spare the rod, spoil the child.''
   Fundamentalist schools lobbied to be exempted from a Michigan
anti-spanking bill that's supported by Roman Catholic schools.
   ``Corporal punishment is too risky,'' said Sister Dorita
Wotiska, superintendent of the Diocese of Lansing Roman Catholic
schools. ``When you hit a child out of anger, the chances of
hurting a child is beyond what you know.''
   But Paul Vanaman, president of the Michigan Association of
Christian Schools, said spanking ``gets results. Why tie everyone's
hands because of the possibility that something might happen on the
ten-thousandth time?''
   The U.S. Department of Education has estimated public school
children are swatted about 1.3 million times a year. But the
figures don't differentiate between a tap with a hand and paddling
that raises welts and do not show the frequency of physical injury
or emotional damage.
   The Education Department's biannual survey of 20 percent of the
nation's school districts, from which the figures were derived,
also showed wide racial and regional fluctuations: children were
more likely to be physically punished in the South, and black
children were paddled at a higher rate than whites.
   The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1977 that corporal punishment
did not constitute cruel and unusual punishment, but the justices
may take another look at the issue.
   The high court is considering whether to hear arguments on an
appeal from a New Mexico case. The parents of Teresa Garcia contend
the 9-year-old's constitutional rights were violated when she was
paddled hard enough to require medical treatment.
   They say she was hit on two occasions, first as punishment for
hitting a boy who kicked her and later for saying she saw a teacher
kiss a student's father.
   Maurer said her research shows that educators get used to using
the paddle, then employ it for lesser and lesser offenses.
   ``There's a lot of sadism,'' she said. ``Children are hit for
academic matters, like not finishing their homework. They're hit
for coming in a little late.''
   In Jackson Hole, Wyo., a sixth-grader was spanked with a wooden
paddle by his teacher and about 19 classmates. The offense: getting
a grade of 79 percent on a math test. A lawsuit later was settled
for more than $20,000.
   In a Pennsylvania case, the parents of a seventh-grader say
they're preparing to sue over the paddling administered to their
son and the rest of his class. The reason: one classmate reported
his math book missing and no one owned up to the theft. The parents
blame the paddling for the seizures their son has suffered since.
   Those aren't isolated cases, according to Irwin Hyman, director
of the National Center for the Study of Corporal Punishment at
Temple University in Philadelphia.
   ``Teachers have legally beaten children severely enough to leave
welts, lacerations and fractured bones,'' he said, adding that he
has documented hundreds of cases. Children have sometimes suffered
nerve damage and in rare cases have even died after being required
to do exhausting exercises, he said.
   Hyman said corporal punishment can inflict on children a version
of post-traumatic stress disorder, the psychological damage
associated with war veterans.
   The people who teach teachers-to-be say they emphasize
discipline techniques that don't rely on the threat of pain.
   ``Most behavior problems can be prevented,'' said Michigan State
University professor Cassandra Book. ``Those people who engage in
corporal punishment don't have other ideas in their head on how to
cope with kids' misbehavior.''
   She urges teachers to give youngsters reasons to behave _ for
instance, by setting up contracts in which they agree to give up
certain privileges if they misbehave.
   Sister Wotiska's technique for stopping misbehavior is a
well-directed stare _ ``an evil eye,'' she called it.
   The National Coalition of Advocates for Students said it's
concerned that paddlings may be racially motivated.
   ``Corporal punishment is used most frequently on poor, minority
students,'' said Joan McCarty First, director of the Boston-based
advocacy group, which analyzed data from the federal government's
most recent school survey.
   Black students made up 16 percent of the nation's school
enrollment and accounted for 28 percent of the episodes of corporal
punishment, according to the analysis.
   In individual state analyses, the group found similar
discrepancies.
   For instance, in Arizona, where black students constitute 4
percent of enrollment, they accounted for 13 percent of the
episodes of physical punishment. In Connecticut, 10 percent
enrollment, 73 percent punishment rate; in Wisconsin, 8 and 39
percent; in Ohio, 14 and 26 percent; in Michigan, 17 and 25
percent; in Arkansas, 25 and 35 percent.
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
supports efforts to ban corporal punishment in schools.
   Also on the record as supporting anti-spanking efforts are the
American Medical Association, American Bar Association, American
Civil Liberties Association and National Parent-Teacher Association.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 28</NOTE>
