<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Peru-President Adv01   03-25 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-President, Adv 01,0795</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 1 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Peru's `President of Hope' in Trouble at Midterm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the youthful Alan Garcia took office as
Peru's ``president of hope'' in July 1985, his energetic policies
won applause from a country besieged for decades by economic and
governmental failures.
   But midway through his five-year term, the 38-year-old populist
has been battered by unrelenting poverty, a leftist insurgency and
growing social chaos.
   In some eyes, Garcia's honeymoon ended in 1986 when he gave
government forces a free hand to quell prison riots in Lima, and
more than 250 leftist guerrilla inmates were slain in a bloodbath.
   Most of Garcia's support in the middle and upper classes has
ebbed since this past July, when he accused Peruvian banks of
exploitation and announced plans to nationalize them.
   Current economic woes have further frayed Garcia's backing even
among the working class and poor, toward whom most of his policies
have been directed and from whom he commands his largest following.
   Garcia's approval rating has fallen from 96 percent during his
first months in office to 44 percent, according to the independent
polling firm Datum.
   ``Alan Garcia is just too young. He scares the middle class,''
said Jose Castro, who drives a taxi between jobs as a civil
engineer. ``The generals might have to come in and straighten
things out again.''
   Though most analysts doubt a military coup is likely, Castro's
comment reflects a constant worry among many people recalling
military rule from 1968 to 1980.
   The 6-foot-3 Garcia won office by a 2-1 margin with a campaign
promising a ``different future.''
   ``There was a massive need to bet on someone who could pull Peru
out of this crisis,'' said Luis Pasara, columnist for Caretas,
Peru's leading news weekly, terming Garcia's appeal as emotional
and lacking in substance.
   Garcia and his center-left Aprista Party, which won a majority
in Congress, moved with dizzying speed to implement policies he
frequently terms ``nationalistic and anti-imperialistic.''
   He limited repayments of Peru's foreign debt, now $16.5 billion,
to a ceiling of 10 percent of exports.
   ``The voracious appetites of imperialists will not be satisfied
with the hunger of the people,'' Garcia said.
   He used the money owed foreign banks to finance an economic
reactivation program that cut inflation to 63 percent and
catapulted the country from its deepest depression this century.
Peru led Latin America with 8.5 percent and 6.7 percent economic
growth in 1986 and 1987.
   The new chief executive took steps to root out police
corruption, decentralize government, boost the fight against
cocaine traffickers, gain more control over the military and reduce
human rights violations in the anti-insurgency campaign.
   His reputation as a ``bad boy'' of the Americas grew as he
nationalized a U.S. oil company, banned foreign companies from
remitting profits to parent firms abroad, drew closer trade links
with the Soviet Union and embraced Nicaragua's leftist government,
while condemning U.S. involvement in Central America.
   ``I am going to speak until Latin America unites and defeats the
imperialism of the rich nations,'' Garcia said in one of his
frequent volleys against U.S. and European foreign policy, which he
blames for keeping Latin America ``dependent and on its knees.''
   Such talk has eroded much of Garcia's foreign support.
   His foes accuse him of being a demagogue, impetuous in making
decisions and insincere about keeping promises.
   Government officials and supporters acknowledge that Garcia has
made serious political and economic errors. But they say the
problems are being corrected and recent fence-mending efforts
reflect a new presidential maturity.
   The bank takeover polarized the nation and awoke a powerful
center-right coalition. Congress went ahead, nevertheless, with the
nationalization plan but only one of the 10 banks affected now is
under government control because of legal challenges by owners of
the others. Garcia's Aprista Party, however, has proposed
amendments softening the nationalization plan in an effort to
lessen the strident opposition to it.
   In the meantime, many foreign companies have cut back on
operations or left the country, prompting the government to revise
policies to attract more foreign investment.
   Spurred by heavy government spending, inflation is expected to
rocket to a record 300 percent this year. The country is virtually
out of dollar reserves due to falling exports and a cutoff in loans
by foreign lenders.
   With the economy pitching toward a recession, Garcia in early
March announced a ``war economy,'' with steep price increases, and
appealed to rival political parties to help find solutions.
   The response, however, has been lukewarm.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 1</NOTE>
