<1ST_LINE>a w AM-MostWanted Adv28   03-25 1002</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Most Wanted, Adv 28,1029</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>TV Show Credited With Capturing Some of America's `Most Wanted'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fox Television's ``America's Most Wanted'' has
become the best thing since Post Office walls for law enforcement
officials, who say the innovative show has led to the capture of
three long-sought fugitives.
   ``This show is just what the fugitive doesn't want,'' said Rex
Tombs, FBI agent who acts as bureau liaison with the Sunday evening
program.
   ``America's Most Wanted,'' produced in Washington because of the
proximity to federal police agencies, is a unique mix of
dramatization, documentary, news, public service and interactive
television.
   The show uses actors and sometimes actual victims to dramatize
crimes, filming when possible on sites where the incidents
occurred. The show uses film and still photos of the real fugitives
and sends camera teams out to cover stakeouts. And it makes direct
appeals for people to get involved in the chase with a 20-line
toll-free number, 800-CRIME88.
   A dozen law enforcement officers, whose expenses are paid by the
show, are assigned by their agencies each week to monitor the calls
_ sometimes as many as 1,600 _ that follow each broadcast.
   ``We don't have anything else that can get the message across
the nation in prime time. This is the only thing we have other than
Post Office walls which are not that effective,'' said Dick
Pederson of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
   Law enforcement officials credit the show and viewer response
for the capture of at least three fugitives, including:
   _Steven Paul Mack, who was wanted for questioning in the
February 1987 slaying of 21-year-old beauty queen Karen Grace
Winlett of Carmichael, Calif., and the death of 19-year-old Annette
Huddle in Ohio.
   _Donald Adams, a convicted rapist in Boston.
   _David James Roberts, who escaped from the prison where he had
been serving six life terms for burning to death a young couple and
their 1-year-old child in Indiana because the man had witnessed him
stealing tires.
   ``We're making a smaller place for these guys to hide,'' said
the show's host, John Walsh, whose 6-year-old son was kidnapped and
killed in 1981. Walsh directs eight child-protection centers around
the country and has become a widely recognized lobbyist for laws
protecting children. The unsolved murder of his son, Adam, was the
subject of two television movies.
   Walsh said he agreed to do the show only if it would meet high
journalistic standards, avoid gratuitous violence and allow him
control over his scripts.
   ``So far Fox has kept their word,'' he said. ``The violence on
this show is off the evening news. This is not a nightmare turned
into a TV show; this is the nightmare of reality.''
   Michael Linder, the show's producer, said it tries to be
meticulous in the details it presents about criminals and clearly
identifies dramatizations so tipsters won't send police after the
actors it uses.
   He said he is also exploring ways to show less dramatic crimes
such as telephone fraud.
   ``I don't want to get the reputation for doing only flamboyant,
flashy stories,'' Linder said. ``The last thing we want is to be
perceived as is Adam 12 or Movie of the Week.''
   And, he said, there are no plans to offer rewards for capturing
criminals, because he doesn't want it to start looking like a game
show.
   ``America's Most Wanted'' is aired on Fox-owned stations in
seven major cities covering about one-fourth of U.S. TV viewers.
With its success in catching criminals and attracting viewers,
several independent stations have begun to pick it up.
   Although the show now is taped about two hours before air time,
plans call for the show to be broadcast live.
   One of the most recent captures attributed the show came earlier
this month on a tip from an Ohio woman who told the Marion County
sheriff she recognized Mack from an episode on ``America's Most
Wanted.''
   The tipster didn't know where Mack was but also told the sheriff
about a call she received from Salt Lake City about a man named
Sean Paul Lanier. She apparently connected the call with Mack.
   The Ohio sheriff sent Mack's fingerprints to Utah where
``America's Most Wanted'' is not aired, and on Tuesday police
discovered Mack and Lanier were one.
   Sacramento County sheriff's spokeswoman Sharon Telles said the
TV show provided deputies with 170 tips.
   ``I think this is going to put some fear into somebody,'' she
said. ``It's a wonderful tool for us.''
   Two weeks ago, Adams, the convicted rapist, hurriedly moved out
of the Boston area apartment where he had been living for several
weeks. Police, who had been staking out the apartment, said he fled
because he saw the dramatization of his brutal 1983 attack on a
Boston area woman on TV that night. Adams was arrested four days
later.
   ``The show helped flush him out,'' said Capt. David Mattioli of
the Massachusetts State Police. ``It was a classic example of a
cooperative effort between `America's Most Wanted' and police.''
   The program's first success came with its first episode, which
had actually been filmed eight months before it was shown last Feb.
7.
   FBI spokesman Milt Ahlerich appeared the following week to thank
viewers who called the show with information about Roberts, a
prison escapee who had been serving six life terms.
   Ahlerich said that before the tips started pouring in the FBI
had no idea that Roberts was living on New York's Staten Island
with a job as coordinator for a homeless shelter, where residents
praised him as a ``sweet guy,'' someone who would help anyone in
trouble.
   Other fugitives profiled on the show include members of a
Jamaican hit squad sought in a drug-related massacre of five people
in a suburb of Washington, D.C., and William ``Pops'' Pegram,
72-year-old bank robber who has blazed a 40-year trail of crime
across several states.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 28</NOTE>
