<1ST_LINE>a w AM-StampsbytheBillion Adv30   03-25 1214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stamps by the Billion, Adv 30,1245</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Billions of Stamps Needed for Postal Rate Change</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix file name, making it b0462. Morison,
with one ``r'' is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-seven tractor-trailers backed up to a
Kansas City, Mo., loading dock earlier this month to collect their
quarry _ six billion ``E'' stamps that had been salted away in a
limestone cave for the next increase in postal rates.
   It was one step in the complex process of raising postal rates
that began March 4, when the independent Postal Rate Commission
recommended a sweeping series of rate increases, including a
25-cent first-class stamp. The rate increase takes effect April 3.
   Assistant Postmaster General Gordon C. Morison knew there would
not be enough time to print new stamps to meet the nation's 100
million-a-day stamp appetite.
   So he turned to the ``E'' stamps that had been stored in Kansas
City for more than a year. The stamps have no denomination _ when
they were printed, no one knew just how large a rate increase would
be enacted.
   ``We printed six billion. It takes about 13.6 billion stamps to
make a rate change. Six billion stamps probably will last us around
45 to 60 days ... in that period of time we can print enough with
denominations to get the next six billion stamps out there and
replenish the inventory,'' Morison said in an interview.
   ``If we waited to get the rate change (to start printing stamps)
... there would be pockets of shortages throughout the country,''
he said.
   It took four days to finish loading the leased tractor-trailers,
which fanned out across the nation delivering the stamps to
sectional postal centers for distribution to local post offices.
   Last Wednesday, the day after the Postal Service board of
governors put its formal seal of approval on the new rates, the
special stamps went on sale across the nation.
   While the public will likely take most notice of the new ``E''
stamps, it takes no less than 45 different postal items to get
through a rate change, according to Morison.
   There are the six billion 25-cent stamps to follow the E stamps,
plus millions of 1- and 3-cent stamps that will be needed to make
up the new rates for people using up old stamps.
   There's postal stationery _ envelopes and postal cards bearing
the new rates _ plus new stamps bearing the 45-cent international
rate and stamps with the new bulk rates, non-profit rates, Express
Mail rates, official mail rates for government use and even special
``E'' envelopes to mail Savings Bonds.
   And for each type of stamp, more than one form is printed _ for
example ``E'' stamps will come in coils, booklets and sheets; there
will be three different booklets of the current 25-cent Jack London
stamp, new booklets of a 25-cent pheasant stamp and other new
items, Morison said.
   To print the stamps needed for the changeover, the Bureau of
Engraving and Printing used 915,000 pounds of ink and 4,680 tons of
paper, Morison said. He wasn't sure how much glue was used.
   ``I don't think people realize,'' how many stamps it takes, he
said, commenting that many people ask why the undenominated stamps
are used during changeovers.
   If all the new stamps required were stacked one on top of
another _ the thin way _ he said, the pile would be 571 miles tall.
   Of course stacking them the thin way makes the smallest possible
pile, and Morison had statistics with much more impressive
illustrations.
   Many people buy stamps in rolls of 100, he said. If all the
rolls needed for the changeover were stretched out, they would go
around the Earth twice at the equator, with a strip 5,255 miles
long leftover.
   The other popular sales method is the booklet, he noted, with
the consumer seeing only a little folder a few inches long.
   ``If we laid out all the stamp booklets we are producing they
would stretch 10,623 miles, or a round trip between San Francisco
and China, so that's why we think we have enough booklets,'' he
said.
   Indeed, the last time rates changed, booklets proved to be the
major problem, he said, with supplies never able to keep up with
demand.
   This time he is determined to have enough.
   In addition, Morison said, postal and business forms have to be
converted to the new rates, decals changed in vending machines,
rate charts replaced, new software produced for computer mail
terminals and postal scales changed.
   In addition to the Bureau of Engraving and Printing, the
American Bank Note Co. has contracted to print some new stamp
booklets to help in the changeover.
   Then comes the problem of getting the new stamps into the hands
of the public _ at a time when budget problems imposed by Congress
have forced a curtailment of hours at many offices.
   To help, Postmaster General Anthony Frank has ordered offices to
extend their hours during the next two weeks. In addition flyers
will be sent to homes to encourage purchase of stamps by mail.
   Plus, telephone stamp sales have also been extended nationwide.
Callers can use credit cards to buy stamps by calling
1-800-STAMP24. There is a $2 service charge.
   Officials don't expect people to be happy paying more, but
Morison says he hopes at least for fewer complaints about the
appearance of the ``E'' stamps.
   Past undenominated stamps have been rather plain stamps with the
head of an eagle. The E stamp has a colorful space-based image of
the Earth because, Morison says, ``over the years we have been
besieged by the public with requests for pretty stamps.''
   ``There's another thing we have to consider as we change rates,
especially on the ordinary issues. We have to make them discernably
different ... because our clerks have gotten used to seeing''
certain stamps.
   For example he cited the popular flag stamps. There will be a
new flag stamp at the 25-cent rate, but the design will be changed
enough to make it easy for clerks to be sure the correct stamp is
being used.
   In 1981, the Postal Service issued a commemorative stamp
honoring White House architect James Hoban at the 18-cent rate, and
then reissued the same stamp at 20 cents when rates changed.
   ``It wasn't a good idea and we don't plan to repeat it,''
Morison said of the confusion.
   With all this effort, when will they start thinking about the
next change and planning an ``F'' stamp?
   ``Well, we'll probably start looking at that in the near future,
at least from the design standpoint,'' he said.
   But that doesn't mean a new rate increase is being considered,
he cautioned. ``We don't look so much at the next rate case, quite
frankly, as we look at what might happen between rate cases.
   ``Theoretically, you could have a requirement for a substitute
stamp in several fashions, for example if we didn't have the
printing capabilities for stamps for some reason, we would have
stamps to tide us over. Or if we had a lawsuit that would change
the rates suddenly on us, either higher or lower.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, March 30</NOTE>
