<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed slightly lower against the
Japanese yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market today, while
stock prices shed more than 150 points following declines in both
currency and stock markets overseas.
   The dollar opened at 125.68 yen, down 0.62 yen from its Thursday
closing, and closed the week at 125.74 yen.
   Japan's central bank reportedly purchased an estimated $200-300
million during the morning to prop up the sagging currency. The
Bank of Japan does not comment on its monetary policies, including
market intervention.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 113.95 points Thursday, closed today at
25,626.71, down 154.57 points, or 0.59 percent.
   The Tokyo market ``was discouraged largely by an overnight
decline in the New York market,'' said Masahiro Umemori, a stock
researcher at Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage firm.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost 43.77 points to close at
2,023.87 points Thursday.
   Umemori said stock prices in Tokyo kept rising ``at a rapid
pace'' in recent weeks and just ``took a little respite the past
two days.''
   Commenting on foreign exchange transactions, a dealer at the
Bank of Tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there were
``no major negative market-affecting factors domestically'' to
explain the dollar decline.
   She said there still was a chance for ``the yen's further
appreciation against the dollar'' and predicted the dollar would
hover at a range between 123.00-127.00 yen next week.
</TEXT>
