<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down in London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Friday following the release of
disappointing British trade figures.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 stocks was off
12.5 points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,770.2 at midday.
   Volume was a relatively active 259.4 million shares, compared to
221.2 million shares at the same time Thursday.
   Traders said the market was unlikely to gain much more before
the opening of the New York market.
   ``If there's strength in the U.S., this market could soar,''
said one London broker. Alternatively, he said, a weaker start in
New York would probably send London shares lower.
   Britain's February trade deficit narrowed to 1.3 billion pounds,
or $2.39 billion, from 1.4 billion pounds in January, and its
current account fell to 720 million pounds from 844 million pounds.
   The deficits were larger than the markets had expected.
</TEXT>
