<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ford-Britain     03-25 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Britain,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Delegation Unable to Change Ford's Mind on Scotland Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has rejected a British union
delegation's appeal that the automaker revive plans for an
electronic components plant in Scotland, a Ford spokesman said.
   The delegation met with Ford officials Thursday night to present
a union agreement to the company and try to persuade Ford to change
its mind.
   But John J. Emmert of Ford's international public affairs
division said Ford officials would stand by their decision not to
build the plant in Dundee, Scotland.
   The $73 million plant would employ about 450 people and
manufacture electronic engine controls to help cars meet tightening
European emissions standards, he said.
   Ford announced its plans not to build in Dundee last week after
it was unable to win a single-union agreement for the plant. The
company's decision followed five months of feuding among British
unions.
   Emmert said the automaker was willing to meet with the unions in
the future but they would have to modify their position.
   ``The feeling was that the unions were not unified in their
commitment,'' he said.
   Earlier, Gavin Laird, head of the Amalgamated Engineering Union,
Britain's second largest, before the five-member delegation left
London's Heathrow Airport, ``We have a monumental task ahead of
us.''
   Britain's national labor federation, the Trades Union Congress,
has agreed to Ford demands for a single-union deal at the proposed
plant.
   However, the Transport and General Workers' Union, Britain's
largest union, remained opposed to a single-union plant. The
transport union represents two-thirds of Ford's more than 32,000
workers in Britain.
</TEXT>
