<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ICN-LaRoche     03-25 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ICN-La Roche,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ICN Pharmaceuticals Sells Hoffmann-La Roche Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc. says it has
sold the 8.6 percent stake in Swiss drug-industry giant F.
Hoffmann-La Roche & Co. it accumulated since September, abandoning
hopes of merging the companies.
   Proceeds from the sale will be used to buy one or more
health-care companies to expand ICN's distribution capabilities,
the Costa Mesa-based company said.
   In announcing the decision to sell its holdings, ICN said, ``We
understand and respect Hoffmann-La Roche's desire to remain in
family control for the rest of this century.''
   La Roche is controlled tightly by descendants of its founder,
Fritz Hoffman, and industry analysts never gave ICN's overtures
much hope of succeeding.
   ICN said it sold its stake for $153,300 per share, or a total of
$209 million.
   The company declined to say whether it had shown a gain or loss
on the stock, adding that the information would be released with
results of its first quarter ended Feb. 29.
   As of the end of its fiscal year on Nov. 30, the company had
paid $169.8 million for a 6.3 percent stake. La Roche has about
16,000 shares outstanding.
   Separately, ICN said that in its first-quarter results, it would
reverse $15.9 million of the $19.4 million in unrealized losses it
posted at the year's end. Most of those losses were atrributable to
the company's government and corporate bond holdings.
   ICN's major product is ribavirin, an antiviral drug that has
been approved in 28 countries thorughout the world for a variety of
viral infections, including influenza, hepatitis B and herpes
simplex.
</TEXT>
