<1ST_LINE>r f BC-DeLaurentiis     03-25 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-De Laurentiis,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Laurentiis to Shut Distribution Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   De Laurentiis Entertainment Group Inc.,
struggling to recover from heavy losses caused by a string of
box-office bombs, says it will close down its five regional
film-distribution offices, eliminating 28 jobs, or about 15 percent
of its 200 workers.
   Among the movies that performed poorly at the box office for DEG
were ``Taipan,'' ``Million Dollar Mystery,'' ``Weeds'' and ``Date
With an Angel.''
   The company said Thursday its future sales would be handled out
of its corporate office but that the company would ``continue to
explore various distribution alternatives.''
   Those alternatives could include contracting with another film
company to handle De Laurentiis' production.
   Currently, De Laurentiis has seven films, most of them completed
except for various amounts of post-production work. That is down
from nine films in 1987.
   The distribution offices to be closed are in Los Angeles,
Chicago, Dallas, Atlanta and New York.
   ``While this news may seem discouraging, in reality the closing
of our branches is in line with our restructuring plans,'' said
Laurence Gleason, president of the company's marketing and
distribution unit.
   The company's restructuring speeded up substantially after its
founder, Dino De Laurentiis, stepped down in February as chairman
and chief executive.
   In mid-March, the firm sold foreign television, video and
non-theatrical rights to virtually its entire 320-movie film
library for $69 million. It is still seeking a burying for the
remaining rights to its library and for the Wilmington, N.C.,
studio where most of its films have been made.
</TEXT>
