<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Ford-SubsidiaryProfits     03-25 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ford-Subsidiary Profits,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Non-Auto Subsidiaries Profitable for First Time Since 1979</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co.'s non-automotive subsidiaries
together earned a $62 million profit in 1987, their first
money-making year since 1979, the No. 2 automaker said in its
annual report.
   The businesses, which include Rouge Steel Corp., the only steel
company owned by a U.S. automaker, and Ford Aerospace Corp., have
been the focus of major efforts to restore profitability rather
than sell.
   The 1987 profit was a strong improvement over 1986's $205
million loss, but still well short of 1979's $181 million profit,
Ford said.
   Although Ford doesn't disclose results for the individual
companies, the biggest loser is believed to be Rouge Steel, which
Ford once tried to sell to a Japanese steel company.
   Instead, Ford opted to modernize Rouge Steel and other
non-automotive and supplier businesses. This year, it will spend
more than $100 million on Rouge Steel alone.
   The biggest winner was Ford Aerospace, which won three major
government space station contracts worth more than $400 million,
Ford said.
   Ford also said it plans to build a $100 million electronics
plant in Lansdale, Pa., to replace an existing plant and keep 2,400
jobs.
</TEXT>
