<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Steady To Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened steady to
mixed today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybeans opened off more than a penny a bushel due to fairly
heavy farmer selling after Thursday's sharp gains, analysts said.
But prices came back quickly and were narrowly mixed within minutes
of the opening bell.
   Soybean prices also were pressured by ideas that the threat of
weather damage to the nearly ripe South American soybean crop has
passed, said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``You haven't had moisture there since mid-February,'' Loewy
said. ``But the perception in the market is that whatever damage
will be done to the crop by the hot, dry weather has already been
done.''
   He said wheat futures were slightly lower due to slackening
export demand; corn was slightly higher on a lack of farmer selling.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.06 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
1 cent higher with May at $2.07} a bushel; oats were } cent lower
to { cent higher with May at $1.69 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents
lower to 1 cent higher with May at $6.49 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .23 cent higher with April at 74.60
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .25 cent higher
with March at 82.45 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to .50 cent
higher with April at 46.50 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.15 cent to .32 cent higher with May at 57.00 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Thursday; pork futures
were mostly higher.
