<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1158EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv28   03-25 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 28,0712</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday March 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Is It a Bull, a Bear Or an Ostrich?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bull charges with a ferocious, head-down
gallop that spikes victims and flings them in the air. A bear
attacks by clawing and stomping enemies into the ground.
   The beasts evolved into the symbols for good times and bad in
the stock market, the bull for charging forward in a buying spree
and the bear for selling at any excuse. They are ingrained in the
securities vocabulary.
   But amid one of Wall Street's most uncertain times, questions
are arising over these terms. Some analysts say the market's
erratic behavior since the October crash suggests it might be time
to scrap the conventional animal analogies in favor of others.
   ``I would rather have eagles and groundhogs,'' said Philip C.
Puccio, manager of institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. in
New York. ``But seriously, how about ostrich? The market is wearing
blinders to what the economic problems are out there, hiding its
head in the sand.''
   Robert Sobel, a Hofstra University professor and financial
author who has written extensively about the stock market, says he
believes the October break was an aberration in the bull market
that began in 1982.
   Now that the market is neither bullish or bearish, he says, ``I
call it a horse market. Just horsing around.''
   Most strategists who routinely use bullish or bearish to
describe the outlook don't know the origin of the terms. Historians
never have documented precisely who invented them.
   ``Throughout my travels I've never seen anything that says,
`Aha, this is where it came from,''' said Yale Hirsch, a veteran
analyst who publishes the Stock Trader's Almanac. ``I've looked
constantly, and nobody seems to know.''
   A common hypothesis is that the symbols evolved during the 1800s
in England, Sobel says.
   ``The theory most people seem to accept is that a bull, when it
goes after you, tries to push you on its horns and lift you up,''
Sobel observed. ``The bear crushes you down.''
   James Medbery, a 19th century stockbroker who wrote a work
titled ``Men and Mysteries of Wall Street,'' was one of the first
to explain the terms in print. If you bought stock cheaply for
future delivery in the hope prices would rise, you were a bull, he
wrote. If you sold stock for future delivery in the hope prices
would fall, you were a bear.
   The official history book of the New York Stock Exchange
suggests the analogy's roots may date back earlier to the proverb,
``To sell the bear's skin before one has caught the bear.''
   The book also mentions natural history as a possible
explanation. ``If a bear finds anything, whether it be a turkey on
a roost or a man on a tree, he lifts its paw and pulls it down,''
it explains. ``The bull, on the contrary, lowers its head only to
give men and things a decided upward tendency.''
   The NYSE helped institutionalize the bull and bear analogies
early this century, when it commissioned a sculpture depicting the
beasts locked in combat, with neither taking the advantage. Merrill
Lynch & Co., one of the country's biggest investment houses, uses
the bull on its logo.
   Animal behaviorists say that generally, the bull and bear
analogies to the stock market are appropriate.
   ``Bears are pretty tough animals,'' said Frederick Sterling,
manager of animal collections for the Bronx Zoo. ``People take them
as being lethargic and easy-going. But if they're disturbed, for
whatever reason, they run you right down. It's like the 8:15 from
Connecticut coming into Grand Central.''
   Lowell L. Wilson, professor of animal science at Pennsylvania
State University, says bulls can have unpredictable behavior
patterns but usually are territorial and ornery.
   ``That's probably one of the main reasons the analogy to the
stock market is made,'' Wilson said. ``On a practical basis though,
the bulls we use in the (husbandry) industry are selected for good
behavior. In other words, if somebody has an aggressive bull, it
probably winds up as hamburger.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday March 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
