<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1223EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     03-25 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates and bond prices were holding
steady in early trading today, following Thursday's volatile
session that ended on a mixed note.
   By midday, the Treasury's 30-year bond slipped 1-32 point, or
about 30 cents per $1,000 face amount, and yielded 8.72 percent,
unchanged from late Thursday.
   The bellwether issue had closed 1-32 point lower in the previous
session after losing as much as { point, or $5, earlier in the day.
   In the absence of any market-moving economic news, some bond
traders were looking at the currency and oil markets, often an
indicator on where inflation might be heading.
   A stable dollar was said to be adding a positive tone to
shorter-maturing securities while a slight increase in oil prices
has hurt some longer-maturing bonds a bit.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments and intermediate maturities were unchanged to 1-16
point higher while 20-year issues were down 1-32 point, according
to figures provided by Telerate Inc.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, rose 0.01 to 111.82. The Shearson Lehman Daily
Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, stood at
1,169.54, up 0.31.
   In corporate trading, industrials and utilities were unchanged
in light trading, according to the investment firm of Salomon
Brothers Inc.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 0.63 to 281.73.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were down 3 basis points to
5.78 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills were unchanged at 6.03 percent and one-year bills
were off 2 basis points at 6.38 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 6| percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
