<2ND_LINE>PM-Roper,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Venue Change in Whirlpool-GE Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Corp., in its quest for
Roper Corp., said today it will move to Michigan its legal battle
challenging the appliance and garden equipment maker's agreement to
be acquired by Whirlpool Corp.
   Separately, Roper said its board will meet next week to review
bids from GE and Whirlpool. GE increased its tender offer for Roper
on Monday to $507 million, topping Whirlpool's $470 million merger
agreement with Roper.
   The GE tender offer amounts to $54 a share; Whirlpool's tender
offer amounts to $50 a share for the Augusta, Ga.-based company.
   A federal judge here denied GE's request to move a lawsuit filed
by Whirlpool to Delaware, where GE filed two suits challenging the
Roper-Whirlpool combination.
   ``It was simply a matter of whether it would be consolidated in
Delaware or Michigan,'' GE spokesman George Jameson said.
   GE said today it will withdraw the federal court actions it
filed in Delaware in and refile them in the Kalamazoo court,
Jameson said from GE headquarters in Fairfield, Conn.
   ``Whirlpool will be inconvenienced by litigating in Delaware,
while GE will be inconvenienced by litigating in Michigan,'' U.S.
District Judge Richard A. Enslen said in a written order issued
Thursday.
   But in ordering the case to be heard in Michigan, Enslen noted
that many of the main witnesses are in Michigan.
   Whirlpool, headquartered in Benton Harbor, Mich., has not said
whether it will top GE's latest bid. ``We don't have a comment on
that at this point,'' spokeswoman Donna McLean said today.
   Analysts have said that merging with Roper would move Whirlpool
ahead of GE as the country's top appliance maker.
   Whirlpool's suit charged that GE's initial $45-a-share offer for
Roper, made on March 6, was an attempt to sabotage a
Whirlpool-Roper merger agreement announced in February in which
Whirlpool said it would pay $37.50 a share.
   Whirlpool later sweetened its bid to $50 a share, and Roper's
board recommended shareholders accept the offer.
   In its lawsuits, GE claimed both Whirlpool and Roper failed to
adequately disclose terms of their merger agreement under
Securities and Exchange Commission laws.
   The suit also claims Whirlpool and Roper failed to publicly
disclose GE's prior interest in acquiring Roper and accuses the
Roper board of concealing from shareholders that GE, as well as
Whirlpool, wanted to buy the company.
</TEXT>
