<2ND_LINE>BC-Britian-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: NEW throughout to included closing</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed lower Friday but finished well
above their worst levels of the day reached after the release of
disappointing British trade figures for February.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 14.8
points, or 0.8 percent, to close at 1,767.9.
   The index moved down as much as 23.3 points on the trade news
but then recovered gradually through the afternoon as trading
volume slackened considerably.
   Volume was light at 412.5 million shares, down from 535.3
million on Thursday.
   Shares traded narrowly in the morning but then plunged when the
government reported at 11:30 a.m. local time that Britain's
February merchandise trade deficit narrowed to 1.3 billion pounds,
about $2.4 billion, from 1.4 billion pounds in January.
   The current account deficit, which includes invisible trade like
financial services, narrowed to 720 million pounds, or $1.3
billion, from 844 million pounds, the Department of Trade and
Industry said.
   Despite the narrowings, both deficits were much larger than the
markets had expected.
   The sharp drop attracted a few bargain hunters. Share prices
recovered further on the back of markups by market makers after
Wall Street opened, apparently in no mood to reenact Thursday's
sharp sell-off. But afternoon trading volume slowed to a trickle
ahead of the weekend.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was 13.3 points lower at
1,408.3 at the close.
   The Financial Times 500-share index fell 9.35 points to close at
999.76.
</TEXT>
