<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv26-27   03-25 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 26-27,0566</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 26-27</NOTE>
<HEAD>Who Are Big `Muni' Buyers? Don't Look At Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uncle Sam has clearly broken up the cozy
relationship between the nation's commerical banks and the
municipal bond market.
   Historically one of the biggest players in that market, banks
have dumped more than $51 billion of their municipal bond holdings
in the last two years due to changes in the tax law, according to a
report by the Public Securities Association, a trade group of bond
dealers.
   The report, released this past week by the PSA and based on
Federal Reserve data, showed that individual investors were the
leading buyers of municipal bonds for the third consecutive year in
1987, either through the purchase of individual bonds, unit
investment trusts or tax-exempt mutual and money market funds.
   The report noted that households owned 39 percent of the $720.5
million outstanding issues last year, up from 33.6 percent in 1986
and 36.5 percent in the previous year.
   Banks came in second with a 25 percent holding, down from 29
percent in 1986 and 35.1 percent in 1985. Their holdings peaked in
1971 with 51.2 percent. Property and casualty insurance companies
owned 13.1 percent; mutual funds, 9.8 percent; and money market
funds, 8.5 percent.
   The dramatic decline in bank holdings came as a result of the
1986 Tax Reform Act, which removed incentives for bank portfolios
to invest in municipal bonds, or ``munis'' as they're known on Wall
Street.
   Banks had been able to deduct from their income taxes 80 percent
of the cost of holding these tax-exempt bonds, but the tax law
eliminated the deduction except on state and local issues totaling
$10 million or less a year. The changes have had a mixed effect on
the market so far, analysts and traders said.
   ``From an issuers point of view ... you're entering the market
realizing that except in very unusual circumstances banks won't be
one of your purchasers, so you're heavily dependent on individual
purchases who face an entirely different set of incentives than do
banks,'' said PSA President Heather Ruth.
   In the recent past, issuers and banks have had a cozy
relationship. As an example, Ruth notes that around tax time when
some individual investors sold bonds to raise cash to pay their
taxes, banks would eagerly snap them up, keeping prices and yields
stable.
   George Friedlander, a managing director at Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co., says it's not surprising that since the tax law most
smaller issues have been doing better than the bigger ones which
dominate the market.
   Because banks are still actively buying them, bonds from the
smallest of issues are more liquid, meaning they could be traded in
a short period of time with relatively small price fluctuations,
Friedlander said.
   That price stability means lower yields, reducing borrowing
expenses for the small issuers but raising them for the bigger ones.
   Analysts note that volatility in the muni market is likely to
continue through 1989, when insurance companies will see their tax
incentives wiped out as a result of the overhaul of the tax system.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 26-27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-StockFutures-Limits     03-25 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stock Futures-Limits,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CFTC Approves Moving Limits On S&P 500 Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange said Friday it
would impose an unusual system of adjustable price limits on its
Standard & Poor's 500 stock-index futures to reduce the volatility
of U.S. financial markets.
   The limits were approved Thursday by the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission and take effect Monday, replacing the 30-point
price limit the Chicago Merc placed on S&P 500 futures in the wake
of the Oct. 19 stock market collapse.
   The new limits will range from 15 index points to 25 index
points depending on the settlement price of the lead-month S&P 500
futures contract on the last business day of the preceding month,
the exchange said in a statement to its members.
   Price limits effectively halt trading of a futures contract
whenever the price of the contract moves above or below the
specified amount.
   Investors use stock-index futures to hedge against losses in the
stock market by betting on the price movement of the stocks that
make up the index.
   S&P 500 futures account for more than 80 percent of all U.S.
stock-index futures trades.
   Chicago Merc officials have said the limits will result in
better coordination of U.S. financial markets, a key recommendation
of the presidential commission that investigated the stock market
crash.
   A one-point move in the S&P 500 index is roughly equivalent to
an eight-point move in the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials.
Some analysts had criticized the 30-point limit on S&P 500 futures
_ equivalent to about 240 points on the Dow _ as being too high to
curtail all but the most violent price swings.
   A 15-point limit will take effect Monday because the June
contract settled Feb. 29 at 268.75 points, within the low-end range
of 0 to 275 points.
   The limit would rise to 20 points if the June contract settled
above 275 points on the last trading day of March, or to 25 points
if the June contract closed above 325 points.
   The June contract settled at 264.10 points on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0274 </DOCNO>
