<1ST_LINE>a f AM-Relocations Adv28   03-25 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Relocations, Adv 28,0366</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs March 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Most Companies Relocate Close to Home, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most companies stay close to home when they
relocate their headquarters, according to a national survey to be
released Monday.
   The survey published by Cushman & Wakefield Inc., a business
real estate firm based in New York, showed that 85 percent of the
companies that relocated their headquarters during the past five
years moved to a similar type of location, while 62 percent
relocated in the same community.
   Only 7 percent of the relocating companies changed states, the
survey indicated.
   The findings are based on interviews with top executives at 400
organizations, including publicly and privately held corporations,
partnerships, non-profit companies and government agencies. All the
organizations polled have 50 or more employees at their
headquarters and have relocated in the past five years.
   While the suburbs of large cities rank first as a preferred
location for head offices with 36 percent, the survey also
suggested a growing tendency for relocating in the biggest U.S.
cities, Cushman & Wakefield said. The survey showed that 28 percent
of the relocating companies consider big cities the best type of
location.
   ``The survey disputes the widespread impression of a sudden wave
of headquarters relocations and a mass exodus from the nation's
largest cities,'' said Arthur J. Mirante, president and chief
executive officer of the real estate company.
   ``Only a handful of organizations relocate across state lines,''
Mirante added.
   He said such moves recently as Mobil Corp.'s from New York to
Fairfax, Va., and Firestone Tire & Rubber Co.'s from Akron, Ohio,
to Chicago are the exceptions rather than the rule.
   The need for more space was the most compelling reason for
relocating, according to the survey.
   Other reasons were a more favorable company image, lower
occupancy costs, a better quality of life for employees, better
access to markets, customers or clients, and a major change in the
company's strategic direction. None of those factors, however, were
considered crucial by more than 24 percent, the survey showed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday AMs March 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
