<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Savings Bjt   03-25 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Savings, Bjt,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trillions of Dollars Up for Grabs as Savings System Ends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $2 trillion in Japanese savings accounts
loses its tax-free status next week, and executives from Tokyo
investment firms to foreign manufacturers are dreaming of tapping
into the treasure trove.
   The April 1 change was prompted by complaints from allies that
Japan needs to spur domestic consumption as a way to recycle some
of its $82.7 billion annual trade surplus.
   The hope is the new 20 percent tax on interest will encourage
Japanese to save less and spend more. But many experts do not
foresee that happening.
   The system of tax-free individual accounts _ known as ``maryu''
_ was set up after World War II to provide a reserve of capital to
finance the rebuilding of Japan's economy. Through it, the average
Japanese family had built a nest egg worth the equivalent of
$82,000 by last year.
   George Nemo, a broker for the investment firm Vickers Da Costa
in Tokyo, estimates such accounts now hold a total of 300 trillion
yen _ or about $2.3 trillion.
   Banks are touting new savings plans to hold onto this treasure,
while securities companies are trying to lure it away. Foreign
countries hope to get part of it through increased sales of exports
to Japan.
   But despite the advertising hoopla, Nemo and other financial
analysts expect much of the money to remain right where it is for
now.
   ``This is not as spectacular as one might expect,'' Nemo said.
   He said recent surveys of Japanese housewives, who handle most
of the money in the average Japanese family, found they would be
willing to pay the new tax and ``leave their nest eggs alone.''
   However, he said there is bound to be at least a small
percentage unwilling to settle for the low interest that banks pay
on such accounts. Some of that money will find new homes, most
probably in Japan's booming stock market.
   Banks pay only four-tenths of 1 percent interest on a regular
savings account and up to about 4 percent for long-term deposits.
   Under the maryu system, no tax was charged for interest on
savings accounts of up to $47,500, postal savings accounts of
$23,800 and installment savings of $4,000. In addition, workers
were allowed to build tax-free savings accounts of $40,000 through
their employers.
   The Japanese are among the industrialized world's biggest
savers. The average family in Japan saves 16.1 percent of its
annual income, compared with 11.6 percent for West Germany, 10.1
percent for France, 7.8 percent for Britain and 6.6 percent in the
United States.
   Nemo is doubtful the next tax will have much effect on saving.
   ``The problem is, they already have just about all the
televisions, videos, and smart clothes they could want,'' he said.
``And if they can't afford to buy homes, where are they going to
spend the money?''
   According to the Economic Planning Agency, 99 percent of the
Japanese own a color television set, refrigerator and washing
machine, 98 percent own a vacuum cleaner and nearly 70 percent own
a car.
   With the high housing and land prices, most Japanese can never
hope to own their own home, so there is little else to do with the
money other than spend it on high-priced cars or travel, invest it
in the stock market or put it in a savings account.
   Takasuke Koneko, a spokesman for Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, said
Japanese are very cautious about where they put their savings
because the burden of providing for old age falls on the individual
in Japan. He predicted many people would be scared off stock
investing because of the worldwide plunge in stock prices last
October.
   Koneko said some of the money probably will go to life
insurance, which is still tax-free if a person signs a contract for
more than five years. However, he said, many people will not be
willing to wait that long for a return on their investment.
   ``The bottom line is that we have to protect ourselves,'' he
said. ``We cannot shift our funds. Still, we will have to save. In
20 years, when we get ready to retire, the stock market could be
two or three times what it could be now, but it could also be
one-half or one-third.
   ``Even with the end of the maryu system, our money has to be
kept where it is safe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
