<DOCNO> AP880325-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ToyComeback Bjt   03-25 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Comeback, Bjt,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toymakers Enjoying a Better Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrival of spring has brought signs of
recovery to the toy industry following 1987's dismal performance.
Stores are selling more toys and manufacturers are getting more
orders.
   But toymakers know the fickle tastes of young customers can take
a promising product and overnight turn it into a dud. So there is
an air of caution in this highly volatile business, although the
early trend is positive.
   ``It's a very good retail environment for the first time in
several years,'' said Paul Valentine, a toy industry analyst with
Standard & Poor's Corp.
   At Toys R Us Inc., the nation's largest toy store chain,
President Norman Ricken said more customers are in the stores and
sales are up ``quite strongly'' over last year.
   ``The indications are that it's a better start for the year than
most people anticipated,'' said Spencer Boise, a spokesman for
Mattel Inc., the nation's second-largest toymaker.
   Good consumer demand usually translates into more orders for
manufacturers, and that has heartened the big toy companies, most
of whom finished 1987 in the red because product lines failed,
sales fell off and costs were too high.
   Toys that were big sellers at Christmas have remained popular in
1988. Among them are Nintendo and other video games, Games Gang
Ltd.'s Pictionary board game, Fisher Price's Fun With Food, Kenner
Parker Toys' Real Ghostbusters action game and Matchbox Toys Ltd.'s
Pee Wee Herman talking doll.
   The popularity of such products _ known as carryover toys in the
business _ contrasts with the events of a year ago, when toys that
had been best sellers at Christmas 1986 fizzled.
   Another positive sign is that the success of the current
best-sellers is becoming contagious.
   ``They spark people to come into the store, and they buy other
things,'' Ricken of Toys R Us said. ``There is a lot of impulse
buying.''
   Rick Anguilla, editor of the trade publication Toy & Hobby
World, agreed, saying, ``The key is, bring people into the stores.''
   Several years ago, Coleco's Trivial Pursuit and Cabbage Patch
Kids were luring consumers in droves, but Pictionary and Nintendo
are today's top draws, Anguilla said.
   But despite the early trends, manufacturers and the people who
track their fortunes are taking a wait-and-see approach for the
remainder of 1988.
   ``It's a little too early to predict a strong year,'' said
Anguilla.
   Mattel's orders are running ahead of the company's conservative
expectations, but Boise warned, ``Orders are not necessarily a good
indication of how the year might go, because they're cancelable
anytime up to delivery.''
   The analysts also caution that after the disappointments of
1987, it's easy to show for companies to show an improvement in
sales.
   ``They're just going from a disaster to a more normal operating
environment,'' said Harold Vogel, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &
Co.
   ``I think they are doing better, but I don't see anything great
happening,'' he said.
   Caution also was the watchword when the industry unveiled its
new products last month at its annual trade show, Toy Fair.
   Burned by the failure of lines such as expensive high-tech
dolls, companies showed fewer new toys and leaned toward smaller,
less expensive ideas. The early returns indicate the strategy is
working.
   Tonka Corp. is getting strong orders for Starting Lineup, a
series of sports figures intended to sell under $5 apiece, said
Robert Meek, a company spokesman.
   Tonka's orders are well above 1987 levels, Meek said. The
company markets a top-selling video game, Sega, but all of its
divisions are showing improvement, he said.
   Industry watchers say another company doing much better is Lewis
Galoob Toys Inc.'s. Galoob, which lost money on high-tech items in
1987, is focusing on less risky ideas such as plastic charms that
contain cosmetics and stationery for girls, tiny dolls and small,
transformable military figures for boys.
   Companies, some of which have laid off workers, also continue to
look for ways to cut expenses. On Friday, Tonka announced a
restructuring in its Canadian operations, including 60 layoffs.
   Such moves will help a company's bottom line, and form a hedge
against heavy losses should sales drop off again.
   Vogel predicted for the toymakers this year, ``They'll have some
modest profits, but no one's setting the world on fire.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
