<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasury Auction,0127</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Short-term Notes Auctioned at 6.20 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department auctioned off $4.06
billion in short-term bills on Friday with an average yield of 6.20
percent.
   The so-called cash management bill will mature in 22 days and
was issued so the government would have enough money on hand to
make tax refund payments during the tax filing season.
   The last time the government had to resort to such short-term
financing was during last year's tax filing season when a 20-day
bill had an average yield of 5.75 percent.
   The discount rate understates the actual return to investors _
6.31 percent with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,962.10. A total of
$38.81 billion in bids were received.
