<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Korea-Corn     03-25 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Corn,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Delegation Signs Contracts For About 10 Million Bushels Of
Corn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean trade delegation signed
contracts in Iowa on Friday to purchase about 10 million bushels of
U.S. corn for about $29.3 million, and an official said about 95
percent of his country's corn purchases this year would be from the
United States.
   That would mark a continued rebound of U.S. shipments, which in
1985 accounted for just 36 percent of the corn purchased by South
Korea, according to the Iowa Corn Promotion Board.
   The drop in U.S. corn sales mainly reflected an aggressive
export drive by China earlier this decade to compete for a growing
share of world sales, said economist Robert Wisner at Iowa State
University.
   He said the resurgence of corn sales to South Korea by the
United States is a result of reduced Chinese sales because of
growing domestic consumption.
   South Korea, meantime, is stepping up imports of feed grains as
it expands its livestock industry, and has increased corn
consumption from 3 million metric tons in 1985 to about 5 million
metric tons this year, said Chan-Kung Park, head of the trade
mission and chairman of the Korea Feed Association.
   The delegation signed contracts Friday to buy 150,000 metric
tons, or about 6 million bushels of corn, from Continental Grain
and to buy another 50,000 metric tons, or about 2 million bushels,
each from Cargill Inc. and Marc Rich Co. A metric ton is
approximately 2,205 pounds.
   After subtracting the cost of transporting the grain to Asia,
South Korea paid an average of about $1.85 a bushel for the grain,
according to the Iowa Corn Promotion Board.
   Those purchases, when added to contracts signed in neighboring
Nebraska and South Dakota, brought sales to the trade mission to
550,000 metric tons.
   Park said that so far this year, South Korea had bought more
than 2.25 million metric tons of U.S. corn and that most of the
remainder of its 1988 purchases would be from the United States. He
estimated the U.S. would account for 95 percent of the corn bought
by his country in 1988.
   ``Korea is purchasing as much as possible from the United
States,'' Park said through an interpreter. He said that with the
decline in the U.S. dollar in the past three years, U.S. corn is
priced competitively on world markets with grain from China and
other Asian sources and he said U.S. agricultural policy has been
very successful since 1984.
   In the early 1980s, South Korea also bought more than 90 percent
of its corn from the United States, before China became a major
competitor.
   Iowa is the nation's leading corn producing state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pickens-Eastern     03-25 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pickens-Eastern,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pickens, Eastern Unions Reportedly Consider Texas Air Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Texas Air Corp. on Friday declined
comment on press reports that investor T. Boone Pickens is
considering helping unions acquire the company.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in Friday's editions that
Pickens met recently with representatives of Eastern Airlines'
unions to propose a plan to take over Texas Air, the parent of
Miami-based Eastern.
   Texas Air, based in Houston, is the nation's largest airline
holding company with about 20 percent of the U.S. market.
   Pickens laid out one strategy whereby his personal investment
company, Boone Co., would assist the unions in seeking a
controlling interest in Texas Air, the newspaper reported.
   ``The longstanding policy of the company is never to comment on
rumor or speculation,'' Texas Air spokesman Bruce Hicks said Friday.
   Pickens' spokesman, David Batchelder, reached by telephone in
Amarillo, Texas, also declined comment.
   Under Pickens' plan, about $1 billion of Eastern employees'
pension fund money would be used as leverage to fund an offer for
the company, the newspaper said.
   Under the arrangement, the unions would negotiate wage
concessions in return for a financial stake in the company, the
Journal said. If the plan succeeded, Pickens would receive a fee,
and would not participate in the management of the company, the
newspaper reported.
   Texas Air has about $5 billion in long-term debt, and Chairman
Frank Lorenzo has control of the company's voting power.
   Lorenzo and a few close associates own a special class of stock
which carries voting rights 10 times those of regular common stock.
   Unidentified participants in the recent discussions between
Pickens and Eastern's unions told the Journal they believed between
75 percent and 80 percent of Eastern's common shares would have to
be tendered in order to dilute Lorenzo's voting control to a
minority position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
