<DOCNO> AP880325-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1701EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Federated     03-25 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau Says It Won't Raise Its Federated Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. says it will not raise its $6.53
billion tender offer for Federated Department Stores Inc., but is
demanding a fair opportunity to compete with R.H. Macy & Co. Inc.
to buy the retailer, Federated said in a filing with the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
   ``Campeau is not increasing its price,'' Federated quoted
Campeau as saying in a statement to Federated's board Thursday.
``It believes its price is already too high.''
   ``This does not mean that you can give Macy's a chance to jigger
its bid or take any other action with respect to Macy's, without
giving Campeau a fair opportunity to respond,'' Federated quoted
Campeau as saying.
   The Federated filing was made public Friday.
   The Cincinnati-based Federated, operator of more than 650 stores
nationwide with total 1987 sales of $11.1 billion, said Thursday it
would discuss Campeau's tender offer with the Toronto-based
developer and talk with Macy about a possible sweetening of Macy's
$6.3 billion bid.
   Federated management has already approved a merger agreement
with Macy.
   Federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer, said its board
would meet by Wednesday, and Macy Chairman Edward Finkelstein and
his counterpart at Campeau, Robert Campeau, both would be allowed
to speak at the session.
   Federated said there is no guarantee the negotiations with Macy
will result in an improved offer.
   Campeau on Tuesday raised its two-step, all-cash offer for
Federated to an aggregate of approximately $73 a share from $68 a
share, or $6.18 billion. Under the new offer, Campeau said it would
pay $82 each for 70.5 million Federated shares and $37 for the
remainder of Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares in a
subsequent merger.
   Campeau also extended the expiration of its offer to midnight
EST April 4, when Macy's offer is scheduled to expire.
   Campeau also proposed to Federated's board an alternate friendly
merger under which it would pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares
in a tender offer and $73 for the remaining shares following the
merger.
   Campeau has proposed that a Campeau-Federated merger be
structured along lines similar to a merger agreement between the
retailer and Macy.
   Macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million
Federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. Macy would exchange
shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities
for the remainder of Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares.
   Analysts value the Macy offer at $6.3 billion.
   Federated's divisions include Bloomingdale's, Abraham and
Straus, Burdine's, Filene's, Foley's, Lazarus and Rich's department
stores; Ralphs supermarkets; Gold Circle discount stores; and Main
Street and Children's Place specialty stores.
   Federated also has delayed putting into effect, until at least
March 30, a ``poison pill'' amendment to the company's shareholder
rights plan that allows shareholders to buy new shares at a steep
discount. It is designed to make an unwanted takeover more
expensive.
   It is not clear if Federated could apply the pill to Campeau but
not to Macy. Some analysts believe the outcome of the takeover
fight may turn on that issue, and that a court might ultimately
decide whether Federated can take such a step.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
