<DOCNO> AP880325-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1748EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Koppers 2ndLd-Writethru   03-25 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Hikes Tender Offer For Koppers; Sparks Sharp Criticism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS x graf to CLARIFY Pennsylvania ad ran in more papers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beazer PLC, unable to lure Koppers Co. into a
friendly deal, on Friday boosted its hostile tender offer for the
building materials and cement company to $1.7 billion.
   Government officials, meanwhile, lashed out at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. for assuming the unusual role of equity partner in the
takeover bid, but Shearson maintains it is merely acting as a
responsible investment banker to Beazer, a long-standing client.
   To protest Shearson's collaboration in the battle for
Pittsburgh-based Koppers, Pennsylvania officials said they have
terminated a $7-billion-a-year relationship with the New York
investment house, and one lawmaker has called for a congressional
investigation into Shearson's role.
   Koppers has rebuffed Beazer ever since it appeared on the scene
three weeks ago with a $45-a-share offer. Last weekend, Beazer
sweetened that bid to $56 a share, or $1.52 billion, which Koppers
characterized as inadequate.
   Before going directly to shareholders with its latest
$60-a-share tender offer, the British construction and building
materials company tried to negotiate a friendly deal at the same
price with Koppers management.
   In staunchly resisting the overtures, Koppers said it is
prepared to go deep into debt to finance a one-time cash payout to
its shareholders as a defensive maneuver. A consortium of banks has
agreed to lend Koppers about $1 billion to finance the payout.
   Beazer has threatened to sue Koppers if the company sells some
or all of its construction materials and services business as part
of a recapitalization plan.
   Separately, Koppers asked the U.S. District Court in Los Angeles
to halt Beazer's tender offer because of antitrust considerations.
Beazer had agreed to sell Koppers' aggregate plant in Los Angeles
if the deal is consumated to satisfy the Justice Department's
antitrust concerns. Beazer called the Koppers move ``completely
without merit.''
   Koppers fell 12.5 cents to $58.625 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   At Koppers annual community business luncheon in Pittsburgh,
President Glen Tenley, a 33-year Koppers veteran, declared
management's intention to remain independent.
   ``Thirty-three years have not been spent with Koppers to be put
under some other company's ownership just because the dollar is
cheap and there are fat financial fees to be made,'' he said.
   In full-page advertisements appearing Friday in papers including
The New York Times and The Wall Street Journal, the Treasurer of
Pennsylvania criticized Shearson and its parent, American Express
Co., for their role in a hostile bid that ``can potentially have a
significant adverse impact on jobs in this state.''
   G. Davis Greene, Jr., said in a letter to Shearson@American
Express Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Peter A. Cohen, that
he suspended all business activity between the state Treasury's
office and Shearson on Wednesday.
   Greene said that ``business activity'' totaled $7 billion over
the past year.
   Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neill said he did not know ``what
the $7 billion refers to,'' but added that ``overall there is no
evidence of any significant business impact.''
   British investor Brian Beazer sees Koppers as a strategic step
in his quest to build a worldwide building materials empire. As an
equity partner in Beazer's BNS Inc., which launched the tender
offer, Shearson agreed to provide the mortar for the deal with $570
million in bridge financing and about $23 million in equity
interest in BNS.
   ``We're providing a form of interim financing ... but it does
not translate into a long-term interest in the company,''
Shearson's O'Neill said. County Natwest Ltd., a British investment
bank, also agreed to take an equity position.
   ``There's a confusion over the nature of our financing ... We're
not the acquirer, Beazer is,'' O'Neill stressed. Under terms of a
complex financial package, Shearson will sell its stake in BNS back
to Beazer.
   On Thursday, Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., called for a
congressional investigation of Shearson's ``unique and highly
questionable hostile takeover attempt.''
   Walgren noted that Shearson's bid ``marks the first time that an
investment banking firm has both conceived of a hostile takeover
and acted as an equity partner in the deal.''
   If investment banks take on equity interests, Walgren said,
``corporate America will be controlled by banks at unprecedented
levels, and America's landscape will be littered with the empty
shells of abandoned office buildings and company plants.''
   Koppers has taken its own action against Shearson and American
Express. Earlier this week Koppers' management canceled its
American Express account, through which the company had been buying
about $1.5 million per year in goods and services.
   Koppers employees also shredded 175 American Express cards in
protest.
   Likewise, the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce urged citizens to
``leave home without it'' by destroying their American Express
cards in sympathy.
   Pennsylvania Gov. Robert Casey on Friday ordered Shearson be
dropped as a potential advisor for a pending bond issue. The City
of Pittsburgh, which has sued Shearson to block the takeover, also
has suspended business dealings with the firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
