<DOCNO> AP880325-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-25 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Prices Ease</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed mixed after moving in jagged
fashion Friday amid rumors that central banks stepped in to steady
the currency.
   Gold prices eased. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid price for gold of $452.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down
from Thursday's late bid of $453.15 an ounce.
   Traders said the Federal Reserve and the Bank of Japan moved to
support the dollar as the yen continued its upward climb against
the major currencies. The dollar fell to levels against the yen not
seen since mid-January.
   Without the intervention, ``the beating would have been fairly
bad'' for the dollar, said Albert Soria, vice president and foreign
exchange manager at Swiss Bank Corp.
   While sentiment is brewing that the narrowing of U.S. trade
deficits might be drawing to a close, traders continued to argue
that the dollar's drop is not so much related to fundamentals as it
is to the continued strengthening of the Japanese yen.
   ``There seems to be a very big demand for investors to be into
yen,'' said Stephen Flanagan, an assistant vice president at
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Dealers are wary that the Japanese will begin to dump their
dollar holdings once their fiscal year comes to a close on March
31, ``so the market is beginning to jump the gun'' by selling the
U.S. currency, Flanagan said.
   The dollar mostly weakened in Europe, where the pound was the
center of attention as it slumped on the heels of a British
government report of a disappointing trade deficit for February.
   The pound was hit by news that Britain's merchandise trade
deficit narrowed slightly in February to 1.3 billion pounds, or
$2.4 billion, from 1.4 billion pounds in January.
   The current account deficit, which includes invisible trade like
financial services, was pegged at 720 million pounds, or $1.3
billion, from 844 million pounds, the Department of Trade and
Industry said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 0.56 yen to a closing 125.74 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 125.33 yen. In New York, the dollar closed at 125.30
yen, down from 125.575 yen Thursday.
   In London, the pound fell to $1.8360 from $1.8435 late Thursday.
In New York, it cost $1.84175 to buy one pound, cheaper than
Thursday's $1.8420.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.6760 West German marks, down from 1.67725;
1.3865 Swiss francs, up from 1.38625; 5.68625 French francs, down
from 5.6995; 1,238.50 Italian lire, down from 1,242.50, and 1.24205
Canadian dollars, down from 1.2421.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
were: 1.6760 West German marks, down from 1.6800; 1.3865 Swiss
francs, down from 1.3885; 5.6860 French francs, down from 5.7120;
1.8820 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8980; 1,241.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,246.95; and 1.2433 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2426.
   Gold prices eased. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold closed
at $453.20, a troy ounce, down from $454.10 on Thursday. In London,
gold fell to a late bid price of $451.70 a troy ounce from late
Thursday's $452.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $451.50 compared
with $452 dollars late Thursday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell
$1.32 an ounce to close at $454.08.
   Silver closed at $6.665 a troy ounce on New York's Comex, down
from $6.735 on Thursday. In London, the metal was trading at a late
bid price of $6.64 a troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's
$6.61.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0296 </DOCNO>
