<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1756EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ResortsInternational Bjt   03-25 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Resorts International, Bjt,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resorts Seeking $600 Million Financing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resorts International Inc., target of rival
takeover bids from entertainer Merv Griffin and real estate
developer Donald Trump, is trying to line up $600 million in
high-yield bond financing, mostly to complete its overdue and
over-budget Taj Mahal hotel-casino.
   The financing negotiations were disclosed Friday by Trump, who
controls 88 percent of Resorts' voting strength, is the company's
chairman and is seeking to buy the rest of its stock and take it
private.
   Besides providing money to complete the Taj Mahal, proceeds from
the financing would be used for working capital and to reimburse
Trump for stock-purchase costs if his tender offer succeeds.
   While terms of the financing aren't complete, Trump said the
arrangement is contingent upon the success of his tender offer for
the company and upon Trump's guarantee that the Taj Mahal will be
finished.
   If Trump's takeover bid fails, the company may seek a smaller
amount of financing, Trump said.
   Trump has estimated it will take $550 million to complete the
sprawling and luxurious Taj Mahal, which would become Atlantic
City's biggest hotel-casino with 42 floors and 1,250 rooms.
   Final cost of the project is estimated to be $938.5 million, up
from an estimated $535 million when work on it began four years ago.
   Resorts has other hotel-casino operations in Atlantic City and
the Bahamas.
   Trump owns nearly all of the company's 572,000 shares of Class B
stock, which carries 100 votes per share. He is offering $22 per
share to buy the remainder.
   Besides Class B stock, the company has 5.7 million Class A
shares, which have one vote each.
   Griffin last week made a rival bid of $35 per share, or $225
million, for all of Resorts' stock, including that held by Trump.
Griffin later increased his offer to $295 million, leaving it up to
Resorts' board to decide how to apportion the $70 million increase
between the two classes of stock.
   Trump has repeatedly refused to sell his stock and has sued
Griffin for $250 million for allegedly interfering with Trump's
contractual obligations with Resorts.
   Griffin has sued Trump and Resorts' outside directors, claiming
among other things that they breached their fiduciary duty by
refusing to pursue Griffin's offer. Resorts' board said it didn't
pursue Griffin's proposal on grounds that Trump's rejection had
rendered it moot.
   On Thursday, the two sides disclosed the Securities and Exchange
Commission had begun looking into allegations of securities
violations, but they blamed each other's activities for triggering
the probe.
   Trump claimed statements and actions by Griffin and an ally had
a ``manipulative effect'' on the market for Resorts' stock.
   Griffin contended the SEC was looking into allegations of breach
of fiduciary duty and failure by Trump to disclose a new and higher
appraisal of Resorts' value in making his $22-per-share offer.
   Resorts shares rose 12{ cents Friday in American Stock Exchange
trading to close at $28.87{.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HighSpeedRail     03-25 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-High Speed Rail,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Apply To Build Bullet Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four applications to build a bullet
train linking Miami, Orlando and Tampa were submitted Friday after
six years of planning for the space-age but still conceptual rail
system.
   Details of the applications are to be revealed Monday in a
ceremony with Gov. Bob Martinez and legislative leaders.
   ``This is a major milestone in this project,'' said Diana Hull,
spokeswoman for the High Speed Rail Commission. ``Today's deadline
will put us one large step along toward putting high-speed rail in
Florida.''
   The commission expects to narrow the list to three
semifinalists, after a year's review, and award the franchise in
September 1991. Planners hope trains will be running by 1995, the
state's 150th birthday.
   State guidelines mandate the multibillion-dollar project must
link Miami, Tampa and Orlando, but the applicants will determine
precise routes, financing agreements and the technology to use.
   ``The first thing I want to know is, is what they're proposing a
real viable plan? Is it a politically do-able deal?'' said Cocoa
Beach developer and attorney Malcolm Kirschenbaum, one of the seven
businessmen on the commission.
   The team that wins the franchise will be allowed to develop
property for rail stations and connecting attractions, a financing
plan that mirrors one used by industrialist Henry Flagler who built
a rail line nearly 100 years ago down Florida's Atlantic Coast and
eventually to Key West.
   ``Property developed as a way to help finance the system must
have some transportation link to the high-speed rail,'' said Hull.
   Theoretically, those development deals will allow the franchisee
to recoup its $2 billion to $5 billion startup costs, while fares
will support rail operation and maintenance.
   Balancing financial arrangements, environmental concerns, growth
patterns and evolving technologies, the commission will select the
best overall plan _ or reject all of them _ and make a
recommendation to the governor and Cabinet.
   Initial fees for applicants are $35,000. Several months from
now, applicants will have to pay about $2,000 per mile, or about
$600,000, to cover more detailed reviews of their proposals.
   The four applicants are:
   _TGV of Florida Inc., a Washington D.C.-based team backed by the
French company Alsthom, which supplies the 160 mph TGV trains to
the French National Railways, and Bombardier Inc., a Canadian
manufacturing consortium.
   _All American MagnePlane Inc. of New Port Richey, which has an
agreement to purchase a Massachusetts Institute of Technology
patent for a magnetically driven rail flight system, said President
David Ramsey, a civil engineer and developer.
   The average speed of the train, which still is being developed,
is 250 mph, Ramsey said.
   _Stone & Webster Engineering Corp., a 100-year-old, Boston-based
international firm. Stone & Webster's proposal is based on the
French ANS Turboliner, a 150 mph train that can run on existing
track.
   _Florida High Speed Rail Corp., a 40-member, international team
based in Deerfield Beach. Headed by Amerifirst Development Corp.,
the company proposes an electrically powered system similar to
Swiss, Italian, West German and some American trains already
operating.
   A fifth company, Orange Blossom Railroad Corp., a division of
the Dallas-based Entrak Systems Inc. engineering firm, had been
considering an application but did not make the 5 p.m. deadline
Friday, said Hull.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880325-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KCSouthern     03-25 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-KC Southern,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas City Southern Rejects Kaskel Merger Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. on
Friday rejected a proposal by New York investor Howard Kaskel to
discuss a merger, saying Kaskel actually intended to mount a
takeover bid.
   The railroad and financial services company received a letter
from Kaskel on Monday proposing talks concerning a possible
negotiated merger.
   Landon H. Rowland, president and chief executive of Kansas City
Southern, said the company's board of directors unanimously
rejected the proposal.
   ``It is clear to us that Mr. Kaskel's letter is merely a salvo
in his proposed proxy contest,'' Rowland said. ``Mr. Kaskel has not
even made a pretense of having sought or obtained financing,
confirming our view that he is merely attempting to put the company
into play.''
   Kaskel's investment group owns 11.3 percent of Kansas City
Southern's stock. The group said Monday it was offering $60 cash a
share, or about $594 million, for the remaining 89 percent.
   The stock closed Friday at $51.62{ per share, down $1.37{ per
share in national trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues.
   Kaskel said in his letter that he would attempt to place his own
slate of directors on the Kansas City Southern board if it rejected
or failed to act on his offer by April 4.
   He also accused the board of having erected obtacles ``designed
to entrench itself and to prevent stockholders from realizing a
full return on their investment.''
   Rowland said Friday that ``contrary to Mr. Kaskel's careless
statements impugning, without foundation, the motives of the Kansas
City Southern Industries directors, every action taken by the
directors has been entirely dedicated to the best interest of
Kansas City Southern Industries and its stockholders.''
   ``The board, after due review of Mr. Kaskel's letter, reaffirmed
its confidence in the company's future and its view that now is not
the time to sell the company,'' Rowland said.
   In reaching its conclusion, the company said the board obtained
an opinion from its investment banker, Lazard Freres & Co., which
reportedly said the Kaskel proposal was ambiguous and inadequate.
   The proposal appeared to be an effort to stimulate trading in
Kansas City Southern stock or to publicize Kaskel's plan to
nominate two persons to the company's board of directors, Kansas
City Southern said earlier.
   Richard Kaskel, one of the nominees, said Wednesday the investor
group would begin a proxy fight for the two slots. Four of Kansas
City Southern's 14 directors will be elected May 3 at the company's
annual meeting.
   Kansas City Southern's main holding is Kansas City Southern
Lines railroad, which is the country's 14th-largest line. The
company also owns 87.3 percent of DST Systems Inc., a financial
record keeper based in Kansas City, where it and affiliated
operations employ about 2,000 people.
   For the fiscal year that ended Dec. 31, Kansas City Southern
reported a profit of $17.7 million, or $1.82 a share, on revenue of
$507.6 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
