<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PacificEnterprises     03-25 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pacific Enterprises,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pacific Enterprises to Buy More Texas Oil, Gas Properties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its second foray into the Texas oil and
gas market this month, Pacific Enterprises said Friday it has
agreed to buy Sabine Corp. of Dallas for $24 per share, or $339
million.
   That is a 20 percent premium over the $20 per share at which
Sabine's stock closed Thursday. In the past year, its stock has
traded as high as $20.75 per share and as low as $9.37{.
   The deal, which is contingent upon 75 percent of the company's
shares being tendered, has been approved unanimously by Sabine's
directors, the companies said.
   As part of the agreement, Pacific Enterprises received an option
to buy 2.6 million shares, or 18{ percent, for $24 per share.
   Sabine is engaged in exploration, development and acquisition of
crude oil and natural gas in the United States.
   Pacific Enterprises, which until recently was known as Pacific
Lighting Corp., is the parent of Southern California Gas Co. It
also has gas and oil exploration and pipeline operations and runs
drugstore and sporting goods chains.
   The deal will give Pacific Enterprises proved oil and gas
reserves equivalent to 32 million barrels of oil, plus $55 million
in cash and mineral rights and leaseholds to nearly 4 million acres
of land.
   It will boost Pacific Enterprises' proved reserves by 36 percent.
   Earlier this month, the company agreed to buy half the oil and
gas mineral rights under 70,000 acres in Texas for $93 million.
That acreage is on the Burnett Ranch in King County, Texas.
</TEXT>
