<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0619EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FCC-CableRates     03-25 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Cable Rates,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Votes To Rescind Rate-Setting Freedom For Small Cable
Operators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission voted
Thursday to rescind the freedom of a small number of cable
television systems to set their own rates for basic service.
   Municipal rate regulation was lifted for more than 90 percent of
the country's 7,800 cable TV systems in January 1987.
   The FCC's rules change, approved 3-0, will subject more systems
to regulation by municipal officials, but neither the FCC nor the
National Cable Television Association could estimate how many.
Both, however, said the number would be small.
   The Cable Communications Act deregulated the rates for basic
service of cable systems in areas that had ``effective
competition.'' Cable systems that met this test became free to set
their own rates for their basic tier of service, which includes the
retransmission of local broadcast TV signals.
   But a federal appeals court struck down one of the components of
the FCC's definition of that term and the agency's vote Thursday
was intended to address that decision.
   Under the new definition, a cable system will be deemed to have
competition if all residents in the franchise area receive at least
three over-the-air broadcast signals, not necessarily the same
three signals.
   Under the old defective definition, a cable system was found to
have competition if any three broadcast signals covered 75 percent
of the county where the cable system operated.
   The NCTA said it was disappointed in the decision since there is
no evidence that cable systems have abused their freedom to set
rates.
   ``But there appears little we can do about it'' because ``the
courts are unlikely to second guess the commission on this
matter,'' the trade association said.
   ``We, therefore, look to the record to be established by the
large majority of cable systems which will continue to be
deregulated to give us the ammunition to go back at some point in
the future and ask the commission to revisit this issue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
