<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FordBonuses     03-25 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Bonuses,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Automaker Earmarks $250 Million For Executive Bonuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will divide up $250 million this
year in bonuses for salaried employees who contributed to the
success of Ford and its subsidiaries in 1987, the company said in
its annual report Thursday.
   A proxy statement in the second week of April will reveal how
many people will be awarded executive bonuses by the board of
directors' compensation and option committee, Ford spokesman Thomas
E. Foote said.
   In 1987, the seven-member committee of directors from outside
the company awarded $164.3 million in bonuses for 1986 to 5,528
salaried Ford employees, Foote said.
   The 1986 bonuses ranged as high as $1.3 million for Donald E.
Petersen, chairman and chief executive officer, and $1.1 million
for Harold A. Poling, then president and now vice-chairman, Foote
said.
   The company does not divulge the amounts of executive bonuses or
other compensation except to the five highest-paid executives.
Their compensation will be revealed in the April proxy report, he
said.
   Ford had said in February it was distributing $635 million, or
about $3,700 each, to hourly employees as their share of the
company's record $4.6 billion in 1987 earnings.
   The compensation and option committee allocated the $250 million
for the executive bonuses out of a possible $363.9 million under a
formula in Ford's stockholder-approved supplemental compensation
plan, the annual report said.
   Foote said the $164.3 million awarded last year was out of a
possible $241.9 million.
   The annual report, mailed Wednesday to Ford's 250,000
shareholders and released publicly on Thursday, cited the income of
$4.6 billion _ highest annual earnings of any company in automotive
history _ despite the year's seven percent drop in U.S. car and
truck sales, higher capital spending and increased marketing costs.
   The report described a ``corporate culture ... based on the
understanding that no individual is responsible for designing,
engineering, manufacturing, assembling and selling a product.''
   The first page of the report was a tribute to Henry Ford II, who
led the company as president or chairman for nearly 35 years prior
to his retirement as chairman in 1979. Ford died Sept. 29. ``On all
he left his imprint,'' Petersen said in the memorial tribute.
</TEXT>
