<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NorthwestContract     03-25 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Northwest Contract,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed Northwest Attendants Contract Would Eliminate Two-Tier
Scale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed contract for Northwest Airlines
flight attendants would eliminate a two-tier wage scale, add $75
million to the company's payroll to cover wage and benefit
increases and unify work rules, a company official said Thursday.
   Terry Erskine, Northwest's chief negotiator in contract talks
with Teamsters Local 2747, said that if ratified by the
rank-and-file the proposed contract would take effect June 1 and
expire Dec. 31, 1992.
   Jeff Musto, a spokesman for Local 2747, said the union
negotiating committee voted Wednesday night to submit the proposal
to the rank-and-file. Union officials have said they expect it to
be approved.
   The proposed contract was reached Tuesday, averting a strike
threatened for March 29.
   The final hurdle to the agreement had been how to treat
lower-paid B-scale employees who were to get an $800-a-month pay
raise by moving to the higher-paid A-scale after their fifth year
of service, Erskine and Musto said.
   The union wanted to retain the provision and Northwest wanted to
delay the pay raise until the eighth year. As a compromise, the
proposed contract will phase the 65 percent increase in after an
employee's seventh year of service.
   Workers would be paid under a single scale after 12 years with
the company, finally unifying scales of Northwest attendants with
those of their counterparts from the former Republic Airlines,
which was acquired by Northwest in 1986.
   The two-tier wage scale issue had intensified since the merger.
About a third of the 2,600 former Republic attendants are on the
lower pay scale, and the other two-thirds had said they wouldn't
get enough out of Northwest's previous wage offer.
   Under the proposal submitted for ratification, flight attendants
would get a 7.7 percent pay increase in their second year; a 6.4
percent increase in their fourth year, a 13.3 percent increase in
their sixth year and a 27 percent increase in their seventh year.
   Under the proposed new wage scale, most senior flight attendants
would earn about $35,500 a year in basic pay _ second in the
industry behind Delta Airlines, Erskine said. Entry-level flight
attendants would be paid about $15,000 a year in basic pay, close
to the industry average, he said.
   The contract also provides for pay raises of 2 percent in June
1990 and 3 percent in January 1992 for all current flight
attendants, and a variety of one-time bonuses.
   Former Republic Airlines workers also would be placed under the
Northwest pension plan, which would have its benefits boosted by 17
percent to make it level with the former Republic plan, Erskine
said.
   The pension and pay increases will add about $75 million to
Northwest's payroll over the life of the contract, Erskine said.
Some of the increase will be made up by adopting Northwest work
rules _ considered less expensive than rules covering the former
Republic workers _ for all the attendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
