<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-25 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures have turned mixed amid doubts by
traders over whether OPEC's pricing committee can soothe the
turbulent market at its scheduled meeting next month.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intemediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled at $16.96 per
barrel Thursday, up 10 cents from Wednesday's close. The contract
had risen 49 cents on Wednesday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the April
contract for wholesale heating oil slipped 0.33 cent to 47.40 cents
per gallon, after rising 1.47 cents Wednesday. Unleaded gasoline,
up 0.93 cent on Wednesday, was up 0.08 cent to 47.33 cents a gallon.
   Oil prices have fallen recently amid allegations that
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries member states were
cheating on production levels as well as pricing rules.
   Rilwanu Lukman, OPEC's president, announced Wednesday that the
cartel's five-member pricing committee would meet during the first
week of April to discuss how to stabilize prices.
   Peter Beutel, an assistant director at Elders Futures Inc.,
speculated that no substantive action would be taken until OPEC's
regular meeting in June.
   ``A lot of people were wondering if anyting will come out of
Luckman's various pronouncements,'' he said.
</TEXT>
