<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   03-25 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Considering Alternatives To Bank Of New York Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. is seeking a ``white knight''
friendly bidder and other alternatives to thwart Bank of New York's
hostile $1.08 billion tender offer, which began earlier this week.
   But Bank of New York says Thursday's announcement, made in a
Securities and Exchange Commission filing, changes nothing in its
six-month effort to acquire the rival bank holding company.
   In the filing, which was an official response to the hostile
bid, Irving said it was in the ``preliminary stages of negotiating
with third parties'' in connection with a possible merger,
reorganization, sale of assets or change in capitalization.
   Irving also said it has begun furnishing information to
unidentified parties its management intended to talk with still
more groups. Irving officials have refused to comment further on
the filing.
   Irving's board of directors repeatedly has denounced as
inadequate Bank of New York's offer to pay $15 in cash and 1.575
shares of its own stock for each of Irving's roughly 18.1 common
shares outstanding.
   ``From the information they've given we have no way of telling
if there's something going on or it's a lot of smoke,'' Bank of New
York spokesman Owen Brady said of Irving's SEC filing. ``We see
nothing substantative.''
   Industry analysts also were at a loss over what Irving's plans
might include, although Wall Street welcomed its disclosure as a
signal the bidding for Irving may escalate.
   In active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Irving rose
$6.62{ to $66.25 a share while Bank of New York rose $1.12{ to
$31.37{ a share.
   ``I have no idea who they might be talking to,'' said Brent
Erensel, senior analyst with Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette Securities
Corp. ``But it seems to me the priority for Irving is to be
independent first, seek a white knight second, and last of all to
submit to the Bank of New York.''
   Michael Starr, an analyst with Duff and Phelps Inc. in Chicago,
said Irving possibly could keep its current managment team intact
by merging with a foreign bank with a strong capital structure.
   ``It would be difficult for one of the larger U.S. banks to
merge with Irving because .. (they) have relatively weak capital
structures,'' he said.
   Last month, the Federal Reserve Board and the New York State
Banking Board cleared a Bank of New York-Irving merger, saying it
wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's biggest financial center.
   Irving has asked the federal courts to overturn the Fed's
decision.
   Earlier this week, Bank of New York received the SEC's go-ahead
to begin its tender offer, and the company also has assembled a
slate of 16 nominees to Irving's board. Bank of New York holds a
4.83 percent stake in Irving.
   Irving has stressed its desire to remain independent and has
taken a number of steps to spurn Bank of New York's advances,
including instituting an anti-takeover ``poison pill'' intended to
make any hostile buyout prohibitively expensive.
   In another effort to bolster its takeover defenses and place
stock in friendly hands, Irving recently issued $100.1 million
worth of cumulative convertible preferred stock to 15 investors.
The stock expands voting rights and offers other entitlements that
could foil a hostile bid.
   Bank of New York sued Irving in New York state court to void the
preferred issue.
   Bank of New York began its takeover efforts in September with a
bid of $1.4 billion, or $80 in cash and securities. It revised the
offer to $68 in cash and securities following October's stock
market crash, and lowered the offer a second time in late January.
   Hostile takeover efforts are rare in the banking industry. A
merger between New York Bank and Irving would create one of the
nation's 15 largest bank holding companies with combined assets of
more than $40 billion.
</TEXT>
