<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chips-GATT     03-25 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chips-GATT,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GATT Rules Against Implementation Of U.S.-Japan Chip Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary finding that Japan has
violated international rules of commerce in its implementation of a
U.S.-Japanese semiconductor trade agreement does not necessarily
void the pact, officials say.
   The preliminary finding disclosed Thursday was made by a panel
of the GATT, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an
international body based in Geneva that oversees the world trading
system.
   The panel report said Japanese companies used improper means to
prop up the export prices of semiconductors, including production
controls and industrywide pricing rules.
   The panel's finding requires the approval of the GATT Council,
which meets May 4. It was made public Thursday by Willy De Clercq,
chief negotiator of the European Economic Community, and later
confirmed by the office of U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter.
   The GATT itself declined to comment on the panel's finding,
saying it remained confidential.
   The GATT panel made the ruling three weeks ago, with copies
given to the United States, Japan and the European Economic
Community. It was kept confidential in hopes that the parties could
work out their differences in private.
   The ruling was distributed Thursday to other GATT member
nations, even though exact terms of the finding have not been
publicly disclosed.
   The 1986 chip agreement was intended to stop Japan from
``dumping'' chips at unfairly low prices in the United States and
other markets and to open up the Japanese chip market to foreign
producers, including Americans.
   In Washington, Yeutter issued a statement saying the United
States was satisfied with the finding.
   ``The GATT panel has determined that the objectives of the
agreement are consistent with GATT rules but that some of the
Japanese implementation methods are not. That is what we have been
saying since the agreement went into effect,'' Yeutter stated.
   ``Some of these methods of implementation, such as production
controls, will need to be changed but the need to make these
changes does not relieve Japan of its obligation under the
semiconductor agreement,'' Yeutter said.
   Japan's alleged failure to abide by the pact triggered $300
million in U.S. retaliatory tariffs last year against selected
Japanese electronics imports. Of those sanctions, some $165 million
remain in place.
   Gary Holmes, a spokesman for Yeutter in Washington, said the
United States never intended that Japan cease third-country dumping
by market manipulation.
   However, he said the Japanese government had sought to comply
with the pact through ``production controls and quantitative
restrictions, things we in the United States never agreed to in the
first place. We never thought they were legal (under GATT
guidelines).''
   The U.S.-based Semiconductor Industry Association said the GATT
findings ``did not challenge the fundamental legitimacy of the
agreement between the United States and Japan.''
   Trade officials in the Japanese Embassy in Washington were away
from their offices near the end of their business hours Thursday
and could not be reached for comment.
   Competition from low-priced Japanese chips knocked most U.S.
producers out of the business of selling the memory chips known as
dynamic random access memories, or D-RAMs.
   In addition to complaining to GATT, the EEC has launched a probe
of its own into possible Japanese dumping of several types of
computer memory chips.
   The EEC probe involves chips known as Eproms, which is short for
erasable programmable read-only memories.
   If the Japanese memory chip manufacturers were found to charge
unfairly low prices, their exports to Europe could be subjected to
punitive levies.
   Francoise Le Bail, the Commission's spokeswoman, said the
Community's dumping investigation will continue despite the GATT
finding.
</TEXT>
