<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 0756EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GM-Book     03-25 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Book,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Book Says GM Chief Has Vision But Not Implementation Skills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. officials are shrugging off
a new book by a former employee who portrays GM Chairman Roger
Smith as a man with a high-tech vision who lacked the people skills
to implement it.
   In his book, ``Call Me Roger, Albert Lee calls Smith's
stewardship at GM since 1981 a ``tragedy in leadership.''
   Lee, a GM speech writer from 1984 to 1987, cites plant closings,
GM's decreasing share of the auto market, Ford Motor Co.'s
ascendance as industry profit leader and Smith's public rift with
former GM board member H. Ross Perot, founder of Electronic Data
Systems, in making his conclusions.
   GM, which acquired EDS in 1984, agreed last year to pay Perot _
a harsh critic of GM management _ $700 million in return for his GM
holdings and resignation from the board of directors.
   Lee wrote of Smith that, following the Perot departure, ``By
almost every measure of management achievement...his leadership had
failed.''
   Lee's former boss, GM public relations vice president Jack
McNulty, questioned Lee's conclusions.
   ``(He's) just one guy who worked here two or three years, and he
was in Roger's office maybe six times. I don't think he's qualified
to talk about GM,'' McNulty said.
   The book is due in bookstores next month and will be excerpted
in Playboy's May issue.
   ``Roger is aware of the book,'' said GM spokesman Jim Crellin,
asked Smith's reaction. ``I don't know if he's read any of it, but
all we're saying is that we don't think the book's worth commenting
on.''
   Lee said Smith advanced via a fast-track executive development
program that left him unschooled in the art of motivating
employees. He said Smith failed to realize that to make full use of
its new technology, GM would require the support of workers from
its design labs to its shop floor.
   McNulty, who helped arrange interviews for Lee and read an early
draft of the book, disputed that contention.
   ``We've got the most modern plant structure in the industry,''
he said. ``We think we've got the best product line. Roger has
often said, `We've crossed the river and others have yet to cross
it.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
